<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="LUK" stage="Final" version="E">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:45:28Z" when="2009-10-05 05:45:28Z" stage="Draft">drafted by Lazarus Aplugi from KM; keyboarded in OW; team checked in Kupang Jan 2005 (whole team: Laz. Aplugi, Michael Sina, Paulus Ledoh, Lazarus Lusi, Helena Aplugi, Pdt. Margreth Erny Hake-Sina [almarhum]); Advisor check in Darwin, April 2005 with Michael, Lazarus A. &amp; Helena + read-thru; finished corrections from read-through in Kupang, July 2005; Uji-coba ; UNS suggestions discussed with team in Kupang 24 April 2006, plus updated to conform to Kupang Final-Ob; worked with LA, MS, HA 6 Juni 2007 di Kupang to match Kupang version Final-Q; ch.1-11, 15 Consultant Checked by Marge Crofts and Joan Finley 7-13 Nov 2007 in Kupang; ch. 12-14, 16-24 Consultant checked by Dave Glasgow 27 Feb - 3 Mar 2008 in Kupang,</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Lukas</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Good Story (*Gospel) about the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">madhutu sasuri<bt>according to the writings of</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Lukas<bt>Lukas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nga tao ka Lukas suri lii lolo ne<bt>Why Lukas writes this story</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-3" />Ama Teofilus<bt>Father Teofilus</bt><note reference="1:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara <span class="Italic">Teofilus</span> madhutu lii Yunani, sasoa na, &lt;dhèu dhu sue Lamatua&gt;. Ne'e ne, sasuri Lukas dhu uru tèka, na suri hia Teofilus. Sasuri ka dua, nuka <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha</span>.<bt>The name <span class="Italic">Teofilus</span> according to the Yunani language means ‘person/people who love/s the Lord’. This is Lukas' first book/writing which he wrote to Teofilus.</bt></note>dhu ja'a pakab'ua.<bt>whom I honour/respect.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lii maho'o nèti ja'a.<bt>Greetings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu ae dhu suri sèku le lii lolo nèti mamuri dènge sasab'a-la'a Yesus dhu j'aj'i ètu talora aae ji'i. Rèngu suri lii lolo sèra pake lii lolo dhu parai reo nèti ji'i asa ji'i karèi nèti uru ka, dhu ji'i nge'a nèti dhèu-dhèu dhu dètu dènge Lamatua Yesus, aa nèti dhèu leo dhu ladhe rèdhi dènge musi madha ra. Lii lolo se'e, lèke mola-mola dènge mamoa Ama Lamatua karèi nèti uru kèna.<bt>Many people have already tried to write the story about the life and work (doublet) of Yesus which have already happened in our-exc midst. They wrote those stories, using stories which have circulated from us-exc to us-exc from long.ago, which we-exc got to know from the people who were close to the Lord Yesus, and from other people who also saw with their very own eyes. All those stories, follow/are.in.accord exactly with what Father God promised beforehand from long ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parai oru = menyebar keliling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">parai oru = menyebar keliling</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De ja'a parisa kore le toke lutu dènge be'a, j'ara sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, mulai nèti j'aj'aj'i ra. Hèia ja'a pama'ète ho sèna ka suri si paie-iie ètu d'ara sasuri ne'e karèi nèti j'aj'aj'i ra. Dènge j'ara ne, ama bisa me'a mèu ngaa dhu j'aj'i le.<bt>So (consequently), I have examined down to the finest details all those matters, beginning from the root/cause of the story. So I decided to write up all those things carefully/well, from the beginning. In that way, you (father) can know exactly what has occurred.</bt><v n="4" />Aa ama bisa parcaya ngaa dhu dhèu lole sèra, lii dhu monya boe. Aa'i-aa'i se j'aj'i tare'a!<bt>And you can also trust what people have told (you), that it is not distorted/deceptive. All of it really happened!</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga peka tèke j'aj'aj'i Yohanis tuka sarani<bt>The Lord's servant from heaven (*angel) tells ahead.of.time the birth of Yohanis the habitual baptizer</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />J'aj'aj'i lii lolo ne sèmi ne'e: lod'o dhèu aae Herodes nèd'u paredha ètu propensi Yudea, abhu ca dhèu, dhu ngara na Sakaria. Nèngu ne, ca dhèu ama agama Yahudi. Aa nèngu kahèi, ca dhèu nèti kaboko ama agama Abia. Dhèu èmu Sakaria, ngara na Elisabet, ca dhèu ana-èpu nèti ama agama kahèi. Te Elisabet ne, ana-èpu nèti Harun, a'a Musa.<bt>This story's root/beginning is like this: when king Herodes was holding power in Yudea province, there was a person, named Sakaria. He [was] a *priest of the Yahudi religion. And he also [was] a member of Abia's group of priests. Sakaria's wife, was named Elisabet, a person who was a descendant of priests also. Cuz (elaboration) she was a descendant of grandfather/ancestor Musa's older.sibling Harun. [EXEG: according to Ex. 7:7, Aaron is older than Moses.]</bt><note reference="1:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 24:10; Kalua nèti Masir 7:7</note><v n="6" />Dua ra mamuri mola madhutu paredha dènge atora aa'i-aa'i nèti Ama Lamatua. Aa dhèu pakab'ua si kahèi.<bt>The two.of.them lived straight following/according to all of Father God's commands and regulations. And people respected them too.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="amemptoi: blameless, without fault"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">amemptoi: blameless, without fault</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dua ra dhu heka le, te ngaa dhu abhu boe kolo, te era ana nèti Elisabet dhu bèdho mèno.<bt>The two of them were also old, but did not have a child, cuz (elaboration) that child place (=womb) of Elisabet's was closed tight (idiomatic).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèno = rapat ; era ana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">mèno = rapat ; era ana = rahim, kandungan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ca tèka, Sakaria dènge dhèu d'ara kaboko Abia lèke lod'o rèngu sab'a ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>One time, Sakaria and his Abia group got rostered (their days) to work at the Central/Main Worship House (*Temple) in Yerusalem city.</bt><v n="9" />Madhutu atora ama agama, hud'i ère lot, ho re'a cee ka dhu maso asa Kama Mola-Mèci dhu ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ètu era èèna, dhèu ne hud'i pasèbu ai pake aj'u hèu mèngi ètu madha Ama Lamatua. Lod'o èèna, Sakaria lèke lot.<bt>Following their regulations/way of doing things, those priests drew lots, to find out who it was that would enter that Central Worship House's Very Holiest/Sacred Room. There, that person should/would burn fragrant wood in front of Father God. That day, the lot fell on Sakaria.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luri = pamali ; pasèbu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">luri = pamali ; pasèbu = bakar dupa, make smoke</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Hèia la'e dènge ka asa d'ara. Nèngu dhu talora pasèbu ai ètu d'ara Kama èèna, dhèu ae-ae dhu sabaj'a ètu madha Èmu.<bt>And so he went in. When he was burning fragrant wood in that Room, many people were worshiping/praying in the yard there.</bt><v n="11" />Cag'ag'a laa, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ca dhèu nèti sorga titu re bèka g'ana era tunu aj'u hèu mèngi ne.<bt>Unexpectedly/Suddenly, one of Father God's servants from heaven stood at the right side of the place for burning fragrant wood.</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00263C.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Ama agama Yahudi pasèbu ai pake a'ju hèu mèngi<bt>A Yahudi priest burns fragrant wood (*incense)</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi, Sakaria madha'u titu kèna, ka ne'a heka tao sèmi ngaa.<bt>When he saw that, Sakaria was exceedingly afraid, and he did not know want to do.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa ana pajuu ne lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sakaria! Baku madha'u! Te Ama Lamatua tadèngi le lii manèngi-mangaj'i èu. De bèli-camèd'a, dhèu èmu èu nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu. Èu hud'i pangare ne, Yohanis.<bt>But that servant spoke saying, “Sakaria! Don't be afraid! Cuz (elaboration) Father God has heard your-sg prayer. So (consequently), in the future your wife will give.birth to a male child. You must name him, Yohanis.</bt><v n="14" />Èèna na dhèu ae karej'e kahèi sama-sama dènge miu, lula miu abhu ana. Bèli-camèd'a, ana ne pakarej'e d'ara èu.<bt>Later many people will also be happy together with you-pl, because you-pl have a gotten a child. In the future, this child make you be joyful/happy.</bt><v n="15" />Koasa nèti Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, bera-bera dènge ne, karèi nèti ina na kad'o nèngu era. Nèngu ne hud'i luri ninu dhua ara-dhua pèd'u. Ropa na kapai, Ama Lamatua pake ne j'aj'i dhèu dhu dènge kolongara.<bt>Power/authority from the Lord's *Holy Spirit's will be with him, starting from when his mother is still pregnant with him. He must avoid/have.a.taboo.against drinking all hard drinks. When he is grown, Father God will use him to be a person with a (good) reputation/influence.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad'o = hamil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kad'o = hamil</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 6:3</note><v n="16" />Bèli-camèd'a èèna pamako nare dhèu Isra'el ae-ae, ho ra lèpa hari asa Ama Lamatua rèngu.<bt>Later he will attempt.to.persuade many Isra'el people to turn back again to their Father God/Lord. [their [Lord] God (built into name), slightly undertranslated, but preferred so as not to skew the focus.]</bt><v n="17" />Tatao dènge koasa na nuka sèmi Elia, ca dhèu dhu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua karèi uru. Nèngu ne mai uuru nèti Lamatua èdhi. Nèngu ne bisa kabèli d'ara ina-ama, ho sue hari ana-ana ra. Aa dhèu dhu rai nèti madha Lamatua, na ad'u si ho ra lèpa hari madhutu dad'èi Lamatua. Nèti sèmi èèna, nèngu tao dhèu sèna ka sadia d'ara ra sèmi mamai Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>His characteristics and power/authority will be like Elia, who was God's *spokesperson long.ago. He came/comes ahead of our Lord/Master. He will make old people (=parents) insides turn to love their children. And people/person who have fled from the Lord/God he will also change, so.that they turn around and follow the God's will. In that way, he (will) make people prepare their insides to receive the Lord's coming.”</bt><note reference="1:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 4:5-6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa Sakaria karèi ana pajuu ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe, sina ma?! Ja'a dènge dhèu èmu ja'a, d'ara heka sèmi ne'e ne! Tasamia ja'a bisa ke'a, na, j'ara se bisa j'aj'i?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Sakaria responded asking that underling, saying, “How can that be?! (=impossible) I and my wife are already old like this! How can I know all these things will/can happen?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karèi (3) = meminang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">karèi (3) = meminang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka ana pajuu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Ja'a ne Gabriel, dhèu pajuu Ama Lamatua. Nèngu ka paleha ja'a mai, sèna ka peka dènge èu lii lolo dhu be'a ne.<bt>Then, that servant replied saying, “Like this! I [am] Gabriel, Father God's *servant. He himself is the one who ordered me to come to tell this good news to you-sg.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="opaa = orang yang raja suru-suru,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">opaa = orang yang raja suru-suru, mandor (status renda)</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 8:16, 9:21</note><v n="20" />Te ngaa èu mo'o boe lèka lii padhai ja'a ne. De tadha dhu èu manèngi, sèmi ne'e! He'o èu èèna na sakaa, ho èu bisa heka padhai lii, nèti deo ne'e ne, toke miu abhu ana. Pe èu mèdhi unu mu. Te ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne, bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i, lèke dènge lod'o na.&gt;&gt;<bt>But you don't want to believe what I say. So (consequently), the sign which you ask will be like.this! Your tongue will be tightened/locked/stiff, and you will not be able to speak anything starting from now, until you-pl get/obtain that child. Later you-sg will see for yourself. But [contrary to normal expectations] what I am saying here will happen, exactly at its right time.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Dhèu-dhèu dhu sabaj'a ètu li'u sèra, bingu titu kèna, lula Sakaria tao bhodho boe.<bt>The many people who were worshipping/praying outside, were already confused, because Sakaria wasn't coming out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhodho = muncul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">bhodho = muncul</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ropa na kalua mai, nèngu bisa heka padhai lii. Ka na hia tadha re kacui-aai na, heka dhèu se'e re'a, na, Lamatua hia tanila ropa nèngu ètu d'ara Kama Mola-Mèci èèna.<bt>When he came outside, he could no longer speak. So he gave a sign to them using his hand/s, and they understood that the Lord had shown him an amazing thing inside that Most Clean/Holy Room.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa èle sasab'a ra, hèia Sakaria lèpa asa èmu na.<bt>When their work was over, then Sakaria went.home to his house.</bt><v n="24-25" />Nèbhu boe ka Elisabet dènge babia. Ka na pea dhoka ètu d'ara èmu toke lèmi hèru. Na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Koa-kio Lamatua! Lod'o d'ai kèna, Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi ja'a. Ladhe ja'a ne dènge ka kolo, dhèu pamakae heka ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long then Elisabet was pregnant (Idiom: lit. was burdened). Then she secluded herself/stayed alone in the house for five months. She spoke, saying, “Praise the Lord! Finally the Lord has shown His good goodness/grace to me. If/when I have a descendant, people will no longer shame me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga mai paraga dènge Maria<bt>The Lord's servant from heaven comes to meet with Maria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa Elisabet dènge babia d'ai èna hèru, hèia Ama Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na nèti sorga, la'e asa rae cue ètu propensi Galilea, ngara na Nasaret. Ngara ana pajuu ne, Gabriel.<bt>When Elisabet's pregnancy/burden had been going for six months, then Father God send His servant from heaven, to go to a village in Galilea province, named Nasaret. That servant's name was Gabriel.</bt><v n="27" />Ètu Nasaret, abhu ana bhèni ngèru ca dhèu, ngara na Maria. Nèngu ne dhèu dhu lii d'ai le, ngara na Yusuf. Yusuf ne, ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud. Gabriel la'e paraga dènge Maria.<bt>In Nasaret there was a young.girl, named Maria. She was already betrothed/engaged/spoken for with a man, named Yusuf. That Yusuf was a descendant of king Daud. Gabriel went to meet with Maria.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii dai = orang su pinang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lii dai = orang su pinang (early in the process)</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 1:18</note><v n="28" />Ka na pad'elo iisi na mi ana bhèni ne, hèia na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Salama, Maria, ee! Ama Lamatua dhu hag'e nare le èu, ho neo ad'u j'ara hua iia èci hia èu. Aa Nèngu bera-bera dènge èu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he showed himself to that female, then he said, “Greeting, Maria, ee! [+friendly] The Father God has chosen you-sg, in.order.to do something good for you. And He is also with you.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka Maria bingu, lula ne'a boe sasoa nèti lii padhai ana pajuu ne.<bt>Hearing like.that, then Maria was confused, because she did not understand what is meaning/intention was of what that servant was saying.</bt><v n="30" />Hèia ana pajuu ne tuhu hari lii padhai na, aku nèngu na,<bt>Then that servant continued speaking, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Maria! Baku madha'u.<bt>“Maria! You-sg do not need to be afraid. (=polite imperative, assuring, don't be afraid)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Ama Lamatua neo pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi èu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Father God's intention is to show His good insides (*grace) to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="31" />Nèbhu heka, èu dènge babia,<bt>Not much longer, you will be pregnant,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho èèna na, èu mora iisi ana mone ca dhèu.<bt>then later you will give.birth to a male child.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Èu hud'i pangare Ne, <span class="Italic">Yesus.</span><bt>You must name Him, <span class="Italic">Yesus.</span></bt><note reference="1:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Yeshua</span> sasoa na, &lt;Ama Lamatua hia mamuri mi dhèu&gt;. &lt;Yeshua&gt; èèna, nuka <span class="Italic">Yesus</span> madhutu lii Yunani. Ladhe kahèi ètu d'ara <span class="Italic">Mateos </span>1:21.<bt>In the Ibrani language, the meaning of <span class="Italic">Yeshua</span> is ‘Father God saves people’. That ‘Yeshua’ [name], is <span class="Italic">Yesus</span> in the Yunani language. See also Mateos 1:21.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="32" />Nèngu ne, bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i Dhèu kapai.<bt>He will become a big=important Person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èèna na Lamatua pangare ne, &lt;Nèngu ne, Ana d'èlu Ja'a.&gt;<bt>Later God?Lord will refer to Him, saying, ‘He is My very own Child.’ [EXEG: "God calls Him" from Gk grammar, Marshall p. 67, and HCE.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nuka, Ana nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele.<bt>That is, the Child from Father God who is the Very Highest.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pe Ama Lamatua ded'e Ne, sèna ka nèd'u paredha,<bt>Later Father God will lift/raise (=appoint) Him up to hold power,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi baki Na, dhèu aae Daud.<bt>the same as His ancestor king Daud.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hypsistos: taken as equivalent to 'El"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hypsistos: taken as equivalent to 'El 'Elyon in the Melchizedek story.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="33" />Nèngu ka dhu nèd'u paredha taa-taa mi dhèu Isra'el.<bt>He will be the one who later rules continually over the Israel people.</bt><note reference="1:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu lii Yunani peka na, &lt;Nèngu ka dhu paredha èmu Yakob&gt;. Sasoa na, &lt;Nèngu ka dhu paredha dhèu Isra'el.&gt;<bt>The Yunani language writes, saying, ‘He is the one who rules/commands Yakob's house’. It's meaning/intention says, ‘He rules/commands Isra'el people’.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te paredha Na dhu dènge boe too-lane.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) His ruling/commanding/government will not end.”</bt><note reference="1:32-33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Samuel 7:12, 13, 16, Yesaya 9:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa Maria karèi Gabriel, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne j'unu kèdhi mèka dènge dhèu mone èci sa! Tasa mera mia ka ja'a dènge babia?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Maria asked Gabriel, saying, “I here, have never slept together with a single male! How can I become pregnant?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Gabriel dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci puru mai asa èu. Aa koasa nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele, èèna na mai sarimu nare èu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Ana dhu bèli-camèd'a èu more iisi èèna, tare'a-re'a mola-mèci, lula Nèngu èèna, Ana Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then Gabriel replied saying, “Like this! God's Holy Spirit will descend coming to you. And the power of Father God who is the Very Highest will later envelop/cover over/blanket you. In that way, that Child which later you will give.birth.to, will be truly-truly clean/holy, because He will be Father God's Child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="to gennoomenon: the baby that is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">to gennoomenon: the baby that is being conceived kleetheesetai: will be called (by God) Holy and Son of God<span class="Italic">(35)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Baku malaa! Te a'ari èu ca dhèu, ngara na Elisabet, dènge le babia kahèi. Dhèu peka na, nèngu èèna bisa heka nara iisi, lula nèngu dhu heka le. Te ngaa limuri ne, nèngu dènge babia èna hèru kèna.<bt>Don't be amazed/surprised! Cuz (elaboration) one of your family members named Elisabet, is already pregnant too. People say/said she was not able to give.birth, because she is already too old. But now she has been pregnant/burdened going for six months.</bt><v n="37" />Te bagi Ama Lamatua, aa'i-aa'i bisa j'aj'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) for Father God, everything can happen/come to be!”</bt><note reference="1:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 18:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ka Maria dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a. Ja'a ne ènu Ama Lamatua. Hud'i laa aa'i-aa'i se j'aj'i madhutu sèmi lii èu èèna ka. Ja'a ke'a dhoka madhutu dad'èi Lamatua di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Maria replied saying, “Ok. I here am Father God's slave/servant. May it be that everything happens according to that speaking of yours. I am prepared to follow only the Lord's will.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle ka ana pajuu nèti sorga ne lèpa, tèke eele Maria.<bt>And then that servant from heaven went (back/home) leaving Maria behind.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Maria la'e ngad'o Elisabet<bt>Maria goes to visit Elisabet</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39-40" />Èle pèri-pèri lod'o, hèia Maria pakèd'i nèti Nasaret, la'e lai-lai asa rae Sakaria, ètu ledhe-ledhe propensi Yudea. D'ai nèi, la'e dènge ka asa d'ara èmu Sakaria. Ka na hia lii maho'o mi Elisabet.<bt>After several days, then Maria quickly left Nasaret and went to Sakaria's village in the mountain (region) of Yudea province. Arriving there, she entered straight.away into Sakaria's house. Then she gave greetings to Elisabet. [DISCOURSE: Nasaret from v.26--required here for foreground-background structure.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ropa Elisabet tadèngi lii maho'o nèti Maria, hèia ana ètu d'ara kabake Elisabet pasèja. Aa Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, maso sa Elisabet.<bt>When Elisabet heard those greetings of Maria, then the child in Elisabet's stomach kicked. And the Lord's Holy Spirit came and entered Elisabet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasèja = bakosi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pasèja = bakosi</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Ka Elisabet pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Maria! Bèli-camèd'a dhèu ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara èu, risi nèti dhèu bhèni aa'i-aa'i ra ètu rai-haha ne! Èèna na dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra j'oke padedha-dedha kahèi Ana dhu èu kad'o èèna.<bt>Then Elisabet called out, saying, “Maria! Later people will elevate your name (=praise, exalt) more than all the women in this world! Later people will also elevate that Child which is in your stomach/womb/pouch!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kad'o = 2) dlm kandungan, 1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kad'o = 2) dlm kandungan, 1) pouch made from sarong for carrying things ; pakèce =</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Ra pakab'ua ja'a kahèi, lula ina nèti Lamatua ja'a mai pangad'o dènge ja'a.<bt>I also follow/participate.in praising, because my Lord's mother has come to visit me.</bt><v n="44" />Ropa èu mèti lii maho'o mi dedha ja'a, cag'ag'a laa ana dhu ja'a kad'o ne pasèja ètu d'ara kabake ja'a, lula karae.<bt>When you came in and gave greetings to me, suddenly/ immediately the child in my stomach also kicked, because of being happy.</bt><v n="45" />Ama Lamatua pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na mi èu, lula èu ne parcaya, peka na, Nèngu tao madhutu lii dhu Na moa tèke.&gt;&gt;<bt>Father God has shown His good insides to you, because you believe that He will do according to His promise.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii padhadha = (Not known by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lii padhadha = (Not known by 2 young UNS) = lii dhu moa tèke le; CHECK oter occurences.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Maria koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua<bt>Maria praises the name/reputation of Father God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Maria bhoka hèb'a, peka na,<bt>Maria opened her mouth (=began to talk), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Nèti d'ara iiki ja'a,<bt>“From my inner-most insides,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ja'a ded'e padedha-dedha Lamatua!<bt>I lift the Lord up high!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="47" />D'ara ja'a karej'e-karae,<bt>My insides are happy (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Ama Lamatua hia ja'a mamuri!<bt>because Father God has saved me/given me life!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="48" />Nèngu ne tao le madha-dhilu mi ja'a,<bt>He has put his eye-ear on me (=watched over me),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao madha-dhilu = perhatikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tao madha-dhilu = perhatikan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka ana pua-paleha Na dhu dènge boe kab'ua ne.<bt>this servant of His who has no meaning/value (=is worthless).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haha dai seli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">haha dai seli</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doulees: cannot be &quot;worka guy.&quot; SK."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">doulees: cannot be "worka guy." SK.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Karèi nèti deo ne'e, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ngee na, ja'a ne,<bt>Starting from now all people will regard me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bhèni dhu kalua mèngi titu kèna,<bt>as the woman who is the most fortunate/blessed (Idiom: lit. fragrant veins/tendons), [EXEG: Gk /makarios/ means “in a fortunate state of affairs”. “Blessed” is church lg and /berkat/ doesn't fit context. Translations of “happy” and “berbahagia” are unacceptable, because Gk term does not have element of “feelings” in it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalua mèngi = fortunate, (Idiom: urat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kalua mèngi = fortunate, (Idiom: urat wangi)</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:48" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 1:11</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="49" />lula Lamatua tao j'ara malaa mi dedha ja'a.<bt>because God does/has.done amazing things for me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu ne, dhu Koasa Dedha Risi aa dhu Mola-Mèci Risi.<bt>He is the one who is Most Powerful and Most Clean/Holy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="onoma: name = character"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">onoma: name = character</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="50" />Ama Lamatua loe boe pad'elo sasue Na mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pakab'ua aa dhu pahaha iisi ra mi Nèngu,<bt>Father God always shows his love/compassion/mercy to all people who worship1 and humble themselves to worship2 Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti lai ana-lai èpu.<bt>from one descendant.group (generation) to the other descendant.group.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="51" />Na pake koasa Na,<bt>He uses His power/authority</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka tao pakaco dhèu-dhèu dhu padedha iisi sèra.<bt>to confuse people who elevate2 themselves (=proud). [EXEG: 1) scatter proud people (ignores some Gk words and has collocational problems), or 2) mess up plans of proud people -- we take 2;; Gilles says “UNS interpreted dong pung akal busuk as evil, cagey”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="52" />Na pamanahu dhèu aae-dhèu kapai dhu rèd'u koasa,<bt>He brings down people who hold power/authority,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula ra padedha iisi.<bt>because they elevate themselves (=pride).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te ngaa Na j'oka padedha-dedha dhèu-dhèu dhu pahaha iisi.<bt>But He lifts up people who have lower themselves (=humble).</bt><note reference="1:52" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 5:11, 12:19</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="53" />Na panga'a dhèu dhu manganga toke bècu,<bt>He feeds hungry people until they are full,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa Na babège-lalèta dhèu-dhèu kaja<bt>but He chases away the rich people</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho lasi dènge ai hua da'u-da'u.<bt>to go with empty hands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai hua dèbha-dèbha = ai hua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ai hua dèbha-dèbha = ai hua da'u-da'u = tangan kosong ; dhèba = female genitals (kasar) *</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="54" />Na soru-bara dhèu Isra'el Na,<bt>He helps (doublet) His Israel people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge loe boe pad'elo sasue Na mi rèngu.<bt>and always shows His love/compassion/mercy to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="55" />Uru èèna, Na pa'èki tèke le lii pajaji dènge bèi-baki èdhi,<bt>Previously, He bound a promise with our ancestor,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka baki Abraham dènge ana-èpu na aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>that is, grandfather/ancestor Abraham and all his descendants.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">D'ai sange ne'e, lii pajaji èèna pa'èki mèno.&gt;&gt;<bt>Now that promise is continually tied.”</bt><note reference="1:46-55" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 17:7; 1 Samuel 2:1-10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Hèia Maria pea dènge Elisabet toke tèlu hèru, heka lèpa asa èmu na ètu Nasaret.<bt>Then Maria stayed with Elisabet for three months. Then she went.home to her house in Nasaret.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Elisabet nara iisi Yohanis<bt>Elisabet gives birth to Yohanis</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Ropa d'ai hèru, ka Elisabet nara iisi ana mone ca dhèu.<bt>When the time arrived, then Elisabet gave.birth to a male child.</bt><v n="58" />Lii ne'e, ra palolo d'ai a'ari na dènge rae lesa, aku rèngu na, Ama Lamatua pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na, ka Na hia Elisabet ana mone ca dhèu. Hèia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e kahèi.<bt>That news spread to her family and the entire village, that Father God had shown His good liver (=grace/ kindness/ favour), and given Elisabet a child. And they all were happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="emegalynen ... to eleos autou met'"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">emegalynen ... to eleos autou met' autees:</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Lod'o ana ne d'ai aru lod'o, ka ra suna ne, madhutu atora dhèu Yahudi. Ra neo pangare ana ne, Sakaria, madhutu ngara ama na.<bt>When that child was eight days old, then they *circumcised (loan) him, according to the Yahudi people's regulation. They want to name that child, Sakaria, following his father's name.</bt><note reference="1:59" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:3</note><v n="60" />Te ngaa ina na b'ala ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o sèmi èèna! Ngara na hud'i Yohanis ku!&gt;&gt;<bt>But his mother responded, saying, “It can't be like that! His name must be Yohanis!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Te ngaa ra b'ala ne, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka pili ngara Yohanis? Nèti a'ari miu, ca dhèu sa dhu ngara dhae, sèmi mèka èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they replied saying, “Why choose the name Yohanis? There is not yet a single person in your-pl family who has that name!”</bt><v n="62" />Ka ra senen ho karèi Sakaria, sèna ka neo pangare ana ne ngara na ngaa.<bt>Then they gave a sign to ask Sakaria, to find out what he wanted to name that child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagape = motion to summon ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pagape = motion to summon ; senen = kasi sein</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="63" />Hèia Sakaria senen ho manèngi lei. Ra hia ne lei, ka na suri peka na, &lt;&lt;Ngara na Yohanis!&gt;&gt; Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i malaa titu kèna.<bt>Then Sakaria made a sign asking for a writing stone (old style.individual chalk board) They gave it to him, then he wrote, saying, “His name is Yohanis!” Then all the people were amazed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lei = batu tulis (old fashioned"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lei = batu tulis (old fashioned school chalk board for individual; pre-1960s; 2 UNS not know)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="64" />Cag'ag'a laa, he'o na dhu sakaa mèno èèna, mako dènge ka. Ka na koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Suddenly/unexpectedly, that tongue of Sakaria's which was tight/locked, became immediately loose/pliable. And he praised (doublet) the reputation of Father God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaj'èpe = malengket"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kaj'èpe = malengket</Message></Annotation><v n="65" />Hèia dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pea padètu ètu sèra sa, madha'u dènge malaa. Ka lii ne'e mulai ra palolo nèti hèb'a sa hèb'a, toke dhèu-dhèu ètu ledhe-ledhe ètu propensi Yudea re'a aa'i kahèi.<bt>Then all the people who were staying/living nearby, were afraid and amazed. And that news began to spread from mouth to mouth, until the people in the mountains of Yudea province also knew all about it.</bt><v n="66" />Dhèu-dhèu dhu tadèngi lii lolo èèna, ra pangee, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tatu koasa nèti Lamatua bera-bera dènge ana ne. Bèli-camèd'a, ladhe na kapai mai, na j'aj'i dhèu sèmi mia, oo?&gt;&gt;<bt>People who heard that story, thought, saying, “Surely the Lord's power is with that child. Later when he grows up, what kind of human will he be, oo [=we wonder]?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ethento ... en teei kardiaai autoon:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">ethento ... en teei kardiaai autoon: pondered, stored it up in their hearts (synonymous with 2:19)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sakaria koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua<bt>Sakaria praises the name/reputation of Father God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="67" />Èle ka, Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci maso asa Sakaria. Ka na padhai lii, peka na,<bt>Afterwards then, the Lord's Holy Spirit entered Sakaria. And (so) he spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="68" />&lt;&lt;Koa-kio Ama Lamatua dhèu Isra'el!<bt>“Praise Father God of the Isra'el people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Na mai le ho sui nare dhèu unu Na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He has already come to *redeem His people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka rèngu baku j'aj'i sèmi ènu sa.<bt>so that they are not like slaves [expanding "freed from what?"].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lytroosin: moral or political: the prayer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">lytroosin: moral or political: the prayer sounds more political.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="69" />Lamatua ded'e le ca Dhèu dhu koasa Na kapai titu kèna,<bt>The Lord has lifted up/appointed a Person whose power is very great,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho hia èdhi mamuri.<bt>in.order.to save us-inc/give us life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sooteeria: nonspecific - doesn't say whether"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">sooteeria: nonspecific - doesn't say whether it's a bad situation (this prayer seems to have political overtones) or moral evil inside us.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèngu ne, ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud.<bt>That He, is a decendant of king Daud.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="70" />Lamatua moa mema, karèi nèti uru ka,<bt>The Lord has promised ahead.of.time from long.ago,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">re dhèu dhu maj'èni rèti lii padhai Na.<bt>using/by means of His faithful/diligent spokespersons. [EXEG: "holy prophets" nonsensical in literal translation "clean prophets"; "holy" = set aside, dedicated, consecrated, special = faithful, as a quality which can distinguish spokespersons.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="71" />Limuri ne Na neo patabuli èdhi<bt>Now He want to/is going to free us-inc</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti musu-musu èdhi,<bt>from our (various) enemies,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa nèti dhèu dhu d'ara pèd'a dènge èdhi.<bt>and from people who are sick.livered (=hate, resentful) toward us-inc.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="72-73" />Na pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi bèi-baki èdhi,<bt>He showed His good insides (grace, kindness) to our-inc ancestors,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Na sanèd'e taruu lii pajaji Na mi rèngu,<bt>because He continually remembered His promise to them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu Na pa'èki dènge baki Abraham.<bt>which He bound with grandfather Abraham.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="74" />Na patabuli le èdhi nèti musu-musu èdhi,<bt>He has freed us-inc from our enemies,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ta pahaha iisi mi Nèngu,<bt>so that we-inc can worship (lit. humble ourselves toward) Him, [EXEG: interlinear 'serve' is actually 'worship' in the lexicon.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu dènge heka d'ara madha'u.<bt>and do it no longer being afraid.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="75" />Na patalale le èdhi,<bt>He has freed2 us,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka èdhi bisa mamuri mola-mèci dènge be'a taa-taa, ètu katanga madha Na.<bt>so that we can live continually live cleanly/holy and well/properly (=moral) before Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="76" />Yohanis, ee! Èu ne, ana ja'a.<bt>Yohanis, my child, ee [vocative + affection]!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bèli-camèd'a dhèu tadhe èu, na, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi aa'i.<bt>You in the future people will know/recognise you, saying that you are the *spokesperson of the Most High Father God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èèna na, lamu peka-padhai dènge dhèu,<bt>Later you will go tell/explain to people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ra pakabhèle kacui-aai ra ho soru mamai Lamatua.<bt>so.that they open their hands (=are hospitable) to receive the coming of the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakabhèle = open hands"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pakabhèle = open hands</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hypsistos: equivalent to 'El 'Elyon (Da"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hypsistos: equivalent to 'El 'Elyon (Da Start 14:19)</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:76" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 3:1</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="77" />Bèli-camèd'a, lamu paj'uj'u j'ara hia mi dhèu unu Lamatua,<bt>In the future, you will go show/reveal the path to the Lord's people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka re'a, na, Ama Lamatua hia mamuri mi rèngu,<bt>so.that they can know, that, they get life/salvation with Father God, [NOTE to daughter translations: If in your language /dapa salamat/ is the same as /dapa idop/, then change to /dong bisa idop deng Tuhan Allah/.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Nèngu ka dhu saku eele sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>because He is the one who has wiped/erased away their wrongs/sins.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hamartia: this is &quot;sin,&quot; not &quot;difficulties&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hamartia: this is "sin," not "difficulties" or "bad circumstances."</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="78-79" />Lula d'ara Lamatua taleo aa rasa kasia mi dedha èdhi,<bt>Because the Lord's insides are broad (generous/kind) and merciful/pityful toward us,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe bhilu = noe babecek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">roe bhilu = noe babecek</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lula dara Lamatua dhu roe bhilu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Lula dara Lamatua dhu roe bhilu ropa nèdhi èdhi,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="splagkhna: here &quot;big heart&quot; is the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">splagkhna: here "big heart" is the functional equivalent</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèti èèna ka, Na hia èdhi taa-tebho dhu hiu,<bt>that's why He has given us new opportunity (doublet),</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tebho = not known by 3"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tebho = not known by 3 UNS's</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nuka sèmi lod'o hiu nèti saraa dhu hiu.<bt>like a new day brings new light.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èdhi dhu mamuri ètu d'ara maroga,<bt>We who live in the darkness,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa èdhi dhu pea dènge d'ara madha'u ètu sanabhu mamadhe,<bt>and we who live2 with fearful insides in the shadow/aura/presence of death,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu'u = sembunyi ; sanabhu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lu'u = sembunyi ; sanabhu = bayangan, aura (sense the presence of)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula pabe'a mèka dènge Lamatua,<bt>because we are not yet in a reciprocally good.relationship (=relational peace) with the Lord, [NOTE: one sense of Gk /eirene/]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a abhu saraa ho lere èdhi asa j'ara dhu nèti mera-milu.&gt;&gt;<bt>later will get light to escort us to the path of peace (external peace, security).” [NOTE: another sense of Gk /eirene/] [NOTE: in next to last clause, “reciprocally at peace” changed to “reciprocally good.relationship” so not heavy with last clause, Both reinforce the picture of what the problem and solution are in vs. 77-79.]</bt><note reference="1:79" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 9:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="80" />Ka Yohanis asa kapai noo-noo. Aa Roh Lamatua pa'èra ne. Na kapai mai, hèia la'e pea ka ètu d'ara mamoo, toke d'ai lod'o na pakako sasab'a mi dhèu Isra'el sèra.<bt>Then Yohanis got increasingly older/bigger. And the Lord's Spirit made him strong. When he grew up, then he went to live in a desolate/quiet place, until the time he started his work among the Isra'el people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noo-noo = tamba hari tamba besar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">noo-noo = tamba hari tamba besar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Maria nara iisi Lamatua Yesus<bt>Maria gives.birth to the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 1:18-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1-2" />Ca tèka, ètu d'ara Kirenius j'aj'i gubernur ètu Siria, dhèu aae kapai Agustus, hia paredha, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu paredha Roma, hud'i lèpa asa rae èta-èsu ra ho madhutu sensus!&gt;&gt; Èèna heka hiu-lai kèna, dhèu paredha Roma ige ana kabarai na.<bt>One time, during when Kirenius was the gubernur in Siria, the big/main king, Agustus, gave a command, which said, “All people who are under the governance of Roma, must return.home to their [ancestral] village to participate in a *census (loan)!” That was the first time for the Roma government to count its populace.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiu-lai = for first time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">hiu-lai = for first time</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i lèpa asa rai èta-èsu ra, sèna ka madhutu sensus.<bt>So, all the people returned to their [ancestral] village to participate in the census.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai èta èsu = tanah kelahiran"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">rai èta èsu = tanah kelahiran</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Lod'o èèna, Yusuf pea ètu rae Nasaret, ètu propensi Galilea. Nèngu dhu lii d'ai ana bhèni ca dhèu, ngara na Maria, dhu dènge le babia. Yusuf ne, ana-èpu nèti dhèu aae Daud. Ka nèngu hud'i lèpa ku asa kota Daud, nuka Betlehem ètu propensi Yudea, sèna ka madhutu sensus.<bt>At that time, Yusuf was living in Nasaret village in Galilea province. He was already engaged to a young.girl, named Maria, who was already pregnant. That Yusuf was king Daud's descendant. So he had to return.home to Daud's Bethlehem city in Yudea province to participate in the census.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nèti èèna ka, dua ra lasi asa kota Betlehem.<bt>That's why the two of them left to go to Bethlehem city.</bt><v n="6" />Ropa dua ra ètu nèi, Maria d'ai lod'o nara iisi.<bt>While they were there, Maria's time for giving.birth arrived. [EXEG: It sounds as if they were in Bethlehem for some time, because it was "during" (en tooi einai autous ekei) that time that the baby came due.]</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa ètu èèna, dua ra abhu boe kama ètu d'ara losmen. Nèti èèna ka, dua ra maso lasi asa d'ara oka badha. Hèia Maria nara iisi Ana uuru, mone ca dhèu. Ka pasig'i Ne dènge kaha'i bèla, aa paj'unu ètu d'ara karab'a, era badha ra'a-rinu.<bt>But there, the two of them did not find a room (loan) in the inn (loan). That's why the two of them entered into a stall/stable/pen. And then, Maria gave.birth to her first Child, a male. Then they wrapped Him with pieces/strips of cloth, and laid him to sleep in a manger/trough, the animal's eating place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasig'i = kasi pake kaen ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pasig'i = kasi pake kaen ; kaha'i = potong ; karab'a = tampa makan-minum binatang (kulit keong, batang tuak), juga tampa mandi ana-ana</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Note Bailey's reading of &quot;katalyma&quot; as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">Note Bailey's reading of "katalyma" as "guest room," not "inn." The scenario is that Joseph had relatives in Bethlehem, his family town of origin. Their guest room (katalyma is also translated "upper room" in the Last Supper story) was already occupied with other relatives who had come in for the registration, so Joseph and Mary lived with the family on the ground floor, in the raised living area bordered by a dirt area for the animals, whose mangers were built into the outside wall. It sounds as if they were in Bethlehem for some time, because it was "during" (en tooi einai autous ekei) that time that the baby came due.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua peka dènge ana madhenge badha<bt>Father God tells the herders</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Mèda èèna, abhu ana madhenga badha dhèu pèri-pèri dhu beke madhenge kahib'i-kalèbho ètu d'ara pad'a ètu li'u kota.<bt>That night, there were several shepherds who were staying.awake.at.night watching their goats-sheep in a field outside the city.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="beke = mete ; ana madhenga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">beke = mete ; ana madhenga badha (n) ; madhenge (v)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00013C.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Ana madhenga badha j'aga kahib'i-kalèbho<bt>Herders stay guarding flocks</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Kaca'a laa, rèngu rèdhi ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga. Hèia saraa Lamatua rai-reo nare rèngu, ka ra madha'u bia.<bt>Suddenly/unexpectedly, they saw Father God's *angel (underling from heaven). Then the Lord's light shone surrounding them, and they were very afraid/terrified.</bt><v n="10" />Te ngaa ana pajuu ne peka,<bt>But that underling told saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Baku madha'u! Nanene pabe'a-be'a! Te ja'a ne mai ho peka lii lolo be'a èci hia miu. Cee dhu tadèngi lii ne'e, tatu rèngu karej'e.<bt>“You-pl don't be afraid [imperative]! Listen well! Cuz (elaboration) I have come to tell a good news/report to you. Whoever hears this news, will surely be happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Lii lolo be'a ne, sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>The good news is like.this: [DISCOURSE: common intro to contents of a message]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Deo ne'e, ca dhèu ina nara iisi le Kristus ètu Betlehem, nuka kota dhèu aae Daud.<bt>Today/earlier, a mother has given.birth to Kristus, in Bethlehem, the city of king Daud.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Kristus ne'e ka dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji tèke le karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>That Kristus is the one whom Father God has promised ahead.of.time from long.ago. [EXEG: explicates “Christ” following TBT article on translating meaning of Christ (the rank). Smith, Jill and Dr. Harold Fehderau. 1981. Translating Christ and Messiah in the NT. TBT 32(4):423-431. (Also, for help with the meaning of “in Christ,” see Hale, Clarence B. 1991. The Meaning of “in Christ.” SIL.) This is following standard SIL and UBS practice, based on those (and related) articles. This is part of the meaning that the shepherds would have understood.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua hia Na mai, sèna ka Na patabuli dhèu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>The Lord is sending Him to save people from their wrongs! [EXEG: explicates “Saviour”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu ne'e, èèna na dhèu paroa Na, &lt;Lamatua&gt;!<bt>He is the one whom people will call, ‘Lord/master/owner/boss’! [EXEG: explicates “Lord”. Note: In English church language ‘Lord’ can stand alone. But in Kupang and other lgs, Bos/Lamatua (etc.) either needs to be possessed, or be in relation to something or someone. /Kotong pung Bos/ would be misread here as ‘Bos of the angels’, but the context is clearly announcing the coming of the Messiah in relation to salvation of humans--hence this rendering. In local church usage ‘Tuhan, Lamatua (etc)’ by itself will almost always trace back to God, not Christ, and is described as ‘the being we worship’, and never ‘the one we obey, who has the say-so rights over us’. By making it possessed, or in relation to something, we can force the latter understanding, which brings out a meaning element important to the Gk /kurios/.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Pe miu tadhe Ne sèmi ne'e ka: miu paraga dènge Ana rara iisi hiu ca dhèu dhu pahutu dènge sig'i. Ra paj'unu Ne ètu d'ara karab'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later you will know/recognise Him like.this: you-pl will meet/find an infant/newborn who is wrapped with cloth. He is sleeping/lying in a trough/manger, the animal's eating place.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sig'i = kaen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">sig'i = kaen</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa na padhai lii nare, hèia cag'ag'a laa, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ae-ae mai nèti sorga. Ka ra pa'èci dènge ne. Hèia ra koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua dènge lii sod'a, peka na,<bt>When he finished speaking like.that then, unexpectedly, the lots and lots of Father God's angels/underlings came from heaven. And they united with him. Then they praised (doublet) Father God and sang, saying, [NOTE to daughter translations: ‘singing’ is not in Greek. It is here as generic action (praise) -- specific symbolic action associated with praise (singing). The contextual sense of celebration doesn't come through without it. NRSV similarly translates /legei/ as ‘sing’ in several places in Rev.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />&lt;&lt;Ji'i ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua!<bt>“We lift up high Father God's name/reputation!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu dhu nèd'u paredha ètu dedha-liru dhu dedha risi.<bt>He is the one who holds power/governs in the highest sky.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hypsistois: the highest realms (probably not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hypsistois: the highest realms (probably not "the most high God"; the contrast is with "on earth")</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua neo hia dame dènge mera-milu mi dhèu rai-haha,<bt>Father God wants to/is going to give peace and prosperity/security to people on earth,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peace: spiritual prosperity, wholeness, salvation; shalom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">peace: spiritual prosperity, wholeness, salvation; shalom</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu pakarej'e d'ara Na!&gt;&gt;<bt>who make His insides happy!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle ka, ana pajuu se lèpa hari asa sorga. Hèia ana madhenga badha se padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati ku asa Betlehem, ho ladhe ku Ana nèi! Te Lamatua pa'adhu le lii ne hia èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the angels/underlings returned back to heaven. Then those shepherds spoke to each other saying, “Let's go to Bethlehem to see that Child! Cuz (elaboration) the Lord has sent that news to us-inc.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia lasi ka lai-lai asa Betlehem. Ka rèngu paraga Maria dènge Yusuf. Aa ladhe rèdhi kahèi Ana dhu heka rara iisi, dhu bhèj'i ètu d'ara karab'a.<bt>Then they quickly went to Bethlehem. And they met/found Maria and Yusuf. And2 they also saw that newborn Child, who was sleeping in the trough/manger.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa rèngu rèdhi Ana ne, hèia ra lolo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Deo na ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga dhu peka le dènge ji'i, lula-nèti Ana ne'e ne!&gt;&gt; Ka ra lolo aa'i-aa'i toke èle.<bt>When they saw that Child, then they narrated, saying, “Earlier (recent) Father God's underlings from heaven told about this Child to us-exc!” And they told the entire story.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i malaa-maloha, tadèngi lii lolo ana madhenga badha se.<bt>Everyone was amazed when they heard those shepherd's story.</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa Maria tèke ka ètu d'ara na, aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i le. Aa na pangee mau-mau, ho neo ne'a sasoa na tasa mera mia.<bt>But Maria put in her insides, all those things that happened. And she thought (repeatedly) quietly seeking to understand what they meant.</bt><v n="20" />Èle ka, ana madhenga badha se lèpa hari asa era kahib'i-kalèbho ra. Hèia ra ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua. Ra manèngi makasi mi Lamatua, lula dhu rèngu tadèngi aa rèdhi dènge musi madha ra, lèke tare'a-re'a sèmi ngaa dhu ana pajuu Ama Lamatua peka sèra.<bt>After that, those shepherds returned to their goats-sheep. And they lifted up high Father God's name. They gave thanks to the Lord, because of what they had heard and seen with their own eyes, was exactly like what the Lord's underling had told them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana iiki ne, ra pangare Na, <span class="Italic">Yesus</span><bt>That infant/small child, they name Him, <span class="Italic">Yesus</span></bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa Ana iiki ne d'ai aru lod'o, ka ra suna Ne madhutu atora Musa. Hèia ama dènge ina Na pangare Ne, &lt;Yesus&gt;. Ngara ne, ngara dhu ana pajuu nèti sorga peka le dènge rèngu, lod'o ina Na dènge mèka babia.<bt>When the Child reached eight days old, then they *circumcised Him according to Musa's regulation. Then His father and mother named Him, ‘Yesus’. That name, is the name which the underling from heaven told to them, when His mother was not yet pregnant (=before).</bt><note reference="2:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 1:31, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:3</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèti Ana iiki ne, asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>They bring small child Child to the Central Worship House</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Atora èci nèti baki Musa peka na, bhèni dhu rara iisi rare, d'ai èpa nguru lod'o hud'i madhutu ku ad'a, pamèu iisi ra ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu bisa maso sèmi biasa asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a. Nèti èèna ka, Yusuf dènge Maria lasi asa kota Yerusalem, sèna ka tao madhutu ad'a. Lasi rèti dènge Ana iiki èèna asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ho saraka Ne, sèna ka j'aj'i unu Lamatua.<bt>There is a regulation from grandfather Musa that says, forty days after a woman has given.birth, [she] must do the ritual/adat of cleaning/purifying herself in the Central Worship House. By doing like.that, they could enter the worship house like usual. That's why Yusuf and Maria went to Yerusalem city to carry out that ritual/adat. Then they brought with them that small Child to the Central Worship House, to surrender/hand over Him to become the Lord's possession.</bt><note reference="2:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:1-8</note><v n="23" />Rèngu madhutu atora Lamatua dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Bhèni dhu nara iisi ana mone uuru, nèngu hud'i saraka ana ne j'aj'i unu Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>They followed the Lord's regulation which says, “A woman who gives.birth to [her] first male child, she must surrender that child to become the Lord's possession.”</bt><note reference="2:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 13:2,12</note><v n="24" />Madhutu atora Lamatua, ladhe saraka ana èèna mi Lamatua, ina-ama hud'i hia ku koro iia ca pasa, do koro j'aha ngèru dua ngi'u. Nèti èèna ka, Yusuf dènge Maria tao madhutu atora èèna.<bt>According to the Lord's regulation, if/when surrendering that child to the Lord, the mother-father (=parents) must give a pair of turtledove birds, or, two young pidgeons/doves. That's why Yusuf and Maria also did according to that regulation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koro iia = turtledove ; koro"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">koro iia = turtledove ; koro j'aha = dove (larger) both eat biji-biji rumput, koro j'aha can be domesticated, but not koro iia</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:22-24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:6-8</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baki Simeon peka na, Ana iiki dhu ngara Na Yesus èèna, nuka Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua jaji tèka le<bt>Grandfather Simeon says that the newborn named Yesus, is Kristus whom Father God had already promised</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25-26" />Taa èèna, abhu mone heka ca dhèu ngara na Simeon, dhu pea ètu kota Yerusalem. Nèngu ne dhèu d'ara mola, aa d'èi Lamatua. Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka le dènge ne, na, nèngu hud'i nèdhi ku Kristus, heka na madhe kèna. Kristus èèna ka, dhu bèli-camèd'a hia mamuri mi dhèu Isra'el.<bt>At that time, there was an old grandfather, named Simeon, who lived in the city of Yerusalem. He was a person whose insides were straight (=righteous) and he yearned for the Lord. The Lord's Holy Spirit had told him, that he would later get to see Kristus first, only.then would he die. That Kristus is the one who would save/give life to the people of Isra'el.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o èèna, Roh Lamatua lere Simeon la'e asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Lod'o èèna kahèi, ina-ama Yesus rèti Ne, ho saraka j'aj'i unu Lamatua.<bt>At that time, the Lord's Spirit escorted Simeon to the Central Worship House. That was also when Yesus' father-mother were bringing Him there, to surrender Him to become the Lord's possession.</bt><v n="28" />Ropa ladhe nèdhi Ana ne, ka Simeon sa'u nare Ne, hèia na koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua, aku nèngu na,<bt>Seeing that Child, then Simeon cuddled Him, and he lifted up praises (doublet) to Father God, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sa'u = koko, gendong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">sa'u = koko, gendong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="29" />&lt;&lt;Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua!<bt>“Praise the name/reputation of the Lord!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua tao le madhutu lii pajaji Na mi dedha ja'a.<bt>The Lord has done according to His promise to me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De ne'e ne Lamatua bisa le patabuli ja'a,<bt>So (consequently), now, the Lord can release me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka ja'a madhe dènge mera-milu,<bt>so that I can die quietly/peacefully,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eireenee: inner peace, more than happiness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">eireenee: inner peace, more than happiness</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="30" />te ja'a kèdhi le Dhèu dhu Lamatua pua mai,<bt>cuz (elaboration) I have seen the Person whom the Lord sent/sends,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho patabuli ji'i nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ji'i!<bt>to save us-exc from our-exc wrongs!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="31" />Lamatua neo pake Ana ne'e,<bt>The Lord will use this Child</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka hia mamuri mi suku aa'i-aa'i.<bt>to save/give life to all nations/ethnic.groups.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="32" />Nèngu nuka sèmi saraa,<bt>He will be like rays.of.light,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu pakab'ua suku-suku Isra'el, dhèu Lamatua sèra.<bt>which brings honour to the tribes of Israel, the Lord's people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu kahèi èci èèna ka dènge saraa,<bt>He is/will.be also like light,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu pad'elo j'ara Lamatua,<bt>which shows/reveals the Lord's path/way</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">pala mi suku-suku leo kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>to all other ethnic.groups/nations.” [NOTE: order reversed, structured as parallelism; "glory" -- "bring honor" (CEV)]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: a light for revelation to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">NRSV: a light for revelation to the Gentiles and for glory to your people Israel.</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 42:6, 49:6, 52:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia Yusuf dènge Maria malaa lula lii padhai dhu Simeon peka lula-nèti Ana rèngu ne.<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yusuf and Maria were amazed about what Simeon said about their Child.</bt><v n="34" />Èle ka Simeon padhai lii hia si mèngi-nale. Hèia na peka dènge Maria, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina Yesus! Bèli-camèd'a dhèu ae ètu Isra'el tule eele Ana èu ne. Te ngaa tatao rèngu mi dedha Nèngu ne, èèna na pamanahu hari rèngu. Ana ne'e, bèli-camèd'a pakarej'e d'ara dhèu ae kahèi.<bt>After that, Simeon spoke giving blessing to them. Then he told Maria, saying, “Yesus' mother! Later many people in Isra'el will push.away/reject this Child of yours. But those doings/deeds of theirs upon Him, will later fall back on them. This Child will also make many peoples ínsides happy/joyful.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seemeion: sign"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">seemeion: sign</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Dènge j'ara èèna, Lamatua bhoke patalele d'ara dhèu. Te ngaa èu, Maria, pe mu paraga dènge j'aj'èra ae-ae, nuka sèmi samala dhu lose adhe-usu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>In that.way, later God will open naked the contents of people's insides. But you, Maria, later you will encounter/experience great suffering, as if a sword pierces entering into your liver-heart (Idiom = depths of your soul).”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakabèdhi = kasi takuju ; lose"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pakabèdhi = kasi takuju ; lose = tembus, tusuk kena ; kèj'i = tikam ; adhe-usu = hati-jantung ; usu = 1) jantung 2) botok 3) hela aer 4) Yusuf (Usu)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bèi Hana manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, lula Yesus<bt>Grandmother Hana gives thanks to Father God, because of Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36-37" />Ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, abhu kahèi bhèni heka ca dhèu, ngara na Hana. Umur na, aru nguru èpa tèu kèna. Ngara ama na Fanuel, nèti suku Aser. Na leo-èmu pidhu tèu, ka dhèu èmu na madhe. Hana ne, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Nèngu loe boe sabaj'a dènge puasa ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ho pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua mèda-mèu.<bt>In the Central Worship House (=temple), there was also an old woman, named Hana. Her age was 84 years. Her father, named Fanuel, was from the Aser clan. She was married seven years, then her spouse died leaving her. This Hana, was Father God's spokesperson. She didn't cease praying/worshiping and fasting (loan) in the Central Worship/Prayer House to worship Father God day-night.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="latreuousa: performing religious rites"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">latreuousa: performing religious rites</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Lod'o Simeon padhai lii dènge Yusuf dènge Maria era, hèia Hana mai padètu-dètu. Ka nanene si padhai lii, hèia na koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua. Ka na padhai lii lula-nèti Yesus mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tatae mamai Dhèu Aae dhu Lamatua lii dhu moa tèke neo pua mai, sèna ka patabuli dhèu Isra'el.<bt>When Simeon was still speaking with Yusuf and Maria, Hana came close by. Then she heard them speaking, and she praised (doublet) Father God. And she spoke about Yesus to all people who were eagerly waiting for the King whom the Lord had promised to send, to free the people of Israel. [EXEG: Marshall p.124 points out that Jerusalem is synecdoche for Israel. Also Green.] [NOTE to consultant: Dhao team has diverged from both the Gk and the Kupang here--I didn't catch it on an earlier passes. Need to restore “spoke about Jesus” and delete “from the power of other people”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lai-lula = about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lai-lula = about</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ina-ama dènge Ana ne lèpa asa rae Nasaret<bt>Mother-father and Child return to Nasaret village</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ropa Yusuf dènge Maria tao le madhutu atora nèti baki Musa ètu kota Yerusalem, ka ra lèpa asa rae Nasaret, ètu propensi Galilea.<bt>When Yusuf and Maria had done according to all grandfather Musa's regulations in Yerusalem city, then they returned.home to Galilea province, to their village Nasaret.</bt><note reference="2:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 2:23</note><v n="40" />Ka Yesus asa kapai, asa èra, asa d'èlu-mèu dènge ne'a madha j'ara ae-ae. Aa Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi Yesus kahèi.<bt>And Yesus kept growing up, becoming increasingly strong, increasingly smart, and understood the ways of many things. Father God also showed his good insides (=was gracious) to Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lod'o Yesus ana iiki era, la'e d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>While Yesus is still a boy, goes into the Central Worship House</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Yusuf dènge Maria dhu tema le, tèu mai-tèu mai lasi asa kota Yerusalem ho madhutu kalela Paska ètu nèi.<bt>Yusuf and Maria's custom was each year they travelled to Yerusalem city, to participate in the Paska feast there.</bt><note reference="2:41" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:1-27, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 16:1-8</note><v n="42" />Ca tèka, ropa umur Yesus canguru dua tèu, hèia la'e palere dènge ina-ama Na asa Yerusalem, lasi ra'a kalela Paska sèmi biasa.<bt>One time, when Yesus was twelve years old, then [He] also went together with his mother-father to Yerusalem to participate in that Paska feast like usual.</bt><v n="43-44" />Lod'o èle Paska, Yusuf dènge Maria mulai lèpa lasi asa Nasaret palere-lere dènge dhèu ae dhu lèpa asa Galilea. Te ngaa rèngu re'a boe, na, Yesus ètu Yerusalem era. Ra pangee, na, Nèngu palere dènge mone aanga-angalai Na. Te ngaa ropa d'ai lod'o nihia, Yusuf dènge Maria rèdhi boe Ne. Ka dua ra mulai patangi-tenge kèna. Lasi pakarèi mi a'ari ra, aa mone aanga-angalai ra.<bt>When the Paska days were over, Yusuf and Maria began to return home to Nasaret together with many people who were going.home to Galilea. But they did not know that Yesus was still in Yerusalem. They thought/assumed He was travelling together with His friends. But when it got to be late.afternoon, they could not see him. So they began to go back and forth hunting for Him and asking among their family and friends.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patangi-tenge = cari keliling, cari-cari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">patangi-tenge = cari keliling, cari-cari</Message></Annotation><v n="45" />Lula rage boe Ne, hèia dua ra lèpa hari sa Yerusalem, lasi tenge Ne ètu nèi.<bt>Because they were not finding Him, they returned again to Yerusalem to go look for Him there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />D'ai nèi, ra patangi-tenge Ne toke tèlu lod'o kateme, heka paraga dènge Ne kèna, ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Nèngu dhu madhèdi padhue-padhai dènge mese agama Yahudi sèra.<bt>Arriving there (yonder/remote), they kept hunting for Him for three whole days, only.then finding Him in the Central Worship House. He was sitting mutually questioning-answering (=debating) with the Yahudi religion teachers.</bt><v n="47" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu nanene lii dhaa Na, malaa-maloha, lula Nèngu tare'a-re'a ne'a mèu isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, aa Na ne'a dhaa lii karèi dènge mola.<bt>All the people who were listening to His responses were amazed (doublet), because He truly understood the contents of Father God's Holy Writings (=scripture), and He could answer their questions well/straight.</bt><v n="48" />Rèdhi sèmi èèna ka, ina-ama Na malaa kahèi. Hèia ina Na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yesus! Nga tao ka Èu paj'èra ji'i sèmi ne'e? Ama Mu dènge ja'a patangi-tenge Èu heo d'èlu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing that, His mother-father were also amazed. Then His mother said, “Yesus! Why are You causing trouble/worry for us-exc like.this? Your father and I have been tied up in knots (idiom) going.all.around here-there looking for You!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heo dèlu = setenga mati, (lit."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">heo dèlu = setenga mati, (lit. lingkar-dalam perut)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka ina dènge ama paj'èra iisi tenge Ja'a? Me'a, si? Ja'a dènge urusan ètu Èmu Ama Ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, “Why are mother and father worrying looking for Me? You know, don't you? I have matters.to.deal.with in My Father's House.”</bt><v n="50" />Te ngaa rèngu re'a rare boe sasoa lii Na.<bt>But they did not really understand His meaning/intent.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Hèia aa'i-aa'i ra lèpa asa Nasaret. Ka Yesus madhutu kahèi dad'èi ina dènge ama Na. Ka ina Na tèke aa'i-aa'i se'e ètu d'ara na.<bt>Then they all returned.home to Nasaret. Yesus did according to his mother and father's will/wishes. And his mother stored away all those things in her inside.</bt><v n="52" />Hèia Yesus asa tabha kapai, asa tabha d'èlu-mèu, asa pakarej'e d'ara Ama Lamatua, dènge dhèu rai-haha asa tabha d'èi Ne.<bt>After that, Yesus increasingly became adult/mature, becoming increasingly wise/knowledgable/intelligent, increasingly pleasing the Lord's insides, and humans increasingly liked/loved Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'asu-pareo = saling mengunjungi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pa'asu-pareo = saling mengunjungi</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:52" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 2:26, Lii Hini 3:4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis tuka sarani pakako sasab'a-la'a na<bt>Yohanis the habitual baptizer starts his work (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 3:1-12; Markus 1:1-8; Yohanis 1:19-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1-2" />Taa èèna, Tiberius j'aj'i dhèu aae kapai dhu nèd'u paredha ètu Roma, canguru lèmi tèu kèna. Pontius Pilatus j'aj'i gubernur ètu propensi Yudea. Herodes j'aj'i gubernur ètu propensi Galilea. A'a Herodes ka Pelipus, j'aj'i gubernur ètu propensi Iturea dènge propensi Trakonitis. Aa Lisanias j'aj'i gubernur ètu propensi Abilene.<bt>At that time, Tiberius was the main king who had been holding rule/government in Roma already fifteen years. Pontius Pilatus was governor in Yudea province. Herodes was governor in Galilea province. Herodes' elder.sibling Filipus, was governor in Iturea province and Trakonitis province. And Lisanias was governor in Abilene province. [EXEG: see IVP dict for kinship chart for the two Philips, plus discussion based on Josephus; also more complete under entry for ‘Herod’; TH says “Philip was Herod's older brother, of a different mother”; different Philip than the one in 3:19. See FTN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="a'a-ari --&gt; a'ari (haplology)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">a'a-ari --&gt; a'ari (haplology)</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:1-2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu paredha Roma pake dhèu Yahudi ca dhèu, ngara na <span class="Italic">Yosefus</span>, sèna ka suri j'aj'aj'i Isra'el ètu d'ara taa ne'e. Nèngu suri kahèi lula-nèti dhèu dhu rèd'u paredha dènge a'ari ra. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi te'a, na, Herodes ne, ngara leo nèti <span class="Italic">Herodes Antipas</span>. Ama na, nuka <span class="Italic">Herodes Kapai</span> (Mateos 2:1-22; Lukas 1:5). <span class="Italic">Pelipus</span> ètu ne'e, nuka a'a nèti Herodes Antipas. Ama Pelipus, nuka Herodes Kapai; ina na, ngara na Kleopatra nèti Yerusalem. Pelipus ne, leo dènge Salome, nuka ana Herodias. Ètu pasal tèlu ayat canguru ceo (3:19), abhu <span class="Italic">Pelipus</span> dhu leo. Nèngu ne, ari nèti Herodes Antipas. Ama na, nuka Herodes Kapai èèna kahèi; te ngaa ina na, ngara na Mariamne. Pelipus ne, leo dènge Herodias. Ana ra, ana bhèni, ngara na Salome. Te ngaa a'a na, nuka Herodes Antipas, parame nare dhèu èmu nèngu. (Mateos 14:3; Markus 6:17; Lukas 3:19).<bt>The Roma government used a Yahudi person named <span class="Italic">Yosefus,</span> to write the happenings/history of Isra'el during this (time) period. He also wrote about people who ruled/governed and their families/relatives. That is why we-inc know that the Herodes here had another name, that is <span class="Italic">Herodes Antipas.</span> His father was <span class="Italic">Herodes the Great</span> (Mateos 2:1-22; Lukas 1:5). The <span class="Italic">Pelipus</span> here is Herodes Antipas' older brother. Pelipus' father was also Herodes the Great; his mother was named Kleopatra from Yerusalem. This Pelipus married Salome, that is Herodias' daughter. In verse 3:19, there is a different <span class="Italic">Pelipus.</span> He is Herodes Antipas' younger brother. His father was also Herodes the Great; but his mother was named Mariamne. This Pelipus married Herodias. Their child was a daughter named Salome. But his older brother Herodes Antipas took/snatched away his wife. (Mateos 14:3; Markus 6:17; Lukas 3:19).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Taa èèna kahèi Hanas dènge Kayafas, dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>At that time also, Hanas and Kayafas were the Yahudi *high priests in Yerusalem city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lod'o èèna, Yohanis, ana Sakaria, dhu pea ètu era kaj'èu nèti rae. Ètu era ne'e, Lamatua pangèd'u ne lii.<bt>At that time2, Yohanis, the child of Sakaria's, was staying in a desolate/quiet place far from villages. At that place, the Lord gave instructions to him.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia Yohanis la'e asa d'ara rae dhu dètu dènge loko Yarden, ho peka dènge dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i ele-ho'a ku, aa tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala sèra. Èle èèna, miu sarani uuru ku, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, miu pabe'a le dènge Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>After hearing [them], then Yohanis went to the villages which were near the Yarden river, to tell people there, saying, “You-pl must confess and leave behind all your wrongs (doublet), so that Father God wipes away those wrongs. After that you must get *baptised [imperative], as a sign that you are in a reciprocally good.relationship with God.” [NOTE: Gk in 3:3 is identical with Gk. in Mk 1:4.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Uru-uru sèra, baki Yesaya, dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua, suri tèke le lula-nèti Yohanis ne, peka na,<bt>Long.ago, the Lord's spokesperson grandfather Yesaya wrote beforehand about this Yohanis, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu dhu ètu d'ara mamoo, pa'oo, peka na:<bt>“There is a person in an empty place (=wilderness) who is shouting (a message), saying, [NOTE: Gk in 3:4 is identical to Gk. in Mk 1:3]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i pa'èra, sèna ka tao paie-iie j'ara, ho sèmi mamai Lamatua!<bt>‘All people prepare to make good/fix the way/path, to receive the Lord's coming!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pamola j'ara sèna ka lami soru Ne.<bt>Make straight the path to greet Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Dhènu pamera era kajèlo aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Fill in making flat [SVC] every dip/hole/ravine/gorge.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhènu = isi dgn tana ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dhènu = isi dgn tana ; loe = goa, cave (horizontally oriented) ; lia = tebing, cliff ; kajèlo = tana yg menurun, yg berlubang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Tao pamera-mera ledhe aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Make flat every mountain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèi = gali ; kabhuku ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kèi = gali ; kabhuku = bukit</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tao pamola j'ara dhu koe-kalèko,<bt>Make straight the crooked paths (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">tao pamilu j'ara dhu ako kabhuku.<bt>make smooth the rough paths.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamilu = kasi licin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pamilu = kasi licin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Sèna ka dhèu nèti suku aa'i-aa'i ra<bt>So that people from every ethnic.group</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bisa re'a, na, Ama Lamatua neo pakaj'èu dhèu<bt>can know that Father God wants to save (spare, separate, put distance between) people</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nèti sasala-sasigo ra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>from their wrongs.’”</bt><note reference="3:4-6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 40:3-5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dhèu ae mai nèti mia-mia, manèngi ho Yohanis sarani si. Te ngaa na jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se dhèu kapod'e-kabèli! Miu èci èèna ka mege dhu dènge raco! Mage miu pangee na miu bisa pakaj'èu nèti hahuku Lamatua, sad'i dhoka ele-ho'a di! Aad'o! Nèbhu heka Lamatua huku dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tare'a-re'a ele boe ho'a.<bt>Many people came from all over the place to request Yohanis to baptise them. But he scolded them, saying, “You-pl habitual evil deceivers! You are just like poisonous snakes! Don't think that you can be freed (spared, separated, put distance between) from the Lord's punishment by merely pretending to repent! No! (=you can't) Not much longer (=soon) the Lord will punish all people who do not truly repent. [EXEG: why “from all over the place”? 1) context, vs.3 “into all the region”; 2) Gk here “coming out” in Kupang /kaluar datang/ and other lgs needs a “from where”? 3) support from Mark 1:5 (normal hyperbole).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tees mellousees orgees: the impending wrath."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">tees mellousees orgees: the impending wrath. This is not "bad kine stuff" in the same sense as the same phrase is used later in the same verse, also connected with "orgees".</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:34, 23:33</note><v n="8" />Mage miu pangee na, &lt;Ja'a ne lèke boe huku, lula ja'a ana-èpu baki Abraham.&gt; Abhu ètu mia sèmi èèna? J'aj'i ana-èpu Abraham bisa boe tao miu j'aj'i dhèu mola-mèci. Lamatua bisa tao hadhu se, sèna ka j'aj'i ana-èpu Abraham. Ja'a peka kèna! Pad'elo ètu d'ara mamuri miu, dhu peka na, miu tèke eele le sasala-sasigo miu, aa mai ho madhutu Lamatua.<bt>Don't you-pl think saying, ‘I won't get punishment because I am grandfather Abraham's descendant.’ Where did you get that? (=Where did you come up with that nonsense?) Being a descendant of Abraham cannot make you become clean/holy people. The Lord is capable of making these stones here become Abraham's descendants. I'm telling (=I'm setting you straight here)! Show with your lives that you have left behind your wrongs, and you have come to follow the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metanoia: &quot;like pau all da kine"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">metanoia: "like pau all da kine bad stuff you doing" is more generic than "da bad kine stuff," which is more specific.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 8:33</note><v n="9" />Miu hud'i tao ku j'ara be'a. Ladhe aad'o, na, hahuku Lamatua dhu bia, bèbhe mai lèke miu, nuka sèmi dhèu pake kataka ho patue aj'u nèti amo na. Nuka sèmi èèna ka! Aj'u dènge boe guna, ladhe hua-hela na nèti boe babe'a! De be'a risi patue ne, aa core eele asa d'ara ai la'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>You-pl must do good things. If not, the Lord's heavy punishment will fall on you, like a person who uses an axe to cut down a tree from its roots. Like that! A tree has no use, if it does not have good results/yield! So (consequently) it's better to cut it down, then throw it away into the fire.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kataka = kapak ; patue ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kataka = kapak ; patue = tebang</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 7:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia dhèu ae karèi Yohanis, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, ji'i se tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those people (crowds) asked Yohanis, “If it's like that, what must we-inc do?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èu dènge kodho dua bèla, hia èci sa dhèu dhu dènge boe kodho. Aa ladhe èu dènge nganga'a, bagi hia dhèu dhu dènge boe nganga'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he answered saying, “If you-sg have two shirts, give one to a person who does not have a shirt. If you have food, then give it out to someone who does not have food.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia dhèu roro bea mai manèngi kahèi, sèna ka Yohanis sarani si. Ka ra karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama mese! Ji'i se hud'i tao sèmi ngaa ku?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, the tax collectors also came and asked Yohanis to baptise them. They asked saying, “Father teacher! What must we-exc do?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roro = pungut ; bea"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">roro = pungut ; bea</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 7:29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Miu se d'èi kapod'e-kabèli. De nèti deo ne'e, miu hud'i sab'a ku dènge mola. Baku roro bea risi nèti atora paredha. Hud'i laa kabarai b'ae madhutu atora na.&gt;&gt;<bt>He replied saying, “You-pl like to habitually decieve. So from now you must work straight/honestly. Don't pull more tax than the government's regulation. It's should be that the populace pays tax exactly according to the regulation.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Abhu kahèi sordad'u pèri-pèri ètu sèra. Ra karèi, na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i se hud'i tao ku sèmi ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>There were also several soldiers there. They asked him, “What about us? What must we do?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yohanis b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku parama doi-dhari dhèu madhutu dad'èi miu. Aa baku galaa leli dhèu. Ladhe sèmi mere gaji, miu hud'i manèngi makasi mi Lamatua, aa rasa d'ai le dènge gaji èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yohanis answered, saying, “Don't habitually extort people's money, according to your own desires. And don't accuse people heedlessly. If/when you receive wages, you must be thankful to the Lord and feel satisfied (=feel sufficient) with that wage.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parama = rampas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">parama = rampas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Miu se, hud'i manèngi makasi mi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Miu se, hud'i manèngi makasi mi Lamatua, lula miu se èle hèru abhu babae.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare, dhèu se mulai pagagai aa paka'uu èci dènge èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Tao-tao Yohanis ne, Kristus, dhu Lamatua peka karèi nèti uru ka, neo hia mai èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing his speaking like.that, those people began to scrape around (=investigate, look for clues) and to whisper to each other saying, “Eeh! What if this Yohanis here is Kristus, that one whom the Lord promised to send long ago!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagagai = bakorek ; tao-tao ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pagagai = bakorek ; tao-tao = jang-jang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa Yohanis b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie! Bèli-camèd'a, Dhèu èci mai dhu kapai risi nèti ja'a. Masi ka j'aj'i ana pua-paleha Na, ja'a ne bisa boe sa hèi.<bt>But Yohanis rebuked them, saying, “Listen well! Later there is a Person coming who is greater than me. Even to just be His *slave/servant (person who is habitually ordered about), I'm not able/fitting/appropriate.</bt><note reference="3:16" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru-uru sèra, peka na, &lt;Neo lècu dhari salapa Na hèi, ja'a nia boe.&gt; Sasoa na, Yohanis ne dhèu haha seli, de masi ka j'aj'i dhèu pajuu nèti Lamatua Yesus, lèke boe sa hèi.<bt>The oldest Yunani writings says, ‘Even to open/untie his shoe strings, I am not worthy/able.’ That means that Yohanis is only just a small (=unimportant) person, and even just to become the Lord Yesus' slave/servant, he is not worthy.</bt></note>Ja'a ne sarani miu dhoka pake èi di, te ngaa bèli-camèd'a Na tao risi eele nèti ja'a, te Na papènu d'ara miu dènge Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Aa Na pamèu d'ara miu nuka sèmi dhèu pake ai ho tunu maruru.<bt>I only *baptize you with/using water, but later He will do more than me, cuz (elaboration) He will make your(pl) insides full with *Lord's *Holy Spirit (=clean, free from impurities, undefiled, holy). And He will make your insides clean, like a person uses fire to burn off crud/rubbish/filth. [EXEG: Gk almost identical to Mk. 1:7-8; Mk has ‘stoop’, Lk adds ‘with fire’ at end. For wind and fire vs. spirit and fire, and fire as judgment leading into vs. 17, see Marshall pp 145-148; wide agreement that ‘fire’ here is not clear, also Trans. Notes p.82. PRINCIPLE: Where leaving it open yields multiple legitimate interpretations, we want to do that. But where it yields zero meaning, we want to give the most likely interpretation in the context--here vs. 17 (not Acts 2). Fire imagery changed to burning rubbish (to resonate with context of vs. 17 and better match 12:49.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èèna na, Na pamèu dara miu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Èèna na, Na pamèu dara miu sèmi tuka hualaa libu hualaa ètu dara ai karoo, ho core eele kaj'alu na, sèna ka abhu isi adhu.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tunu = heat (gold) ; libu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tunu = heat (gold) ; libu = kasi cair emas ; ai karoo = api panas sekali ; isi adhu = murni ; lècu = undo, buka</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Na huku dhèu dhu ad'u-ue sasala, tao si cakaraa dhèu sab'a oka, dhu patiri are ho ngèlu tiu eele kètu na. Èle ku, heka soli are dhu mèu asa d'ara soka, aa kètu dènge kaj'alu are sèra, tunu pakèpu si. Nuka sèmi èèna kahèi, bèli-camèd'a Kristus huku dhèu dhu ad'u-ue sasala, dènge j'ara pèci si asa d'ara ai dhu heo robhe-robhe dhu madhe nèdhi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>He will punish people who do wrongs, like a farmer who uses wind to separate away the impurities from the padi. Then he stores the clean padi in a grain bin, and burns up the impurities. Like that also, Kristus will punish people who do wrongs, and throw them away into the fire which never ends/dies. [EXEG: Explication follows HCE &amp; KM].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patiri = drop grain from above"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">patiri = drop grain from above so wind takes away the lighter stuff, winnow ; kètu (2) = are yg tidak ada isi, biji padi yang kosong ; soli = isi masuk ; soka = lumbung ; pakèpu = bekin angus ; hake = pukul</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="However &quot;fire&quot; is handled, it has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">However "fire" is handled, it has to be clear that it's forever.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\HK00097C.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu pake lai ngèlu ho tiu eele kaj'alu nèti are-gandum<bt>A person uses the wind to blow away the impurities from the grain-wheat</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dènge j'ara ne'e Yohanis pasanèd'e dhèu nèti rupa-rupa madha j'ara, aa lole dènge ra Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua.<bt>In that way, Yohanis reminded/warned people of all sorts of things, and told them the Lord's Good News.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Taa èèna, Yohanis padhai lii pahuni heka, j'ara-j'ara dhu Herodes ad'u-ue. Lii langu Herodes nuka sèmi ne'e ka: Herodes ne, gubernur ètu propensi Galilea. Sasala na udhu sèmi kadhèna hèru hadhu sa. Sasala na èci ka, parame nare Herodias, dhèu èmu ari na, masi ka ari na mamuri era, dhu dhae pa'ia mèka. J'ara mamuri Herodes sèmi ne'e, ka Yohanis kai dènge madha na, toke Herodes nasa dènge ne. Nèti èèna ka, Herodes kèpe ne, hèia pamaso asa d'ara èmu bèdho.<bt>At that time, Yohanis also started to speak openly about Herodes' deeds. The problem/dispute was like.this: this Herodes, was governor of Galilea province. His wrongs were piled up like a stack of firewood in October (idiom: in preparation for rendering sap to sugar). For example he had snatched away his younger.sibling's wife, Herodias, even though his younger.sibling was still alive, and had not yet divorced. That way of living of Herodes', Yohanis rebuked him openly, to.the.point.that Herodes was angry with him. Because of that, Herodes caught/arrested him, and put him in jail. [NOTE: Different Philip than in 3:1. See FTN at 3:1; younger brother from same father, different mother.]</bt><note reference="3:19-20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Baca catatan kaki ètu Lukas 3:1-2. Ladhe kahèi ètu Mateos 14:3-4; Markus 6:17-18.<bt>Read the footnote at Lukas 3:1-2. See also Mateos 14:3-4; Markus 6:17-18.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis sarani Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yohanis baptizes the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 3:13-17; Markus 1:9-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Uru èèna, lod'o dhu ra kèpe mèka Yohanis ne, nèngu sarani dhèu ae le. Aa na sarani Yesus kahèi. Sarani èle, ka Yesus sabaj'a, kabèdhi laa, liru bhoka eele.<bt>Previously, when they still had not yet captured/arrested Yohanis (=before they had...), he was baptising many people. And he also baptised Yesus. After (he finished) baptising, Yesus prayed, and suddenly the sky opened up.</bt><v n="22" />Hèia Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci puru mai sa Yesus. Roh ne rupa na sèmi koro j'aha sa. Hèia lii nèti dedha-liru peka na,<bt>Next the Lord's Holy Spirit came down to Him. That Spirit's form/shape was like a dove/pidgeon. And there was a voice from the sky, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Èu ne, Ana pasue Ja'a.<bt>“You-sg here, [are] My dear Child.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Èu ne, loe boe pakarej'e d'ara Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>You always please My insides.” [NOTE: Gk in Lk and Mk identical in quote].</bt><note reference="3:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:2, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7, Yesaya 42:1, Mateos 3:17, Markus 1:11, Lukas 9:35</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bèi-baki Lamatua Yesus madhutu nèti bèi-baki Yusuf<bt>The Lord Yesus' ancestors, following Yusuf's ancestors</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 1:1-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lod'o Yesus mulai lole dènge dhèu j'ara mamuri Lamatua, umur Na pe d'ai tèlu nguru tèu sa. Dhèu tadhe Yesus ne, Ana nèti Yusuf. Bèi-baki Yusuf sèmi ne'e:<bt>When Yesus began to tell people about the Lord's life way, His age was approximately thirty years. People knew Yesus as Yusuf's Child. Yusuf's ancestors, [are] like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yusuf, ama na, Eli.<bt>Yusuf's father, [was] Eli.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="24" />Eli, ama na, Matat.<bt>Eli's father, Matat.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Matat, ama na, Lewi.<bt>Matat's father, Lewi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lewi, ama na Melki.<bt>Lewi's father, Melki.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Melki, ama na, Yanai.<bt>Melki's father, Yanai.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yanai, ama na, Yusuf.<bt>Yanai's father, Yusuf.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="25" />Yusuf, ama na, Matatias.<bt>Yusuf's father, Matatias.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Matatias, ama na, Amos.<bt>Matatias' father, Amos.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Amos, ama na, Nahum.<bt>Amos' father, Nahum.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nahum, ama na, Hesli.<bt>Nahum's father, Hesli.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hesli, ama na, Nagai.<bt>Hesli's father, Nagai.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="26" />Nagai, ama na, Maat.<bt>Nagai's father, Maat.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Maat, ama na, Matatias.<bt>Maat's father, Matatias.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Matatias, ama na, Semein.<bt>Matatias' father, Semein.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Semein, ama na, Yosek.<bt>Semein's father, Yosek.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yosek, ama na, Yoda.<bt>Yosek's father, Yoda.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="27" />Yoda, ama na, Yohanan.<bt>Yoda's father, Yohanan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yohanan, ama na, Resa.<bt>Yohanan's father, Resa.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Resa, ama na, Serubabel.<bt>Resa's father, Serubabel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Serubabel, ama na, Sealtiel.<bt>Serubabel's father, Sealtiel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sealtiel, ama na, Neri.<bt>Sealtiel's father, Neri.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="28" />Neri, ama na, Melki.<bt>Neri's father, Melki.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Melki, ama na, Adi.<bt>Melki's father, Adi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Adi, ama na, Kosam.<bt>Adi's father, Kosam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kosam, ama na, Elmadam.<bt>Kosam's father, Elmadam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Elmadam, ama na, Er.<bt>Elmadam's father, Er.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="29" />Er, ama na, Yosua.<bt>Er's father, Yosua.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yosua, ama na, Elieser.<bt>Yosua's father, Elieser.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Elieser, ama na, Yorim.<bt>Elieser's father, Yorim.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yorim, ama na, Matat.<bt>Yorim's father, Matat.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Matat, ama na, Lewi.<bt>Matat's father, Lewi.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="30" />Lewi, ama na, Simeon.<bt>Lewi's father, Simeon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Simeon, ama na, Yahuda.<bt>Simeon's father, Yahuda.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yahuda, ama na, Yusuf.<bt>Yahuda's father, Yusuf.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yusuf, ama na, Yonam.<bt>Yusuf's father, Yonam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yonam, ama na, Elyakim.<bt>Yonam's father, Elyakim.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="31" />Elyakim, ama na, Melea.<bt>Elyakim's father, Melea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Melea, ama na, Mena.<bt>Melea's father, Mena.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mena, ama na, Matata.<bt>Mena's father, Matata.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Matata, ama na, Natan.<bt>Matata's father, Natan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Natan, ama na, Daud.<bt>Natan's father, Daud.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="32" />Daud, ama na, Isai.<bt>Daud's father, Isai.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Isai, ama na, Obet.<bt>Isai's father, Obet.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Obet, ama na, Boas.<bt>Obet's father, Boas.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Boas, ama na, Salmon.<bt>Boas' father, Salmon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Salmon, ama na, Nahason.<bt>Salmon's father, Nahason.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="33" />Nahason, ama na, Aminadab.<bt>Nahason's father, Aminadab.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aminadab, ama na, Admin.<bt>Aminadab's father, Admin.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Admin, ama na, Arni.<bt>Admin's father, Arni.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Arni, ama na, Hesron.<bt>Arni's father, Hesron.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Hesron, ama na, Peres.<bt>Hesron's father, Peres.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Peres, ama na, Yahuda.<bt>Peres' father, Yahuda.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="34" />Yahuda, ama na, Yakob.<bt>Yahuda's father, Yakob.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakob, ama na, Isak.<bt>Yakob's father, Isak.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Isak, ama na, Abraham.<bt>Isak's father, Abraham.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abraham, ama na, Tera.<bt>Abraham's father, Tera.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tera, ama na, Nahor.<bt>Tera's father, Nahor.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="35" />Nahor, ama na, Seruk.<bt>Nahor's father, Seruk.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Seruk, ama na, Rehu.<bt>Seruk's father, Rehu.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Rehu, ama na, Pelek.<bt>Rehu's father, Pelek.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pelek, ama na, Eber.<bt>Pelek's father, Eber.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Eber, ama na, Sela.<bt>Eber's father, Sela.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="36" />Sela, ama na, Kenan.<bt>Sela's father, Kenan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Kenan, ama na, Arpaksad.<bt>Kenan's father, Arpaksad.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Arpaksad, ama na, Sem.<bt>Arpaksad's father, Sem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sem, ama na, Noh.<bt>Sem's father, Noh.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Noh, ama na, Lamek.<bt>Noh's father, Lamek.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="37" />Lamek, ama na, Metusalak.<bt>Lamek's father, Metusalak.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Metusalak, ama na, Henok.<bt>Metusalak's father, Henok.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Henok, ama na, Yared.<bt>Henok's father, Yared.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yared, ama na, Mahalalel.<bt>Yared's father, Mahalalel.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mahalalel, ama na, Kenan.<bt>Mahalalel's father, Kenan.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="38" />Kenan, ama na, Enos.<bt>Kenan's father, Enos.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Enos, ama na, Set.<bt>Enos' father, Set.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Set, ama na, Adam.<bt>Set's father, Adam.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Adam ne'e ka, pa'ue-ai Ama Lamatua.<bt>That Adam, [was] Father God's created child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'ue-ai = buatan tangan, hasil karja"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pa'ue-ai = buatan tangan, hasil karja</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Pa'ue-ai artinya Allah menciptakan dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Diperhatikan: Pa'ue-ai artinya Allah menciptakan dari tangan Nya sendiri.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae nidhu sèku Lamatua Yesus<bt>The *evil spirits' king tempts/tests character of the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 4:1-11; Markus 1:12-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yohanis sarani nare Yesus, hèia Yesus la'e, tèke eele loko Yarden. Roh Ama Lamatua bera-bera dènge Ne, ka pakako Ne asa d'ara mamoo èci.<bt>When Yohanis had finished baptising Yesus, then Yesus went leaving behind Yarden river. The Lord's Spirit was together with Him, and brought Him to a desolate/lonely place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jajuku = tolak, dorong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">jajuku = tolak, dorong</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ka Yesus pea ètu èèna toke èpa nguru lod'o. Ètu era ne'e, na'a-ninu boe ngaa-ngaa, ka Na manganga titu kèna. Aa dhèu aae nidhu mai sèku Ne.<bt>And Yesus stayed there for forty days. In that place He did not eat anything, and He became/was very hungry. Then, the king of the evil spirits came and tempted/test character of Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Na peka dènge Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Èu ne tare'a Ana Ama Lamatua, Èu dènge koasa. De tao hadhu se j'aj'i roti, ho mu'a si.&gt;&gt;<bt>He spoke to Yesus, saying, “If You-sg truly are the Child of Father God, You have power/authority. So (consequently), make these rocks to become bread, so that You can eat them.” [NOTE: Gk for bread is sg, but KM is plural for fitting worldview, from their kinds of bread (like small rolls in plastic on a ferry) plus context of hungry person--people buy several per individual.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu hari! Me'a boe, do? Dhu suri tèke le ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>But Yesus responded saying, “Don't you wish! (=idiom refusing a suggestion) Don't you know? It's already written in the *Scriptures (God's Writings), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mamuri dhèu rai-haha, mesa boe dhoka nèti nganga'a-nganginu di!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>‘The life of humans, is not just only from food-drink (doublet)!’”</bt><note reference="4:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 8:3, Mateos 4:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae nidhu nèti hari Yesus asa era èci dhu dedha aae, hèia na paj'uj'u dènge Yesus a'èra dènge koasa paredha aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Hèia na pamako Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;A'èra dènge koasa paredha aa'i-aa'i sèra, ètu d'ara kacui-aai ja'a. De ja'a dènge hak ho pangèd'u mi cee èèna ka, sad'i ja'a ko'o.<bt>After that, the evil.spirits king brought Him to a very tall/high place, and showed Him the strength/incredibleness/glory and power/authority of all the governments on earth. Then he coaxed Yesus, saying, “All that strength/incredibleness/glory and power/authority to govern is in my hands. So (consequently), I have the right/authority to give it/hand it over to whomever I like.</bt><v n="7" />Aa'i-aa'i se, ja'a neo hia mi Èu. Te ngaa sad'i Èu tao ku ca j'ara, heka ja'a hia Èu kèna. Mud'a iiki-iiki! Èu pahaha iisi mi ja'a! Dhoka èèna di.&gt;&gt;<bt>I'm willing to give it all to You. But only as long as You do one thing first, only.then I will give [it]. It's easy! You just worship me (do obeiscence to me). Merely that!"</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ètu mia j'ara na sèmi èèna? Te ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, dhu suri, na,<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, “Where did you get that from? Cuz (elaboration) in the *Scriptures it is written saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èu dhoka pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua di.<bt>‘You must worship (do obeiscence) only Father God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa èu sogo-tagu dhoka mi Nèngu di.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>And you-sg must serve (doublet) only/just Him.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tangare = perhatikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tangare = perhatikan</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle ka, dhèu aae nidhu nèti hari Yesus asa kota Yerusalem. D'ai era ne'e, na paca'e Yesus asa era dhu dedha risi ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ladhe tare'a-re'a Èu ne Ana Ama Lamatua, na, ridhu asa haha nèi!<bt>After that, the king of the evil.spirits brought Yesus to Yerusalem city. There, he brought Yesus up to the highest place of the Central Worship House. Then he said, “If You truly are Father God's Child, then You throw Yourself down there!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kolo bhèngu = bubungan ; ridhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kolo bhèngu = bubungan ; ridhu = terjun</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Te dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) it is written in the Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Pe Ama Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na nèti sorga,<bt>‘Father God will order His underling/s from heaven,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho mai j'aga Èu.<bt>to come watch.over/guard You.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="11" />Èèna na ra sibhe Èu,<bt>later they will come collect/catch You,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sibhe ~ sibha = tada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">sibhe ~ sibha = tada</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka haga Èu goi lèke boe hadhu sa hèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>so that Your foot does not even touch the rock/s a tiny.bit.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goi = toki ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">goi = toki ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:10-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 91:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala lii nidhu ne, &lt;&lt;Èu baku karihu kahadhu dènge Ja'a ne. Lula dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, na,<bt>But Yesus responded to what the evil spirit said, “Don't play dishonestly with Me. Because it is written in the Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Baku sèku Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>‘Don't try/tempt/test Father God!’”</bt><note reference="4:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dhèu aae nidhu ne tenge j'ara rupa-rupa ho sèku Yesus, te ngaa tao nare boe. Ka la'e tèke eele Yesus, na mate hari lod'o dhu be'a.<bt>The evil.spirits king tried to find all.sorts.of ways to tempt/test character of Yesus, but could not succeed. So he went leaving behind Yesus, and waited for a good time (another opportunity).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus la'e Galilea ho lole Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua<bt>The Lord Yesus goes to Galilea to tell the Lord's Good News</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 4:12-17; Markus 1:14-15)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus lèpa hari asa propensi Galilea, te Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci hia Ne koasa. Nèbhu boe ka dhèu-dhèu ètu d'ara rai èèna, mulai tadhe kolongara Na.<bt>After that, then Yesus returned again to Galilea province, cuz (elaboration) the Lord's Holy Spirit gave power to Him. Not long, then people in that area began to recognize/know His reputation.</bt><v n="15" />Na aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi ètu mia-mia. Ka dhèu koa-kio Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus ne dhu ele madha, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>He taught (doublet) in the Yahudi people's worship houses all.over.the.place. And the people praised (doublet) Him, saying, “That Yesus, is an amazing Person, nga!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ro'o boe sèmi rare Lamatua Yesus ètu Nasaret<bt>People do not want to receive/accept the Lord Yesus in Nasaret</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:53-58; Markus 6:1-6)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ca tèka, Yesus mai asa rae Na Nasaret. Lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi, dhu ra pangare na &lt;sabat&gt;, hèia la'e asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a sèmi dhu tema Na tao. Ka Na kèd'i titu ho neo baca nèti Sasuri Ama Lamatua.<bt>One time, Yesus came to His village Nasaret. On the Yahudi people's worship day, which they call ‘sabat’, He went into the worship house, as was His custom/norm. Then He stood up to read from the Scriptures.</bt><v n="17" />Ka ra j'ole hia Ne sasuri nèti baki Yesaya. Hèia Na bhoke tenge ayat, ka Na baca, peka na,<bt>And they extended to Him grandfather Yesaya's writing. Then He opened [it], looked for verse/passage, and He read, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="propheetees?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">propheetees?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00244C.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Dhèu baca Sasuri Ama Lamatua ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi<bt>A person reads the Scriptures in a Yahudi worship house</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />&lt;&lt;Koasa Roh Ama Lamatua abhu ètu Ja'a.<bt>“Father God's Spirit's power/authority is at/on Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, Na paj'uj'u Ja'a,<bt>that.is.why He appoints/chooses/designates Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua mi dhèu-dhèu dhu unu aad'o.<bt>to tell (doublet) the God's Good News to poor people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu pua le Ja'a mai,<bt>He has sent/commissioned Me,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ekhrisen me: anointed me = gave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">ekhrisen me: anointed me = gave me the commission</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho lole, na,<bt>to tell saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu ana bèdho, èèna na patalala si;<bt>those who are prisoners, will be freed;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu bèdhu, èèna na bisa rèdhi hari;<bt>those who are blind, will see again;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu lèke ènyi nèti dhèu, èèna na patabuli eele.<bt>those who are afflicted with oppression, will be freed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèke kabhie = tindas ; samaa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lèke kabhie = tindas ; samaa = ringan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="19" />Te limuri ne d'ai le lod'o Lamatua,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) now, the Lord's time/day has arrived,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka pala mamuri mi dhèu unu Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>to save (distribute life/salvation upon) His people.”</bt><note reference="4:18-19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat dua ra ètu ne'e madhutu sasuri lii Yunani asli. Alkitab lii Idhonesia (TB) tao nomer 19 ètu era dhu lèke boe.</note><note reference="4:18-19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 61:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Baca nare sasuri ne, ka Yesus lulu hari, hèia Na j'ole asa ama dhu nèd'u kasasi, ka Na madhèdi. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a èèna ladhe patae Ne.<bt>After finishing reading that writing, then Yesus rolled it up again and hand.over to the leader of the religious.service, then He sat.down. All the people who were in that worship house stared at Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasasi = household service ; patae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kasasi = household service ; patae = kaloo = lihat tanpa lia ke tampa laen, nantang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hypeeretees: assistant, attendant"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hypeeretees: assistant, attendant</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Hèia Na peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Dhu miu tadèngi nèti Sasuri Ama Lamatua deo na, ne'e ne, j'aj'i le!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He told them, saying, “What you-pl just heard from the Scriptures, has happened now!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka dhèu sèra mulai padhai lii padedha Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Ngaa dhu Na padhai lii deo na, be'a titu kèna! Te ngaa Nèngu ne Ana Yusuf, si? Tasamia ka Na bisa sèmi ne'e ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then all the people who were there began to speak raising.up (=praising) Yesus, saying, “Waa! What He said just then, was very good! But He's Usu's Child, isn't.he? How can it be like.this?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia Yesus lole dènge si, &lt;&lt;Tatu miu tadèngi le lii dhu peka na, &lt;Wee, dote! Puri uuru ku ngi'u èu!&gt; Miu neo pake lii èèna, ho kabèli hari sa Ja'a, peka na, &lt;Nga tao ka Èu tao boe tadha malaa èci hia ji'i ètu ne'e, sèmi dhu Èu tao le ètu kota Kapernaum nèi?&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “Surely you all know there is a saying that says, ‘Wee, doctor! Heal yourself first!’ You want to use that saying to retort to Me, saying, ‘Why don't You do/make an amazing sign for us-exc here, like You did in Kapernaum city over there (remote)?’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèli = omong balik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kabèli = omong balik</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Mamola na sèmi ne'e: dhèu ro'o boe sèmi rare dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua nèti d'ara rae unu na.<bt>The truth is like.this: people do not want to accept the Lord's spokesperson in his own village.</bt><note reference="4:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 6:4; Yohanis 4:44</note><v n="25-26" />Tare conto nuka sèmi baki Elia, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Ca tèka, èj'i mai boe tèlu tèu catenga. Taa èèna, abhu bhèni balu ae ètu Isra'el. Te ngaa Lamatua hia boe Elia ho soru-bara si ètu Isra'el sèra. Lamatua dhoka pua la'e asa ca dhèu bhèni balu ètu rae Sarfat, dhu dètu dènge kota Sidon. Masi ka bhèni ne dhèu Yahudi boe, te ngaa na parcaya koasa Ama Lamatua.<bt>Take an example from the Lord's spokesperson, grandfather Elia. One time, rain did not come for three and a half years. At that time, there were many widows in Israel. But the Lord did not send/have Elia to help them in Israel. The Lord only sent him to one widow in Sarfat village near Sidon city. Even though that woman was not a Yahudi person, nevertheless she believed in Father God's power.</bt><note reference="4:25-26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 17:1, 8-16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Tare hari conto leo nèti Elisa, dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Taa èèna, dhèu Yahudi ae dhu lèke èi papèd'a kusta ètu Isra'el. Te ngaa Lamatua pa'èle boe si nèti papèd'a ra. Ama Lamatua dhoka pua Elisa la'e puri-pa'èle dhèu kusta èci, ngara na Naaman, masi ka nèngu ne dhèu Siria, dhèu Yahudi boe. Te ngaa na parcaya koasa Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Take another example from the Lord's spokesperson Elisa. At that time, there were many Yahudi people who had leprosy illness in Isra'el. But the Lord did not heal them from their disease. God only ordered Elisa to go heal one leprosy person, named Naaman. Even though he was a Siria person, not a Yahudi person. Nevertheless he believed in Father God's power.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: There were also many lepers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">NRSV: There were also many lepers in Israel in the time of the prophet Elisha, and none of them was cleansed except Naaman the Syrian."</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae sèra 5:1-14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa ra tadèngi lii padhai lii Yesus ne, hèia aa'i-aa'i ra nasa titu kèna dènge Ne.<bt>When they heard Yesus' speaking like.that, then they all got furious with Him.</bt><v n="29" />Ka ra kèd'i aa'i-aa'i, ra babège eele Ne nèti d'ara èmu sabaj'a èèna. Hèia ra nuni rèti Ne asa karasa rae, ho neo tule Ne nèti dedha tèbhi ètu èèna, asa haha la'e.<bt>And they all got up and threw Him out (evicted) of that worship house. Then they dragged brought Him to the edge of the village, wanting to shove him off into a ravine there. [EXEG: “hill on which the city was built” -- explicit to implicit. Skews information load and focus. Carried by implications of ‘ravine’.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèbhi = tebing ; karasa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tèbhi = tebing ; karasa = right at the edge (of town)</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Te ngaa Na kako asa li'u la'e re talora aae rèngu, ka tèke eele si ètu era èèna.<bt>But He walked out via/through the midst of those many people, then left them there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus babège eele nidhu nèti dhèu èci<bt>The Lord Yesus evicts an evil.spirit from a person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:21-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus puru la'e asa kota Kapernaum ètu sebhe dano Galilea. D'ai lod'o-lod'o sabaj'a, Na aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i.<bt>After that, Yesus went.down to Kapernaum city on Galilea lake's edge. Every worship day He taught people in the worship house.</bt><v n="32" />Dhèu sèra malaa ladhe ra nanene lii padhai Na, te ne'a mèu isi lii holo-nori sèra.<bt>People were amazed hearing His talking, cuz (elaboration) He truly knew/understood the contents of that teaching. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. words for 'amazed' and 'authority' same as in Mk.1:22.]</bt><note reference="4:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 7:28-29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ca tèka, ropa Yesus aj'a-nori ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i, abhu ca dhèu dhu nidhu tao, na pa'oo-parodha, peka na,<bt>One time, when Yesus was teaching in the worship house, there was a person who was afflicted by an evil.spirit who began to shout loudly, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akathartos: unclean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">akathartos: unclean</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />&lt;&lt;Ee! Yesus, Dhèu Nasaret! Èu neo tao ngaa mi ji'i? Èu mai sèna ka palaho ji'i, do? Ji'i se tadhe Èu. Èu ne, Dhèu Mola, dhu uru èèna Ama Lamatua pajaji tèke ho hia mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>“Ee! Yesus, the Nasaret Person! What are You-sg going to do with/to us-exc! You've come to destroy us-exc, right? We-exc know/recognise You. You here are that Clean/Holy Person whom long.ago God promised to send.” [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk is identical with Mk. 1:24.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Te ngaa Yesus jèke ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Rèno laa! Hutu hèb'a èu na! Kalua ka nèti dhèu ne'e!&gt;&gt; Cag'ag'a laa, nidhu ded'e kalabhe dhèu ne asa rai, ètu talora aae dhèu sèra. Ropa pabèbhe nare, hèia nidhu ne kalua tèke eele aa papèd'a boe isi dhèu ne hèi.<bt>But Yesus rebuked him, saying, “Quiet! Shut your mouth! Come out of that person!” Unexpectedly/suddenly, the evil.spirit lifted up threw down that person on the floor/ground in the midst of the people. After throwing him down, then that evil.spirit come out leaving that person, and did not hurt him either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèno = diam (bicara dgn kasar;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">rèno = diam (bicara dgn kasar; papèda boe isi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Rèno artinya: Diam! Bicara dengan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Diperhatikan: Rèno artinya: Diam! Bicara dengan kata kasar.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i malaa-maloha, ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Lii padhai Dhèu ne'e, dènge koasa kapai bia! Toke nidhu madhutu paredha Na kahèi, ka kalua nèti dhèu!&gt;&gt;<bt>All the people were open-mouthed (=surprised), saying, “Ira, ee! [+amazement] This Person's speaking has great power! To.the.point.that evil.spirits also follow His command to come out of people!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epitassei: present tense, generic, not referring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">epitassei: present tense, generic, not referring to just the man in front of them akathartoi: unclean<span class="Italic">(36)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Hèia lii lolo lula-nèti Yesus pale-lème rai èèna aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then story/stories about Yesus began to spread throughout that whole region.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'èle papèd'a ina dhèu èmu Petrus, dènge papèd'a dhèu-dhèu leo<bt>The Lord Yesus heals Petrus' mother-in-law, and many other sick people</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu ae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu ae</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:14-17; Markus 1:29-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Lod'o rèngu kalua nèti èmu sabaj'a, Yesus la'e asa èmu dhèu èci, ngara na Simon.<bt>When they came out of that worship house, Yesus went to a person's house. His name was Simon.</bt><note reference="4:38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Simon ne, ngara leo na, Petrus.<bt>Simon is Petrus' other name.</bt></note>Lod'o èèna, teto na dhu pèd'a maringi-sagoro isi pana bia. Hèia ra manèngi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Puri-pa'èle ku bhèni heka ne, laa!&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time his FZ/mother-in-law was sick with fever, so her body was very hot. Then they asked Yesus, saying, “Father! Please heal the elder.lady [polite command]!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teto = tante, mama mantu, FZ,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">teto = tante, mama mantu, FZ,</Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Ka Yesus la'e titu ètu sebhe koi, ka puri papèd'a bhèni heka ne. Cag'ag'a laa, èi papèd'a na ele dènge ka. Hèia na kèd'i la'e lalau nganga'a hia si ra'a-rinu.<bt>So Yesus went to stand a the edge of the bed, then healed that disease from the elder.lady. Suddenly, her sickness disappeared immediately. And then she got up and went to prepare food-drink for them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ètu d'ara lod'o nihia èèna kahèi, ropa lod'o oe cèna, dhèu lere rèti dhèu pèd'a ae-ae mai asa Yesus. Èi papèd'a ra rupa-rupa. Hèia Na bane ai mi dhèu pèd'a se'e, ka aa'i-aa'i ra èle nèti papèd'a-tarègu ra.<bt>In the late afternoon/evening, when the sun was about to drown, people brought a great many sick people to Yesus. Their illness were all.sorts. Then He put his hand/s on the sick people, and healed them all of their various diseases (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bane ai = placed hands (touch)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">bane ai = placed hands (touch)</Message></Annotation><v n="41" />Nèti dhèu pèd'a se abhu kahèi dhu nidhu tao. Hèia Yesus paredha nidhu se, sèna ka kalua nèti dhèu sèra. Ra rai kalua dènge lii taraa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, Ana Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt; Te nidhu se re'a, na, Nèngu ne Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji karèi nèti uru ka, ho hia mai. Nèti èèna ka, Yesus kai si sèna ka bisa boe ra padhai ca hèb'a sa, lula-nèti Nèngu.<bt>Among those sick people, there were several who were afflicted by evil.spirit/s. Then Yesus ordered those evil.spirits to come out of people. They came.out yelling, saying, “You here, are Father God's Child!” Cuz (elaboration) those evil.spirits knew that He was Kristus, whom Father God had promised long.ago to send. Because of that, Yesus warned them that they were not allowed to speak even one word about Himself.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii taraa = batarea ; lii"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lii taraa = batarea ; lii pakèce = batarea secara histeris</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus la'e lole Lii Lolo Be'a ètu èmu-èmu sabaj'a<bt>The Lord Yesus goes to tell Good News in the worship houses</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 1:35-39)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Asa bèli d'ara oe mèu sa, Yesus kèd'i, ka la'e asa era dhu kaliu èci ètu li'u kota. Hèia dhèu tenge Ne asa mia-mia. Ropa paraga dènge Ne, ka ra pamako Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama pea ka dènge ji'i laa! Lamu iia ka asa era leo!&gt;&gt;<bt>The next day almost light, Yesus got up and went to a place outside the city. People looked for Him all.over.the.place. When they found him, then they nagged/persisted Him, saying, “Father just stay with us! It's not neccessary (=polite don't) to go to another place!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Te ngaa Na dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a hud'i laku asa rae-rae leo, ho peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a nèti paredha Ama Lamatua. Te Ama Lamatua pua Ja'a mai ne, sèna ka pakako sasab'a èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But he replied, saying, “I also must to the other villages, to go tell Good News about Father God's rule/governing. Cuz (elaboration) Father God has sent Me here to carry out that task/responsibility.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Hèia Na kako nèti rae èci asa rae leo, ho aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara èmu-èmu sabaj'a ètu propensi Yudea.<bt>The He travelled from one village to the next village to teach people in the worship houses in Yudea province.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèngu pèku, ka abhu i'a ae-ae<bt>They fish.with.net obtaining many-many fish</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 4:18-22; Markus 1:16-20)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, Yesus aj'a dhèu ètu sebhe dano Galilea.<bt>One time, Yesus taught people at the edge of Galilea lake.</bt><note reference="5:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani peka na, &lt;ètu sebhe dano Genesaret.&gt; Ngara leo nèti dano Genesaret, nuka dano Galilea.<bt>The Yunani language Bible says ‘at the edge of lake Genesaret’. Lake Genesaret's other name is lake Galilea.</bt></note>Dhèu ae mai sèna ka neo nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua. Rèngu mai toke ra kalibhu rare Yesus.<bt>Many people came to hear Father God's Words/Teachings/ Advice/Sayings. To.the.point.that they were pressing crowding around Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalibhu rare = berdesakan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kalibhu rare = berdesakan</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Padètu dènge era èèna, abhu dhèu dhu pamèu pèku ra ètu dedha nebhe. Ka Yesus nèdhi koha dua bua dhu panahu ètu era èèna.<bt>Nearby that place, there were people who were cleaning their fishnet/s on the shore. And Yesus saw two empty boats that were bow.touching.land/anchored there.</bt><v n="3" />Cue nèti koha se, unu Simon. Èle ka, Yesus ca'e asa dedha koha ne, ka Na manèngi sèna ka Simon tob'e asa era marèma ciki. Hèia Na madhèdi ho aj'a dhèu ae sèra.<bt>One of those boats, was Simon's. So Yesus got into that boat, and asked Simon to push out into the deep a bit. Then2 He sat to teach those many people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tob'e = pole &amp; push"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tob'e = pole &amp; push</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:1-3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 13:1-2, Markus 3:9-10, 4:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Aj'a nare, hèia Na padhai lii dènge Simon, peka na, &lt;&lt;Simon! Padedha hari ku asa d'ara marèma, ho core pèku la'a. Te èèna na miu abhu i'a ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>After teaching, then He spoke with Simon, saying, “Simon! Go to the place that is a bit deeper to throw the net out there. Cuz (elaboration) there you-pl will get many fish.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kao = dayung ; padedha hari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kao = dayung ; padedha hari = further toward deep @@ CULTURAL DEIXIS</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00212C.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu pili rare i'a nèti d'ara pèku<bt>Fishermen select out/retrieve fish from the net</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Simon dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te ngaa, Ama. Ji'i sab'a d'ai madhe d'ara camèd'a kateme kèna, te abhu boe ci'u sa hèi! Te ngaa lula Ama ku peka le sèmi èèna, ja'a madhutu! Ja'a papuru sèku.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Simon responded, saying, “But Father. We-exc have worked nearly dead (idiom) for an entire night, but we didn't get even a single one! But because Father (=you) has said that, I'll go along with it/obey! I'll just try to put [it] down.”</bt><note reference="5:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 21:3</note><v n="6" />Hèia ra papuru pèku. Ropa ra neo ère paca'e hari, re'a boe na pèku ne dhu pènu dènge i'a, ka mulai mae.<bt>Then they put down the net. When they wanted to pull it back up, wouldn't you know that net was already full of fish, and began to tear.</bt><note reference="5:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 21:6</note><v n="7" />Hèia Simon rodhe angalai na ètu koha leo sèra, ho mai bara rèngu ère pèku. Ka ra da'u i'a tao asa d'ara koha, toke koha dua bua se pènu dènge i'a, ka oe cène.<bt>Then2 Simon called out to his friends from the other boats to come help bring in the net. Then they scooped up the fish and put them in the boat, until those two boats were full of fish and almost ready to sink.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="da'u = ra'u ; dara roa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">da'u = ra'u ; dara roa koha = belly of boat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="metokhois: business partners"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">metokhois: business partners</Message></Annotation><v n="8-10" />Angalai Simon se, nuka Yakobis dènge Yohanis, ana nèti Sabadeus, ètu era èèna kahèi. Rèngu se malaa, lula ra abhu i'a ae titu kèna. Ropa Simon Petrus ladhe nèdhi ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne, hèia na patitu dènge ka, kètu urutuu na ètu madha Yesus, hèia na peka, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, ca dhèu dhu ue le sasala ae-ae. De be'a risi, Lamatua padètu ia ka dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Simon's friends, Yakobis and Yohanis, the children of Sebedeus, were there as well. They were also very amazed, because they got so many fish like that. When Simon Petrus saw what had happened, then he immediately knelt in front of Yesus, and said, “I here, am a person who done/made very many wrongs. So (consequently), it's better that the Lord doesn't get near me.” [NOTE: check 1st sentence whether two people or three.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="check 1st sentence whether two people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">check 1st sentence whether two people or three</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koinoonoi: partners"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">koinoonoi: partners</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:8-10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Simon, do Petrus, do Simon Petrus, ngara nèti ca dhèu di.<bt>Simon, or Petrus, or Simon Petrus, those are names from just one person.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Simon! Pangee ia ka j'ara ne'e, te Ja'a neo pake miu se. Miu tema le tenge i'a. Te ngaa deo ne'e ne, Ja'a aj'a miu sèna ka tenge dhèu ho madhutu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, “Simon! Don't think/worry too much about that, cuz (elaboration) I want to use you-pl. You-pl here, usually/habitually hunt/look for fish. But now I teach you-pl to hunt/look for people to follow Me.” [EXEG: Why does “fear” go to “worry about” here? It fits the immediate context better. “Fear can match vs.8, but in KM &amp; Dhao doesn't transition into the last two sentences, which are the peak of this exchange.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle ka, rèngu nuni dènge ka koha ra asa dedha nebhe. Ka lasi tèke eele ka ngaa-ngaa ra aa'i-aa'i, lasi madhutu Yesus.<bt>And then they immediately pulled/dragged their boats up on shore. And they went leaving behind everything, to follow Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ca dhèu dhu pèd'a kusta<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a person who is afflicted with leprosy (loan) illness</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:1-4; Markus 1:40-45)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ètu rae èci, Yesus paraga dènge ca dhèu dhu ngi'u na pènu dènge èi papèd'a kusta. Ropa dhèu ne nèdhi Yesus, ka la'e patitu kètu urutuu na, aa na pacud'u d'ai rai. Hèia na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Sue ku ja'a laa! Te ja'a ke'a, na, Ama bisa puri-pa'èle papèd'a ja'a ne, sèna ka dhèu madenge ia ka dènge ja'a. Sad'i Ama mo'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>In one village, Yesus met a person whose body was full with leprosy illness. When he saw Yesus, then he went to kneel and bow to the ground. Then he spoke, saying, “Father! Help/pity/love me! Cuz (elaboration) I know Father (you) can heal this illness of mine, so that people are not repulsed/revolted/ disgusted at me anymore. As.long.as (you) want to.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacudu = tondo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pacudu = tondo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka Yesus j'ole kacui-aai Na ho g'ag'e ne. Aa Na peka, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ko'o! Èu èle dènge kèna!&gt;&gt; Ropa Na padhai lii nare, èi papèd'a dhèu ne èle dènge.<bt>Then Yesus extended his hand to touch him. And He said, “Of course I want to! You are better!” When He spoke, that person's illness immediately disappeared.</bt><v n="14" />Hèia Yesus pasanèd'e ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku bhèlu, ee! Èu èle le, te ngaa baku peka dènge dhèu èci sa! Èu hud'i madhutu uuru ku paredha baki Musa. De lamu asa ama agama, ho na parisa ngi'u èu, sèna ka ne'a èi papèd'a ne èle tare'a, do dhae. Èle èèna na, èu hia mèdha èci sèmi tadha makasi, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a, èu ne èle tare'a le nèti papèd'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus reminded/warned him, saying, “Don't forget, ee! You are now healed, but you may not tell anyone! You must follow ancestor/grandfather Musa's command first. So (consequently), go first/now to the head of religion, in.order.that he examine your body, to see if your illness is really disappeared or not yet. Then, you must give an offering as a sign of thanks, in.order.that all people know that you are truly healed from your disease.” [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. is same as Mk. 1:44.]</bt><note reference="5:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 14:1-32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Masi ka Yesus kai, te ngaa lii lolo nèti koasa Na, pale-lème nèti dhèu èci asa èci d'ai mia-mia. Ka dhèu mai sèmi tao cèci sa, ho ra nanene Na aj'a-nori. Hèia Na puri-pa'èle dhèu ae nèti rupa-rupa èi papèd'a ra.<bt>Even though Yesus forbade it, nevertheless that story about that power of His, spread from one person to another all.over.the.place. So people kept flowing non-stop coming to listen to His teaching. Then He healed many people from their illness of all.sorts.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèci = kasi padat (Idiom; great"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">cèci = kasi padat (Idiom; great quantity)</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Te ngaa catèka-catèka, Yesus d'èi kahèi patalele iisi, ho la'e manèngi-mangaj'i asa era dhu kaliu.<bt>But sometimes Yesus also liked to retreat himself (get away), to go pray/worship in a quiet/desolate place. [EXEG: Taken as general statement, not one off. See NRSV, NLT, CEV, HCE, NIV, TH "imperfect may be iterative or durative, preferably the former:" TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaliu = sunyi ; patalele ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kaliu = sunyi ; patalele = ondor dari karamaian/kesibukan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'èle dhèu karuku èci<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a lame (unable to walk) person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 9:1-8; Markus 2:1-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ca lod'o, Yesus aj'a dhèu ètu d'ara èmu cue. Lod'o èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi, dènge pèri-pèri mese agama, mai ho nanene lii padhai Na. Dhèu se mai nèti rae-rae ètu propensi Galilea, propensi Yudea, dènge kota Yerusalem. Ama Lamatua hia Yesus koasa, sèna ka pa'èle dhèu-dhèu pèd'a.<bt>One time, Yesus was teaching people in a house. That time there were people from the Parisi religious party and several religion teachers, who came to listen to what He was saying. They came from different.villages all.around Galilea province, from Yudea province, and from Yerusalem city. Father God was giving Yesus power/authority to heal sick people.</bt><v n="18-19" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu pèri-pèri ded'e rèti dhèu karuku èci ètu dedha karad'a. Rèngu tenge-tenge j'ara, sèna ka Yesus puri-pa'èle ne. Te ngaa ètu d'ara èmu ne, dhèu sèmi tao cacèci sa, ka rèngu bisa boe pasuki asa d'ara. Nèti èèna ka, ra ded'e dhèu ne asa kolo èmu. Rare dedha, ka ra bèdi eele rèu èmu, sèna ka tao ro'a, ho dulu dhèu karuku ne dènge karad'a kateme asa haha la'e. Ra dulu dhèu ne'e asa talora aae dhèu ae-ae se, lèke mola-mola ètu madha Yesus.<bt>That time, there were several people who carried brought a lame person on top a stretcher. They kept trying to find a way so Yesus could heal him. But that house was too crowded with people, so they were not able to squeeze their way in. That's why they carried that lame person up to the top of the house. Up there, then they dismantled the roofing to1 make a hole, to2 lower (with rope) that lame person down with the stretcher. They lowered him in the midst of those many people, exactly in front of Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karad'a = 2-3 kayu diikat dgn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">karad'a = 2-3 kayu diikat dgn tali, ; cacèci ; lake = 1) kesempatan 2) ganjar, bèdi = bongkar (hands or instruments) ; dulu = kasi turun pake tali ; kateme = here is sekaligus ; pasori = cepat-cepat ; pasuki = force way into a crowd</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ropa nèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia Yesus ne'a, na, rèngu se parcaya, na, Nèngu bisa pa'èle angalai ra nèti karuku na. Ka Na lii dènge dhèu karuku ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana, ee! Ja'a saku pamèu le sasala èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing that, Yesus knew they believed He could heal that friend of his lameness. Then He spoke to that lame person, saying, “Child, ee [+affection]! I have wiped away your wrongs.” [EXEG: Trans Notes p.116-117, and following reactions.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ropa tadèngi Yesus padhai lii sèmi èèna, ka dhèu Parisi dènge mese agama sèra, pakarèi, na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Dhoka Ama Lamatua dhu dènge hak di, ho saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu. Cee ka Nèngu ne, ka Na tao iisi Na nuka sèmi Ama Lamatua! Ne'e ne pa'ele iie kolongara Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing Yesus speak like that, then those Parisi people and the religion teachers began to ask each other, saying, “Eeh! [+objection] Father God alone is the only one who has the right to erase away a person's wrongs. Who does he think he is, making himself out to be the same as Father God! This here is insulting/ruining God's name/reputation (=slander/blasphemy)!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="blaspheemiai: evil speech against God and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">blaspheemiai: evil speech against God and what belongs to him. But here, Jesus isn't saying anything detrimental to God. In the Pharisees' minds, he is insulting God by aping him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a d'ai d'ara rèngu. Hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu se ngee, na, Ja'a ne padhai lii pa'ele iie kolongara Lamatua?<bt>But Yesus knew their insides. So He spoke, saying, “Why do you-pl think that I am speaking insulting/ruining God's name/reputation (=slander/blasphemy)?</bt><v n="23-24" />Ja'a ne Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Aa Ja'a ne dènge hak kahèi, ho abho sasala-sasigo dhèu. Ladhe Ja'a lii dènge dhèu karuku ne, &lt;Ja'a abho le sasala èu,&gt; miu mèdhi boe koasa Ja'a ètu rai-haha ne. Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a peka na, &lt;Kèd'i ka! Ded'e karad'a èu, ho lèpa ka.&gt; Ladhe nèngu kèd'i dènge ka, na, miu heka mèdhi koasa Ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a neo puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku ne, sèna ka miu me'a, na, Ja'a dènge hak ho abho sasala-sasigo dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I here, am the *Genuine Human. And I have the right/authority to *forgive people's wrongs. If I say to this lame person here saying, ‘I have forgiven your-sg wrong/s,’ you-pl don't see My power/authority here on earth. But if I say, ‘Get.up [imperative]! Pick up your stretcher to go.home!’ If he gets up immediately, only.then will you-pl be able to see My power/authority. That's why I will heal this lame person so that you-pl can also know that I have the right/authority to *forgive people's wrongs.” [EXEG: “Which is easier?” implicit in the structure, so as to not force it.] [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. is almost identical to Mk 2:9-10.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mia dhu muda risi? Ladhe Ja'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Mia dhu muda risi? Ladhe Ja'a lii dènge dhèu karuku ne, &lt;Ja'a abho le sasala èu,&gt; miu me'a boe, na j'aj'i sèmi èèna, do aad'o. Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a peka na, &lt;Kèdi ka! Ded'e karad'a èu, ho lèpa ka.&gt; Ladhe nèngu kèdi dènge ka, na miu heka me'a na, Ja'a ne Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Te Ja'a ne dènge hak kahèi, ho abho sasala-sasigo dhèu.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Na piku asa dhèu karuku ne, aa lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Titu ka! Ded'e karad'a èu, ho lèpa ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He turned to speak with that lame person, saying, “Stand up! Pick up your stretcher, to go home!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Cag'ag'a laa, dhèu ne kèd'i titu ètu madha dhèu ae sèra, ka kèpe nare karad'a na. Hèia na lèpa ka dènge koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Suddenly/Unexpectedly, that person stood up in front of the many people, then1 picked up his stretcher. Then2 he went home while praising (doublet) the name/reputation of Father God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doksazoon: giving full credit to God,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">doksazoon: giving full credit to God, talking up God's reputation</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Rèdhi sèmi èèna, ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i se malaa. Ka ra ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua kapai risi eele! Deo ne'e ne, èdhi tèdhi le dènge musi madha èdhi unu ti, tadha malaa dhu kapai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing like that then, everyone was amazed. Then1 they lifted up high Father God's name/reputation, saying, “The Lord is great! Today we-inc have seen an *amazing sign with our very own eyes!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus paroa Lewi ho madhutu Ne<bt>The Lord Yesus calls/summons Lewi to follow Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 9:9-13; Markus 2:13-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Nèbhu boe ka Yesus kalua nèti d'ara èmu, hèia ladhe nèdhi dhèu roro bea ca dhèu, dhu madhèdi ètu era roro doi bea. Ngara dhèu ne, Lewi.<bt>Not long then, Yesus came out of that house, and he saw a tax collector person who was sitting in his tax collecting place. That person's name was Lewi.</bt><note reference="5:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara leo Lewi nuka, Mateos.<bt>Lewi's other name, was Mateos.</bt></note>Ka Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Mai ka madhutu Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke to him, saying, “Come follow Me!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka here signals invite, not command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ka here signals invite, not command</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Ropa tadèngi lii paroa ne, hèia Lewi kèd'i dènge ka, tèke eele aa'i-aa'i sèra, la'e madhutu Yesus.<bt>Hearing that invitation/summons, then Lewi got up immediately, and walked away leaving everything there, to follow Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Èle ka, Lewi tao tatao kapai ètu èmu na, ka na nèru Yesus. Aa na nèru kahèi angalai na dhèu roro bea sèra, dènge tamu-tamu dhu leo ho lasi ra'a-rinu.<bt>After that, Lewi made a big feast at his house, and he invited Yesus. He also invited his tax collector friends, and other guests to come and feast.</bt><v n="30" />Te ngaa pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi, dènge mese-mese agama, ka'uu-kamuki mi ana madhutu Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka miu mi'a-minu pa'èci dènge dhèu dhu laku boe, nuka dhèu roro bea, dènge dhèu karehe sèra? Dhèu be'a bisa boe pa'èci dènge dhèu sèmi sèra sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were several people of the Parisi religion party, and religion teachers, who grumbled (doublet) to Yesus' underlings, saying, “Why do you-pl sit and eat-drink with people who are nobodies/dispised, like those tax collectors and those other evil people? Good people shouldn't mix with that sort/type of people!” [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. same terms as in Mk. 2:16.]</bt><note reference="5:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 15:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yesus lii dènge rèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu pèd'a parluu dote-matarii. Te ngaa dhu pèd'a boe, parluu boe.<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “Sick people need a doctor (doublet). But people who are not sick, don't need [a doctor]. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. almost identical to Mk. 2:17.]</bt><v n="32" />Mamai Ja'a ne, ho lalau-lalo'o dhèu karehe sèra. Te ngaa Ja'a mai boe ho uri dhèu dhu ngee na, ngi'u ra mola le.&gt;&gt;<bt>I came to look.after/serve the needs of evil people. But [contrary to expectation] I didn't come to look.after/serve the needs of people who feel/consider themselves to be straight/correct/righteous.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalo'o"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lalo'o</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mese-mese agama pasisu dènge Lamatua Yesus lula j'ara-j'ara puasa<bt>Religion teachers debate with the Lord Yesus about fasting</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 9:14-17; Markus 2:18-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi dènge mese-mese agama ka'ugu mi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, Ama! Ana madhutu Yohanis tuka sarani dhèu, rèngu tema puasa dènge sabaj'a. Ana-ana madhutu dhèu Parisi sèmi èèna kahèi. Te ngaa tasamia ka, ana madhutu Ama sèra, loe boe dènge ra'a-rinu? Rèngu se re'a boe puasa, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, those people from the Parisi religion party and the religion teachers also grumbled to Yesus, saying, “It's like.this, Father! Yohanis the habitual baptizer's underlings fasted and prayed repeatedly/often. The Parisi people's underlings also do like.that. But why do Father's (=your) underlings continually eat-drink all the time? Don't they know how to fast, [+tag]?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'ugu = comel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ka'ugu = comel</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka Na dhaa pake lii pakasame, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu me'a le, ladhe dhèu tao pesta kab'i, dhèu-dhèu dhu ra nèru sèra, bisa boe puasa, te ngaa ra'a toke bècu. Ladhe mone dhu kab'i èèna, dènge rèngu era, tatu rèngu ra'a palere aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>So Yesus responded using a comparison, saying, “Obviously you-pl already know, that if there's a marriage feast, the guests don't fast, but they eat until.satisfied/full. If the groom is still there, of course they all eat together having.a.good.time. [NOTE: Gk only different in one word from Mk. 2:19].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pesta kab'i = pesta kawin ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pesta kab'i = pesta kawin ; mone dhu kab'i</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu leo rai rèti mone dhu kab'i ne, hèia angalai na susa, heka ra puasa kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But later at some time, if other person/people kidnap/run off with that groom, only then his friends will be in.a.state.of.difficulty, and only.then will they fast.” [NOTE: Gk same as Mk 2:20, except final phrase "in those days" -- "in that day".]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Hèia Yesus padhai lii pakasame èci hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu mèka dhèu dhu rare bèla hiu ca'èta, ho kalape mi kodho dhui dhu mae. Te ladhe base kodho ne, bèla hiu dhu kalape la'a èèna karuku, na kodho ne asa mae aae.<bt>Then Yesus told another comparison.story, saying, “No one takes a piece of new cloth, to attach/patch it on to an old shirt that is ripped. Cuz (elaboration) when that shirt is washed, that attached new cloth will shrink, and that shirt will rip more. [NOTE: undertranslated like CEV; to include “from a new garment” etc. would be overtranslating and make for very heavy information load in these lgs.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parabolee: this time it isn't really"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">parabolee: this time it isn't really a "story" in Pidgin terms; it's a possible scenario</Message></Annotation><v n="37-38" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, dhua dhu heka rèti nèti kapua, dhèu bhori boe asa sabha dhui. Te aad'o na, sabha madhore eele, aa dhua èèna soli soo-soo asa rai la'e. De dhua dhu hiu, hud'i bhori ku asa d'ara sabha hiu.<bt>Similarly, people don't fill new (just-tapped) palmwine in a fragile/decayed/old leaf bucket. Cuz perhaps/possibly that pail will break/leak, and that aforementioned palmwine seep.out wasted on the ground. So (consequently), new palmwine must be poured into a pail that is new.</bt><note reference="5:38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Yunani uru sèra peka na, &lt;&lt;èi anggor dhu hiu, baku soli asa d'ara tas ka'uri dhui, sèna ka baku mae ho bhori eele.&gt;&gt;<bt>According to the original Greek language writings, “grape juice that is new, don't put in a skin bag that is old, so.that it doen't get.to-point-that it breaks and.so tears.”</bt></note>[Sèmi èèna ka, Yesus aj'a si, peka na, lii aj'a Na dhu hiu bisa boe pab'ali dènge lii aj'a dhu dhui nèti dhèu Parisi.]<bt>[In that way, Yesus taught them saying his new teaching shouldn't be mixed with the Parisi people's old teaching.] [EXPLICATION: parenthesis info -- following suggestion in Trans. Notes p. 124. ; Gk. vocab is same as Mk. 2:22, with slightly different arrangment, but same meaning.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhore = tembus ; sabha ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">madhore = tembus ; sabha = haik ; soli soo-soo = malele turun ; soo-soo = ?</Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Dhèu dhu rinu rèdhi le èi anggor dhui, d'èi boe rinu dhu hiu. Te dhu re'a na, &lt;Èi anggor dhu kee risi nuka èi anggor dhui!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>A person who have ever drunk grape juice that is old, doesn't like to drink that which is new. Cuz (elaboration) he/she knows that, ‘The sweetest wine is the old wine!’” [NOTE to daughter translations: some teams want to go literal, saying “the old is the best”. But old wine = vinegar, so that's why we say “stored for a long time”, suggesting a deliberate process of aging.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pakarèi Lamatua Yesus lula-nèti lod'o a'ae sasab'a<bt>People ask/argue with the Lord Yesus (collective) about the day of stopping work</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:1-8; Markus 2:23-28)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, kako re j'ara ètu sebhe oka dhèu. Ka ana madhutu Na puru are-gandum dhu ètu madha rèngu sèra. Hèia ra sarod'e d'ara kacui-aai, ka ra'a.<bt>One time, exactly when it was the Yahudi people's day of stopping work, Yesus and His underlings were walking by the edge of a person's garden. Then His underlings stripped.seeds off the grainheads of wheat padi was right in front of their face (ie, they were not stealing it or mass harvesting it). And they rolled/rubbed between hands and ate it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huri = bulir ; kaliji ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">huri = bulir ; kaliji = ma'isi (one at a time) ; sarod'e = roll between hands, gosok</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 23:25</note><v n="2" />Ètu era èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi dhu kèpe pa'èra ad'a Yahudi ra. Ropa ladhe rèdhi ana madhutu Yesus tao sèmi èèna, ka ra kai Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka ana-ana Èu se sisu atora agama èdhi? Rèngu sab'a lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a! Ladhe ku laa! Rèngu puru are-gandum nèi. Baku tao sèmi èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>There there were several people from the Parisi religious party who held tightly to their Yahudi traditions/adat. Seeing Yesus' underlings do like that, they rebuked Him, saying, “Why are your-sg underlings violating our-inc religious regulations? They are working on the day of stopping work! Look! They are picking wheat padi. Can't/Shouldn't do like.that!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ad'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ad'a</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3-4" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ee? Miu sanèd'e lii lolo baki Daud? Daud dènge dhèu madhutu na lula manganga ae, ka maso lasi asa d'ara Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Hèia ra'e roti dhu ama agama hia le Lamatua. Te ngaa roti se'e dhodhoka ama agama di dhu bisa ra'e. Dhèu leo bisa boe. Ka baki Daud si ra'e, te ngaa ca dhèu sa peka boe, na, rèngu sale. Miu se, sèmi baca mèdhi boe Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua!<bt>But Yesus responded/retorted, saying, “How is it, ee? Don't you-pl remember that story about grandfather/ancestor Daud? Daud and his underlings' were very hungry, so they entered into Father God's Worship Tent. Then they ate that bread which the religion fathers (*priests) had given to the Lord. But it was only just the religion fathers who could eat (that bread). Other people couldn't. Then grandfather Daud (collective) ate [it], but no one accused them. You just don't know how to read Father God's Clean/Holy Writing!</bt><note reference="6:3-4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 21:1-6; Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 24:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Pasa dhilu ho nanene paie-iie! Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Ja'a dènge hak ho pama'ète, na, dhèu bisa sab'a ngaa, lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Attach your ear holes to listen carefully! I am the Original/Authentic Human. I have the right/authority to decide what people can do on the day of stopping work.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu ai madhe cabèka<bt>Person with arm dead on one.side (=paralyzed arm)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:9-14; Markus 3:1-6)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ca tèka, lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a dhu leo, Yesus la'e aj'a ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i. Ètu era èèna, abhu dhèu mone èci, dhu ai madhe cabèka.<bt>One day, on another day of stopping work, Yesus went to teach in the worship house. There, there was male whose arm on one side was dead/paralyzed.</bt><v n="7" />Ètu èèna, abhu kahèi pèri-pèri mese agama, dènge dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi, dhu tenge j'ara ho pamanahu Yesus. Ra tatae, tao-tao Na neo puri-pa'èle dhèu dhu ai madhe cabèka ne, lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a. Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu bisa abhu j'ara ho galaa Ne ètu madha dhèu ae.<bt>There, there were also several religion teachers and people from the Parisi religion party, who were looking for a way to bring down Yesus. So they were waiting to see if He would heal that person who arm on one.side was dead, on the day of stopping work. In that way, they could find a way to accuse Him publically/before many people.</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a ngangee rèngu. Nèti èèna ka, Na paroa dhèu dhu ai madhe cabèka ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Angalai! Mai ku. Titu ètu talora aae ne!&gt;&gt; Hèia la'e titu dènge ka ètu talora èèna.<bt>But Yesus knew exactly what their thoughts/intentions were. That's why He called that person whose arm on one side was dead, saying, “Friend! Come stand in the middle here!” And he immediately went to stand [there].</bt><v n="9" />Ka Yesus karèi dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a karèi ku miu laa. Madhutu atora agama èdhi, ngaa dhu èdhi bisa tao ètu lod'o a'ae sasab'a? Èdhi tao dhu be'a, do, tao dhu karehe? Hia mamuri mi dhèu, do, pa'ele iie mamuri na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked those people there, saying, “Let Me ask you. According ot our-inc religious regulations, what can we-inc do on the day of stopping work? Do we do good, or do evil? Do we save/give life to someone, or destroy his/her life?”</bt><v n="10" />Hèia Yesus ladhe palème rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, ka Na lii dènge dhèu dhu ai madhe cabèka ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;J'ole ai èu mai!&gt;&gt; Ka na soro ai na, hèia èle dènge ka.<bt>Next Yesus looked around at them all, and He spoke with that person whose arm was dead on one side, saying, “Extend your arm here!” And he extended it, and his arm was immediately well.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, ka dhèu kapai se nasa titu kèna. Hèia ra peka, na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi tenge hari ku j'ara leo, sèna ka pamanahu Ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing like.that, then those important people were furious. Then they said, “We-exc must find yet another way, to make Him fall!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus hag'e nare ana madhutu Na canguru dua dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus chooses/selects out His twelve underlings</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:1-4; Markus 3:13-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Nèbhu boe ka, Yesus la'e sabaj'a asa ledhe èci. Na sabaj'a ètu èèna camèd'a kateme.<bt>Not much longer, Yesus went to a mountain to pray. He prayed there for an entire night.</bt><v n="13" />Asa bèli mad'ae, Yesus paroa ana madhutu Na. Ka nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, hag'e nare canguru dua dhèu ho j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. Dhèu dhu hag'e nare sèra, nuka:<bt>Early the next morning, Yesus called His underlings. Then from among them all, He chose/selected out twelve people to be/become his messengers/emissaries/*apostles. Those people whom He chose are:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="14" />Simon (dhu Yesus pangare ne, &lt;Petrus&gt;)<bt>Simon (whom Yesus called ‘Petrus’),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Anderias (ari Simon),<bt>Anderias (Simon's younger.sibling),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis,<bt>Yakobis,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yohanis (ari Yakobis),<bt>Yohanis (Yakobis' younger.sibling),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pelipus,<bt>Pelipus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bertolomeos,<bt>Bertolomeos,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="15" />Mateos,<bt>Mateos,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tomas,<bt>Tomas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis (ana Alpius),<bt>Yakobis (Alpius' child),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Simon (nèti partei politik Selot),<bt>Simon (who followed the Selot political party),</bt><note reference="6:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Partei Selot ne, dhu tenge j'ara, sèna ka Roma paredha heka ra. Ka ra pangare partei ne &lt;Patriot&gt; kahèi.<bt>This Selot party, was seeking a way for them to be independent of Roma's government. And they also called this party ‘Patriot’.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="16" />Yudas (ana Yakobis), aa<bt>Yudas (Yakobis' child), and</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yudas Iskariot (dhu èèna na pahia Yesus).<bt>Yudas Iskariot (who later sold (=*betrayed) Yesus).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a ae-ae<bt>The Lord Yesus heals many sick people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 4:23-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa puru mai nèti ledhe deo na, Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, ae taha ètu era mera èci. Ètu èèna, abhu dhèu ae dhu pakaboko. Dhèu se mai nèti propensi Yudea, nèti kota Yerusalem, aa nèti Tirus dènge Sidon, nuka dua kota ètu sebhe dhasi.<bt>When they came down from that mountain, Yesus and His underlings stopped (temporarily, not to stay) on flat land. There, many people had gathered. They were ones who had come from Yudea province, from Yerusalem city, and Tirus and Sidon, which were two cities on the edge of the sea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ae taha = barenti tahan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ae taha = barenti tahan</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Rèngu mai ho nanene lii padhai Yesus, aa abhu kahèi dhu neo manèngi sèna ka Na puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a. Ka Yesus pa'èle si. Na pa'èle kahèi dhèu dhu nidhu tao, dènge magèle eele nidhu nèti dhèu sèra.<bt>These people came to hear Yesus, and also to request Him to heal sick people. Then/So He healed them. He also healed poeple who were afflicted by evil.spirits, and expelled2/by expelling evil.spirits out of those people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akathartoi: unclean, made them so they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">akathartoi: unclean, made them so they could not associate with God's people or take part in worship</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Dhèu ae dhu neo goi Ne. Te ropa goi lèke Ne, dhèu se èle dènge nèti papèd'a ra, lula abhu koasa dhu kalua nèti Nèngu.<bt>Many people wanted to touch Him. Cuz when they touched him, people were healed of their sicknesses, because of the power came out of Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu abhu a'oto, dènge dhèu dhu abhu mamadhe-mamopo<bt>People who obtain good.fortune/benefit, and people who obtain misfortune/disaster</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 5:1-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle ka Yesus kabib'a asa ana madhutu Na, hèia Na aj'a si, aku Nèngu na,<bt>Then Yesus turned to face His underlings, and taught them, saying, [NOTE: CEV future for this whole passage really isn't justified. Dallas Willard agrees it is not justified.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Dhèu unu aad'o sèra!<bt>“Poor/pitiful people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu a'oto,<bt>You-pl are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Ama Lamatua mesa Na, j'aj'i Dhèu Aae miu dhu be'a.<bt>because Father God himself is your-pl King who is good.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="21" />Dhèu dhu kabake manganga sèra!<bt>Hungry people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu a'oto,<bt>You-pl are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Lamatua ka dhu hia miu bècu-manèsa.<bt>because the Lord is the one who will make you become full/satisfied (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu dhu tangi dènge d'ara susa sèra!<bt>People who cry from distressed insides!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu a'oto,<bt>You are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula èèna na d'ara mi karej'e.<bt>because your insides will be happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="22-23" />Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a.<bt>I am the Orginal Human.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ka dhèu dhu abhu susa lula madhutu Ja'a,<bt>And people who are afflicted with difficulty because of following Me here!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">miu abhu a'oto,<bt>You are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula èèna na Lamatua b'ala rui-j'aj'èra miu ètu sorga.<bt>because the Lord will later reciprocate/reward your suffering in heaven.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Masi ka dhèu tèka d'ara dènge miu,<bt>Even.though people hate you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do pakarehe kolongara miu,<bt>or destroy your name/reputation,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do j'èli marèu miu,<bt>or step.all.over (=oppress) you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">do bata eele miu, tao sèmi dhèu bhelu sa,<bt>or expel evict3 you out like evil people,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bata = usir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">bata = usir</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">miu abhu a'oto,<bt>you are fortunate,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula èèna na Lamatua bhèlu boe miu ètu sorga.<bt>because the Lord will not forget (=remember) you in heaven. [DISCOURSE: Order following regional perceptions of light to heavy.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ekbaloosin to onoma hymoon hoos poneeron:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">ekbaloosin to onoma hymoon hoos poneeron: cast out your name as evil</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Petrus 4:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De ladhe dhèu paj'èra miu sèmi èèna, pakarej'e laa d'ara miu! Aa karae laa dènge pasoa-pasoka! Mage malaa kahèi, lula dhèu dhu paj'èra miu limuri ne, bèi-baki ra dhu uru èèna, paj'èra le dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua sèra kahèi.<bt>So (consequently), if/when people cause difficulty for/to you like.that, well, just make your insides happy (=joyful)! And leap for joy! Don't be amazed/surprised, because those people who cause you difficulty now, their very own ancestors are the ones who caused difficulty for Lord's spokespersons long.ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoka = leap around ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pasoka = leap around ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De ladhe miu paraga dènge j'aj'èra sèmi sèra,<bt>So (consequently), if/when you encounter difficulty like.that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">pakarej'e laa d'ara miu,<bt>just make your insides happy (=be joyful),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula èèna na Lamatua b'ala hia miu ae-ae ètu sorga!<bt>because the Lord will reciprocate/reward you lots.and.lots in heaven!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoi pateres autoon: The antecedent of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hoi pateres autoon: The antecedent of autoon is the people in Verse 22 who are against you. It's far enough removed from the end of Verse 23 to really complicate things. So we've had to bleach out the meaning to "the people from that time," that is, "long ago," rather than specifically ancestors and descendants. That way we don't lose the train of thought.</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 36:16, Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 7:52</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Te ngaa dhèu kaja!<bt>But rich people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo,<bt>You-pl will get misfortune/disaster,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula mamuri karej'e miu, dhoka d'ai ne'e di.<bt>because your life's happiness, only lasts until now.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="25" />Dhèu dhu bècu-manèsa!<bt>Full/satisfied people!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo,<bt>You are misfortunate/disastrous,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula hèru manganga madèu dhu seli eele, mai salake nare miu.<bt>because a horrific hunger season will envelop/overwhelm you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="salake = tutu ame"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">salake = tutu ame</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu dhu kea rae-rae sèra!<bt>People who show mirth heedlessly!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kea rae-rae = sukacita yg tidak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kea rae-rae = sukacita yg tidak terbatas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo,<bt>You are misfortunate/disastrous,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula j'aj'èra mai, tao miu tangi ngob'i-ngob'i.<bt>because suffering comes to make you cry wailing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="26" />Dhèu dhu d'èi dhèu koa-kad'iri!<bt>People infatuated with honour/getting praise!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koa-kadiri = angka puji (kita) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">koa-kadiri = angka puji (kita) ; padiri = (different)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu abhu mamadhe-mamopo,<bt>You are misfortunate/disastrous,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula uru sèra bèi-baki miu<bt>because previously/long.ago your ancestors</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">d'èi pad'iri kahèi dhèu-dhèu dhu rèti lii leko-monya sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>also praised the nonsense-talking (=deceptive/lying) spokespersons!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoi pateres autoon: same problem as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">hoi pateres autoon: same problem as in Verse 23, except that the antecedent of autoon is "everybody," so it's more accessible. Turning Verse 26 around would make the reference of autoon even more jammed up.<span class="Italic">(26)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Miu hud'i sue ku musu mi<bt>You-pl must love your enemies</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 5:38-48, 7:12a)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, &lt;&lt;Pasa dhilu ho nanene paie-iie! Èu hud'i sue ku musu èu, aa tao pabe'a laa mi dhèu dhu tèka d'ara dènge èu.<bt>Then Yesus continued, saying, “Attach your ears to listen well! You-sg must love your enemies, and do good things for people who hate you. [NOTE: Gk in 2p for whole passage, but Kupang &amp; Dhao changed to 2s to fit the genre.]</bt><v n="28" />Sabaj'a ho manèngi Ama Lamatua, sèna ka hia babe'a mi dhèu dhu dhoo èu. Aa manèngi sèna ka Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi dhèu dhu paj'èra èu rupa-rupa.<bt>Pray requesting Father God to do good things for people who curse you. And request that the Lord give blessing to people who make mistreat you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhoo = kutuk ; tibha ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dhoo = kutuk ; tibha = manyangkali</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ladhe dhèu tèb'e ripi èu cabèka, soro hari ripi cabèka ho na tèb'e. Ladhe dhèu parame rare kodho pana èu, na, hia hari laa kodho èu dhu leo.<bt>If a person slaps your cheek on one.side, turn your other cheek so that s/he can slap (it). If someone snatches/steals your warm shirt, then, give another of your shirts to him/her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ripi = pipi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ripi = pipi</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ladhe dhèu manèngi mèdha èu èci, hia laa. Aa ladhe dhèu ded'e rèti mèdha èu èci, soro tèke sène. Mage mu manèngi hari!<bt>If someone requests something of yours, go ahead and give it. And if someone carries off something of yours, just let him/her have it. Don't ask for it back!</bt><v n="31" />Èu hud'i tao ku dhèu leo, nuka sèmi èu neo dhèu tao mi ngi'u èu.<bt>You must do for/toward other people, like you want them to do for/toward yourself.</bt><note reference="6:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 7:12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Èu d'èi pad'elo sasue mi dhèu èu mesa mu. Èèna be'a. Te ngaa kolo-karisi na ngaa? Te dhèu bhelu sue dhèu rèngu kahèi.<bt>You like/habitually show love to the your own people. That's good. But what is so special about that? Cuz evil people also love their own people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kolo karisi = kelebihan, special"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kolo karisi = kelebihan, special</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Ladhe èu pabe'a dhoka dènge dhèu dhu be'a dènge èu di, kolo-karisi ètu mia? Te dhèu bhelu sèra, re'a b'ala babe'a dhèu sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>If you only do good to people who do good to you, where/what is so special? Cuz (elaboration) evil people also know how to reciprocate each other like that.</bt><v n="34" />Ladhe èu dhodhoka hia pija mi dhèu dhu bisa pula hari doi èu, kolo-karisi na ngaa? Te dhèu bhelu kahèi re'a hia dhèu leo pija doi, sad'i bèli-camèd'a sèmi aa'i hari dhu kateme iisi.<bt>If you only loan money to people who can pay it back, well, what is so special about that? Cuz (elaboration) evil people also loan money to other people (implies outside their social group), as.long.as tomorrow or the next day they get back the entire amount.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hia pija = pinjamkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">hia pija = pinjamkan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Te ngaa dhu lèke ka, sèmi ne'e: sue la musu èu sèra! Aa tao la be'a mi rèngu. Ngaa dhu ra parluu, hia si pija. Baku pangee, na, ra pula hari do aad'o. Dènge j'ara ne, èèna na Ama Lamatua b'ala èu. Pe èu j'aj'i ana nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele. Lula mamuri èu sama sèmi Ama mu, dhu d'èi ad'u-ue j'ara hua iia hia dhèu bhelu. Nèngu d'èi kahèi tao j'ara hua iia hia dhèu dhu re'a boe manèngi makasi.<bt>But what's right is like this: love your enemies! And do good things for/to them. Whatever they need, just lend it to them. Don't think/worry about whether they will give it back or not. In that way, Father God will reciprocate/repay you. And you will become the child of the Very Highest Father God. Because you live in the same way as your Father who likes to do good/nice things to/for evil people. He also does good things for people who do not know how to say thankyou. [NOTE to daughter translations: #1 “What is amazing is this” is explicating the high-level dynamics of the exchange. If your language does not have a really close match leave it out. Don't force it. #2 If there is not a good match for /pinjam/ or if it evokes only money, then use /kasi pake (tahan)/.]</bt><v n="36" />De èu hud'i pad'elo ku kasia mi dhèu, nuka sèmi Ama mu ètu sorga dhu pad'elo kasia Na mi èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), you must show compassion/mercy/pity to people, the same as your Father in heaven also shows compassion to you.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasia = pity, mercy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kasia = pity, mercy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku kahèti leli dhèu<bt>Don't heedlessly habitually find.fault/criticize</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 7:1-5)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii aj'a Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku lee dhèu, sèna ka dhèu baku lee hari èu. Baku kahèti leli lii padhai dhèu, te aad'o na dhèu tao hari èu sèmi èèna kahèi. Pabhèlu eele sasala dhèu, sèna ka rèngu baku nui sasala èu.<bt>And Yesus continued teaching, saying, “Don't evaluate/judge/ criticise people, so that people don't evaluate/j/c you in return. Don't criticize2 people, cuz (elaboration) later people will criticize you in return. Completely forget people's wrong/s, so.that they also not store up your wrong/s.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kahèti = kuti, fiti ; leli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kahèti = kuti, fiti ; leli = sembarangan ; padhai = bekin busuk orang pung nama ; nui = simpan (kesalahan org), tidak pernah lupa, inga terus ; kahèti leli lii padhai dhèu = karitik orang ; lee = nilei, also evaluating looking in a mirror ; pasala = accuse</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apolyete, kai apolytheesesthe: pardon, release --"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">apolyete, kai apolytheesesthe: pardon, release -- not the ordinary word for forgiving sins.</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Ladhe èu hia dhèu ngaa dhu ra parluu, pe èu abhu hari. Te bèli-camèd'a ra hia hari èu pènu ai. Èèna, nuka sèmi dhèu isi kab'ui asa d'ara balee a'uku, ka ra karèko ne, aa cèci ne, toke bua lale eele. Dhu èu abhu, sama èci èèna ka. Ladhe èu hia ciki, èu abhu hari ciki kahèi. Te ngaa ladhe èu hia ae, èu abhu hari ae-ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>If you give people what they need, you will receive in return. Cuz (elaboration) later it will be given for you to receive back full-full (abundantly/ overflowing). That is like a person who pours many nuts/peanuts in a measuring tin, then shakes it, presses down on it, then fills up more until even the heap/ excessive. amount spills over. That which you will get/receive, will be like that. If you give a little, you will also receive back a little. But if you give much, you will receive back lots and lots.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pènu ai = limpah (di tangan)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pènu ai = limpah (di tangan) ; kabui = kacang (umum) ; balee = balek ; a'uku = ukuran ; karèko = goyang-goyang ; pènu tolo = (seeds, nuts) overflow ; tolo (Kupang = male genitals) ; bua = maspurak ; lale = mengalir</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Baku kahèti leli lii padhai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Diperhatikan: Baku kahèti leli lii padhai dhèu, te aad'o na dhèu tao hari èu sèmi èèna kahèi. Baku nui sasala dhèu, sèna ka rèngu pa' bhèlu sasala èu. (Nui arti nya: Simpan kesalahan org)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Yesus aj'a pake lii upama kahèi. Na lole, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu bèdhu bisa boe pad'elo j'ara hia dhèu bèdhu dhu leo. Te aad'o na, dua ra manahu asa d'ara ro'a lasi!<bt>Yesus also taught using a comparison.story. He storied saying, “It's impossible for a blind person to show the way/path for another blind person. Cuz (elaboration) the two of them will fall into a hole.</bt><note reference="6:39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 15:14</note><v n="40" />Ana sakola bisa boe mèu risi nèti mese na! Te ngaa ladhe na madhutu dènge be'a lii a'aj'a mese na, nèngu bisa j'aj'i sama sèmi mese na.<bt>It's impossible for a student to be more impressive that his/her teacher. But if s/he carefully follows his/her teacher's teaching, s/he can become like his/her teacher.</bt><note reference="6:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:24-25, Yohanis 13:16, 15:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Èu pa'èki more sasala dhèu, masi ka ana iiki-iiki èèna ka. Te ngaa sasala èu dhu kapai, èu sèmi pame'a boe sa. Èèna, nuka sèmi èu mèdhi ahu ca katèd'a ètu musi madha dhèu. Masi ka agarii aae dhu pa'abhe nare musi madha èu, te ngaa èu oe sèmi pame'a boe sa!<bt>You-sg like.to/habitually take careful note of people's teeny-tiny wrongs. But your wrongs which are big, you consider it as if they just don't exist. That is like you see a dot of dust in someone's eye. But.in.actual.fact there is a big block/beam blocking your eye, but you don't feel/know about it!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'èki more = simpan terus ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pa'èki more = simpan terus ; ahu ca katèd'a = satu titik debu</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Tasamia ka èu bani peka dènge angalai mu, na, &lt;Mai, ho ja'a tiu eele ahu nèti d'ara madha èu.&gt; Te ngaa èu mesa mu bisa boe ladhe mèdhi ngaa-ngaa, te agarii dhu pa'abhe nare musi madha èu! Weeh! Èu ne, mema dhèu kapod'e-kabèli! Tao eele uru ku agarii nèti d'ara madha èu, heka èu ladhe mèdhi, ho tiu eele ahu ca katèd'a èèna, nèti d'ara madha angalai mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>How is it that you dare to speak with your friend, saying, ‘Come let me help wipe that dust out of your eye.’ But you yourself can't see anything, cuz there is obviously a block/beam blocking your eye! Weeh! You are truly a deceitful person (=hypocrite)! Take out and throw away that block/beam from your own eye first. Only.then can you see, to help wipe away that tiny bit of dust from your friend's eye.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Babe'a-karehe dhèu te'a nèti tatao na<bt>A person's good-evil (doublet) is apparent/known from his/her deeds</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 7:16-20, 12:33-35)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Ka Yesus tabha lii pakasame èci hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ètu mia, aj'u be'a, ladhe d'ai lod'o hua, hua na karehe. Aa abhu boe ladhe aj'u karehe na hua, hua na be'a.<bt>Yesus added another comparison story, saying, “You're not going to find (idiomatic) a tree which is good, producing fruit which is bad. And you're not going to get a tree which is bad, producing fruit which is good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abhu ètu mia = dapat di"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">abhu ètu mia = dapat di mana</Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Dhèu bisa tadhe ladhe aj'u ca kapua, be'a do aad'o, mai nèti hua na. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a, peka na, ètu mia dhèu puu lolobhangi, do, hua anggor nèti aj'u padhudhu.<bt>People can note/see.a.sign, if one particular tree is good or not, that is its fruit. All people know that, it is not possible for someone to pick papaya fruit or grape fruit from a thorn tree.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lolobhangi = papaya ; padhudhu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lolobhangi = papaya ; padhudhu = baduri</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:44" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, dhèu puu nare boe σῦκον (<span class="Italic">sukon</span>) nèti ἀκανθα (<span class="Italic">akantha</span>). Rèngu abhu boe kahèi σταφυλή (<span class="Italic">stafulei</span>) nèti βάτος (<span class="Italic">batos</span>). Sasoa na, nèti ana aaj'u èci, èdhi abhu hua madhutu rupa na.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, people don't pick σῦκον (<span class="Italic">sukon</span>) from ἀκανθα (<span class="Italic">akantha</span>). And they don't get σταφυλή (<span class="Italic">stafulei</span>) from βάτος (<span class="Italic">batos</span>). It means that from one (type of) tree, we-inc get fruit according to its kind.</bt></note><note reference="6:44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:33</note><v n="45" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu d'ara mola-mèci, ne'a tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a. Te ngaa dhèu dhu d'ara kaj'alu, tao j'ara-j'ara dhu bhelu-katub'a. Te nèti lii padhai na, èdhi bisa tadhe babe'a-karehe dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Similarly a person whose insides are clean/holy (doublet), does deeds which are good. But a person whose liver is dirty/defiled does evil things. Cuz (elaboration) from a person's speaking, we can know a person's true.nature (good-evil).”</bt><note reference="6:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:34</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu mèu dènge dhèu goa dhu patitu èmu<bt>A smart person and a stupid person build house</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 7:24-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Hèia Yesus tuhu lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se loe boe paroa Ja'a, na, &lt;Lamatua&gt;. Te ngaa tasamia ka miu mo'o boe tao madhutu lii padhai Ja'a?<bt>Then Yesus continued speaking, saying, “You keep calling Me, saying, ‘Lord/Master/Owner’. But why do you-pl not want to follow/obey My talking?</bt><v n="47" />Dhèu dhu mai nanene lii padhai Ja'a, ho na tao madhutu, nèngu ne èci èèna ka<bt>The person who comes-hears what I say, then does according to it, that person is like</bt><v n="48" />dènge dhèu dhu neo patitu èmu dhu èra. Na kèi ro'a fanderen toke abhu hadhu. Hèia na padhèdi fanderen, heka na patitu èmu kèna. Ladhe èi aae lala, èmu ne gaged'o boe sa hèi, lula era padhèdi na èra.<bt>a person who is going to build a house that is strong/firm/lasting. S/he carefully digs the foundation hole, until s/he hits rock. Then s/he sets the foundation, and.only.then does s/he build the house. If/when a flood comes, that house does not sway, because it's foundation is strong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagedo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">gagedo</Message></Annotation><v n="49" />Te ngaa dhèu nanene dènge d'ara kajari, aa madhutu boe lii padhai Ja'a, nèngu ne èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu neo patitu èmu sad'i j'aj'i di. Na tao boe fanderen, te ngaa na patitu èmu na ètu dedha rai ètu sebhe loko. Hèia ropa èi aae lala, èmu na guri laho mae-mae!&gt;&gt;<bt>But the person who only hears half-heartedly and doesn't follow My talking, s/he is like a person who just wants to build a house that's good-enough-as-long-as-its-made. S/he doesn make a foundation, but s/he only places that house on top of the soil/ground at the edge of the river. Then when the flood comes, it then sweeps away destroys that house!” [NOTE to daughter translations: Matthew mentions sand; Luke mentions ground.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara kajari = dara kacanga ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dara kajari = dara kacanga = hati bacabang ; guri = rubu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ana sab'a ca dhèu nèti komedhaa sordad'u Roma<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a Roman army commander's worker</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:5-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa aj'a nare, ka Yesus lèpa asa kota Kapernaum.<bt>After teaching like that, then Yesus returned to Kapernaum city.</bt><v n="2" />Ca dhèu komedhaa sordad'u Roma pea ètu ne'e. Abhu dhèu sab'a na èci dhu nèngu parcaya. Dhèu sab'a ne dhu pèd'a oe madhe.<bt>There there lived a Roman army/military commander. He had a worker whom he trusted. That worker had fallen sick and was almost dead.</bt><v n="3" />Lod'o èèna, komedhaa tadèngi le tatao Yesus, hèia na pua dhèu heka Yahudi pèri-pèri lasi manèngi Yesus mai puri dhèu sab'a ne.<bt>When that commander heard about Yesus' deeds, then he sent several elder Yahudi people to go request Yesus to come heal that worker.</bt><v n="4" />D'ai nèi, ra pamako Yesus, sèna ka Na la'e palere dènge rèngu. Ra manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Roma ne, dhèu be'a! Ama hud'i tolong ne.<bt>Arriving there, they begged Yesus, so that He would accompany them. They requested, saying, “This Roma person is a good person! He is someone Father (=you) must/needs to/ought to help.</bt><v n="5" />Te nèngu ka patitu èmu sabaj'a cue hia ji'i, lula na sue èdhi dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) he has build a worship house for us-inc, because he loves us-inc Yahudi people.”</bt><v n="6" />Ka Yesus madhutu dènge si.<bt>Then Yesus accompanied them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rèngu dhae rare mèka èmu, te ngaa komedhaa ne pua le angalai na la'e peka dènge Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;Ama roca ia ka mai asa d'ara èmu ja'a, te ja'a nia boe sèmi Ama asa d'ara èmu ja'a.<bt>They had not yet arrived at the house, but that commander had already sent his friend to go tell Yesus, saying, “Father doesn't need to get all tired.out coming to my house, cuz I am not worthy of receiving Father (=you) at my house.</bt><v n="7-8" />Aa ja'a nia boe kahèi ara dhiu asa katanga madha Ama. Ja'a ke'a Ama dènge koasa. De sad'i Ama padhai lii nèti èèna, tatu dhèu sab'a ja'a ne èle dènge nèti papèd'a na. Ja'a ke'a j'ara ne'e ne, lula ja'a dènge dhèu paredha dedha kahèi, dhu dènge koasa ho paredha ja'a. Aa ja'a dènge koasa kahèi ho paredha sordad'u ja'a. Ladhe ja'a hia paredha mi sordad'u ja'a, peka na, &lt;Lamu sa nèi!&gt; tatu la'e dènge. Aa ladhe ja'a peka, na, &lt;Mai sa ne'e.&gt; tatu na mai. Aa ladhe ja'a pua dhèu sab'a ja'a, &lt;Sab'a ne'e.&gt; tatu na sab'a madhutu kahèi. De sad'i Ama padhai lii di, dhèu sab'a ja'a ne, èle dènge.&gt;&gt;<bt>And I also am not worthy of coming to face Father. I know that Father has power/authority. So, as.long.as Father just speaks from there, certainly my worker will be immediately healed from his sickness. I understand these things, because I also have people who govern above me who have power/authority to order me. And I also have power/authority to order my soldiers. If I order my soldier saying, ‘Go there (remote)!’ surely he goes straightaway. If I say, ‘Come here!’ surely he comes. And if I order my worker(s), saying, ‘Work/Do this!’ surely he does accordingly. So, as.long.as Father just speaks, this worker of mine will be healed right.away.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, Yesus malaa. Ka Na kabib'a sa dhèu ae dhu madhutu Na sèra, hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Nia kahèi nga! Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, Ja'a paraga kèdhi mèka dènge dhèu Yahudi dhu lèka èra sama sèmi dhèu Roma ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that Yesus was amazed. And He turned to face those people (crowds) who were following Him, and He said, “How about that (idiom)! It's been this long, but I have never yet ever met a Yahudi person who believes as strongly as this Roma person!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nia kahèi nga = bisa juga,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Nia kahèi nga = bisa juga, ee!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />De Yesus d'ai dhoka era èèna di. Hèia angalai komedhaa se lèpa. Ropa d'ai èmu komedhaa, ladhe na, dhèu sab'a ne èle le nèti papèd'a na.<bt>Thus Yesus only traveled just to that point. Then, the commanders friends returned home. Arriving at that commander's house, then they saw that that worker was indeed already healed of his sickness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pamamuri hari ana nèti ca dhèu bhèni balu<bt>The Lord Yesus makes a widow's child alive</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Asa bèli èèna, Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, pakèd'i lasi asa rae èci, ngara na Nain. Dhèu ae kako palere dènge Ne.<bt>The next day, then Yesus and His underlings left to go a village, named Nain. There were many people who travelled together with Him.</bt><v n="12" />Ropa rèngu oe dètu dènge hèb'a tedhe maso asa rae ne, ra paraga dènge dhèu ca nau lasi padhane dhèu madhe. Dhèu madhe ne, ana mone mesa nèti ca dhèu bhèni balu.<bt>When they were about to come close to that village's entrance door/gate, there was a procession of people wanting to go bury a dead person. The one who had died, was a mama widow's only male child. [NOTE: "carried out" is carried by the Dhao term "procession of a dead person...going to bury him"].</bt><v n="13" />Ropa Yesus nèdhi bhèni balu ne, ka d'ara Na roe. Hèia Na lii dènge bhèni ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina! Tangi ia ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus saw that mama widow, He felt compassion. Then He spoke with that woman, saying, “Mama! Don't cry anymore!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Hèia Yesus la'e padètu-dètu, ka Na g'ag'e karad'a dhèu madhe ne. Ka dhèu dhu pasae karad'a ne titu taha. Hèia Yesus lii dènge dhèu madhe, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana! Kèd'i ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus went close, and touched that dead person's stretcher. Then the people who carried that stretcher, temporarily stopped. Then2 Yesus spoke to that dead person saying, “Child! Get up!” [NOTE: “young man” is not a form of address in Dhao.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kopa = peti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kopa = peti</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neaniske: In Pidgin there are terms"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">neaniske: In Pidgin there are terms of address for members of one's own family that get up into the neaniskos age range. But for unrelated people, onoly a more general term is appropriate. It spans teen age to elderly, and in some contexts is gender neutral.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ka ana ne mamuri hari, hèia na kèd'i madhèdi. Èle èèna ka, na padhai lii dènge dhèu ae dhu titu reo rare ne. Aa Yesus peka dènge bhèni balu ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina! Ana mu ka ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, that child lived again/came back to life, and he sat up right away. Then3 he began to speak back.and.forth with the many people who were standing around him. Then4 Yesus said to that widow woman, “Mother! Here is your child.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reo = lingkar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">reo = lingkar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ne'e ne, ana ina.&gt;&gt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Ne'e ne, ana ina.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu sèra madha'u titu kèna! Ka ra koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua pua le ca dhèu Na dhu kapai risi, dhu nèti lii padhai Na hia èdhi!&gt;&gt; Abhu hari dhu leo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua mai le ètu talora aae èdhi, ho pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na!&gt;&gt;<bt>All the people who were there, were very afraid! And they praised Father God, saying, “Father God has sent one of His amazing spokesperson to us!” There were others who said, “Father God has come into our midst, to show His goodness/kindness/ grace/generosity!”</bt><v n="17" />Hèia lii lolo ne, ra palolo d'ai mia-mia ètu propensi Yudea dènge era leo kahèi.<bt>Then that story spread all.over.the.place in Yudea province, and also in other regions.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis tuka sarani, pua dhèu dua lasi paraga dènge Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yohanis the Habitual Baptizer sends two people to go meet with the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 11:2-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-20" />Ana madhutu Yohanis tadèngi aa'i le ngaa-ngaa dhu Yesus ad'u-ue. Ka lasi lole dènge Yohanis ètu d'ara bèdho. Hèia na pua dhèu dua lasi, ho karèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama ne tare'a-re'a Kristus dhu ji'i mate tae-tae, do? Do, ji'i mate hari ku dhèu leo?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yohanis' underlings had heard all the things which Yesus did. So they went to tell (them) to Yohanis in jail. Then he sent two people to Yesus to ask Him saying, “Is Father here truly Kristus, who we-exc are waiting for [tag question]? Or must we-exc wait yet again for another person?” [EXEG: Prison location from Lk.3:20, Matt. 11, Trans. Notes p.152, and Marshall p.289].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tae-tae = wait (adds intensity, keep"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tae-tae = wait (adds intensity, keep waiting for earnestly)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle ka ra paraga dènge Yesus, ka ra karèi sèmi èèna ka.<bt>So they met Yesus, and they asked like.that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Lod'o ana madhutu Yohanis se ètu èèna, Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu ae nèti papèd'a ra. Na bata eele nidhu nèti dhèu. Aa Na pa'èle dhèu bèdhu, ka rèdhi hari.<bt>When those messengers were there, Yesus was healing many people from their sicknesses. And He was expelling out evil.spirits from people. And was healing blind people so they could see again.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Lèpa ka ho mi peka dènge a'a Ku Yohanis, aa'i-aa'i dhu miu tadèngi dènge mèdhi unu mi, sèmi dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya, suri tèke,<bt>Then Yesus told them, “You-pl go.home and tell My elder.sibling Yohanis about everything which you have heard and seen for yourselves, just like Father God's spokesperson named Yesaya wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Dhèu bèdhu rèdhi hari.<bt>&lt;Blind people are.able to see.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu karuku, kèd'i ho kako hari.<bt>People with crippled foot/feet, get up and walk.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu pèd'a kusta, isi ra milu hari.<bt>People with leprosy illness, their bodies become clean.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu katele-katipa, tadèngi hari.<bt>Deaf people (doublet), hear.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu madhe, mamuri hari.<bt>Dead people, live again/come back to life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu dhu dènge boe unu, nanene Lii Lolo Be'a.&gt;<bt>Poor people, hear Good News.’</bt><note reference="7:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 35:5-6, 61:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lami ho peka kahèi dènge a'a Ku Yohanis, na, &lt;Dhèu dhu makae boe sèmi rare Ja'a, rèngu abhu a'oto.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Go and tell My elder.sibling Yohanis, saying, ‘People who are not ashamed to receive/accept Me, they will be truly fortunate/get benefit.”&gt; [CHECK ambiguity “receive Me” vs. “like/similar to Me”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skandalistheei: bent out of shape by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">skandalistheei: bent out of shape by something another person does or says</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa ana madhutu Yohanis se lèpa, hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu ae sèra lula-nèti Yohanis, na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o miu lami tenge Yohanis ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a èèna, miu pangee, na, paraga dènge dhèu dhu lalole na sèmi ngaa? Tatu miu lami boe ho paraga dènge dhèu dhu roe aai-roe èèla, nuka sèmi kalai èèu dhu bhabheu madhutu lai ngèlu di!<bt>When Yohanis' underlings had gone home, then Yesus spoke with those many people about Yohanis, saying, “When you-pl went looking for Yohanis in that isolated/lonely place over there, what kind of person did you think you were going to meet? Surely you didn't go there to met a person who is swaying back and forth (=conforming), like bamboo that sways.to.and.fro merely following the wind! [CHECK if swaying phrase is known by younger gen.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalole = rupa, bentuk, potongan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lalole = rupa, bentuk, potongan ; roe aai-roe èèla = sway back and forth ; kalai èèu = bambu (umum) ; bhabheu = bagoyang</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Tatu lami boe ho ladhe dhèu dhu pake mèdha-papake dhu kab'ua aae, te dhèu sèmi èèna, era pea na dhodhoka ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae di!<bt>Surely you didn't go there to see a person who wears expensive clothing, cuz people/person like that only stay/live in king's palaces!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malakois himatiois: clothes made from soft"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">malakois himatiois: clothes made from soft fabrics, or for taking it easy en himatismooi endoksooi kai trypheei: with amazing clothing and luxury<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="26" />De miu lami tenge dhèu cee ètu nèi? Miu pangee na lami tenge dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, do? Tare'a! Te nèngu risi nèti ca dhèu nèti padhai lii Lamatua.<bt>So (consequently), who did you go to see over there? Do you think you went to find Father God's spokesperson? True/Correct! But this one is the greatest of God's spokespersons.</bt><v n="27" />Te ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci dhu suri tèke le, na,<bt>Cuz the Clean/Holy Writing writes ahead.of.time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Nanene! Ja'a pua dhèu Ja'a,<bt>'Listen! I am sending/commissioning a person of Mine,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka bhoke j'ara hia Èu.&gt;<bt>to go open the way for You.' [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. identical to Mk. 1:2]</bt><note reference="7:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Meliaki 3:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ètu rai-haha ne, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu kapai risi nèti Yohanis. Te ngaa dhèu dhu ana iiki-iiki ètu talora aae dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, kapai risi nèti Yohanis.&gt;&gt;<bt>In this world, there is not a single person who is greater than Yohanis. But among Father God's people, the person is the very lowest/worthless/least.valued is already greater than Yohanis.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Dhèu dhu tadèngi lii padhai Yesus, rèngu re'a le, peka na, j'ara Lamatua èèna, j'ara mamuri dhu lèke. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu roro bea sèra. Lula rèngu uru èèna abhu sarani aa nanene kahèi lii aj'a-nori nèti Yohanis.<bt>The people who heard that speaking of Yesus', they understood that that path of the Lord's, was the true life path. Tax collectors were also like.that. Because previously Yohanis had baptised and taught them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="edikaioosan ton theon: They declared (or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">edikaioosan ton theon: They declared (or admitted) that God is just, righteous.</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Te ngaa dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi dènge dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi sèra, ro'o boe madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, ra manèngi boe Yohanis sarani si.<bt>But the people from the Parisi religious party and experts in Yahudi religious law/regulations did not want to follow Father God's will2 (=the things of God). That's why they did not request Yohanis to baptise them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca dhèu dèlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ca dhèu dèlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:29-30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 21:32, Lukas 3:12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia Yesus karèi dhèu se'e, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pakasame dhèu-dhèu taa limuri se'e dènge ngaa? Dhèu sèmi ngaa ka see?<bt>So Yesus asked these people, saying, “What should I compare contemporary people with? What kind of people are they?</bt><v n="32" />Rèngu se, èci èèna ka dènge ana-ana dhu madhèdi ètu d'ara pasa. Ra re'a dhoka pa'oo-parodha dènge ka'uu-kamuki, peka na,<bt>They are like children who are sitting.around in the market. They are habitually yelling to.each.other and complaining.to.each, saying, [‘Complain’ from Gk. context, and NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi tiu sakino,<bt>‘We-exc all blew the flute (festively),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu roge boe dènge karej'e.<bt>but you-pl did not dance happily.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ji'i sod'a lii beke dhèu madhe,<bt>Then we sang funeral.wake songs,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu tangi boe.&gt;<bt>but you did not cry.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Te, Yohanis tuka sarani ninu boe èi anggor, aa na d'èi puasa, miu ka'uu-kamuki, peka na, &lt;Nèngu ne nidhu tao!&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Yohanis the Habitual Baptizer did not drink wine, and he liked to fast, and you-pl complain, saying, ‘He is afflicted by evil.spirit/s!’</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa limuri ne, Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, tema kinu èi anggor dènge ku'a roti. Ka miu ka'uu-kamuki, peka na, &lt;Dhèu ne, dhèu gagoo-gagehu! Aa tema mahu! Pa'angalai dènge dhèu roro bea! Aa partei èci dènge dhèu dhu laku-laku boe! Dhu ne'a heka ngi'u na!&gt;<bt>But now I, the Original/Authentic Human, drink wine and eat bread like usual. And you complain, saying, ‘This person is a greedy person! And [he's] a heavy drinker! [He] goes and befriends tax collectors! One party (=friend) with the nobodies! [He] doesn't know how to act properly anymore!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoo-gagehu = balalas, rakus (makan)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">gagoo-gagehu = balalas, rakus (makan)</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Te ngaa mi patadhe lii Ja'a ne! Dhèu dhu re'a mèu, tatu rèngu madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But you-pl just take note of My speaking (=you'll see evidence later)! People who truly/correctly understand, surely they follow the Lord's will2 (=the things of God).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus na'a-ninu ètu èmu Simon<bt>The Lord Yesus eats a feast at Simon's house</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ètu d'ara kota ne, abhu dhèu Parisi ca dhèu, ngara na Simon. Ca lod'o, na nèru Yesus si mai ra'a asa èmu nèngu. Hèia Yesus si lasi madhèdi, ka neo ra'a.<bt>In that city, there was a Parisi person, named Simon. One time, he invited Yesus (collective) to come eat at his house. Then Yeus (coll) went to sit and eat.</bt><v n="37" />Lod'o èèna, bhèni kajeo ca dhèu tadèngi kahèi, na, Yesus si neo ra'a-rinu ètu èèna. Ka na maso la'e, nèd'u dènge èi hèu mèngi ca boto dhu kab'ua aae.<bt>At that time, there was a naughty woman (=prostitute) who heard that Yesus was eating there. So she went in, holding a bottle of fragrant oil that was very expensive.</bt><v n="38" />Na mai padètu dènge Yesus re kabodho Na. Hèia na patitu kètu urutuu na ètu haga Yesus. Na tangi d'ara pèd'a dènge roma iisi, toke èi madha na hae lèke haga Yesus. Ka na seka haga Yesus pake rèu kètu na, aa na loe boe uu haga Yesus kahèi. Èle ka, na pasuti èi hèu mèngi èèna mi haga Yesus.<bt>She came close to Yesus from behind. Then she went and knelt at Yesus' feet. She cried sobbingly until her tears fell onto Yesus' feet. She wiped Yesus' feet using her own hair, and repeatedly kissed Yesus' feet too. Then she poured that fragrant oil on Yesus' feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seka = lap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">seka = lap</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:37-38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:7, Markus 14:3, Yohanis 12:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Simon ne'a mèu j'ara mamuri bhèni ne. Nèti èèna ka, na pajiko ètu d'ara na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e j'aj'i mi tadha, na, Yesus ne, dhèu dhu nèti boe lii padhai Ama Lamatua! Ladhe tare'a-re'a Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Ne mai, tatu Nèngu ne'a, na, bhèni dhu g'ag'e Nèngu ne, bhèni kajeo. Dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, sèmi boe Nèngu ne, lula dhèu mola-mèci bisa boe padètu dènge dhèu kaj'alu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Simon knew that woman's way of life. That's why he thought to himself, “This has become evidence that this Yesus here, is not Father God's spokesperson! If Father God had truly sent Him, surely He would know that that woman who is touching Him there, is a naughty woman. The Father God's spokesperson/s can't be like Him there, because clean/holy people can not be near/associate.with dirty/defiled people!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a ngaa dhu Simon ngee. Ka Na peka, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Simon! Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a neo peka dènge èu ca j'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus knew what Simon was thinking. And He said, “Simon! It's like.this. I want to tell you something.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Simon dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese, peka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Simon answered, saying, “Ok. Father Teacher, go ahead and talk.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ka Yesus core lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu dhu tema hia dhèu pija doi na. Uru èèna, na hia nèdhi dhèu dua pija doi na. Dhèu èci, abhu lèmi ngasu doi iia, aa ca dhèu hari lèmi nguru di.<bt>Then Yesus threw language out at him (=spoke in parables/veiled speech), saying, “There was a person who was a habitual loaner of money to other people. Previously, he had loaned money to two people. To one person, he loaned 500 silver monies, the other person, only just 50.</bt><v n="42" />Te ngaa d'ai lod'o pula doi se'e, dua ra bisa boe b'ae rare. Ka dhèu dhu hia pija, rasa kasia mi rèngu dua ra. Nèti èèna ka, na peka mi dua ra, sèna ka b'ae ia ka kèlu ra sèra. De madhutu èu, nèti dhèu dua se, cee ka dhu sue risi dhèu tema hia dhèu pija doi ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>But when it was time to return that money, the two of them were not able/capable to pay. And that money loaner, felt pity/compassion for the two of them. That's why he told the two of them they no longer needed to pay their debts. So/Now [shift topic], according to you, from those two people, which one loved the habitual money loaner more?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pula doi = pay off debt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pula doi = pay off debt ; kèlu = utang ; hia pija</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Ètu d'ara ciki oo'e na kahèi, Simon dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tatu dhèu dhu kèlu na ae risi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Simon answered straightaway, saying, “Of course the one who had the bigger debt!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus replied, saying, “True/correct!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ka Yesus ladhe bhèni ne, hèia Na peka dènge Simon, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ladhe sèku bhèni ne. Deo na Ja'a maso asa d'ara èmu èu, èu tèke boe èi sèna ka rase haga Ja'a, madhutu ad'a èdhi. Te ngaa bhèni ne pabasa haga Ja'a dènge èi madha na, ka na seka pake rèu kètu na.<bt>Then Yesus turned and faced that woman, and said to Simon, “You have a look at this woman. When I entered into your house, you did not prepare water to wash My feet following our custom. But this woman wetted My feet using her tears, then wiped them clean using her hair. [NOTE: streamlined by removing “who has been kneeling here for a while.” Not needed for participant identification.]</bt><v n="45" />Aa ropa èu soru Ja'a maso asa d'ara èmu èu, èu uu boe Ja'a, madhutu ad'a èdhi. Te ngaa karèi nèti Ja'a ètu d'ara èmu èu, bhèni ne loe boe uu haga Ja'a.<bt>And earlier, when greeting Me coming into your house, you did not kiss Me following our habits. But starting from when I entered this house, this woman has not stopped kissing My feet.</bt><v n="46" />Èu bhèlu eele ad'a dhu palona èi hèu mèngi mi kètu tamu, ropa Ja'a mai deo na. Te ngaa bhèni ne bhori le èi hèu mèngi dhu kab'ua titu kèna mi haga Ja'a.<bt>You also forgot our custom of pouring oil on the head of a guest, when I entered earlier. But this woman has poured fragrant oil that is very expensive on My feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palona = minyaki"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">palona = minyaki</Message></Annotation><v n="47" />Èu nanene paie! Sasala bhèni ne, mema ae. Te ngaa Lamatua saku eele aa'i le, lula na pad'elo le sasue na dènge manèngi makasi ae-ae mi Ja'a. Te ngaa bagi dhèu dhu rasa na tao boe sasala ae, nèngu ngee na parluu boe abhu abho ae kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu ne'a boe sue aa ne'a boe manèngi makasi mi Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen carefully! The wrongs/sins of this woman are truly many. But the Lord has erased them all away, because she has shown her love and feelings of much thankfulness to Me. But a person who considers him/her.self to not have done many wrongs, s/he also does not feel a need for obtaining much forgiveness. That's why s/he does not know how to love, and does not know how to feel thankfulness in return to the Lord.” [EXEG: Trans. Notes, p.164, bottom].</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge bhèni ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a saku eele le sasala èu aa'i-aa'i ra!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke to that woman, saying, “I have erased all your wrongs away!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhèdi ra'a palere-lere, paka'uu, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Huuh! Na ngee na, Nèngu ne cee?! Na bani titu kèna saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu! J'ara ne'e ne dhodhoka Ama Lamatua mesa Na, dhu dènge hak ho saku eele sasala dhèu!&gt;&gt;<bt>All the people who were sitting eating together, began to whisper to each other saying, “Huuh! [=sign of disgust] Who does He think He is? He dares to forgive a person's wrongs! In.actual.fact, only just Father God alone is the one who has the right to erase people's wrongs!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge bhèni ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lula èu lèka le Ja'a, nèti èèna ka Lamatua hia le èu mamuri. Lèpa ka dènge mera-milu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told that woman, saying, “Because you have believed/trusted Me, that's why the Lord has saved you. Go.home in peace!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu bhèni-dhèu bhèni dhu madhutu Lamatua Yesus<bt>Women who follow/accompany the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Nèbhu boe ka Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, dhèu canguru dua sèra, kako palème kota-kota dènge rae-rae ètu sèra. La'e lolo dènge dhèu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Èèna ka dhu j'aj'i lii lolo be'a hia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Not long after that, Yesus and His twelve underlings, were walking around going to the cities and villages there. He went to tell people about Father God's ruling/governing. That is/became good news to all of them.</bt><v n="2" />Ètu d'ara kaboko rèngu, abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu bhèni dhu madhutu. Bhèni se dhu uru èèna abhu rupa-rupa papèd'a, aa cahag'e dhu nidhu tao. Te ngaa Yesus ka dhu puri-pa'èle aa'i si. Nuka sèmi Maria nèti rae Magdala, dhu uru èèna, Yesus bata eele pidhu nidhu nèti nèngu.<bt>In that group there were several women who also followed. These women there were those who were once sick with all.sorts. of sickness, and some who once were afflicted with evil.spirits. But Yesus had healed them all. Like Maria from Magdala village, who previously Yesus had expelled seven evil.spirits out of her.</bt><v n="3" />Abhu kahèi Susana, dènge mama Yohana. Yohana ne, dhèu èmu Kusa. Kusa ne, kapala urusan nèti èmu dhèu aae Herodes. Aa abhu ae kahèi bhèni leo dhu lasi palere-lere dènge Yesus si. Bhèni se pake doi-dhari rèngu mesa ra ho ogo Yesus si ètu j'ara.<bt>There was also Susana, and mama Yohana. This Yohana, was Kusa's wife. Kusa was the manager of raja Herodes' official house/palace. And there were still many other women who travelled together with Yesus (collective). These women used their own money to pay.for/be.responsible.for Yesus (collective)'s costs on the road.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ogo = ongkos (vt) biayai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ogo = ongkos (vt) biayai</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="the house manager"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">the house manager</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:2-3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:55-56, Markus 15:40-41, Lukas 23:49</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu ceb'e hini ètu rupa-rupa rai<bt>Comparison.story about a person who plants seed in various kinds of soil</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:1-9; Markus 4:1-9)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ca tèka, dhèu mai nèti rae-rae ho tenge Yesus. Ropa dhèu ae se pakaboko, hèia Na lolo dènge ra pake lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na,<bt>One time, people came out from many villages to look for Yesus. When many people/a crowd had gathered, He told them a comparison.stories/parable, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ètu mia-mia, ladhe abhu dhèu pakaboko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Ètu mia-mia, ladhe abhu dhèu pakaboko ae-ae, Yesus dèi lolo hia ra pake lii pakasame. Ca tèka, Na lolo sèmi ne'e ka:</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />&lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu sab'a oka-tedhe, dhu la'e ceb'e hini asa d'ara oka na. Hini se cahag'e lèke ètu j'ara. Ropa dhèu kako re èèna, j'èli lèke hini se. Aa manu-bhui mai ka tutu ra'e aa'i.<bt>“There was a farmer went to scatter/broadcast seed in his/her garden. Some of the seed fell on the path. When people walked by there, they stepped all.over those seeds. Then the bird/s came to peck them until completely gone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tutu = 1) toto, 2) pangkas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">tutu = 1) toto, 2) pangkas cabang atau ranting, daun rumah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="para teen hodon: alongside the trail,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">para teen hodon: alongside the trail, right next to the trail</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Hini cahag'e, lèke ètu dedha rai dhu pènu dènge hadhu. Hini se muri, te ngaa nèbhu boe hèia kamale dhae-dhae, lula èi kura.<bt>Some other seeds fell on the rocky soil/land. Those seeds began to sprout/live, but they soon wilted away, because of lacking water.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kamale dhae-dhae = layu sekali"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kamale dhae-dhae = layu sekali</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Hini cahag'e hari lèke ètu era aj'u padhudhu. Te ngaa ropa hini muri, aj'u padhudhu hèlu pamadhe aa'i si.<bt>Some other seeds fell in a thorny plant place. But when those seeds began to sprout/live, the thorn plants/trees pressed in killing them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèlu = belit ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">hèlu = belit ;</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Aa hini dhu leo lèke ètu dedha rai hèu mèngi. Hini se muri dènge sega, toke kapai ka hua. Hua ae titu kèna, d'ai cangasu hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And other seeds fell on the soil which was fertile. They sprouted luxuriantly, then grew becoming big until they fruit-ed. Those seeds gave back a yield one hundred times.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sega = subur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">sega = subur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lolo èle ka, Yesus pa'èle lii pakasame ne, dènge lii dhu mèdhu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu dhu pasa dhilu, na, ngee paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>After finishing story-ing like that, then Yesus locked/closed that comparison.story, and called out, saying, “You-pl who are wearing ears (=paying attention), well, think about.this carefully!” [DISCOURSE: Normally in these lgs, a quote margin signals a change of speaker. So here, giving the function of “closing the parable” is needed to allow any quote margin at all.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka na, nga tao ka Nèngu d'èi pake lii pakasame<bt>The Lord Yesus tells why He likes to use comparison.stories</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:10-17; Markus 4:10-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle èèna ka, ana madhutu Yesus karèi sasoa nèti lii pakasame deo na.<bt>After that, Yesus' underlings asked the meaning of the recent comparison.story.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Lula miu se d'èi madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua dènge d'ara kateme, nèti èèna ka Ja'a peka paled'a, ho miu me'a tasamia Lamatua neo paredha dhèu unu Na. Te ngaa dhèu leo ro'o boe pare'a dènge dad'èi Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a aj'a-nori si pake lii pakasame di. Te dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu suri tèke le, peka na,<bt>He answered, saying, “It's like.this! Because you-pl are wholehearted about following Father God's will2 (the things of God), that's why I will clearly reveal so that you know, how the Lord will command/rule His people. But other people don't want to be concerned about the Lord's will2 (the things of God). That's why I teach them using only comparison.stories. Cuz (elaboration) the Lord's spokesperson has already written ahead.of.time, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Rèngu se rèdhi le,<bt>‘They have seen,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ro'o boe re'a.<bt>but don't want to understand.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rèngu tadèngi le,<bt>They have heard,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ro'o boe sèmi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>but don't want to accept.”’</bt><note reference="8:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 6:9-10</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka sasoa nèti hini deo sa<bt>The Lord Yesus tells the meaning of that comparison.story about seed/s</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:18-23; Markus 4:13-20)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus peka sasoa nèti lii pakasame ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hini se, nuka Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then Yesus told that comparison.story's meaning, saying, “That seed, it is Father God's Words/Teachings/Advice (broad range).</bt><v n="12" />Hini dhu lèke ètu j'ara, nuka dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, te ngaa dhèu aae nidhu mai parame nare nèti d'ara rèngu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu parcaya boe Lamatua, aa abhu boe mamuri.<bt>That seed which fell on the path, that is people who hear the Lord's Words, but then the evil.spirit's king comes and snatches away those Words from their insides. In that way, they don't believe in the Lord, and don't get/obtain life/salvation.</bt><v n="13" />Hini dhu lèke dedha hadhu, nuka dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dènge d'ara karej'e. Te ngaa amo na marèma boe. Rèngu parcaya, te ngaa ropa paraga dènge j'aj'èra, rèngu manahu.<bt>That seed which fell on the rocks, that's people who hear the Lord's Word's happily. But their roots don't go deep inside. They believe, but if/when they encounter/experience difficulty/suffering, they fall.</bt><v n="14" />Hini dhu lèke era aj'u padhudhu, nuka dhèu dhu tadèngi, ka ra sèmi rare Lii Lolo Be'a. Te ngaa nare nèbhu boe, ka rèngu bhèlu eele Lii Lolo Be'a, lula rèngu bhute dènge laladhe sasab'a-la'a rèngu, mèdha-panyau rèngu, aa dènge neo mamuri karej'e di. Nèti èèna ka, parcaya rèngu dènge boe kab'ua ngaa-ngaa.<bt>That seed which fell on that thorny place, is like people who hear and receive the Good News. But not long and they completely forget those Words, because they are more worried/thinking about their own affairs, and their various kinds of possessions, and they want to just live happily/pleasantly. That's why that faith of theirs, doesn't have any value at all.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhute = batasibu, barepot ; unu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">bhute = batasibu, barepot ; unu boe ngaa-ngaa</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Te ngaa hini dhu lèke ètu dedha rai hèu mèngi, nuka dhèu dhu mamuri mola dènge d'ara hua iia. Ropa rèngu tadèngi Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua, rèngu sèle asa d'ara rèngu. Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu parcaya taa-taa, aa ad'u-ue j'ara dhu be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the seed which fell on that fertile soil, that is people whose lives are straight/righteous and who have good insides/character. When they hear Father God's Good News, then they store them carefully in their livers. In that way, they keep believing, and do many things which are good.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii upama nèti saguru labhu pake èru rai<bt>Comparison.story about covering a lamp using a clay pot</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 4:21-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka Yesus peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ètu mia, dhèu paheo rare labhu iiki, ho èèna na saguru dènge èru rai. Aa abhu ètu mia, dhèu tao labhu ètu ro'a koi. Te ladhe tao sèmi èèna, dhèu bisa boe rèdhi heo na. Labhu dhu guna, nuka padhèdi ètu era dedha, sèna ka heo na bisa pasaraa dhèu dhu maso mai.<bt>Then Yesus spoke again, saying, “It's not possible that people light a lamp/lantern, then cover it over with a clay pot. And no one puts a lamp underneath the bed. Cuz (elaboration) if [someone] does like.that, people cannot see its light anymore. A lamp which is useful, is set in a high place, so that its radiance/light illuminates the people who come in.</bt><note reference="8:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:15, Lukas 11:33</note><v n="17" />Èci èèna kahèi dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu pahuni limuri ne, bèli-camèd'a pasabhoka. Aa madha j'ara-madha j'ara dhu dhèu re'a boe limuri ne, èèna na dhèu bisa re'a mèu.<bt>That's also like everything that is hidden now, will later become obvious. And everything that people do not know now, later people will be able to know clearly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sabhoka = revealed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">sabhoka = revealed</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:26, Lukas 12:2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />De miu hud'i pangee paie-iie ku j'ara se'e. Dhèu dhu neo tenge tare'a-re'a dad'èi Lamatua, nèngu asa d'èlu-mèu. Te ngaa rèngu dhu pusi pahae boe dad'èi Lamatua, rèngu asa goa.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), you-pl must think carefully about these things. A person who truly wants to know the Lord's will (=the things of the Lord), s/he will increase in knowledge/wisdom. But the person who is not concerned with the Lord's will, he increases in stupidity.” [TEXT: Gk. identical to Mk. 4:25]. [EXEG: context is about wisdom and spiritual understanding (about the Kingdom). TN on this verse, also Gundry on Mark; Marshall on Luke thinks it's about knowledge about teaching.]</bt><note reference="8:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:29, Markus 4:25, Lukas 19:26</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Cee ka dhu tare'a-re'a a'ari Lamatua Yesus?<bt>Who is really the Lord Yesus' family?</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:46-50; Markus 3:31-35)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ca tèka, Yesus bhute dènge dhèu ae. Hèia ina dènge ari Na mai neo paraga dènge Ne. Te ngaa ra bisa boe lasi padètu, lula dhèu se, ae titu kèna.<bt>One time, Yesus was busy/preoccupied with many people. Then His mother and his younger.siblings came to meet with Him. But they could not get close, because there were too many people.</bt><v n="20" />Ka abhu dhèu la'e peka dènge Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ina dènge ari Ama, ètu li'u sèi. Ra neo paraga dènge Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then a person went and told Yesus, saying, “Father! Father's mother and younger.siblings are outside. They want to meet with Father.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Te ngaa sèmi ne'e. Ina dènge a'ari Ja'a, nuka rèngu dhu tare'a-re'a d'èi nanene Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua, aa tao madhutu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He replied, saying, “Yes! But it's like this. My mother and siblings, are people who trully like to listen to Father God's Words, and then follow/obey them.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pamau ngèlu aae<bt>The Lord Yesus calms the great wind (=storm)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:23-27; Markus 4:35-41)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ca lod'o, Yesus gale dhèu pajuu-paleha Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati ka asa cabèka dano.&gt;&gt; Ka ra ca'e koha cue, hèia pakèd'i lasi.<bt>One time, Yesus invited His underlings, saying, “Let's us-inc get in the boat, to go to the lake's other side.” And they got in a boat, to begin to go.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamau = bekin tado, kasi tanang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pamau = bekin tado, kasi tanang</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Ropa rèngu ètu talora dano, Yesus bhèj'i. Nèbhu boe cag'ag'a laa, ngèlu aae mai. Naha tèb'e koha, hèia èi maso sa d'ara, ka oe molo.<bt>When they were in the middle of the lake, Yesus slept. Not long then, a great wind (storm) came. Waves beat the boat, and water came inside, and they nearly sank.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèu = fits salt water better"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">lèu = fits salt water better</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ana madhutu se parèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama! Kèd'i ho tolong ku laa! Te èdhi madhe aa'i kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Seeing like.that, then the underlings woke Him up, saying, “Father! Father! Wake.up and help! We-inc are about to all die!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus kèd'i. Hèia Na kai ngèlu dènge naha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mau ka!&gt;&gt; Kaca'a laa, ngèlu dènge naha mau dènge ka.<bt>And Yesus woke up/got up. Then He scolded/forbade/rebuked the wind and waves, saying, “Calm down!” Suddenly, the waves and the wind became calm immediately.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Na pasanèd'e ana-ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu parcaya mèka Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He reminded/warned His underlings, saying, “Why do you still not believe in Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rèngu madha'u dènge malaa, ka ra pakarèi èci dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Cee ka Yesus ne? Tasamia ka Nèngu bisa paredha ngèlu dènge naha, ka ra madhutu dad'èi Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>They were afraid and amazed. Then they asked each.other, saying, “Who is this Yesus? How is it that He can command the wind and waves, so they follow/obey His will?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus babège eele nidhu nèti dhèu huj'u<bt>The Lord Yesus expels evil.spirits from a crazy person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:28-34; Markus 5:1-20)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Nèbhu boe rèngu d'ai rai Garasa, ètu sebhe dano Galilea.<bt>Not long again, they arrived at Garasa region, on lake Galilea's other side.</bt><note reference="8:26" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi, peka na, &lt;Garasa&gt;. Abhu kahèi sasuri cahag'e dhu suri na, &lt;Gadara&gt;. Aa abhu kahèi dhu suri na, &lt;Gergesa&gt;.<bt>The best Yunani language writings write, saying, ‘Garasa’. There are some writings which write, saying, ‘Gadara’. And there are some others which write, saying, ‘Gergesa’.</bt></note><v n="27-29" />Ètu era ne'e, dhèu èci dhu nèbhu ae le, nidhu ae pahuj'u ne. Dhèu ne dènge boe èmu, ka na pea ètu era ro'a dhèu madhe. Bèli-bèli èèna kako la'e-mai, dhu pake boe mèdha-papake. Te nidhu sèra loe boe paredha ne. Dhèu dhu èki le pèri-pèri hari dènge rate aa pakanau ne dènge kanau bèsi, te ngaa na lèku èta si. Ka nidhu se laka-seti ne ho la'e asa era dhu kaliu.<bt>There, there was a person who had been afflicted for a long time by evil.spirits. He did not have a house, and he only lived just in the graveyard. Everyday he went hither and thither without wearing any clothes. Cuz (elaboration) the evil.spirits continually ordered him around. People had tied him over and over with chains and iron bracelets, but he would just break them apart. Then the evil.spirits habitually forced him to run to isolated/deserted place/s.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kanau = galang ; lèku ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kanau = galang ; lèku = patah ; èta = potong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Yesus si puru nèti dedha koha, ka dhèu huj'u ne mai asa Yesus. Hèia na pa'oo-parodha. Ka na pabèbhe iisi, aa na patitu kètu urutuu ètu haga Yesus. Hèia Yesus paredha nidhu sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee, nidhu! Rai eele nèti dhèu ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus (collective) got out of the boat, that crazy person came to Him. That person yelled, then threw himself kneeling at Yesus' feet. Then Yesus ordered, saying, “Hey, evil.spirit! Come out of this person!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu huj'u ne pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku gagu ja'a! Te ja'a ke'a Èu ne Yesus, Ana nèti Ama Lamatua dhu Dedha Risi Eele! Èu baku paj'èra ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that crazy person yelled, saying, “Don't bother me! Cuz (elaboration) I know that You here are Yesus, the Child of the highest Father God! You don't torture/ill.treat me!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagagai = bakorek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pagagai = bakorek</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akathartos: unclean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">akathartos: unclean</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka Yesus karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Ngara èu cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked him, saying, “What is your name?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia nidhu se dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">Legion,</span> te ji'i se ae, sèmi sordad'u riho-riho.&gt;&gt; Na lii sèmi èèna, lula nidhu se ae-ae dhu maso ètu d'ara ngi'u dhèu èèna.<bt>Then that/those evil.spirit/s answered, saying, “<span class="Italic">Legion,</span> cuz we-exc are many, like thousands of soldiers.” He said like.that, because there were many evil.spirits who entered in and stayed inside him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Nidhu se loe boe pamako Yesus, sèna ka baku pua rèngu lasi asa d'ara Ro'a J'aj'èra, nuka era taha koasa bhabhelu-katub'a.<bt>Those evil.spirits continually asked over.and.over to Yesus to not ordered them to go to the Torture Hole, that is the place of detaining the powers of evil. [EXEG: Marshall; CEV also explicates in verse. NOTE to daughter translations: If made direct quote, perhaps explication should be put in ftn, since this is fast-moving narrative.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuka era jaj'èra nidhu."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">nuka era jaj'èra nidhu.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Te ngaa dhu padètu ètu èèna, hahi canau kateme dhu nyuu rai ètu sebhe ledhe. Ka nidhu se manèngi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pua la ji'i maso asa d'ara hahi sèi!&gt;&gt; Hèia Yesus d'èi kahèi.<bt>But nearby there, there was a big group of pigs who were rooting around on the side/slope of the mountain. Then those evil.spirits asked Yesus, saying, “Just order us-exc to enter into those pigs!” And Yesus was agreeable.</bt><v n="33" />Ka nidhu se kalua ka nèti d'ara dhèu mone ne, lasi maso asa hahi. Hahi se aa'i-aa'i ra huj'u, ka ra rai paj'ala puru nèti sebhe ledhe ne, hèia caroco asa d'ara dano. Aa cène, ka madhe aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Then, those evil.spirits come out and left that male, and they entered into those pigs. Those pigs all became crazy, and they ran helter-skelter down that mountain, then slid/fell into the lake. Then they all died drowning. [NOTE to daughter translations: There is no cliff around Galilee, but there are steep banks, so make sure your word matches steep slope /gunung pung pinggir/ or just /pinggir/. /Jurang/ creates too much noise. Match Mark 5:13.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paj'ala = tidak teratur ; cène"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">paj'ala = tidak teratur ; cène = tenggelam = molo ; caroco = tergelincir, KM = taroso</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoa lasi asa dara dano."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pasoa lasi asa dara dano.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, dhèu madhenge hahi se, rai lasi palème rae-rae ètu sèra, lolo aa'i-aa'i ngaa dhu j'aj'i.<bt>Seeing like.that then, the habitual guarders of the pigs ran to all the villages around there, and they told everything that had happened.</bt><v n="35" />Ropa dhèu ètu rae se tadèngi lii lolo se, ka lasi ae-ae sèna ka neo rèdhi unu ra tatao dhu j'aj'i le. D'ai era èèna, rèngu ladhe, na, dhèu dhu nidhu tao èèna, madhèdi mau-mau padètu ètu haga Yesus. Nèngu pake le mèdha-papake, aa na huj'u heka. Ladhe rèdhi sèmi ne'e, ka aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i madha'u.<bt>Hearing their story like.that, many people in the village come out to that place, so they could see for themselves what had happened. Arriving there, they saw that person who was/had.been afflicted by evil.spirits/s was sitting quietly near Yesus' feet. He had clothes on, and his craziness was gone/disappeared. Seeing like.that, then they all became afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Note @@ grammar of 2nd clause"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Note @@ grammar of 2nd clause</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Hèia dhèu-dhèu dhu ladhe rèdhi ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne, ra palolo dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu heka mai sèra, tasamia ka dhèu huj'u ne èle nèti papèd'a na.<bt>Then the people who had seen that event, told the people who had just come how it happened that that crazy person had become well again.</bt><v n="37" />Ka dhèu Garasa aa'i-aa'i ra manèngi Yesus ho tèke eele rai rèngu, te rèngu madha'u titu kèna.<bt>Then all the Garasa people who lived in that area, requested Yesus that He go leaving them, cuz they all were very afraid.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus si ca'e lasi asa dedha koha, sèna ka lèpa hari asa cabèka dano Galilea.<bt>Then Yesus (collective) went into the boat, to go back again to the other side of Galilea lake.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Te ngaa dhèu deo na dhu nidhu tao, loe boe pamako Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Hud'i laa ja'a madhutu Ama kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>But that person who previously been afflicted by evil.spirits, repeatedly begged/insisted Yesus, saying, “Father! Allow that I also go with Father!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yesus dhaa ne, peka na,<bt>But Yesus replied, saying,</bt><v n="39" />&lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ku laa! Be'a risi èu lèpa ka asa a'ari èu. Lamu lolo aa'i dènge ra, na, Ama Lamatua tao le j'ara dhu be'a hia èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>“It's like this! It's better (=polite imperative) you go.home to your family, to tell them about Father God's goodness, which He has done for you.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara hua iia Ama Lamatua, dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dara hua iia Ama Lamatua, dhu tao pa'èle le èu nèti papèda.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu ne kako palème d'ara kota ne, na palolo dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, peka na, Yesus ka dhu pa'èle nèngu.<bt>Then, that person went all around that city, and he told all the people about Yesus healing him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pamamuri hari ana bhèni nèti Yairus, aa pa'èle bhèni èci dhu lèke papèd'a bhèni<bt>The Lord Yesus brings Yairus' daughter back to life, and heals a woman who was afflicted with a women's disease</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 9:18-26; Markus 5:21-43)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus si lasi hari dènge koha asa cabèka dano Galilea. Lod'o rèngu puru nèti dedha koha, dhèu ae dhu mate mema le Yesus. Dhèu se mai ae-ae ho soru Ne.<bt>Then Yesus (collective) went by boat back to lake Galilea's other side. When they got out of the boat, many people were already waiting for Him. They came crowding around to welcome Him.</bt><v n="41-42" />Ètu ne'e abhu ca dhèu, ngara na Yairus. Nèngu kapala èmu manèngi-mangaj'i ètu d'ara kota ne. Ana na dhoka ca dhèu di; ana bhèni, umur na canguru dua tèu. Ana bhèni ne dhu pèd'a aae, oe madhe. Ropa Yairus nèdhi Yesus mai, hèia la'e patitu kètu urutuu na ètu madha Yesus. Na manèngi ho Yesus dhuli èmu na, sèna ka puri-pa'èle ana na.<bt>There also, was a person, named Yairus. He was the head of the worship house in that city. His child, was only one single child; a daughter, twelve years old. That daughter was very sick almost dead. When Yairus saw Yesus' coming, he went and knelt in front of Yesus. He requested that Yesus stop by his house, to heal his daughter.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhaa nare ka, Yesus madhutu dènge ne asa èmu na. Aa dhèu ae madhutu rèngu. Ka rèngu paseti èci dènge èci.<bt>After responding to him, Yesus followed/accompanied him to his house. And many people also followed them (with bustle, festively). And/so they walked pushing.and.shoving each other.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Abhu kahèi dhèu bhèni èci dhu kako dènge rèngu. Bhèni ne dhu lèke papèd'a dhèu bhèni dhu loe boe canguru dua tèu kèna. Doi-dhari dènge mèdha-panyau na èle aa'i le, ho b'ae dote-matarii. Te ngaa abhu boe dhu bisa puri-pa'èle ne. Papèd'a na asa na hoe.<bt>There was also a woman who walked following them. She had a women's disease that had not stopped correctly for twelve years. She had already spent all here money and possessions, to pay the doctors (doublet). But there was no one who could heal her. That illness of her's, continued to relapse continually. [EXEG: Last sentence implied from “no one could cure her”; NOTE to daughter tranlations: Gk TEXT: UBS 4th edition, AGNT, NRSV, NLT, CEV has info on physicians in text. TB2 has info on physicians in brackets. Some Gk manuscripts do not have it at all. NIV puts it in a ftn. Marshall notes “which is sufficiently different in wording from Mk. to suggest that it may be an original part of Luke's text”. FTN added.]</bt><note reference="8:43" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu sasuri lii Yunani, cahag'e dhu suri boe, &lt;&lt;Doi-dhari dènge mèdha-panyau na èle aa'i le ho b'ae dote-matarii.&gt;&gt;<bt>Some Yunani writings don't write “She had already spent all her money and possessions, to pay the doctors.”</bt></note><v n="44" />Ka na ara padètu-dètu asa Yesus nèti kabodho. Hèia na gai lèke suu kodho Yesus. Ropa na gai lèke kodho Yesus ne, hèia papèd'a na èle dènge ka.<bt>Then she came close to Yesus from behind. Then2 she touched the edge of Yesus' clothing. When she had touched Yesus' clothing, then2 her unrestrained blood stopped immediately.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Cag'ag'a laa, Yesus titu taha. Hèia Na karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu goi lèke Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Unexpectedly Yesus stopped walking temporarily (lit: stood), then He asked, saying, “Who was it who touched Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu mangaku. Ka Petrus b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Dhèu ae-ae ka dhu tao paseti aa patule-pajuku nèti kabodho. Sèmi ne'e ne, te'a na cee ka dhu goi lèke Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>But not a single person acknowledged/confessed. Then Petrus said, “Father! So many people are jostling and shoving (doublet) from behind. In that way, there's no way of knowing who touched Father!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="&lt;&lt;Ama! Dhèu ae-ae dhu tao paseti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">&lt;&lt;Ama! Dhèu ae-ae dhu tao paseti sèmi ne'e ne, te'a na cee ka dhu goi lèke Èu! Rèngu se ka dhu patule-pajuku nèti kabodho.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Deo na Ja'a rasa abhu koasa dhu kalua nèti ngi'u Ja'a. De Ja'a ke'a, na, ca dhèu dhu sangaja gai Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke to him, “No! I recently/just felt power which went out of Me. So (consequently), I know there was a person who purposefully touched Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ropa bhèni ne ne'a, na, nèngu bisa boe pasili, hèia na madha'u titu kèna. Isi na rèbha-rèbha, ka la'e patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Yesus. Hèia na lolo mi dhèu ae sèra, nga tao ka nèngu gai Yesus. Aa na lolo kahèi, na, ropa nèngu gai lèke Yesus, nèngu èle dènge nèti papèd'a na.<bt>When that woman was aware that she could not hide/deny it, then she was very afraid. She trembled, and knelt before Yesus. Then she storied in from of many people why she touched Yesus. Then3 she also told that, exactly when she touched Yesus, she was healed immediately of her disease.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèbha-rèbha = gamatar ; gai ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">rèbha-rèbha = gamatar ; gai = touch intentionally ; goi = touch accidentally</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hèia na lolo ètu madha dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Hèia na lolo ètu madha dhèu ae-ae sèra nga tao ka nèngu gai Yesus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana hèni! Èu èle nèti papèd'a, lula èu parcaya Ja'a. Lèpa ka dènge mera-milu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke to her, saying, “Sister! You are healed of your disease, because you believed in Me. Go home in peace (doublet)!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Lod'o Yesus padhai lii era dènge bhèni ne, ca dhèu nèti Yairus mai peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Ana ama aad'o heka. Na madhe le, de paj'èra ia ka Ama Mese.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus was still speaking with that woman, then one of Yairus' people came and told him saying, “Father, ee! Father's child is no more (=is dead)! She has died, so it's not neccessary to bother Father Teacher anymore.” [NOTE to daughter translations: make sure /kasi tau sang dia/ traces to Yairus, not Jesus (who is gramatically in focus). If read beyond quote margin it's almost impossible to link to anyone except Yairus.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalicu = ana kacil (Lii Pacele)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kalicu = ana kacil (Lii Pacele) 2) buah yg masih muda</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca dhèu nèti Yairus mai peka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ca dhèu nèti Yairus mai peka dènge ne,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Te ngaa ropa Yesus tadèngi nare lii peka dhèu èèna, hèia Yesus lii dènge Yairus, &lt;&lt;Mau-mau! Baku madha'u! Parcaya mi Ama Lamatua di. Nèngu ka dhu hia mamuri mi ana èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But when Yesus heard that person's report, then He said to Yairus, “Be calm! Don't be afraid! Just believe in Father God. He is the one who saves/gives life to your child.” [EXEG: Gk. is the word for ‘saved’ here, although Eng. trans have ‘healed’, but 'healed' doesn't collocate in Dhao with a dead person--‘saved/give life to’ does.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51-53" />Ropa rèngu d'ai èmu Yairus, dhèu ae le. Ra tangi dènge d'ara pèd'a. Ka Yesus kai si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ae eele ka tangi laa! Ana ne madhe boe. Dhoka na bhèj'i di!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they arrived at Yairus' house, people where already full/crowded.in there. They were crying sobbingly. Then Yesus scolded/rebuked them, saying, “Stop crying already! This child is not dead. She is only just sleeping!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dhèu se pahae boe, ra mari pakapengo hèb'a, te rèngu rèdhi unu ra ana ne ma'ète a'ae. Hèia Yesus manèngi sèna ka ina-ama nèti ana bhèni ne, Petrus, Yohanis dènge Yakobis maso lasi palere-lere dènge Ne. Dhèu leo sèra, Na hia si mate ètu li'u.<bt>But they only just laughed with a crooked mouth at Him (-mocking, cynically), cuz (elaboration) they were the ones who had seen for themselves that child's last breath. Then Yesus requested that daughter's mother-father, Petrus, Yohanis and Yakobis to go in together with Him. The others He told to just stay outside.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakapengo hèb'a = olok, sinis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pakapengo hèb'a = olok, sinis</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kategeloon (imperfect): they were laughing him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">kategeloon (imperfect): they were laughing him down, ridiculing him. Not mockery ("make fun"), just reacting to how he could be so dumb. While they were doing that, Jesus went ahead and brought her back to life.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Rare d'ara, ka Yesus kèpe ai ana ne, hèia Na paroa peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana! Kèd'i ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>They entered, then Yesus held that child's hand, and called, saying, “Child! Get up!”</bt><v n="55" />Cag'ag'a laa, ana ne mamuri hari, ka na kèd'i titu. Hèia Yesus lii dènge ina ana bhèni ne, na, &lt;&lt;Hia ana ne na'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Unexpectedly/suddenly that child lived again, and she got/woke up immediately. Then Yesus told that daughter's mother saying, “Give this child food!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pneuma: in this case, &quot;her life&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">pneuma: in this case, "her life"</Message></Annotation><v n="56" />Ina-ama ana ne malaa-maloha. Te ngaa Yesus pasanèd'e si, baku palolo dènge dhèu, ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne.<bt>Her mother-father were very surprised (doublet). But Yesus reminded/warned them, to not tell people about what had happened.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pua ana madhutu Na dhèu canguru dua sèra pakako sasab'a Na<bt>The Lord Yesus sends His twelve underlings to go carry out His work</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:5-15; Markus 6:7-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, Yesus pakaboko nare ana madhutu Na, dhèu canguru dua sèra. Ka Na hia si koasa, ho babège eele nidhu, aa puri-pa'èle dhèu nèti rupa-rupa èi papèd'a.<bt>One time, Yesus gathered his twelve underlings. Then He gave them power/authority to expel evil.spirits, and to heal sick people from all sorts of illnesses.</bt><v n="2" />Na pua si lasi lole j'ara-j'ara paredha Ama Lamatua, aa puri-pa'èle papèd'a dhèu ètu mia-mia.<bt>He sent them to go tell people about the ways of Father God's governing/ruling, to heal sick people everywhere.</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa Na peka dènge si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e paie-iie! Baku mèti kahèi ngaa-ngaa ètu j'ara. Kako dhoka dènge kodho ètu ua di. Baku mèti kodho silu. Baku mèti kahèi tatea, tas, gee j'ara, do doi-dhari!<bt>But (contrary to expectation) He told them saying, “Remember well! You do not need to take anything on the road/journey. Travel just with a shirt/dress on your body. Don't take a change of clothes. Don't bring a walking.stick, or a bag, travel.food, or money!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gee j'ara = bakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">gee j'ara = bakal</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ladhe d'ai ka d'ara rae èci, abhu dhèu dhu soru miu, na lami pea dènge ne. Mage mi hag'e-hag'e èmu kahèi. Pea taruu ètu d'ara èmu èèna, toke miu pakèd'i, tèke eele rae èèna.<bt>If/when you-pl enter into a village, there are person/people who welcome you, well, just go stay with him. Don't be picky.selecting a house. Keep staying in that house, until you leave that village.</bt><v n="5" />Ladhe miu maso asa d'ara rae èci, hèia dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra ro'o boe sèmi miu, aa ro'o boe nanene lii padhai miu, na, pakèd'i tèke eele rae èèna. Lod'o miu tèke eele rae èèna, tao madhutu ad'a ho caro eele ahu nèti haga miu. Aa mi peka dènge ra, &lt;Miu se ladhe mo'o boe nanene lii ji'i, pe miu sèmi mere pala mi!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>If/when you enter into a village, and the people there do not want to receive and don't want to listen to what you have to say, well, just leave that village behind. If/when you leave there, do according to the custom of brushing off the dust from your feet. Tell them, saying, ‘You don't want to hear what we have to say, so, may it be that you carry the responsibility/consequences yourselves!”’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhaa pala = manyaot bosong pung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dhaa pala = manyaot bosong pung bagian = sèmi mere (more frequent)</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:3-5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:4-11; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 13:51</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Èle ka, ana madhutu se lasi ka asa rae-rae. Ra lole dènge dhèu-dhèu Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua. Aa puri-pa'èle kahèi dhèu nèti papèd'a ètu mia-mia.<bt>Afterwards then, those underlings went traveling from village to village. They told people about Father God's Good News. And they also healed sick people everywhere.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae Herodes bingu lula Yesus<bt>King Herodes is confused about who the Lord Yesus is</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 14:1-12; Markus 6:14-29)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ca tèka, rupa-rupa lii lolo lula-nèti Yesus ne d'ai le dhèu aae Herodes Antipas.<bt>One time, all.sorts.of stories about Yesus had arrived at king Herodes Antipas'.</bt><note reference="9:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Herodes Antipas ne, ana nèti Herodes Kapai. Herodes Kapai èèna ka pua pamadhe ana iiki-ana iiki ètu Betlehem lèke dènge lod'o rara iisi Lamatua Yesus. Ladhe ètu Mateos 2:16-18.<bt>That Herodes Antipas, was the Great Herodes' child. That Great Herodes was the one who ordered to murder kill the small children in Bethlehem at the time of the Lord Yesus' birth. See Mateos 2:16-18.</bt></note>Ropa na tadèngi lii lolo se, hèia na bingu, lula dhèu cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus ne, nuka Yohanis tuka sarani, dhu mamuri hari le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing those stories, he became confused, because there were some people who said, “That Yesus, is Yohanis the Habitual Baptizer who has come back to life.”</bt><v n="8" />Aa cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, baki Elia dhu mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>There were some others who said, “He's Gf Elia who has lived again.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Abhu dhu leo hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, ca dhèu nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu uru-uru sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>And there were still others who said, “He is one of the Lord's other spokespersons from long.ago.”</bt><note reference="9:7-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:14, Markus 8:28, Lukas 9:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa Herodes sanèd'e era, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ca hari ni, ja'a pua le poro pama'ète kètu Yohanis. De na mamuri hari, do? Aa ca dhèu ne, cee hari?&gt;&gt; Ka na tenge j'ara, sèna ka patoo madha dènge Yesus.<bt>But Herodes remembered, saying, “A while ago, I gave the order to cut off Yohanis' head. Is he now alive again, or what? Then this one here, who else is he?” And so he tried to find a way to meet Yesus face to face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patoo madha = meet face to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">patoo madha = meet face to face</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus panga'a lèmi riho dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus feeds five thousand people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 14:13-21; Markus 6:30-44; Yohanis 6:1-14)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ca lod'o, ana madhutu dhu Yesus pua sèra, lèpa mai pa'èci hari dènge Ne. Ra lolo dènge Ne aa'i-aa'i dhu rèngu tao. Ka Yesus si kako mesa-mesa ra asa era èci, dhu padètu dènge rae Betsaida, ho ra ae ètu èèna.<bt>One time, those underlings which Yesus had sent out, they returned to unite again with Him. They told Him everything which they had done. Then Yesus mob went by themselves to a place near Betsaida village, so that they could rest there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kako mau-mau = jalan santai ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kako mau-mau = jalan santai ;</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Te ngaa dhèu ae dhu re'a rare, na, Yesus si neo lasi sa mia, ka ra paki'u re limuri. Yesus sèmi si, hèia Na pa'èle dhèu pèd'a aa'i-aa'i, aa Na peka-padhai dènge ra, j'ara-j'ara Ama Lamatua nèd'u paredha.<bt>But many people found out where Yesus mob were going, so they tailed along after Him. Yesus accepted them, and He healed all the sick people, and He told them about Father God's holding rule (=things of God). [GRAMM: reversed order because of grammatical clash of complement clauses].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paki'u = jalan iko balakang (vulgar);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">paki'u = jalan iko balakang (vulgar); sangèd'u = cium supaya tau bau karmana, tes ciom</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa d'ai lod'o nihia, ka canguru dua ana madhutu Yesus sèra, peka dènge Ne, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi Ama pua dhèu se'e lasi asa rae-rae dhu padètu dènge era ne'e, sèna ka ra tenge nganga'a unu ra. Aa hud'i laa ra lasi tenge era ho j'unu taha. Te era dhu kaj'èu nèti rae sèmi ne'e, tasamia ka rèngu bisa abhu ra'a-rinu?&gt;&gt;<bt>When it was late.afternoon, then Yesus' twelve underlings, brought a suggestion to Him, saying, “It's better Father (=you) to send these people to go to the villages near here, so they can find their own food. And let them go look for a place to sleep overnight. Cuz (elaboration) in a place far from villages like.this, how are they able to eat (doublet)?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="era goro-b'adha = tampa yang sonde"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">era goro-b'adha = tampa yang sonde ada orang (not widely known)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Miu ka dhu panga'a si!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied saying, “Like.this! You-pl be the ones who feed them!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ana madhutu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ama, ee! Tasamia bisa sèmi èèna? Dhèu se risi nèti lèmi riho dhèu! Èèna dhèu mone di, ige mèka bhèni dènge ana niki! Ètu d'ara adhe-aai ji'i, abhu dhoka roti lèmi bua, dènge i'a dua ngi'u di. Ladhe Ama neo sèna ka ji'i panga'e dhèu se'e, tasa mera mia ho ji'i hèli nganga'a ae-ae hia ra?!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the underlings responded, saying, “Ira èèi! [+protest] Father, ee! How can we do like.that? These people here, there's more than five thousand of them! That only just the men, not yet counting the women and children! And in our-exc hands there is just five pieces (counter) of bread, and just two tails (counter) of fish. If Father wants us to feed these people, how is it that we can buy lots.and.lots of food for them?!”</bt><note reference="9:13-14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Pakaboko si madhèdi lèmi nguru-lèmi nguru dhèu, ca kaboko.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus responded, “Group these people to sit gathered in fifties per one group.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia lasi tao sèmi èèna.<bt>So they went to do like.that.</bt><v n="16" />Ropa dhèu se madhèdi, ka Yesus nare roti lèmi bua dènge i'a dua ngi'u sèra. Ka Na tangara sa dedha, ho Na manèngi makasi. Èle ka Yesus pamae roti dènge i'a sèra. Hèia Na j'ole sa ana-ana madhutu Na, ho papala mi dhèu-dhèu sèra.<bt>When they had sat.down, then Yesus took those five pieces of bread and two tails of fish. Then He looked up to the sky, to give thankyou. Then He broke up that bread and fish. And He extended them to his underling to go divide out to those people.</bt><v n="17" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i se ra'a toke bècu. Ka nganga'a dhu risi sèra, kaboko rare pènu canguru dua soe.<bt>They all ate until they were full. Then, they gathered that leftover food, to the point that there were twelve baskets full. [NOTE: Gk term here same as in Mrk 6:43.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hahake = lebi besar dari bakul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">hahake = lebi besar dari bakul ; soe used in Mark, Gk term the same in both books.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus mulai ne'a mèu, na, Lamatua Yesus, nuka Kristus<bt>Petrus starts to be aware that the Lord Yesus is Kristus, that is, the Person whom Father God had promised ahead.of.time from long.ago</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 16:13-19; Markus 8:27-29)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ca tèka, Yesus la'e mesa Na ho sabaj'a ètu era èci. Hèia ana madhutu Na mai ka pa'èci dènge Ne. Sabaj'a nare, ka Yesus karèi si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu tadèngi-tadèngi dhèu palolo na Ja'a ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Yesus was alone praying at a place. Then His underlings gathered together with Him. After praying, then He asked them, saying, “You-pl hear people talking about me, who are they saying I am?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = sadar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">mase'a = sadar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia ra dhaa, &lt;&lt;Cahag'e peka na, Yohanis tuka sarani. Aa cahag'e peka na, baki Elia. Ladhe aad'o, na, ca dhèu nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra dhu mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>They answered saying, “There are those who say Yohanis the Habitual Baptiser. Others say, grandfather Elia. If not, then, one of Father God's spokespersons from long.ago who has lived again.”</bt><note reference="9:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:1-2, Markus 6:14-15, Lukas 9:7-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia Yesus karèi hari si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu a'abhu miu, na, Ja'a ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked them again, saying, “According to you-pl yourselves, na, who am I?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Petrus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ama ne, Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u karèi nèti uru ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus replied, saying, “Father here is Kristus, that is the Person whom Father God appointed/designated ahead.of.time long.ago.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ho khriston tou theou: only here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">ho khriston tou theou: only here</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 6:68-69</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle ka Yesus kai si, sèna ka baku ale dènge dhèu èci sa, peka na, Nèngu na, Kristus.<bt>Then Yesus forbade them to not tell anyone that He was Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ale = sebut, kasi tau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">ale = sebut, kasi tau</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka j'ara mamadhe, dènge mamuri hari Na<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks about His death, and His living again</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 16:21-28; Markus 8:31--9:1)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Ja'a hud'i pasae ku rupa-rupa j'aj'èra dhu bia. Bèli-camèd'a dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi, kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra, ro'o boe sèmi, ladhe peka, na, Ja'a ne Kristus. Aa èèna na, ra pamadhe Ja'a. Mema tare'a-re'a Ja'a madhe, te ngaa asa camèd'a èèna, Ja'a mamuri hari!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke further, saying, “I here am the Original/Authentic Human. I must bear all.sorts of heavy suffering. Later the traditional Yahudi elders, the *chief priests, and the religion teachers will not accept (=reject) that I here am Kristus. Then later they will kill Me. Certainly I will die, but on the day.after.the.tomorrow, I will live again!” [EXEG: UBS HB says /te trete heimera/ = on third day after this one = day after tomorrow].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Problem: camèda can be 1) day"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Problem: camèda can be 1) day after tomorrow (from speaking event) 2) day after tomorrow from point of reference, or (unlikely) 3) one night (ca mèda)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apodokimastheenai: be rejected, repudiated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">apodokimastheenai: be rejected, repudiated</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ladhe ra ige lod'o, nuka: deo ne'e ne, lod'o ka èci (1); bèli = lod'o ka dua (2); camèd'a = lod'o ka tèlu (3). De mamadhe Lamatua Yesus ra ige lèke lod'o ka èci (nuka Jumat Agung), aa lod'o Na mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na lèke lod'o ka tèlu, nuka camèd'a (Migu Paska).<bt>The Yunani language way of counting days, is, today = the first day; tomorrow = the second day; the day.after.tomorrow = the third day. So, the Lord Yesus' death, count it on the first day (Good Friday), and His living again, count it the third day, which was the day.after.tomorrow (Easter Sunday).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle ka Na peka dènge dhèu ae se, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a, nèngu hud'i madhutu dènge d'ara kateme ètu lod'o bèli-lod'o bèli. Nèngu hud'i core eele ku dad'èi d'ara na. Nèngu hud'i madhutu taruu, masi ka dhèu neo pamadhe ne, nuka sèmi dhèu pasae aj'u palolo-palèbha na, ho la'e asa era ra pamadhe ne.<bt>Afterwards then, He told the many people saying, “The person who wants to follow Me, well, s/he must follow wholeheartedly every day. S/he must throw away his/her own desires. S/he must follow continually, even.though someone wants to kill him/her, like a person carrying his/her *cross to go to his/her place of being killed.</bt><note reference="9:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:38, Lukas 14:27</note><v n="24" />Te dhèu dhu sadia madhe lula madhutu Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a nèngu unu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa dhèu dhu neo dhoka mamuri hia ngi'u aae na, bèli-camèd'a nèngu pakaj'èu-j'èu nèti Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who is prepared to die because s/he follows Me, later s/he will be able to live continually with Father God. But the person who only wants to live just for him/herself, later s/he will be separated off/cut off from God. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk. almost identical with Mk. 8:35; Gk here is the ‘perish’ term, so KT].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèli-camèda mamuri nèngu abhu boe mamuri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">bèli-camèda mamuri nèngu abhu boe mamuri pa'èci dènge Lamatua.</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:39, Lukas 17:33, Yohanis 12:25</note><v n="25" />Ladhe dhèu unu aa'i ngaa-ngaa ètu rai-haha ne, te ngaa Ama Lamatua tule eele ne, a'oto na ngaa?<bt>If a person obtains everything in this world, but Father God throws him/her away, what has s/he gained/benefited?</bt><v n="26" />Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. De dhèu dhu makae madhutu Ja'a, aa makae sèmi lii aj'a Ja'a, Ja'a kahèi makae mangaku nèngu ètu madha Ama Lamatua, lod'o Ja'a lèpa mai nèti sorga. Te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a puru mai dènge dadedha Ama Ku, palere-lere dènge ana-ana pajuu Na nèti sorga.<bt>I here, am the Authentic Human. So (consequently) the person who is ashamed to follow Me, and ashamed to accept My teachings, I also will later be ashamed to acknowledge him/her in front of Father God when I return from heaven. Cuz (elaboration) later I will come down with Father's great power, together with His underlings from heaven (*angels). [NOTE: ‘holy’ angels undertranslated so as not to make heavy information load and skew the focus.]</bt><v n="27" />Ja'a peka patare'a dènge miu. Abhu pèri-pèri nèti miu ètu se'e se, bèli-camèd'a ladhe rèdhi unu ra Lamatua nèd'u paredha, heka ra madhe kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>I'm telling you plainly. There are several of you who are here now, who later will see for themselves the Lord's governing/ruling, and only.then they die.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patare'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">patare'a</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rupa Yesus ub'a eele ètu kolo ledhe<bt>The Lord Yesus becomes different on top of the mountain</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 17:1-8; Markus 9:2-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Èle aru lod'o, ka Yesus nèti Petrus, Yohanis dènge Yakobis, lasi ca'e asa ledhe èci, ho neo sabaj'a.<bt>After eight days, then Yesus took Petrus, Yohanis and Yakobis up a mountain to pray.</bt><v n="29" />Dhu Na sabaj'a era, rèhu Na j'aj'i leko-leo, aa mèdha-papake Na pudhi lao-lao.<bt>When He was praying, then His face changed, and His clothing became pure white.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="leko leo = lain dari yang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">leko leo = lain dari yang lain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Cag'ag'a laa, dhèu dua cèu mai. Dhèu se, nuka baki Musa dènge baki Elia. Ka ra padhai lii dènge Yesus.<bt>Unexpectedly/suddenly two people appeared. Those two were grandfather Musa and grandfather Elia. Then they were speaking with Yesus.</bt><v n="31" />Dua ra ladhe na le'e-le'e hèti-hèti. Tèlu ra padhue-padhai lula-nèti mamadhe Yesus bèli-camèd'a ètu Yerusalem.<bt>The two of them also appeared/were brilliant to the max. The three of them spoke about Yesus' death later in Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gaa dia-dia = semacam bercahaya, cerah,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">gaa dia-dia = semacam bercahaya, cerah, secara seluruh (not known); (UNS say = terbuka, or bersih [like not wearing clothes]) ; le'e-le'e = flashing/brilliant ; le'e-le'e hèti-hèti \lf Max</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dua ra se ladhe na gaa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Dua ra se ladhe na gaa dia-dia.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lod'o èèna, Petrus dènge angalai na dhèu dua sèra musi madha sakaa titu kèna, ka ra bhèj'i luu. Ropa ra kabèdhi, hèia rèdhi Yesus titu dènge dhèu dua. Aa rèdhi Yesus dhu kaha'a kahèi.<bt>At that time, Petrus and his two friends were so drowsy they couldn't endure, and they fell asleep. When they woke up, then they saw Yesus standing with two people. And they saw Yesus shining bright.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaha'a = bacaya ; kabèdhi (2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">kaha'a = bacaya ; kabèdhi (2) = bangun dari tidur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa Musa dènge Elia neo lèpa, Petrus bingu, ne'a heka tao tasamia. Ka na padhai lii leli, na peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i ètu ne'e, be'a d'ai seli! De hua iia ji'i tao paleo tèlu bua. Cue hia Ama, cue hia baki Musa, aa cue hari hia baki Elia.&gt;&gt;<bt>When grandfather Musa and grandfather Elia were about to go, Petrus was confused and didn't know what to do. Then he spoke thoughtlessly/unthinkingly saying, “Father! We-exc are here, and it's so good! So it's better/good (=suggestion) if we-exc build three shelters. One for Father (=you), one for grandfather Musa, and one more for grandfather Elia.”</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa ropa Petrus padhai lii era, ra'i-liru puru mai, ka saguru rare rèngu. Hèia Petrus si madha'u bia.<bt>But when Petrus was still speaking like.that, a cloud came down and covered/enveloped them. Then Petrus (collective) became afraid.</bt><v n="35" />Ka ra tadèngi lii nèti d'ara ra'i-liru èèna, peka na,<bt>And they heard a voice from inside that cloud, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, Ana Ja'a dhu Ja'a hag'e kore le!<bt>“This, is My Child whom I have chosen/set aside ahead.of.time!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ladhe Na padhai lii, nanene Ne paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>When He speaks, listen carefully to Him!”</bt><note reference="9:28-35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Petrus 1:17-18; Yesaya 42:1, Mateos 3:17, 12:18, Markus 1:11, Lukas 3:22</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ropa lii na èle, Petrus si ladhe rèdhi dhoka Yesus mesa-mesa na. Rèngu tèlu ra, peka boe dènge dhèu èci sa, ngaa dhu rèngu rèdhi le. D'ai nèbhu ku, heka ra palolo dènge dhèu leo kèna.<bt>After talking, then Petrus (collective) only saw just Yesus alone. The three of them didn't tell anyone at all what that had seen there. Eventually, only.then did they open their mouths to tell other people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle ana èci dhu nidhu bhelu tao ne<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a child who is afflicted by evil spirit</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 17:14-18; Markus 9:14-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Asa bèli èèna, lod'o Yesus dènge Petrus si puru mai nèti ledhe, dhèu ae mai paraga dènge Yesus.<bt>The next day, when Yesus and Petrus (collective) came down from that mountain, many people came to meet Yesus.</bt><v n="38" />Ka dhèu èci rodhe Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ladhe ku ana mone ja'a ca dhèu ne laa!<bt>Then a person called out to Him, saying, “Father Teacher! Help my one and only male child!</bt><v n="39" />Te abhu nidhu dhu loe boe kèpe ne, ka na pakèce sahèka, aa nyanyoko ne, toke hèb'a na horo karaka. Nidhu ne loe boe dhadhedhe ana ne, aa d'èi boe hia ana ne ae nare ciki sa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there is evil.spirit who continually grabs him, to make him suddenly yell, and convulses him until foam comes out of his mouth. That evil.spirit also keeps slapping/hitting him, and keeps bother him all the time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakèce = berteriak ; sahèka ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pakèce = berteriak ; sahèka = takuju ; nyanyoko = convulse like epyleptic fit ; horo karaka = berbuih (after action of a kind of crab); dhadhedhe = beat repeatedly</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Ja'a manèngi le kahèi ana madhutu Ama se ho ra babège eele nidhu ne, te ngaa tao rare boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>I have requested assistance from Father's underlings to expel that evil.spirit, but they could not overcome it!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ka Yesus jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Miu se parcaya boe, na, Lamatua bisa pa'èle dhèu nèti papèd'a ra. Miu mema dhèu dhu me'a boe mamuri madhutu j'ara mola! De Ja'a hud'i tatae hari miu toke pèri lod'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus scolded them, saying, “Ee! You-pl don't believe the Lord can heal people from their sicknesses. You really are people who don't know how to live following the straight path! How much longer must I be patient with you?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Na peka dènge ama ana ne, &lt;&lt;Mèti ana mu sa ne'e mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he turned.back to speak with that child's father, saying, “Bring your child here!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ropa pakako rèti ana ne asa Yesus, hèia nidhu hake pabèbhe, aa rarumu ne. Te ngaa Yesus paredha nidhu ho kalua tèke eele ana ne, hèia na èle dènge. Ka Yesus hia ana ne asa ama na la'e.<bt>When they brought that child to Yesus, then that evil.spirit threw him on the ground, repeatedly shook him. But Yesus ordered that evil.spirit to come out and leave that child, then he was immediately well. And Yesus gave that child to his father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rarumu = kneed, ramas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">rarumu = kneed, ramas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akathartos: unclean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">akathartos: unclean</Message></Annotation><v n="43a" />Dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra dhu ladhe rèdhi koasa Yesus, aa'i-aa'i ra malaa-maloha.<bt>People who saw that amazing power of Yesus, they were all amazed (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka hari j'ara mamadhe Na<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks again about His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 17:22-23; Markus 9:30-32)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43b" />Ropa dhèu se padhue era tadha malaa dhu Yesus tao, Nèngu lii dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>When the people there were still talking.to.each.other about lthe *amazing signs which Yesus was doing, He told His underlings, saying,</bt><v n="44" />&lt;&lt;Miu patadhe paie lii padhai Ja'a ne! Nèbhu boe dhèu neo pahie Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Ka ra soro Ja'a asa d'ara adhe-aai dhèu leo.&gt;&gt;<bt>“You-pl mark this speaking of mine well! Not much longer, (elaboration) people/person will sell Me off (*betray), the Original Human here. Then they will hand Me over into the hands of outsiders.” [NOTE: not Hebraism. And not from Kupang.]</bt><v n="45" />Te ngaa ana madhutu Na se bingu. Masi ka rèngu dhane rare boe sasoa na, te ngaa ra madha'u karèi Ne, sasoa na ngaa.<bt>But His underlings were confused. They did not understand the intention. They also were afraid to ask the meaning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhane = re'a (known by 18"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dhane = re'a (known by 18 year old UNS) ; padhane kubur</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Cee ka dhu j'aj'i dhèu re madha<bt>Who becomes the up-front/prominent person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 18:1-5; Markus 9:33-37)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Ca lod'o, ana madhutu Yesus pasisu lula-nèti rèngu se, cee ka dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i dhèu re madha.<bt>One time, Yesus' underlings started to argue about who among them would later become the up-front/prominent person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="re madha = 1) prominent, (social)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">re madha = 1) prominent, (social) 2) in front (location)</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 22:24</note><v n="47" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a ngaa dhu rèngu pasisu. Ka Na paroa nare ana iiki ca dhèu, hèia Na patitu ètu karasa Na.<bt>But Yesus knew what they were arguing about. And He called a small child, then stood that child at His side.</bt><v n="48" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie! Dhèu dhu madhutu Ja'a, ho na ladhe-leru dhèu haha, dhu sama sèmi ana iiki ne, sasoa na nèngu ladhe-leru Ja'a kahèi. Aa na ladhe-leru kahèi Ama Ku ètu sorga dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne. Abhu dhèu ae dhu pusi-pahae boe dhèu sèmi se'e se. Dhèu se'e, nuka: dhu unu aad'o, dhu susa, dhu laku-laku boe, dhu kalua aapa, aa dènge dhèu haha. De dhèu dhu d'èi lalau-lalo'o dhèu sèmi se'e se, madhutu Ama Lamatua, nèngu ka dhu dhèu re madha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He told them, saying, “Listen well! The person who follows Me in.order.to serve low people (=unimportant people) like this child, that means, that person also serves Me. And He also serves My Father in heaven who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world. There are many people who like to look.down.on/ belittle people like them. That is, like: the poor , those in trouble, those not considered good, bad luck people, and small/unimportant people. So, whoever likes to serve people like those is who Father God considers to be the most up-front/prominent.” [EXEG: explication from TN p.211; NOTE to daughter translations: compare wording in Mrk 9:37.].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu haha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">dhèu haha</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:48" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:40, Lukas 10:16, Yohanis 13:20</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu cee dhu lab'a boe èdhi, nèngu èèna angalai èdhi<bt>A person who doesn't oppose us, s/he is our-inc friend</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 9:38-40)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Hèia Yohanis peka dènge Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ca lod'o ji'i ngèdhi ca dhèu babège eele nidhu, dènge ale kolongara Ama. Ka ji'i kai ne, sèna ka na ale ia ka ngara Ama, lula nèngu ne dhèu èdhi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yohanis told Yesus saying, “Father! One time, we-exc saw a person expelling evil.spirit/s by using/mentioning Father's name. And we forbade him to not use Father's name, because he is not our-inc person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku! Te dhèu dhu lab'a boe èdhi, nèngu èèna angalai èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, “Don't! Cuz (elaboration) a person who does not oppose us-inc, he is our own friend.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ca rae ètu Samaria ro'o boe sèmi rare Lamatua Yesus<bt>People in a village in Samaria do not want to accept the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Yesus ne'a le lod'o Na ca'e asa sorga dètu le. Ka Na pama'ète nare, ho la'e asa kota Yerusalem.<bt>Yesus knew that His day of going up to heaven was near. And He decided to leave to go to Yerusalem city.</bt><v n="52" />Na pua dhèu lasi uuru, sèna ka ra lalau nganga'a-nganginu. Ka dhèu lasi uuru se, maso lasi asa d'ara rae cue ètu propensi Samaria, ho lalau mema era rèngu manubha.<bt>He sent person/people to go in front of them, so that they could arrange food-drink (=all logistics, can include lodging). Then they entered into a village in Samaria province to try to arrange a place to stay.overnight/ temporarily.</bt><v n="53" />Te ngaa dhèu ètu Samaria se, ro'o boe sèmi rare Yesus si, lula Nèngu neo la'e sogo-tagu Ama Lamatua ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>But those Samaria people did not want to receive Yesus (collective), because He wanted to go worship Father God in Yerusalem city.</bt><note reference="9:53" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Era dhèu Samaria sogo-tagu mi Ama Lamatua ètu ledhe Gerasim, ètu rai rèngu. Rèngu se nèbhu le dhu tao lii langu dènge dhèu Yahudi dhu mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>The Samaria people's place of worshiping God is on Gerasim mountain, in their region. For a long them they had had a dispute with Yahudi people who worship Father God in Yerusalem city.</bt></note><v n="54" />Ropa Yakobis dènge Yohanis tadèngi lii ne'e, ka ra pamako Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Tasamia na ti manèngi Ama Lamatua papuru ai mai nèti dedha-liru, ho tunu pakèpu si?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yakobis and Yohanis heard about it, then they tried to persuade Yesus, saying, “Father! How about it if we request Father God to send down fire from the sky to burn them up?”</bt><note reference="9:54" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Dhèu Aae sèra 1:9-16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Te ngaa Yesus ladhe asa dua ra, hèia Na kai si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku pangee sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus looked at the two of them, and scolded, saying, “Don't think like.that.”</bt><v n="56" />Èle èèna ka, lasi hari asa rae leo.<bt>So they travelled on going to another village.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">J'ara-j'ara madhutu Lamatua Yesus<bt>Requirements for following the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 8:19-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Ropa rèngu kako era, dhèu èci lii dènge Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama neo asa mia èèna ka, ja'a neo madhutu Ama taruu!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were still walking, one person spoke to Yesus, saying, “Father! Where ever Father goes, I want to always go with Father!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parai eela boe = sonde kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">parai eela boe = sonde kasi tenga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />Hèia Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a kahèi! Te ngaa pangee ku laa. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dènge era pea-palu'u. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge badha-manu. Busa hui lèpa la'e asa d'ara ro'a na. Manu-bhui lasi asa d'ara rèd'a ra. Te ngaa Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a, dènge boe era pea-palu'u ho pasoru iisi Ja'a ne. Era lalaka kètu, aad'o kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, “That's good! But remember this. All people have their own place to stay (doublet). It's the same with animals. A wild dog returns to his hole. A bird returns to its nest. But I, the Authentic Human, do not have my own house to stop in and rest. Not even a place for laying/supporting the head.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoru = enter (and rest) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pasoru = enter (and rest) ; lalaka = alas, ; lalaka jara = saddle ; era lalaka kètu = kamub'u = wooden pillow</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Ca tèka, Yesus paroa dhèu leo ca dhèu, ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Mai madhutu Ja'a, ho j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Yesus called another person, saying, “Come follow Me, to become My person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a kahèi, do! Te ngaa sèmi ne'e, Ama. Hud'i ja'a lèpa ku ladhe-leru ina-ama ja'a. Ladhe padhane kore ama ku, heka ja'a madhutu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person replied saying, “Alright (reluctant agreement)! But it's like.this, Father. Let me go.home to take.care of my parents first. If/When I have buried my father, only.then will I follow.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="60" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Hud'i laa dhèu dhu parcaya boe Lamatua, uri dhèu rèngu dhu madhe. Te ngaa miu dhu lèka Lamatua, sasab'a miu lami peka-padhai j'ara-j'ara paredha Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told him, saying, “It's like this! Allow people who do not have faith/belief in the Lord arrange their dead people. But you-pl who believe in the Lord, your work/task is to go tell about Father God's reign/rule/governing.” [NLT; NOTE: Gk is singular in last sentence. But here we have seen a pattern that they won't broaden the application to themselves unless it is plural. So plural for genre (instruction) reasons. If changed to singular, would have to delete first clause in last sentence, which is then too broad for local audiences. So implication here of /miu/ is “you-sg and people like you”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: But Jesus said to him,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z" status="Information">NRSV: But Jesus said to him, “Let the dead bury their own dead; but as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God.”</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Abhu dhèu leo dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a kahèi. Ja'a neo madhutu Ama taruu. Te ngaa hud'i ja'a laku palangu ku lii dènge a'ari ja'a, heka ja'a mai madhutu Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>There was another person saying, “That's good. I want to follow Father continually. But let me go take leave of my family first, only.then I will come back and follow Father.” [NOTE: added last clause for higher level context]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palangu lii = pamit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">palangu lii = pamit</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:61" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 19:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="62" />Te ngaa Yesus lii dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe dhèu neo pare rai, te ngaa tao hari ngaa-ngaa dhu leo, toke bhèlu sèle, tatu oka na j'aj'i boe. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu pama'ète nare le neo madhutu Ja'a, te ngaa pangee taruu mamuri na lod'o dhu uru sèra. Dhèu sèmi èèna gaguna na aad'o j'aj'i dhèu sab'a ètu d'ara paredha Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told him, saying, “It's like.this! If a person begins to turn the soil, but then gets preoccupied with other matters to the point that he forgets to plant, obviously his garden won't happen. It's like that also with a person who decides to follow Me, but continually keeps remembering/thinking about his former life. A person like that does not have any value/use in becoming a worker in Father God's rule/governance.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pare rai = balek tana (lit."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">pare rai = balek tana (lit. potong tana)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pua ana madhutu Na, pidhu nguru dua dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus sends out/commissions seventy two underlings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, Yesus hag'e nare ana madhutu Na dhu leo, pidhu nguru dua dhèu.<bt>After that, Yesus chose other underlings, 72 people. [EXEG: Marshall p.414-415, Ex.Summ. &amp; Trans Notes p.216 discuss 70 vs. 72; most recent translations go with 72, (NLT, CEV, TNIV, ESV, REB, NET, NCV); team favours 72.]</bt><note reference="10:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e suri, na, &lt;ana madhutu 72 dhèu&gt;. Dhu leo hari suri, na, &lt;ana madhutu 70 dhèu&gt;. Madhutu terjemahan dhu hiu, ae dhu pili &lt;72 dhèu&gt;.<bt>Some Yunani language writings have written, saying, ‘72 underlings’. Some others, say, ‘70 underlings’. The modern translations, many have chosen ‘72’.</bt></note>Ka Na hag'e si, dua-dua dhèu, sèna ka lasi uuru asa era-era dhu Nèngu neo la'e.<bt>Then He sorted them into pairs, for them to go ahead of Him to places which He would come to later.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia Na pua si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu ae dhu nuka sèmi are dhu karara le. Ka lamatua oka pua dhèu sab'a na lasi g'ètu are se. De miu hud'i sabaj'a, sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia tabha dhèu-dhèu sab'a Na, ho oru rare dhèu-dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a. Lula dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a, ae. Te ngaa dhèu sab'a dhoka ciki oo'e di.<bt>He sent them, saying, “There are many people who are like padi that is already yellow. The only thing lacking is just for the garden owner to send his workers to come harvest. So, you must pray requesting Father God to sent extra of His workers to collect people who want to follow Me. Because people who want to follow Me, are many. But the workers are only just a few. [EXEG: Explication modifying Trans. Notes]. [CHECK variant suggestion.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oe mango le = su mau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">oe mango le = su mau kering ; karara le</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:37-38</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />De lami ka! Ja'a pua miu lami asa dhèu ae. Te ngaa sanèd'e sèmi ne'e. Miu èci èèna ka dènge ana kahib'i-kalèbho dhu lami asa talora aae busa hui dhu bhelu.<bt>Now go! I send/commission you to go to many people. But remember this. You are like sheep offspring, who go into the midst of wild dogs that are evil.</bt><note reference="10:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Miu baku mèti doi-dhari, tas tao mèdha-papake, do salapa dhu risi ètu d'ara kakako miu. Mage core eele ai lod'o dènge padhai lii iia d'ara dènge dhèu ètu talora j'ara.<bt>You don't need to bring money, or clothes bag, or extra sandals on the road/journey. Don't waste time needlessly by talking trivially with people on the road/journey.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-8" />Ladhe miu maso asa d'ara rae èci, miu baku pidha-pidha era pea. Ladhe dhèu sèmi rare miu dènge be'a ètu d'ara èmu cue, pea dhoka ètu èèna toke miu pakèd'i tèke eele rae èèna. Ladhe miu maso asa èmu cue, miu hud'i manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua hia berkat mi dhèu isi èmu èèna. Ladhe lamatua èmu ètu sèra sèmi nare miu dènge be'a, tatu Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi isi èmu èèna. Te ngaa ladhe ro'o boe sèmi miu, na, hud'i laa Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na hia miu mesa mi. Ladhe miu maso asa èmu cue, do, asa rae èci, ra hia miu nganga'a, mi'a-minu laa dènge karej'e. Te ra hia èèna pamèci dènge èi kabhèsu miu dhu hae.<bt>If/when you enter into a village, you don't need to move around from one house to another house. If a person accepts you graciously in one house, just stay there, until you leave that village. If you enter into a house, you must request that Father God give blessing to the people in that house. If the house master there accepts you graciously, surely the Lord will show his good insides (=grace/generosity) to that household. But if they don't want to accept you, well.then, let the Lord show His good insides just to you yourselves. If you enter a house, or a village, eat-drink happily/without concern. Cuz (elaboration) it's appropriate that they give to you like that, to replace your sweat (=reciprocate for your work).</bt><note reference="10:5-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 9:14, 1 Timotius 5:18</note><v n="9" />Puri-pa'èle dhèu rèngu dhu pèd'a. Aa peka-padhai dènge dhèu sèra, na, &lt;Paredha Ama Lamatua ètu katanga madha miu le!&gt;<bt>Heal their sick people. And tell them, saying, ‘Father God's ruling/governing is right in front of your face!&gt; [EXEG: Dallas Willard. We take this here as a condensed flag representing the nature of the topic, not the details of what is to be communicated.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Paredha Ama Lamatua nèbhu heka mai!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:28Z">Paredha Ama Lamatua nèbhu heka mai! // dhu abhu mema le ètu madha miu!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi rae dhu dhèu ra ro'o boe sèmi rare miu. Ladhe ra tao miu sèmi èèna, na, lami titu asa j'ara-j'ara ètu d'ara rae èèna, mi lii dènge ra, peka na,<bt>But there will also be villages whose people don't want to receive you. If they do like.that to you, well.then, go stand at that village's roads and tell them, saying,</bt><v n="11" />&lt;Nanene paie! Miu dhèu dhu ètu d'ara rae ne. Ji'i mai le ngèti Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua hia miu, te ngaa miu pusi-pahae boe. De ji'i caro eele ahu rae ne'e nèti haga ji'i, ho j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, pe bèli-camèd'a sèmi mere pala mi! Te ngaa sanèd'e paie-iie! Paredha Ama Lamatua ètu katanga madha miu le.&gt;<bt>‘Listen carefully! You people of this village. We-exc have come bring the Lord's Words to you, but you do not care even a little bit. So, we now brush.off this village's dust from our feet, to become a sign that, later you yourselves are responsible for the risk! But remember well! The Father God's ruling/governing is right in front of your face.’</bt><note reference="10:4-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:7-14, Markus 6:8-11, Lukas 9:3-5; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 13:51</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Miu me'a, sina ma, bhabhelu dhèu kota Sodom? Ja'a pasanèd'e miu! Bèli-camèd'a, d'ai lod'o èle rai-haha ne, Ama Lamatua huku dhèu-dhèu dhu ro'o boe sèmi rare miu, bia risi nèti dhèu Sodom!&gt;&gt;<bt>You know the evil of the people of Sodom city, right? I'm reminding/warning you! Later at the end of the world, the Lord will judge those people who reject you, far heavier than the Sodom people!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Aa Yesus peka hari dènge dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Aa Yesus peka hari dènge dhèu pidhu nguru dua sèra, &lt;&lt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:24-28, Mateos 10:15, 11:24</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu ro'o boe sèmi rare Lamatua Yesus<bt>People who do not want to receive the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 11:20-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mate unu miu dhu pea ètu rae Korasin<bt>And Yesus continued speaking, saying, “Watch out you-pl who live in Korasin village</bt><note reference="10:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Suri madhutu lii Idhonesia, &lt;Khorazim&gt;. Lii uuru nèti lii Yunani dhu suri tèke, Χοραζίν &lt;Choradzin&gt;.<bt>Indonesian writes &lt;Khorazim&gt;. The original, from the Yunani language writes Χοραζίν &lt;Choradzin&gt;.</bt></note>dènge miu ètu rae Betsaida! Miu dui mere j'aj'èra! Ja'a tao tadha-tadha malaa ètu katanga madha miu, te ngaa miu mo'o boe parcaya Lamatua. Ngaa hari miu dhèu Yahudi dhu peka na, miu tadhe Ne. Ladhe sèmi tadha-tadha malaa se, dhu Ja'a tao ètu rae miu, lèke ètu kota Tirus dènge kota Sidon, tatu nèbhu nare sange ne'e dhèu sèra ele-ho'a le, aa ra tèke eele sasala-sasigo ra, ho mai madhutu Lamatua. Aa rèngu tatu pake le mèdha sasusa, dènge tao ahu ètu kètu ra j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, rèngu manyasa nèti sasala-sasigo ra. Te ngaa dhèu Tirus dènge dhèu Sidon sèra, dhèu Yahudi boe. De ra peka boe, na, rèngu dhèu dhu tadhe Lamatua.<bt>and Betsaida village! Misfortune afflicts you! I have done all.sorts.of miracles right in front of your face, but you do not want to believe in the Lord. Furthermore, you here are Yahudi people who acknowledge knowing Him. If (it were the case that) those miracles which I did in your villages happened in Tirus city and Sidon city, surely after this long people there would have repented and they would have left their wrongs to come follow/obey the Lord. And they also surely would have put on mourning clothes, and put ashes on their heads to be a sign that they are regretting their wrongs. But (contrary to expectation) these Tirus people and Sidon people, aren't Yahudi people. So they don't say they are people who know the Lord. [EXEG: in unpacking “repent” we introduce “believe” which opens the question “believe in God” vs. “believe in me (Jesus)”. This question is only touched on indirectly in the commentaries and there are good arguments in both directions--both with contextual support. Broader passage has high-level themes. Words like “cities” “repent”, “sackcloth and ashes” (w/ “judgment” in 14; “heaven and hell” in 15) make us lean toward God evoking OT stories like Job (but people in the Jewish cities would think they already believed in God, it was Jesus they were rejecting). Direct support for God from CEV, and indirect from Green. Made ambiguous to “Lord”, to keep open both possibilities.]</bt><note reference="10:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 23:1-18, Yeskial 26:1--28:26, Yoel 3:4-8, Amos 1:9-10, Sakaria 9:2-4</note><v n="14" />Tare'a! Miu ladhe ku laa! Bèli-camèd'a d'ai lod'o Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i, hahuku nèti Lamatua mi dhèu Tirus dènge dhèu Sidon samaa risi nèti hahuku miu.<bt>It's true! You-pl just look/watch! Later when the Lord decides all people's cases/disputes, His punishment of Tirus people and Sidon people will still be far more light than your punishment.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Mata unu miu, kabarai Kapernaum! Miu baku pangee, na, bèli-camèd'a Lamatua nedhe miu pamaso asa d'ara sorga. Aad'o! Mola-mèu èi! Èèna na Lamatua pèci miu asa d'ara naraka lami!<bt>Be careful you people from Kapernaum village! You shouldn't think that the Lord will lift you up to enter heaven. No! It's not gonna happen (idiom)! Later the Lord will throw you away into hell!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mola mèu èi! = Idiom (lit:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Mola mèu èi! = Idiom (lit: benar dlm kejernihan air) --&gt; 1) "sonde mungkin!" 2) tidak ada hasil</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 14:13-15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Sanèd'e pabe'a-be'a. Dhèu dhu nanene lii miu, nuka sèmi rèngu nanene Ja'a. Aa dhèu dhu pusi boe nanene miu, èci èèna ka ra pahae boe Ja'a. Aa dhèu dhu ro'o boe nanene Ja'a, èci èèna ka dènge rèngu dhu pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua, dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Think about this! A person who listens to/obeys you-pl, it's just like he listens to/obeys Me. And a person who ignores you-pl, it's just like he ignores Me. And that person who will not listen to/obey Me, it's just like he will not listen to/obey Father God, who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hèia Yesus aj'a-nori mi dhèu madhutu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Hèia Yesus aj'a-nori mi dhèu madhutu Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:40, Markus 9:37, Lukas 9:48, Yohanis 13:20</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana madhutu Yesus dhèu pidhu nguru dua sèra lèpa hari<bt>Seventy two underling/followers return</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa ana madhutu pidhu nguru dua sèra lèpa hari mai,<bt>When those 72 underling/followers came back,</bt><note reference="10:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri na, &lt;ana madhutu 72 dhèu&gt;. Cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;ana madhutu 70 dhèu&gt;. Nèti terjemahan dhu hiu, ae ka dhu suri, &lt;72 dhèu&gt;.<bt>Some of the Yunani language writing write saying, ‘72 underlings&gt;. Some others sayi, ‘70 underlings&gt;. Modern translations, many have chosen &lt;72&gt;.</bt></note>d'ara ra karej'e bia. Ka ra lole dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Kakako ji'i ne, be'a bia! Ropa ji'i pake kolongara Ama ho babège eele nidhu, na, nidhu sèra nanene lii ji'i, hèia ra rai bhalèta.&gt;&gt;<bt>their livers were joyful. And they reported to Yesus, saying, “Ira ii! [+amazement] Our journey was so good! When we-exc used Father's name to expel the evil.spirits. Those evil.spirits heard/obeyed us, and they came out immediately!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhalèta = berhamburan, lari tasiram"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bhalèta = berhamburan, lari tasiram</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Lod'o miu tao sèra sa, Ja'a ladhe kèdhi Ama Lamatua pèci eele nidhu dènge dhèu aae ra nèti dedha-liru nèi, nuka sèmi bela dhu kaha'a nèti haa, nèti dhimu!<bt>But (contrary to expectation) Yesus responded to them, saying, “True! When you-pl did like.that, I saw Father God throw the evil.spirit's king from the sky, just like lightning comes flashing from the west, from the east!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaha'a = like blitz"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaha'a = like blitz</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaan: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Satanaan: da Devil</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Sanèd'e! Dhèu aae nidhu èèna, musu èdhi. Aa nèngu dènge koasa kahèi. Te ngaa Ja'a pangèd'u le miu koasa, ho palaho koasa na. Ladhe miu j'èli lèke kaisao, do karaka rai, miu ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Ngaa èci sa bisa boe paj'èra miu.<bt>Remember! That king of the evil.spirit's is our enemy. And he has power/authority also! But I have given power/authority to you to break/sever his power/authority. And if you step on a poisonous snake, or a scorpion, you won't be harmed at all. There is nothing that can cause misfortune/harm to you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaisao = ular ijo ; karaka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaisao = ular ijo ; karaka rai = kalajengkeng</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 91:13</note><v n="20" />Miu karej'e lula nidhu nanene miu. Be'a kahèi, te ngaa sèra sa ana iiki era! Dhu be'a risi, d'ara miu karej'e, lula Lamatua suri nare le ngara miu, j'aj'i ana kabarai Na ètu sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Your livers are joyful, because the evil.spirits listen.to/obeyed you. That's ok, but that is just a small matter! It's better that your livers be joyful because the Lord has written your names to become His citizens in heaven.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">D'ara Lamatua Yesus karej'e-karae [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus' insides is joyful [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 11:25-27, 13:16-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Lod'o èèna, Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci tao d'ara Yesus karej'e-karae. Hèia Na koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhu j'aj'i Lamatua ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha. Ja'a manèngi makasi ae-ae, lula Ama pa'abhe j'ara-j'ara se'e nèti dhèu dhu tao iisi d'èlu-mèu dènge dhèu lela dedha. Te ngaa Ama bhoke patalele aa'i-aa'i se hia mi ana iiki-ana iiki dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu pahaha iisi. Tare'a Ama! Lula èèna ka dhu pakarej'e d'ara Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, the Lord's Holy Spirit made Yesus' insides joyful (doublet). Then He praised the Lord, saying, “Father (-you) is the one who is the Lord/Master in the sky and on earth. I give thanks, because Father covers these things from people who consider themselves to be smart/wise and those who elevate themselves (= pride). But Father open/reveal all these things to the small children and the people who lower themselves (=humble). True, Father! Cuz (elaboration) that is what makes Father's insides happy!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lela dedha = padedha iisi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lela dedha = padedha iisi = tinggi diri (terbang tinggi) ; dara taleo = hati luas, pandangan luas, sabar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu ae sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie! Ama Ku ètu sorga pangèd'u aa'i le koasa mi Ja'a. Dhu tadhe mèu, Ja'a ne cee, dhoka Ama di. Aa dhu tadhe mèu, Ama èèna cee, dhoka Ana nèti Ama di, nuka Ja'a ne. Aa Ja'a hag'e kore dhèu leo, sèna ka nori si, ho ra tadhe mèu Nèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told those many people saying, “Listen well! My Father in heaven has given all power/authority to Me. Those who truly know who I am, it's only just Father. And those who truly know who Father is, is only just the Father's Child, which is Me. And I choose other people, to tell/teach/advise them, so that they also know Him.” [NOTE: shift from 2nd person to 3rd person in Gk. taken as a shift in audience, as per Marshall and Trans. Notes p.226-227; EXEG: NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patadha = 1) perkenalkan 2) saling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">patadha = 1) perkenalkan 2) saling kenal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: All things have been handed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">NRSV: All things have been handed over to me by my Father; and no one knows who the Son is except the Father, or who the Father is except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him.”</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 3:35, 10:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus kabib'a asa ana madhutu Na, hèia Na peka dènge rèngu mesa ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se oto titu kèna, lula mèdhi le koasa Lamatua.<bt>Then Yesus turned facing His underlings, and told them alone, saying, “You-pl are very fortunate, because you have seen the Lord's power.</bt><v n="24" />Dhèu aae-dhèu aae dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua uru-uru sèra, d'èi titu kèna neo rèdhi ngaa dhu miu limuri ne mèdhi, te ngaa rèdhi boe. Rèngu d'èi kahèi neo tadèngi ngaa dhu miu nanene ne, te ngaa ra tadèngi rèdhi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Kings and spokespersons of long.ago yearned to see what you have seen, but they couldn't. They also yearned to hear what you have heard, but they couldn't.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Samaria dhu d'ara hualaa<bt>The Samaria person with the golden liver (=extremely good/upright/generous)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ca tèka, ca dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi, titu ho neo sèku pamanahu Yesus. Na karèi peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Mu peka ku laa! Ja'a ad'u j'ara sèmi ngaa, sèna ka ja'a mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua ètu sorga?&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, a Yahudi law expert stood up to try to trap Yesus. He asked, saying, “Father Teacher! Please tell/explain! What must I do, so that I can know I will live continually together with the Lord in heaven?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ka Yesus b'ala ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Musa suri tasamia lula-nèti j'ara ne'e ne? Aa madhutu mame'a èu, tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus replied, answering, “What did Musa write about this matter? What is your understanding about it?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia dhèu ne dhaa peka na, &lt;&lt;Na suri sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>That person tresponded, saying, “He wrote, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èu hud'i sue ku Ama Lamatua, <span class="Italic">risi</span> nèti ngaa-ngaa aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>‘You-sg must love Father God, <span class="Italic">more</span> than everything else.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, d'ara èu hud'i d'èi Nèngu titu kèna,<bt>Because of that we must always yearn.affectionately for Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sab'a pa'èra ho madhutu dad'èi Na,<bt>work hard to follow His will,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa tadhe mèu Ne.&gt;<bt>and know Him well/fully,’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhu suri kahèi, peka na, &lt;Èu hud'i sue ku dhèu èu, sama sèmi èu sue ngi'u èu mesa mu.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>It is also written, saying, ‘You-sg must love your people, the same as you love your own self.”&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rae lesa = sekampung, tetangga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">rae lesa = sekampung, tetangga</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pleesion: not just the person next"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">pleesion: not just the person next door</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 19:18, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 6:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia Yesus b'ala ne, &lt;&lt;Dhu lèke kèna! Ladhe èu tao madhutu sèmi sèra, na, èu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus replied, saying, “That's right! If you do like that, you will live forever with Father God.”</bt><note reference="10:25-28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 22:35-40, Markus 12:28-34; Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 18:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa dhèu ne, tao iisi na sèmi dhèu mola sa. Ka na karèi hari Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Te ngaa, &lt;dhèu ja'a&gt; èèna, ka cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>But that person wanted to make himself out to be like a religious/pious person. So he asked Yesus further, saying, “But, ‘my people&gt; means who?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia Yesus b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a neo lolo dènge èu lii pakasame èci. Pe èu mesa mu ka dhu peka, na, mia ka dhu tare'a-re'a &lt;dhèu èu&gt;. Lii pakasame ne, sèmi ne'e ka: ca lod'o, abhu dhèu Yahudi ca dhèu pakèd'i nèti kota Yerusalem, puru la'e asa kota Jeriko. Te ngaa ropa d'ai talora j'ara, cag'ag'a laa parapo mai game paroe ne. Ra game, aa parame rare aa'i doi-dhari dènge mèdha-papake dhèu ne. Ka parapo se core ne asa sebhe j'ara la'e, aa ra rai tèke eele ne. Dhèu ne, oe madhe.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “Like.this! I will give a comparison.story. Then you will know, who/which.one is truly &lt;your people&gt;. The story is like.this: One day there was a Yahudi person who left from Yerusalem city, walking down to Yeriko. But in the middle of the journey, robbers suddenly came and beat him up. They beat him, then snatched his money and all his clothes. Then they threw him off to the side of the road, and ran off leaving him behind. That person was about to die.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="game paroe = pukul kasi noe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">game paroe = pukul kasi noe (berat)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="Wade\gw086.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Ca dhèu ama agama kako paseli eele ne<bt>A priest passes by on the road</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa nèbhu boe, ka ama agama Yahudi ca dhèu puru mai re j'ara èèna. Te ngaa ropa na ladhe nèdhi dhèu ne dhu diu raa, aa dhu tarenga ètu sebhe j'ara, ama agama ne titu boe sa hèi, ho uri dhèu ne. Na kako paseli eele dhèu ne'e, la'e asa cabèka j'ara, ka na taruu.<bt>But by chance, a Yahudi priest was walking down also passed by there. But when he saw there was a bloodied/wounded person laying face.up on the side of the road, he didn't stop to help him. He diverged over to the other side to just keep going. [NOTE: Greek doesn't say how the person is laying, but this is how he is in picture.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="diu raa = mandi dara ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">diu raa = mandi dara ; sag'èba mopo-mopo = matono ; tarenga = malenggang ; tarenga hara-hara = (lf = Max)</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Nèbhu boe ka dhèu leo hari èci kako re èèna. Nèngu ne nèti suku Lewi dhu tema sab'a ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Ropa nèdhi dhèu ne dhu baa-baa ètu sebhe j'ara, hèia la'e padètu-dètu ho ladhe, te ngaa na bara boe ne kahèi. Na sigo eele j'ara, ka la'e taruu.<bt>Not long then, another person passed.by there. He was a person from the Lewi tribe who usually helped in Father God's Central Worship House. When he saw that person thrown on the side of the road, he only went close to have a look, but didn't help him either. Then he diverged to the other side and continued walking.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baa-baa = tergelentang, tatidor ; sigo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">baa-baa = tergelentang, tatidor ; sigo = langgar pi di tampa laen, serong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33-34" />Nèbhu boe ka, dhèu èci nèti rai Samaria mai re j'ara èèna dènge badha keled'ei na. Dhèu Yahudi pahae boe dhèu Samaria. Te ngaa ropa dhèu Samaria ne nèdhi dhèu dhu lèke rapo èèna, ka d'ara na mèke boe. Na mai padètu-dètu ho neo sarad'e ne. Ka pamèu nu'a dhèu ne dènge èi anggor, hèia na pana'i dènge èi mènyi. Aa na parbaan nu'a na, èle ka na paca'e asa keled'ei na. Hèia nèti ne la'e asa d'ara kota. Na pamaso ne asa d'ara losmen, aa lalau pabe'a-be'a ne.<bt>Not long again, another person from the Samaria region passed by there with his donkey animal. Yahudi people usually look sideways (disparagingly) at the Samaria people. But (contrary to expectation) when this Samaria person saw that person who had been robbed, he felt pity on him. He came close to help that person. He poured wine to clean that person's wounds, then he put oil on them. Next he bandaged him well, and put him on his donkey. Then he brought that person to the city. Then he arranged for that person to stay.temporarily at a guest.house, and arranged things well for him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara na mèke boe = hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dara na mèke boe = hati tidak sampe = jato hati ; parbaan ; sarad'e &amp; sare = yang alami pingsang, kasi bangun dan beri bantuan, topang</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:33-34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 28:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Asa bèli mad'ae èèna, dhèu ne la'e b'ae uuru kètu, doi iia dua bua<bt>The next day, that person went to give an advance of money, two silvers</bt><note reference="10:35" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;dua dinari&gt;&gt;.<bt>The Yunani language writes, saying, “two dinari&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>mi lamatua losmen ne, ka na peka, &lt;Pake uuru doi ne ho lalau dhèu ne toke èle. Ladhe d'ai boe, pake uuru doi èu. Pe ja'a lèpa, pula hari doi sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>to that guesthouse owner, and told him saying, ‘Use this money to take care of that person until he is well. If it's not enough, please use father's (=your) own money temporarily. When I come back again, then I will replace all of the money.”&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bae uuru kètu = panjar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bae uuru kètu = panjar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Lii pakasame Yesus ne d'ai sange ne'e ka. Hèia Yesus karèi mi dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu èu, mia ka dhu tare'a-re'a &lt;dhèu nèngu,&gt; mi dhèu dhu lèke rapo ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus' comparison.story concluded there. Then He asked that law expert, saying, “According to you, which.one was truly a &lt;his person&gt; for that person who was robbed there?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tatu dhèu dhu lalau ne toke èle.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person replied saying, “Of course it was that person who served/took care of him until he was well.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! De lamu ka, tao madhutu sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus said, “True. Go, do accordingly.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus, Marta dènge Maria<bt>The Lord Yesus, Marta and Maria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38-40" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na, lasi taruu asa Yerusalem. Hèia ra dhuli ètu rae èci. Ètu era ne'e, dhèu dua dhu pa'a'ari, ngara ra, Marta dènge Maria. Marta manèngi ho Yesus si manubha ètu èmu rèngu. Ka ra pea taha ètu èèna.<bt>After that, Yesus and His underlings traveled on to Yerusalem. They stopped at a village. There there were two siblings, named Marta and Maria. Marta requested that Yesus (collective) spend the night at their house. So they stayed.temporarily there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Yesus madhèdi ho aj'a si, Marta bhute dènge pananasu. Te ngaa ari na Maria, madhèdi padètu-dètu haga Yesus, ho nanene lii padhai Na. Nèbhu boe ka Marta mai ka'ugu ètu madha Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Tasamia, ee? Ja'a d'ai madhe lalau nganga'a-nganginu mesa-mesa ku, te ngaa ari ja'a madhèdi mau-mau. Peka ku dènge ne laa, sèna ka mai bara ja'a ètu dapu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus sat to teach people, Marta was busy with cooking (doublet). But her younger.sibling Maria, was sitting near Yesus' feet, in.order.to hear His talking. Not long then, Marta came in to complain to Yesus, saying, “Father! How is it? I am half dead taking care of the food-drink by myself, while my younger.sibling just sits pleasantly here. Tell her to help me a bit in the kitchen!”</bt><note reference="10:38-39" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 11:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Te ngaa Lamatua Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Marta. Èu ne bhute dènge ngangee rupa-rupa.<bt>But the Lord Yesus replied, saying, “Marta. You are the one very busy with all sorts of thoughts/worries.</bt><v n="42" />Be'a kahèi do, te ngaa j'ara èci dhu be'a risi. Maria pili nare dhu be'a risi le, nuka madhèdi ho nanene Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Ja'a. Dhèu bisa boe parame rare nèti nèngu Lii Lolo Be'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's ok, but there is one thing that is better. By sitting and hearing My Words, Mia has chosen was is the best. People cannot snatch the Good News away from her.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Aj'a ji'i sabaj'a&gt;&gt;<bt>“Teach us-exc to pray&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 6:9-13, 7:7-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, Yesus la'e manèngi-mangaj'i. Manèngi-mangaj'i nare, hèia ana madhutu Na ca dhèu mai, ka na manèngi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Yohanis tuka sarani, aj'a ana madhutu na ka re'a sabaj'a. Ji'i manèngi sèna ka Ama aj'a ji'i sabaj'a kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, Yesus went to pray. After praying, then one of His underlings came and requested, saying, “Father! Yohanis the habitual baptizer also taught his underlings, so that they would know how to pray. We-exc request that Father teach us to pray too [polite imperative]!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ka Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Be'a! Sabaj'a pake conto sèmi ne'e:<bt>Then Yesus said, “Ok! Pray using an example like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama! Kolongara Ama dhu mola-mèci.<bt>‘Father! Father's name/reputation is clean/holy (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i j'oka padedha-dedha kolongara Ama dhu kapai na.<bt>May.it.be that all people lift up high that great name/reputation of Father's.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hud'i laa Ama j'aj'i Dhèu Aae mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>May.it.be.that Father become King for all people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Ama hia laa ji'i bèli-bèli, nganga'a dhu d'ai.<bt>Father help/please give us food that is enough each day.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Ji'i manèngi Ama pabhèlu eele sasala-sasigo ji'i,<bt>We request that Father thoroughly forget our wrongs,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka sèmi ji'i kahèi pabhèlu eele sasala-sasala dhèu dhu tao mi dedha ji'i.<bt>the same as we also thoroughly forget people's wrongs which they do to/against us.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama magee ji'i, sèna ka ji'i baku ad'u-ue bhelu-katub'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Father guard us so.that we don't do evil (doublet).” [cf. Wierzbicka]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kai gar autoi aphiomen: &quot;let go"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">kai gar autoi aphiomen: "let go ... an no stay huhu" is the way people do it: "let go ... an hemo da shame" is the way God does it.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus nori hari si, j'ara-j'ara sabaj'a. Na pake upama, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi d'ai talora mèda, angalai èu mai nèti kaj'èu, ho manubha ètu èmu èu. Te ngaa èu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, sèna ka hia ne na'a. Ka èu lamu asa èmu angalai dhu leo, ho pamako nèti li'u, peka na, &lt;Lai aae na, ee! Hia taha ku ja'a roti d'ai tèlu bua sa! Te ji'i abhu tamu ètu èmu, te ngaa ji'i dhu mola-mèu èi! De lai aae na, ee! Dhoka tèlu bua di. Pe ja'a g'ati hari!&gt;<bt>Then Yesus taught them further about prayer. He used a comparison.story, saying, “Suppose.that it's the middle of night, your friend comes from far, to overnight at your-sg house. But you don't have anything to give him to eat. So you go to your other friend's house, to beg/insist from outside, saying, “Elder.brother! Loan me three loaves of bread! Cuz (elaboration) I have guests at the house, but we-exc have no food in house (Idiom = straight clean water)! Elder.brother, help! Just three loaves! I'll replace them!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mola mèu èi = kosong sama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">mola mèu èi = kosong sama sekali (lit: lurus bersih air) ; lai aae = lai aago = sapaan untuk teman laki-laki yg akrap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ladhe sèmi angalai èu dhaa, peka na, &lt;Te a'a, ee! Dhèu bhèj'i luu, na, èu mai parèi! Babèdho dhu patèke le! Ana iiki se dhu bhèj'i aa'i le. De mage mu nasa kahèi! Pe lod'o leo hari ku laa!&gt;<bt>Probably your friend will reply back saying, ‘But elder.brother2, ee! People are sleeping soundly, but you come and bother us! The doors are locked now! The kids are all asleep. Don't get angry =sorry! But come back another time!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa masi ka sèmi èèna, ngee paie-iie. Masi ka dhèu ne kèd'i boe lula èu angalai nèngu, te ngaa ladhe èu loe boe pamako, tatu na kèd'i, ho hia èu roti sèra.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless remember this well. Even.though that person does not get.up to give you [anything] because you are his friend, but if you repeatedly keep on insisting and insisting, surely he will get.up to give you that bread.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge manèngi-mangaj'i.<bt>It's like that also, with prayer.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Manèngi taruu mi Lamatua;<bt>[If you] Continually request from the Lord;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">pe Na hia.<bt>He will give.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tenge taruu;<bt>Continually seek;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">pe Na paj'uj'u j'ara.<bt>He will reveal the path/way.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Paroa taruu;<bt>Continually call.out;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">pe Na bhoke hèb'a èmu.<bt>He will open the door.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu manèngi taruu mi Ama Lamatua, èèna na rèngu sèmi. Dhu loe boe tenge, èèna na abhu. Dhu ma'ète boe paroa, pe Na bhoke babèdho.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) all people who continually request of Father God, will receive. Those who continually seek, will find. Those who continually call.out, He will open the door [for them].</bt><v n="11" />Miu pangee ku laa. Abhu ètu mia ladhe ama, dhu ana na manèngi i'a, na hia mege?<bt>Think about it! Where is there a father, if his child requests fish, then he gives snake?</bt><v n="12" />Do, ladhe ana manèngi kanadhu manu, na hia karaka rai? Tatu aad'o, si?<bt>Or, if a child requests egg, then he gives a scorpion? Surely not, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kanadhu manu = telur ayam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kanadhu manu = telur ayam</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Dhèu rai-haha ne, mema bhelu. Te ngaa Ama miu ètu sorga, Nèngu ne mema be'a. De ladhe miu dhèu dhu bhelu, d'èi hia mèdha dhu be'a mi ana-ana miu, ngaa hari Ama! Nèngu ne hia, mesa boe ngaa dhu miu parluu, te ngaa risi nèti èèna. Na pala-bagi Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci mi dhèu dhu manèngi mi Nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Humans really are evil. But that Father of yours in heaven, He really is good. So, if you-pl people who are evil, like to give things which are good to your children, even.more.so Father! He not only gives just what you-pl need, but more than that, He gives out His Holy Spirit to people who request [it] from Him.” [EXEG: "how much more" is built implicitly into the syntax of the last two sentences.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pake boe koasa nèti dhèu aae nidhu<bt>The Lord Yesus doesn't use power from the evil.spirits' king</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:22-30; Markus 3:20-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ca lod'o, Yesus magèle eele nidhu nèti ca dhèu dhu lii aad'o. Ka dhèu ne bisa padhai lii hari. Dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra malaa.<bt>One time, Yesus expelled evil.spirit/s out of a dumb/mute person. Then that person began to speak again. The people there were amazed.</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Mema, Nèngu bisa magèle eele nidhu, lula Nèngu abhu koasa nèti dhèu aae nidhu, nuka Baalsebul.&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were also some who said, “Of course He can expel evil.spirit/s. It's because He gets power from the king of the evil.spirits, who is Ba'alsebul.”</bt><note reference="11:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 9:34, 10:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Abhu dhèu leo neo sèku Yesus. Ka ra manèngi ho Yesus tao tadha malaa èci hari, sèna ka dhèu re'a, na, koasa Na nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>Other people wanted to test (character of) Yesus. And/so they requested Him to do another miracle to show them that His power/authority truly was from the Lord.</bt><note reference="11:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:38, 16:1, Markus 8:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a nare le kahadhu kaj'alu rèngu sèra. Ka Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ètu rai cue, kabarai na pamusu, tatu rai ne laho mae-mae. Sèmi èèna kahèi, ladhe ètu d'ara èmu cue, isi èmu loe boe patao-palaha, tatu èmu ne j'aj'i boe mi ngaa sa èci!<bt>But Yesus already knew those dirty/impure brains of theirs. So He spoke, saying, “If a country, its populace is mutual.enemies, surely that country will break apart. Like that also, if in a household, it's members are continually fighting each other, surely that household won't become anything at all!</bt><v n="18" />De ladhe nidhu se pamusu aa pabata èci dènge èci, tatu dhèu aae ra bisa boe rèd'u paredha dènge nèbhu. De maso boe asa d'ara kahadhu, ladhe miu peka, na, Ja'a pake koasa nidhu ho bata eele hari nidhu.<bt>So (consequently), if evil.spirits continually are mutual.enemies and continually mutually.expel each other, surely their king is not capable of holding authority/ruling much longer. So (consequently) it doesn't make any sense if you-pl say I am using evil.spirits' power/authority to expel evil.spirits themselves!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pabata = usir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pabata = usir</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaas: da Devil hee basileia autou:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Satanaas: da Devil hee basileia autou: his kingdom<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Sanèd'e paie! Dhèu miu kahèi dhu re'a magèle eele nidhu. Rèngu pake koasa nèti nidhu, do? Aad'o, si! De miu baku sad'i padhai lii di, dhu peka na, Ja'a ne pake koasa nidhu sèna ka bata eele si. Pe dhèu miu ka dhu pama'ète, peka na, ngaa dhu miu galaa ne, lèke boe.<bt>Remember! Your-pl people also know how to expel evil.spirit/s. Do they use power from evil.spirit/s? No, right? So (consequently), you shouldn't speak thoughtlessly, saying, I am using evil.spirit's power/authority to expel them. Later your own people will decide/resolve that that which you are accusing here, is false.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Beelzeboul: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Beelzeboul: da Devil</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a tare'a-re'a bata nidhu pake koasa Ama Lamatua, èèna dhu peka na, paredha Lamatua ètu katanga madha miu le. Paredha ne abhu le, te ngaa miu oe sèmi pame'a boe sa.<bt>But if I truly expel evil.spirit/s using power from Father God, that shows that the Lord's rule/reigning is right in front of your faces. The rule/reign is there, but it's as if you don't know/aren't aware. [EXEG: last clause from implicature of Gk. See HCE and UBS TH.] [last clause from implicature of Gk. (see HCE and UBS Trans.HB)].</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ladhe dhèu èra èci dènge rèka, dhu bori tèke ètu keja g'ana-kariu madhenge èmu na, tatu mèdha-panyau na, dhèu bani boe lasi mana'u.<bt>If a strongman/gangster has weapons strapped on right-left to protect his house, surely his things will be safe (lit. there is nobody who dares to go steal them).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bori = ta'ika di badan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bori = ta'ika di badan ; keja = pinggang</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu èra risi nèti nèngu mai segi ne, aa parame nèti rèka na. Hèia na parame nèti mèdha-panyau na kahèi, ho papala mi dhèu-dhèu na. Nèbhu nare sange ne'e lamatua èmu èèna maena dhoka mi rèka na. Te ngaa limuri ne, na maena heka rèka na sèra.<bt>But if/when there is someone stronger than him who comes-defeats him, and snatches away his weapons. After that, he then snatches away his possessions to go divide out to his people. For a long time that first house-owner hoped/trusted in his weapons. But now he cannot hope in those weapons anymore. [EXEG: TH, TN and Marshall all take “the stronger man” to be Jesus, so /geng/ carries inappropriate baggage --deleted.]</bt><note reference="11:21-22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu dhèu d'èlu-mèu Alkitab, &lt;&lt;dhèu èra&gt;&gt; ètu ne'e, nuka dhèu aae nidhu. Aa &lt;&lt;dhèu dhu èra risi&gt;&gt; èèna, nuka Lamatua Yesus.<bt>According to people who are knowledgable about the Bible, “strong man” here is the king of the evil spirits. And “someone stronger than him” is the Lord Yesus.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Dhèu dhu pa'èci boe dènge Ja'a, nèngu musu Ja'a. Aa dhèu dhu soru-bara boe ètu d'ara sasab'a Ja'a, nèngu ne'a dhoka ad'u-ue j'ara maruru di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well! A person is not mutually.united with Me, s/he is My enemy. And the person doesn't mutually.help with My work, he/she is just causing chaos.”</bt><note reference="11:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 9:40</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nidhu neo lèpa asa era uru na<bt>Evil.spirit wants to return to his previous place</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:43-45)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Yesus tuhu hari lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èdhi bata eele nidhu nèti ca dhèu, nidhu ne rai la'e asa era kaliu, ho tenge era ae iisi. Lula na abhu boe era dhu pamèci dènge dad'èi na, hèia na pangee na, &lt;Aah! Abhu boe era ae iisi, be'a risi ja'a lèpa hari asa dhèu dhu uru èèna ja'a pea.&gt;<bt>Yesus continued speaking, saying, “If we-inc expel an evil.spirit out of a person. that evil spirit goes to a deserted place to look for a place to rest. Because he does not find a place that matches his desires, then he thinks, saying, “Aah! There is no place to rest, (so) it's better I return again to that previous person where I lived/stayed.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="akathartos: unclean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">akathartos: unclean</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Ropa na lèpa, rage hari era uru èèna, dhu mèu le, aa dhu lalau pabe'a-be'a.<bt>So he returns, and he encounters that previous place, it is already clean and arranged well/orderly.</bt><v n="26" />Hèia nidhu ne la'e paroa angalai na pidhu dhu bhelu risi nèti nèngu. Ka aa'i-aa'i ra lasi pea ètu dhèu èèna, ka ra madahu ne. De lèpa limuri, mamuri dhèu ne asa aae ka ele iie.&gt;&gt;<bt>So that evil.spirit goes and calls his seven friends who are more evil than he. Then they all go stay at that person, and overwhelm/gang up on him. So (consequently), now that person's life is even more misfortunate (idiomatic).”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madahu = karoyo, kasi kaluar kotoran"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">madahu = karoyo, kasi kaluar kotoran (mis. dari kapas)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="asa ele iia aae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">asa ele iia aae</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhu oto risi<bt>Those who are the most fortunate</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o Yesus padhai lii era dènge dhèu ae sèra, dhèu bhèni èci ètu èèna pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ina Mu oto kapai, lula nara iisi Èu, aa pasusu Èu!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus was still speaking with those many people, a woman there called out, saying, “Your-sg mother is very fortunate, because she gave.birth to You, and nursed You!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka Yesus b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a ina! Te ngaa dhu oto risi, nuka dhèu dhu pasa dhilu ho nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua aa tao madhutu!&gt;&gt;<bt>And/so Yesus replied, saying, “True, mother! But those who are even more fortunate, are the people who fasten their ears [pay attention] to hear Father God's Words, and follow/obey them!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu manèngi Lamatua Yesus pad'elo uru ku tadha<bt>People request the Lord Yesus to show a sign [+ impatience/imperative]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 12:38-42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Lod'o Yesus padhai lii era, dhèu oke rare Ne, hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Dhèu limuri ne re'a dhoka ad'u-ue bhabhelu di. Rèngu loe boe manèngi ho Ja'a tao tadha malaa hia rèngu, sèna ka re'a, na, Ja'a ne tare'a-re'a dhèu unu Lamatua. Te ngaa Lamatua dhu tao le tadha malaa uru èèna, re dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, nuka Yunus. Èèna na d'ai le!<bt>When Yesus was still talking, many people came crowding around Him, and/then He said, “People nowadays, only know how to do evil. They continually request that I do miracles (amazing signs) for them, so that they can know that I here, am truly the Lord's person. But the Lord has already given a miracle to them previously using His spokesperson Yunus. That is enough!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oke = ron = rae reo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">oke = ron = rae reo rare</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Ngaa dhu lèke mi dedha Yunus èèna, j'aj'i tadha hia dhèu ètu kota Niniwe, peka na, Ama Lamatua ka dhu paleha ne mai. Èci èèna ka dènge Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Ngaa dhu lèke mi Ja'a, èèna na j'aj'i mi tadha hia dhèu limuri ne, dhu peka na, mema Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>What happened with Yunus previously, became a sign for the people of Niniwe city, that Father God was the one who had sent him. It's like.that also with the Orginal/Authentic Human. What happens to Me, will become a sign for people nowadays, that, Father God is truly the one who has sent Me coming.</bt><note reference="11:29-30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:4, Markus 8:12; Yunus 3:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ladhe lod'o d'ai èle rai-haha ne, ho Lamatua j'aj'i ka Hakim, pe bhèni aae nèti balèu mamuri hari ho na j'aj'i sakasii. Na paj'uj'u ho galaa miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu mamuri taa limuri ne, peka na, &lt;Miu aa'i-aa'i mi se, goa!&gt; Te uru èèna, bhèni aae mai nèti j'ara kaj'èu, ho nèdhi dènge madha na, mamèu dhèu aae Soleman. Te ngaa limuri ne abhu Dhèu ètu talora aae miu, dhu kapai risi nèti dhèu aae Soleman. Te ngaa miu pusi boe Ne!<bt>Later at the end.of.the.world, for the Lord being Judge, later the queen from the south will live again to be a witness. She will point to accuse you-pl all who live nowadays, saying, ‘All of you here are stupid!’ Cuz (elaboration) previously that queen came from far.away to see with her very own eyes the wisdom/intelligence of king Soleman. But now there is a Person in your midst who is greater than king Soleman. But you don't want to care even a little bit about Him! [EXEG vs.31-32: “You're all stupid/ignorant,” or “You're all guilty”? Context is about reading the signs, connecting the dots. In Kupang and surrounding lgs, chiding people for not reading the signs is “You're stupid!” = failing to discern. To use a phrase like “You're guilty” is highly restricted to a formal court decision. Doesn't fit the RL here. Sense of accuse/condemn is carried by the symbolic action of finger pointing. See also HCE. TH.]</bt><note reference="11:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 10:1-10, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 9:1-12</note><v n="32" />Mesa boe nèngu di! Èèna na dhèu-dhèu nèti Niniwe kèd'i titu ho paj'uj'u ai asa miu dhu mamuri limuri ne, peka na, &lt;Miu aa'i-aa'i mi se, goa!&gt; Ra peka sèmi èèna, lula uru èèna, ropa Yunus la'e peka dad'èi Lamatua dènge rèngu, hèia ra ele-ho'a dènge. Masi ka Dhèu dhu kapai risi nèti Yunus ètu talora aae miu, te ngaa mo'o boe ele-ho'a sa hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And it won't be just her alone! Later people from Niniwe will also stand up and point their fingers at you who live nowadays, saying, ‘All of you here are stupid!’ They will speak like.that, because long ago when Yunus went to tell the Lord's will to them, they repented straight.away. But even though there is a Person who is greater than Yunus in your midst, nevertheless you don't want to repent even a little bit! [EXEG: Last clause implied by context/purpose of 29-32, and following NLT]</bt><note reference="11:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yunus 3:5</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamuri dhu saraa<bt>Clear/Bright living</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 5:15, 6:22-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu suru labhu, na padhèdi ètu era dhu dedha, sèna ka pasaraa d'ara kama hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu maso asa era èèna. Abhu ètu mia dhèu suru labhu, ho saguru ne dènge soe, sèna ka pahuni ne!<bt>Yesus continued again His speaking saying, “People light a lantern, then set it on a high place, so that it makes that room bright for all the people who enter there. No one lights a lantern, then covers it with a basket, to hide it.</bt><note reference="11:33" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e suri boe, peka na, &lt;&lt;ho saguru ne dènge soe&gt;&gt;.<bt>Some Yunani language writings, don't write “or cover it with a basket”.</bt></note>Èèna guna boe ngaa-ngaa!<bt>That has no use at all! [EXEG: LEX: Gk secret place/cellar (TB di kolong rumah); but in eastern Indonesia it actually is quite common to put a lamp under a pile house, so this is not recommended. NLT = basket]</bt><note reference="11:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:15, Markus 4:21, Lukas 8:16</note><v n="34" />Musi madha miu èci èèna ka dènge labhu. Nèngu ka dhu pasaraa d'ara miu. Ladhe musi madha maroga, dhèu ladhe ngaa aa'i-aa'i dènge d'ara dhu maroga. Te ngaa ladhe musi madha mèu, dhèu rèdhi dènge d'ara dhu be'a.<bt>Your eye is like a lamp. It makes your insides bright. If the eye is dark, people see everything with dark insides. But if the eye is clear, people see everything with good insides.</bt><v n="35" />Tenge j'ara sèna ka saraa ètu d'ara miu, j'aj'i mèu aae sèmi saraa madha lod'o. Saraa ètu d'ara miu, mage sèmi heo hèru, dhu pad'elo dhoka mamaho di.<bt>Make.an.effort so that that light in your insides, becomes very bright/clear, like the sun's brightness. That light/brightness in your insides, shouldn't be like the moon's brightness, which only shows/reveals just shadows. [COMMENT (Chuck): I can't find the source or justification for this apparent overtranslation. But I assume it's there for a reason--I just can't reconstruct it.]</bt><v n="36" />Ladhe d'ara miu saraa, abhu boe sasanga èci sa dhu maroga, tatu mamuri miu j'aj'i mèu, nuka sèmi labhu aae dhu d'elo mamuri miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>If your insides are bright, there is not a single gap that is dark, surely all [parts of] your lives will be bright/clear, as if there is a big lantern which illuminates your lives.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasanga = cela ; delo ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sasanga = cela ; delo = menyinari, menerangi, loti</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus jèke ama agama dhèu Yahudi sèra<bt>The Lord Yesus scolds the Yahudi people's heads of religion</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 23:1-36; Markus 12:38-40)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Yesus padhai lii nare, ka dhèu èci nèti partei agama Parisi nèru Ne, lasi ra'a asa èmu na. D'ai d'ara èmu èèna, ka Yesus madhèdi ètu mei ra'a.<bt>After Yesus finished speaking, (then) a person from the Parisi religious party invited Him to come eat at his house. Arriving in the house, then Yesus sat down at the eating table.</bt><v n="38" />Te ngaa lamatua èmu ne malaa ladhe Yesus madhèdi na'a, dhu j'amo uru boe ai, madhutu atora dhèu Parisi.<bt>But the house owner was amazed seeing Yesus sitting eating without handwashing first, according to the Parisi people's regulation.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka Yesus lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Miu dhèu Parisi se seli-kolane! Miu kèpe pa'èra atora agama miu! Miu bhèlu boe rase pega dènge galaa re li'u toke kale'e, te ngaa sanèd'e boe ho pamèu d'ara miu dhu kaj'alu, dhu bhelu-katub'a dènge manga'a dèu ngara!<bt>Then Yesus told him saying, “Eeh! You-pl Parisi people are too much! You hold on tight to your religious regulations! You don't forget to clean the outside of the plates and glasses until they are shiny, but you don't remember to clean those filthy insides of yours which are evil and exceedingly greedy (idiom)!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manga'a dèu ngara = (amat) rakus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">manga'a dèu ngara = (amat) rakus celup nama (\lf = Max) Idiom ; mera era = bosong dapa tampa (sok-sok) ; kahèti = karitik ; pèci lii = indirect</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />Goa, ee! Baku bhèlu. Ama Lamatua ka dhu paj'aj'i re li'u, aa tao re d'ara kahèi.<bt>Stupid! Don't forget. Father God is the one who made the outside, and also the inside.</bt><v n="41" />Te ngaa dhu be'a risi eele, miu pala-bagi dhèu dènge boe unu sèra, nèti ngaa dhu miu unu, sèna ka miu mola ètu katanga madha Lamatua.<bt>But it's better [=you should], you give out to the poor people from what you own, so.that you be clean before the Lord.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Manga'a dèu ngara! artinya: Amat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Manga'a dèu ngara! artinya: Amat rakus</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Miu dhèu Parisi! Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere mamadhe-mamopo! Ca pala nèti canguru pala dhu miu hia mi Lamatua, miu pa'iga taruu nèti dhu ana iiki toke kapai. Toke bubhu-lara dhu ana iiki-iiki d'ara oka, miu pa'iga hèi! Te ngaa miu pusi boe dènge j'ara dhu kapai risi. J'ara-j'ara sasue mi Ama Lamatua, aa dènge boe bia cabèka, miu pabhèlu eele! Mema tare'a, èdhi hud'i hia ku pala Lamatua, te ngaa baku bhèlu kahèi dènge j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai risi sèra.<bt>You-pl Parisi people! In the future you will get/experience misfortune (doublet)! One part out of ten that you give to the Lord, you keep counting everything, small-big. Even your tiny little kitchen-spices from the garden, you count every last one! But you don't care about the most/more important things. In.regards to loving Father God, and matters of justice/fairness/even-handed, you just completely forget about them! Certainly we must continue to give the Lord His share, but don't also forget about the things which are more important.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bubhu-lara = bumbu dapur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bubhu-lara = bumbu dapur</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:42" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 27:30</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere mamadhe-mamopo! Te miu d'èi dhoka tenge era re madha ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a, aa d'èi dhèu pakab'ua miu ètu madha dhèu ae.<bt>You will obtain misfortune! Cuz (elaboration) you like to find the best place up front in the worship house, and like people to honour you in front of many people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere mamadhe-mamopo! Te miu nuka sèmi ro'a dhèu madhe dhu pamera le dènge rai. Dhèu kako re dedha, te ngaa re'a boe, na, ètu èèna na abhu ro'a dhèu madhe, lula ro'a èèna ètu dedha na tèdhi na mèu, te ngaa d'ara na laho kao-kao. Masi ka madhutu ad'a èdhi, ladhe dhèu j'èli lèke ro'a dhèu madhe, pakaj'alu ngi'u na, de nèngu nia boe maso asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a. Miu dhèu Parisi se, ca ropa dènge ro'a dhèu madhe èèna! Re li'u, miu mèu titu kèna. Te ngaa ètu d'ara miu pènu dènge kaj'alu. Dhèu dhu padètu dènge miu, j'aj'i mi kaj'alu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>In the future you will get/experience misfortune (doublet)! Cuz (elaboration) you are like a grave whose dirt is already flat. People walk on top, but they don't know that there is a grave there, because the dirt on top of the grave appears to be clean, but inside it is rotten. In.actual.fact, according to our-inc tradition, a person who steps on a grave makes him/herself dirty/defiled, and thus no appropriate to enter the worship house. You Parisi people are like that grave. On the outside you are very clean. But your insides are full of rotten things. People who are near you, also get dirty/defiled.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèu bhob'o = bau busuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">hèu bhob'o = bau busuk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ètu èèna, abhu ca dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi. Ropa na tadèngi lii Yesus, ka b'ala dènge, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lii padhai Ama deo na, lèke mi dedha ji'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>There was a Yahudi law expert there. When he heard what Yesus said, he retorted, saying, “Those words of Father's, hit at us-exc!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Hèia Yesus b'ala lii na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Miu dhèu d'èlu-mèu agama Yahudi, hud'i dui mamadhe-mamopo kahèi! Miu soru boe dhèu ho pasamaa si, te ngaa miu asa pasusa si dènge j'ara pabia atora agama miu. Ka miu pua dhèu sèra pasae rupa-rupa babia nèti atora miu sèra. Te ngaa miu mesa mi, mo'o boe pasae babia ne dènge kacui-aai miu ca laa sa hèi!<bt>Then Yesus responded to him, saying, “True! You Yahudi law experts, must also obtain misfortune! You don't help people by making their lives light/unburdened, but you make their difficulty increase by/with your heavy religious regulations. Then you make people carry all.kinds.of regulations of yours. But you yourselves don't even want to lift a finger to help carry that burden!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca laa = satu jari, satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ca laa = satu jari, satu batang ; pasamaa = lighten (weight)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere mamadhe-mamopo! Te miu bhute dhoka pudhi hadhu tao tugu hia dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu uru sèra, sèna ka pakab'ua si. Te ngaa bèi-baki miu se'e ka dhu pamadhe si!<bt>In the future you will get/experience misfortune! Cuz (elaboration) you are busy building pillar/monument rocks for the Lord's spokespersons from long.ago to give honor to them. But your own ancestors are the ones who killed them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dame = labur ; pudhi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dame = labur ; pudhi = susun (batu)</Message></Annotation><v n="48" />Miu èci èèna kahèi dènge bèi-baki miu sèra. Rèngu tule eele dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua, ka ra pamadhe si. Hèia miu dame hadhu ro'a ho j'aj'i tadha, peka na, miu se mo'o kahèi dènge tatao bèi-baki miu.<bt>You are the same as those ancestors of yours. They rejected the Lord's spokespersons, and murdered/killed them. Then you-pl build grave stones as a sign that you also agree with the deeds of your ancestors.</bt><v n="49" />Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua dhu ne'a aa'i, peka nèdhi le, na, &lt;Pe Ja'a pua dhèu rèti lii padhai Ja'a, dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha dhu leo, sèna ka lasi asa dhèu sèra. Hèia dhèu sèra kalabhe paj'èra cahag'e, aa cahag'e hari ra pamadhe si.&gt;<bt>Because of that, Father God who knows everything, once spoke saying, ‘I will commission my spokespersons and other commissioned.ones to go to people. Then those people will torture some, and murder kill some.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50-51" />Dhèu taa limuri ne, hud'i tago rare tatao nèti dhèu-dhèu dhu pamadhe dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua. Sèra sa, mulai ige nèti Lamatua paj'aj'i rai-haha ne, karèi nèti mamadhe Habel, toke d'ai dhèu dhu limuri tèka, nuka Sakaria. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu ra pamadhe ne ètu talora aae mei korban dènge Kama Mola-Mèci ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Miu se kahèi pasae mere hahuku ra!<bt>People who live nowadays, must carry the responsibility for the ddeds of people who have murdered/killed the Lord's spokespersons. That counts/calculates beginning from when the Lord created this world, starting with Habel's death, until the last, Sakaria. He was the one who was murdered in between the sacrifice table and the the Holy Room in Father God's Central Worship House. You also bear/carry that punishment of theirs.</bt><note reference="11:51" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 4:8, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 24:20-21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Miu dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora agama Yahudi! Bèli-camèd'a miu dui mere mamadhe-mamopo! Te miu dhu mèd'u gagoe ho bisa bhoke babèdho, sèna ka dhèu re'a mèu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa miu mesa mi maso boe asa d'ara. Dhu karehe risi hari, miu pahèb'e dhèu, ho baku ra lasi asa èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>You Yahudi law experts! You will obtain misfortune! Cuz you hold the key that can open the door so people can understand plainly Father God's will. But you yourselves don't/won't enter there. And even more evil, you block people, so that they can't go there!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoe = anak kunci ; pahèbe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">gagoe = anak kunci ; pahèbe = pele, halangi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: pahèbe artinya: Pele"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: pahèbe artinya: Pele</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53-54" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, ka mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi sèra jèke Ne. Karèi nèti lod'o èèna ka, rèngu karèi rupa-rupa j'ara, sèna ka neo pamanahu Ne. Ra loe boe tenge j'ara ho pabèbhe Ne.<bt>When Yesus had finished speaking, then those religion teachers and Parisi people were furious at Him. Starting from that time, they continually asked all.sorts.of.things to attempt to make Him fall. They continually looked for issues/disputes to bring Him down.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku madhutu j'ara mamuri dhèu Parisi dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo<bt>Watch yourself in.order.to not follow the Parisi people's hypocrisy (saying one thing, doing another)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:26-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu pèri-pèri riho dhu mai ho nanene lii padhai Yesus. Dhèu se mai pasuki, lingu rare Ne. Ka Na peka uru dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;J'aga ngi'u ho baku madhutu j'ara mamuri dhèu Parisi. Te rèngu padhai lii leo, tao leo.<bt>At that time, several thousand people came to listen to Yesus. They walked shoving/elbowing each other and crowding around Him. Then He spoke first with His underlings, saying, “Watch yourselves so you don't follow the Parisi people's way of life. Cuz (elaboration) they like to say one.thing, do another (=hypocricy).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasuki = basesak ; lingu rare"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasuki = basesak ; lingu rare = kelilingi</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:6, Markus 8:15</note><v n="2" />Rèngu sangaja be'a, te ngaa bèli-camèd'a abhu hui. Te aa'i-aa'i dhu pahuni ne, bèli-camèd'a sabhoka.<bt>They pretend to be good, but that pretending of their's will have a tip (become visible). Cuz (elaboration) everything that is hidden now, will be seen.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hui = ujung, sisa, kedok (pura-pura,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">hui = ujung, sisa, kedok (pura-pura, kejelakan) ; sabhoka</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 4:22, Lukas 8:17</note><v n="3" />Ngaa dhu deo ne'e miu padhai pahuni, bèli-camèd'a dhèu tadèngi dènge mèu. Ngaa dhu miu paholo ètu d'ara kama, èèna na dhèu peka paled'a ètu madha dhèu ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>What you-pl speak hiddenly now, later people will hear it clearly/openly. What you whisper in the room, later people will explain/proclaim in front of many people.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paholo = bisik ; patalebo ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">paholo = bisik ; patalebo = terapung, kasi jelas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dènge kab'ua ètu madha Ama Lamatua<bt>The value of humans in front of the Lord</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:28-31)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ana-ana, ee! Mage miu madha'u, ladhe dhèu neo pamadhe miu. Te rèngu pamadhe dhoka ngi'u aae di, te ngaa ra bisa boe tao ngaa mi samanga miu.<bt>And Yesus continued speaking, saying, “Children! It's not neccessary (=don't) be afraid if people want to kill you. Cuz (elaboration) they only can murder just your body, but they can't do anything with your *soul.</bt><v n="5" />De Ja'a neo peka, na, miu hud'i madha'u mi cee ku. Miu hud'i madha'u ku dènge Ama Lamatua. Te Nèngu ka dhu bisa pamadhe miu, aa pèci asa d'ara ai naraka. De miu hud'i madha'u tare'a-re'a mi Nèngu.<bt>So I want to tell who you should be afraid of. You must be afraid of Father God. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who can kill you, and/then throw you away into the fires of hell (fixed phrase). So (consequently) He is the one, whom you must truly fear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miu hud'i madha'u dènge cee."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">miu hud'i madha'u dènge cee.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Miu pangee sèku, ana mangungu kab'ua ca ngaa? Mura titu kèna! Lèmi ngi'u, dua doi, si? Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua bhèlu boe ci'u sa hèi.<bt>You try to think, what is the price of a (sparrow-like) bird? They're very cheap! Five bodies (=bird counter) for two cents/coins, right? Even though that's the case, nevertheless Father God does not forget even one body.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana mangungu = burung pipit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ana mangungu = burung pipit</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Aa sèmi èèna kahèi, Lamatua tao ai-hèb'a mi miu. Lamatua ne'a mèu, abhu rèu kètu pèri loa ètu kaba kètu miu. De miu baku madha'u, te Lamatua pakab'ua miu risi nèti ana mangungu ae-ae sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>And in the same way, the Lord also pays attention to you-pl like.that. The Lord knows exactly how many hairs on your-pl heads. So, you-pl don't need to be afraid, cuz (elaboration) the Lord values you more than those many pipit birds.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku makae mangaku Lamatua Yesus<bt>Don't be ashamed to acknowledge the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:32-33, 12:32, 10:19-20)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èle ka, Yesus padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pasa dhilu miu paie-iie! Ladhe dhèu bani mangaku Ja'a ètu madha dhèu ae ètu rai-haha ne, pe Ja'a mangaku nèngu kahèi ètu madha ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, peka na, nèngu ne dhèu Ja'a.<bt>Then Yesus spoke again with His underlings, saying, “Attach your ears well (=pay attention)! If someone is brave to acknowledge Me in front of many people in this world, later I will acknowledge her/him in front of Father God's emmisaries in heaven (*angels), saying that s/he is My person.</bt><v n="9" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu padhai lii ètu madha dhèu rai-haha, peka na, nèngu tadhe boe Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a ètu madha ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, Ja'a tadhe boe nèngu kahèi.<bt>But if someone speaks in front of humans saying that s/he does not know Me, later I also will speak in front of Father God's underlings in heaven, that I don't know him/her either.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu padhai pakarehe kolongara Ja'a, Ama Lamatua sadia ho pabhèlu eele sasala na era. Te ngaa ladhe na padhai pakarehe kolongara Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci èèna, Ama Lamatua bhèlu boe sasala na.<bt>I here, am the Authentic Human. If someone speaks defiling My name/reputation (=slander/blaspheme), Father God is still prepared to completely forget that wrong. But if s/he speaks slandering the name of the Lord's Holy Spirit, Father God will not forget his/her wrong. [EXEG: 'speak against' parallels 'blaspheme against', cf. TH]</bt><note reference="12:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:32, Markus 3:29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ladhe dhèu ère rèti miu asa era uri lii langu agama, do, rèti miu asa dhèu paredha, lula miu parcaya Ja'a, mage miu pangee, na, tasamia miu bisa siri iisi.<bt>If/when people drag you-pl off to the place of settling religious disputes, or, take you to the people who govern, because you-pl believe in Me, you don't need to be worried about how you will defend yourselves.</bt><v n="12" />Te ètu d'ara lai-lai èèna kahèi, Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci èèna, peka dènge miu lii dhu pamèci ho b'ala dhèu sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) later at that time, Father God's Holy Spirit will tell you words which are exact/precise so.that you-pl can respond to them.”</bt><note reference="12:11-12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:19-20, Markus 13:11, Lukas 21:14-15</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii lolo dhèu kaja dhu goa<bt>Story of the rich person who was stupid</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, ca dhèu nèti dhèu ae sèra, karèi Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Peka ku dènge a'a ku, ho pabagi dènge ja'a pusaka ama ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, one of those many people asked Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher! Please tell my elder.sibling to divide our father's inheritance with me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala ne, &lt;&lt;Waa! Dhèu cee ka dhu ded'e Ja'a j'aj'i hakim, sèna ka pama'ète lii langu miu sèmi èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus answered him, saying, “Waa! [+exasperation] Who raised me up to be Judge to decide your-pl disputes like.that?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia Yesus peka mi dhèu ae sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e, ee! Miu baku j'aj'i dhèu manga'a. Te kakaja-sasu'i bisa boe nèti mamuri dhu mera-milu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke to those many people, saying, “Remember! You-pl must be careful to not be a greedy person. Cuz (elaboration) wealth (doublet) cannot bring a safe/calm/stable/peaceful life.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK ma vs. mi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">CHECK ma vs. mi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Miu hud'i mage ku, sèna ka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Miu hud'i mage ku, sèna ka baku manga'a.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Èle ka, Na padhai lii pake lii pakasame, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu kaja ca dhèu, isi oka na ae titu kèna.<bt>Then, He story-ed a comparison story, saying, “There was a rich person, whose gardens/fields had lots of harvest.</bt><v n="17" />Ka èmu-èmu dhu tèka nganga'a na pènu tao cacèci, aa risi eele hèi, ka ne'a heka tao tasamia.<bt>And his food storage houses were packed full and overflowing. And he did not know what to do (with it all).</bt><v n="18" />Ka na pama'ète, peka na, &lt;Ja'a neo tao sèmi ne'e ka! Èmu era tèka nganga'a dhu dhui se, ja'a sag'e eele ho patitu hari dhu kapai risi, sèna ka tèke nganga'a nèti d'ara oka dènge mèdha-panyau ja'a aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>So he decided saying, “I'll just do like this! I'll knock down this old storage.house to build a bigger one, then I'll store my garden/field's harvest and all other possessions there.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sag'e = bongkar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sag'e = bongkar</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ladhe j'aj'i ka sèmi èèna, ja'a pama'ète kore, na, &lt;&lt;Gud'a pènu le! Nganga'a tesa le, ku'a d'ai tèu-tèu. De ku'a-kinu pakarej'e iisi dènge pacapa haga!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>When it's like that, then I'll make a decision, saying, ‘The storage.house(s) is full! There is enough food to me to eat for years and years. So (consequently) I'll eat-drink pleasing myself and sit with crossed-legs (=image of lazy/wealthy living)!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="guda = gudang ; pacapa haga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">guda = gudang ; pacapa haga = sit with crossed legs ;</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka dènge ne, na, &lt;Heeh! Dhèu goa! Mèda ne'e kahèi, èu madhe. Aa cee ka dhu abhu aa'i isi gud'a èu sèra?&gt;<bt>But Father God told him saying, ‘Heeh! You are stupid! This night you die. And/then who will get all the contents of your storage house(s)?’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />De sèmi ne'e! Bisa kahèi, dhèu pakaboko mèdha-panyau ae-ae ètu rai-haha ne hia ngi'u na, te ngaa ètu d'ara ngangee Ama Lamatua, nèngu ne, dhèu unu aad'o, lula pabe'a boe dènge Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>So it's like! A person can/could gather lots of inheritance in this world for him/herself, but in Father God's thinking, he/she is poor, because he/she is not in a good relationship with the Lord.” [spiritual poverty following NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Parcaya dhoka mi Ama Lamatua di<bt>Just believe in Father God</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 6:25-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Yesus aj'a tabha hari ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu mage dhoka pangee mamuri miu bèli-bèli, nèti nganga'a-nganginu, do mèdha-papake.<bt>Then Yesus taught His underlings further, saying, “You-pl don't need to be overly worried/preoccupied with your every.day lives, about food or clothing.</bt><v n="23" />Te mamuri èdhi ne risi nèti ngaa dhu èdhi ta'a, aa ngaa dhu èdhi pake.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) these lives of ours-inc are more than what we-inc eat, and what we wear.</bt><v n="24" />Ladhe sèku lakaa! Rèngu sèra sèla boe, puu-g'ètu boe, dènge boe gud'a ho tèke nganga'a, te ngaa Ama Lamatua kab'oi si. Ladhe sèmi èèna, tatu Nèngu piara miu kahèi. Lula Na pakab'ua miu risi nèti manu-bhui sèra.<bt>Have a look at the /lakaa/ birds! They don't plant, don't harvest (doublet), don't have a storage.house to store food, but Father God takes.care of1 them. If/Since that's the case, surely He also can take.care of2 you. Because He values you more than those birds (generic).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lakaa = medium-large bird, makan cicak,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lakaa = medium-large bird, makan cicak, toke, belalang, itam (but when shown picture, had reservations whether it is the same as a raven); kaboi = piara, kasi makan</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Sèmi dhèu titu ètu madha tèru, ho lalau iisi na, nèngu bisa pamadhera mamuri na, do? Aad'o, sina ma!<bt>It's as if a person stands in front of a mirror, then serves/takes cares of3 him/herself, (do you think) s/he can lengthen his/her life any longer, (or what)? Can't [+emphatic]! [EXEG: Message has “mirror”. Is first clause required to set a thinking context for the rest? People reflect on their lives when standing in front of mirrors -- associated context. Otherwise phrasing seems to imply busy-ness, not worry. Has had input from several consultants (one objecting as addition).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèmi here is like &lt;&lt;andainya&gt;&gt; ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sèmi here is like &lt;&lt;andainya&gt;&gt; ; tèri iisi = mengamati (di muka cermin) suda rapi ko balom, suda gaga ko balom similar to</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />De ladhe bhute dènge ngaa-ngaa dhu ana iiki sèra, dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua, tasamia hari ka miu bhute dènge madha j'ara dhu kapai? A'oto na ngaa?<bt>So (consequently), if busy-ing one's.self with small things like that doesn't produce any effect, why do you-pl still want to busy your self with big things? What is the gain/benefit?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ladhe sèku bunga dhu muri tab'a ètu d'ara j'ami. Rèngu sab'a boe oka-tedhe, aa ra manènu boe sig'i-rabhi. Te ngaa mèdha-papake dhèu aae Soleman dhu kab'ua aae, saraga risi boe hela bunga dhu muri tab'a ètu d'ara j'ami sèra.<bt>Have a look at the flowers that grow by themselves in the bush/forest. They don't work gardens/fields, and don't weave selimuts and sarongs (doublet = generic woven cloth). But even the most fancy/expensive clothes of king Soleman, is not more beautiful than those wild/jungle flowers. [EXEG: wildflower as per BAGD and Louw &amp; Nida; work field (male) nor spin/weave cloth (female) following TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="muri tab'a = tumbuh sendiri, tumbuh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">muri tab'a = tumbuh sendiri, tumbuh liar ; manènu = tenun ; sig'i-rabhi = selimut-sarong ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 10:4-7, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 9:3-6</note><v n="28" />Te Ama Lamatua piara j'u'u dhu ana iiki-iiki dhu kab'ua aad'o, dhu dhoka mamuri deo ne'e, aa bèli madhe, ho dhèu core asa d'ara ai. Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, Nèngu bisa kab'oi miu dhu kab'ua risi eele nèti j'u'u sèra. De tasamia ka parcaya miu èra boe mi Lamatua?<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Father God takes.care of the small grasses which don't have any value, which only live today, then die tomorrow, so that people throw them into the fire. If/Since that's the case, He can take.care of3 you-pl whose worth is far more than that grass. So (consequently), why do you-pl not firmly believe in the Lord/God?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaboi (dhèu, badha) = piara (j'u'u)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaboi (dhèu, badha) = piara (j'u'u)</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, miu baku bhute dènge nganga'a-nganginu. Te èèna na, Lamatua uri hia miu.<bt>Similarly, you-pl don't need to be busy-ing yourselves about eating-drinking. Cuz (elaboration) the Lord will handle/arrange it. [/bhute/ covers both the effort of 'striving for' and the emotion of 'worrying about' from the Gk. Last sentence from context, needed for naturalness.]</bt><v n="30" />Dhèu dhu tadhe boe Lamatua, rèngu sèra sab'a toke madhe, sèna ka tao j'ara sèra. Te ngaa miu baku sèmi rèngu, te Ama miu ètu sorga dhu ne'a aa'i le ngaa dhu miu parluu.<bt>People who don't know/recognise the Lord, they work very hard to do those things. But you-pl shouldn't be like them, cuz (elaboration) your Father in heaven already knows everything which you need.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ethnee: da peopo dat donno God,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">ethnee: da peopo dat donno God, da odda peopos all ova da world? He's talking about everybody who isn't part of God's Kingdom.</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Te ngaa pakako uuru ku sasab'a Ama Lamatua, pe Na uri j'ara se'e hia miu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But carry out Father God's work first, then3 He will arrange/take.care.of these things for you too.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Taba artinya: Tumbuh liar."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Taba artinya: Tumbuh liar.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tèke laa mèdha-panyau ètu sorga<bt>Store possessions (doublet) in heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 6:19-21)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu nuka sèmi cakaboko iiki kahib'i-kalèbho dhu èra boe. Te ngaa baku madha'u! Te Ama miu ètu sorga, Dhèu Aae Kapai. Ngaa dhu unu Nèngu, Na hia mi ana-ana Na dènge d'ara karej'e.<bt>Then Yesus continued again, saying, “You-pl are like a small group of sheep who have no strength. But don't be afraid! Cuz (elaboration) your Father in heaven, is the Great King. What He owns, He is happy to give to His children. [EXEG: leaves open 1. share in blessings of Kingdom, and/or 2. share in rule of Kingdom, see Marshall.]</bt><v n="33" />De lami pahie mèdha-panyau miu, ho kab'ua na pabagi dènge dhèu dhu dènge boe unu. Dènge sèmi èèna, miu tèke le mèdha-panyau miu ètu sorga ètu era dhu ele iie boe taa-taa. Dhèu mana'u bisa boe lasi mana'u rare. Ana cangèpi bisa boe pa'ele iie.<bt>So (consequently) go sell off your-pl things, to divide out the money to the poor people. In that way you store possessions in heaven in a place that never breaks down/decays/rusak. Thieves cannot go steal it. Even cockroaches cannot destroy it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana cangèpi = moth ; ana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ana cangèpi = moth ; ana gorohai = jengkrik ; kadhi ; ele iie boe = tidak rusak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miu tèke le mèdha-panyau miu ètu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">miu tèke le mèdha-panyau miu ètu sorga ètu era dhu ele iia boe taa-taa.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="This is not just future; this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">This is not just future; this is an investment we are making every day now.</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Mèdha-panyau miu ètu mia, na, d'ara miu ètu èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well! Where your-pl possession are, na, your livers are also there.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana pajuu dhu bori mema dhari<bt>Low.ranking.servant who is always prepared (idiom)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35-36" />Yesus padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mèda-mèu miu musti bori mema dhari ho lalau Lamatua. Nuka sèmi ènu dhu beke, mate lamatua èmu na lèpa nèti pesta kab'i. Ropa lamatua na kad'eu babèdho èmu, nèngu bhoke dènge.<bt>Yesus spoke again, saying, “Day-night you-pl must be always prepared to serve the Lord. Like a servant/slave who stays.awake.at.night waiting for the house owner to come home from a wedding feast. When the master knocks on the door, he can open it straightaway. [EXEG: prepare to serve God? prepare for the Lord's return? NLT, Marshall seem to go with the former. TN the latter. Many evade the issue and just say “gird up your loins” --an unknown idiom meaning “be prepared for action”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bori = lingkar ; bori mema"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bori = lingkar ; bori mema dhari = Idiom: siap-siaga ; kadeu = toki</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:35-36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:1-13; Markus 13:34-36</note><v n="37" />Ladhe lamatua mai nèdhi dhèu sab'a se dhu mate tae-tae, tatu rèngu oto. Pe lamatua ra pad'elo d'ara be'a na mi rèngu. Na pake mèdha-papake dhèu sab'a, ho la'e lalau nganga'a be'a, sèna ka hia dhèu sab'a se'e ra'a-rinu.<bt>If the master comes and finds his workers are waiting like.that, surely they will benefit/profit. Later the master himself will show his good insides/kindness/generosity to them. He will put on worker's clothes, to serve good food so he can have those servants feast.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tatae ~ tae-tae ; mate tae-tae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">tatae ~ tae-tae ; mate tae-tae = menunggu dgn tekun</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Dhèu sab'a se mema oto, lula rèngu ladhe-leru lamatua ra dènge be'a. Masi ka lamatua ra lèpa èmu hake pèri èèna ka, d'ara talora mèda, do oe mèu, rèngu dhu bori mema dhari.<bt>Those servants truly benefit/fortunate, because they served their master well. No matter what time the master comes home, middle of the night, or almost dawn, they are/were always prepared.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaruru boe = sonde dapa tidor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasaruru boe = sonde dapa tidor sadiki</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Ladhe abhu lamatua èmu dhu ne'a mema hake pèri dhèu mana'u mai mana'u, tatu na soro tèke boe ho dhèu mana'u huki èmu na.<bt>Think carefully! If there is a house owner who knows beforehand what time a thief comes to steal, surely he will not allow an opportunity for that thief to pry (physically) into his house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huki = cungkil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">huki = cungkil</Message></Annotation><v n="40" />De miu hud'i bori mema dhari, te ca dhèu sa dhu re'a boe pèri lod'o Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a èèna mai hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), you-pl must always be prepared, cuz (elaboration) there is not a single person who knows exactly when the Authentic Human will come back.”</bt><note reference="12:39-40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 24:43-44</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana madhutu dhu satia, dènge dhu satia boe<bt>Underlings who are faithful (loan), and underlings who are not faithful</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:45-51)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Hèia Petrus karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Lii pakasame Ama deo na, lèke dhoka mi ji'i do, lèke mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus asked Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher! That comparison.story of Father's earlier, is it only about us-inc ourselves or about all people?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42-44" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Lii pakasame deo na lèke mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tao sèmi kapala urusan dhu satia. Nèngu d'èlu-mèu uri j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a hia mi lamatua na. Te èèna na, lamatua na ded'e ne, sèna ka papala nganga'a hia mi dhèu sab'a dhu leo sèra. Ladhe nèngu maj'èni sab'e madhutu sasab'a na sèmi èèna, masi ka lamatua na mai sange mera mia èèna ka, te ngaa nèngu ne dhu loe boe tao j'ara dhu lèke. Hèia na oto, lula lamatua na ded'e ne ho ladhe-leru mèdha-panyau na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then Yesus replied saying, “That comparison.story is about all people who do like a faithful manager. He is skilled in managing things well for his master. Cuz (elaboration) later his master will lift him up (appoint him) to divide food for the other workers. [EXEG: Gk here is /oikonomos/ ‘kapala urusan’, not ‘hamba’.] If he is diligent in following his work like.that, no matter what time his master comes, but [contrary to expectation] he is always doing things correctly. So then he profits/is fortunate, because his master will appoint him to take care of all his belongings-possessions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pistos: trustworthy oikonomos: person in charge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">pistos: trustworthy oikonomos: person in charge of managing a household or an estate.<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Te ngaa carui bagi kapala urusan dhu pangee, na, &lt;Ele boe nèbhu ku, heka lamatua ne lèpa kèna.&gt; Hèia na kalabhe dhèu sab'a dhu leo sèra, mone dènge bhèni. Ka na madhèdi na'a-ninu dènge kea rae-rae toke mahu.<bt>But misfortune if that manager starts to think saying, ‘Perhaps it will be a long time before the master comes home.’ Then he begins to beat up the other workers, male and female. Then2 he sits eating-drinking in excessive pleasure until drunk. [EXEG: LEX: Gk shifts from /oikonomos/ to /doulos/ here, but it has the anaphoric article, so for our NTT lgs need to keep ‘kapala urusan’ for referent tracking.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kea rae-rae = sukacita yg berkelebihan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kea rae-rae = sukacita yg berkelebihan</Message></Annotation><v n="46" />Te ngaa ca tèka kapala urusan ne ne'a nare boe, cag'ag'a laa, lamatua na lèpa. Ka lamatua na kalabhe ne, hèia babège eele ne, sèna ka sèmi nare pala na ètu li'u, palere-lere dènge dhèu dhu satia boe, tao madhutu dad'èi lamatua ra.<bt>But one day, when that servant is not suspecting anything, unexpectedly the master comes.home. Then the master immediately beats him up, then expels him, to receive his portion (Fig: just desserts) outside, together with the people who are not faithful (loan) in following the master's will.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Te dhèu sab'a dhu re'a dad'èi lamatua ra, te ngaa pa'èra boe tao madhutu, do, d'èi boe sab'e madhutu, bèli-camèd'a ra dui rare hahuku dhu bia.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the workers who knows their masters' will, but are not ready to follow/obey it, or does not want to follow it, will be afflicted with heavy/severe punishment. [NOTE: plural for genre reasons.]</bt><v n="48" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a dhu sab'e sale, lula re'a boe dad'èi lamatua ra, rèngu abhu boe hahuku dhu bia. Te dhèu dhu abhu ae, ra manèngi ae nèti nèngu kahèi. Dhèu dhu abhu sasab'a kapai, dhadhaa na kapai kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the worker who works wrong because he did/does not know his master's will, he will be afflicted with punishment that is not heavy. Cuz (elaboration) a person who gets/receives/obtains much, much will also be asked of him. A person who gets/receives big/important work, his responsibility is also big/important.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhadhaa = tanggung jawab ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhadhaa = tanggung jawab ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii holo-nori Lamatua Yesus bisa tao dhèu mae-manyèla<bt>The Lord Yesus' teaching/message can cause people to break apart/divide (doublet)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lii holo nori Lamatua Yesus nèti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Lii holo nori Lamatua Yesus nèti boe dadame</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:34-36)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mamai Ja'a ne ho cèri eele dhèu Ja'a nèti dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne. Ne'e nuka sèmi dhèu pake ai, ho tunu eele maruru. Dad'èi Ja'a ka ladhe ai ne mulai heo ètu mia-mia.<bt>After that, Yesus spoke further, saying, “I've come to separate out My people from other people in this world. That is like people use fire to burn off the crud/filth/rubbish. I would like it if that fire was begin to burn everywhere. [EXEG: Marshall says in context of Luke ‘fire’ here should be taken as judgment (broad sense). He says interpretation as representing “power of the Spirit” has no contextual support here. Green agrees. TN favours “division” in context of 12:49-53. UNS's at one check took fire literally, hence unpacking the metaphor. Western Bukidnon Manobo BT.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahag'a-pacèri = kasi pisa satu dng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pahag'a-pacèri = kasi pisa satu dng satu ; na'e dai = lit. makan (fire consume) ; heo = nyala, cahaya</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mamai Ja'a ne kèti dènge ai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Mamai Ja'a ne kèti dènge ai asa rai-haha ne. Ja'a dèi sèna ka ai ne heo asa mia-mia.</Message></Annotation><v n="50" />Te ngaa uru nèti èèna, Ja'a hud'i pasae ku j'aj'èra dhu bia. Ja'a bèli-camèd'a j'èra ae, toke d'ai èle sasab'a-la'a Ja'a.<bt>But I must bear/experience heavy suffering first. I will truly suffer until My work/task/responsibilities are over/complete. [EXEG: until the time is over? or until my work is completed? NLT in 49 “that my task were already completed, 50 until it (burden) is accomplished”; Marshall in 50 “a destiny to be fulfilled” Green “within the … framework of his mission”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="toke dai èle lod'o na."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">toke dai èle lod'o na.</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:50" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 10:38</note><v n="51" />Miu pangee, na, Ja'a mai kèti dame ètu rai-haha, do? Aad'o! Ja'a mai sèna ka tao dhèu rai-haha ne patao-palaha dènge mae-manyèla, lula lii holo-nori Ja'a.<bt>You-pl think I come/came to bring peace to this world, right? No! I come/came to make humans fight-argue (doublet) with each other and break apart/divide (doublet) because of My teaching.</bt><v n="52" />Nèti deo ne'e, dhèu dhu pa'a'ari mae-manyèla. Ètu d'ara èmu cue, dhèu tèlu lab'a dhèu dua, dua lab'a tèlu.<bt>Starting now people who are mutually.siblings will tear/break.apart (doublet). In one household, three will oppose two, two will oppose three.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karèi nèti uru ; (*karèi) nèti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">karèi nèti uru ; (*karèi) nèti deo ne'e (Lazarus wants for both);</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="53" />Ama lab'a ana,<bt>Father will oppose child;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana lab'a ama.<bt>child will oppose father.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ina lab'a ana;<bt>Mother will oppose child;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana lab'a ina.<bt>child will oppose mother.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Teto lab'a ana mantu;<bt>Mother-in-law/FZ will oppose child-in-law</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana mantu lab'a teto na.&gt;&gt;<bt>child in law will oppose mother in law/FZ.”</bt><note reference="12:53" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mika 7:6</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Patadhe paie-iie tadha lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra sèra<bt>Recognise/know well the signs of difficult days/days of suffering</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 16:2-3)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge dhèu ae sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu mèdhi ra'i-liru mèdhi aae cèu nèti haa, miu peka na, &lt;Ne'e, tadha èj'i oe mai kèna.&gt; Mema lèke sèmi èèna.<bt>Then Yesus spoke with those many people, saying, “If/when you-pl see black clouds appearing in the west, you say, ‘This is a sign that rain will come.’ Certainly that's true.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ma'aa = tebal ; ra'i-liru mèdhi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ma'aa = tebal ; ra'i-liru mèdhi aae = black cloud</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="On different parts of the same"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">On different parts of the same island, a storm normally comes in from different directions. It also depends on the wind pattern and whether there is a hurricane. "Black cloud" matches ombros 'rain storm, thunderstorm,' though thunderstorms are not very frequent.</Message></Annotation><v n="55" />Ladhe ngèlu balèu mai, miu peka na, &lt;Ne'e, tadha lod'o pana titu kèna.&gt; Mema tare'a sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>If/when the south wind comes, you say, ‘This is a sign that today will be very hot.’ Certainly that's also true.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="notos: south, southwest; the &quot;kona&quot; direction"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">notos: south, southwest; the "kona" direction is from what is normally the leeward side, and on all islands it is southwest to west southwest. It brings hot, muggy weather. LN: "All get asthma."</Message></Annotation><v n="56" />Weeh! Miu dhèu leko-monya dhu padhai lii leo, tao leo! Miu d'èlu-mèu titu kèna me'a peka mia lod'o èj'i, aa mia lod'o pana aae. Te ngaa tasamia ka mo'o boe me'a dènge dad'èi Lamatua ètu taa limuri ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Weeh! [+not so fast] You-pl hypocritical people who speak one thing, do another! You are so skilled in understanding when it's going to rain and when it's going to be really hot. But why do you not want to understand the will of God in this time/now?” [EXEG: ‘unwilling to understand’ from Marshall and LB. “interpret the present time” God's power in the miracles Jesus does (too narrow); the significance of what I do (TN-OK); Marshall argues that it is quite broad, including political developments, and this is the broad sense we are aiming for. Os Guinness also understands this broad sense.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Miu dèlu-mèu titu kèna me'a peka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Miu dèlu-mèu titu kèna me'a peka mia lod'o èj'i, aa mia lod'o pana aae.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Padame dènge musu miu<bt>(Make) mutual.peace with your-pl enemies</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 5:25-26)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57-58" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu tao lii langu, nga tao ka miu bisa boe pama'ète unu mi, mia dhu lèke! Be'a risi uri uuru ku dame! Mage dhoka miu d'ai katanga madha hakim, ho na pama'ète, na, miu maso asa d'ara bèdho.<bt>Yesus spoke again, saying, “If/when you-pl have a dispute, why don't you decide yourselves which (of options) is correct! It's better to arrange/make peace first! May it not be that you-pl arrive in front of the judge, then he decides to put you in jail.</bt><v n="59" />Te ladhe sèmi èèna, miu bisa boe kalua, ladhe miu b'ae mere mèka dedha dhu hakim pama'ète nare èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if that's the case, surely you will not get out until you have completely paid off that fine which the judge has decided.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kélu = debt, utang ; dhedha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kélu = debt, utang ; dhedha = denda</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="arkhon: magistrate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">arkhon: magistrate</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tèke eele tatao dhu bhelu, ho madhutu dad'èi Lamatua<bt>Leave behind deeds which are evil, to follow/obey God's will (=things of God)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu mai peka dènge Yesus, na, gubernur Pilatus pamadhe le dhèu Yahudi pèri-pèri nèti Galilea, lod'o dhu mai asa Yerusalem, rèti korban asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i.<bt>At that time, people came to tell Yesus that gubernur Pilatus had killed several Yahudi people from Galilea, when they were bringing sacrifices to the Central Worship House in Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mignymi: Hebraism, does not imply mixing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">mignymi: Hebraism, does not imply mixing of bloods, but simultaneity</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ropa tadèngi nare, ka Yesus karèi si, &lt;&lt;Madhutu miu, na, tasamia? Dhèu dhu ra pamadhe sèra, sasala ra kapai risi nèti dhèu Galilea dhu leo aa'i-aa'i ra, do? Nèti èèna ka, ra huku pamadhe si, do?<bt>When (He) heard that, then Yesus asked them, “According to you-pl, how is it? (Do you think that perhaps) Those people who were killed, their wrongs were bigger/greater than all the other Galilea people? Is that why they were punished with being killed, or what?</bt><v n="3" />Aad'o! Te ngaa ladhe miu tèke eele boe mamuri miu dhu bhelu, ho lèpa madhutu dad'èi Lamatua, lod'o limuri miu laho nuka sèmi rèngu kahèi.<bt>No! But if you don't leave behind your lives which are evil, to return and follow/obey the God's will (=things of God), you also will be ruined/destroyed2 like them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aapa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">aapa =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="miu ele iie nuka sèmi rèngu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">miu ele iie nuka sèmi rèngu se kahèi.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Aa tasa mera mia hari dènge canguru aru dhèu dhu madhe ca hari ni, ropa ètu Siloam manara guri, hèia kabhie nare si, èèna? Sasala si ae risi nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu Yerusalem, do?<bt>And, how.about those eighteen people who died that time when the tower fell.down at Siloam crushed them? [Were] their wrongs bigger/greater than all other people in Yerusalem, or what?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhie nare ; guri = rubu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kabhie nare ; guri = rubu</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Aad'o! Te ngaa ladhe miu tèke eele boe mamuri miu dhu bhelu, ho lèpa asa j'ara Lamatua dhu mola, miu èèna na laho sèmi rèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>No! But if you don't leave behind your lives which are evil, to return and follow the Lord's straight path, you also will be destroyed2 like them.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Aj'u dhu hua boe, nuka sèmi dhèu unu Lamatua dhu tao nare boe dhu be'a<bt>Tree/s which don't bear fruit are like the Lord's people who don't produce/accomplish anything good</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lii pakasame nèti aj'u dhu hua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Lii pakasame nèti aj'u dhu hua boe // dhu dènge boe kabua //dhu dènge boe hasil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yesus peka lii pakasame èci, na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu dhu dènge ana aaj'u<bt>Then Yesus gave a comparison.story saying, “There was a person who had a tree</bt><note reference="13:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Idhonesia &lt;aj'u ara&gt;. Madhutu lii Yunani na <span class="Italic">sukein.</span> Te ngaa Alkitab pad'elo aj'u èci ètu nèi dhu hua na dhèu bisa ra'a. Ètu Idhonesia re bèka dhimu dhèu ra'a boe hua &lt;aj'u ara&gt;. De &lt;aj'u ara&gt; ètu Idhonesia bèka dhimu sama boe dènge &lt;aj'u ara&gt; ètu Alkitab.<bt>The Indonesian language uses the word ‘ara tree’. According to the Yunani language it is <span class="Italic">sukein.</span> But the Bible indicates a tree there (remote) which people can eat its fruit. In eastern Indonesia, people do not eat ‘ara tree’ fruit. So ‘ara tree’ in eastern Indonesia, is not the same as ‘ara trees’ in the Bible.</bt></note>ètu d'ara oka na. Bèli-bèli, na la'e patigi, teko-teko ana aaj'u ne hua le, do dhae. Te ngaa ana aaj'u ne dhae hua mèka.<bt>in his garden. He habitually/daily went to inspect it wanting to know if perhaps that tree had fruit already, or not yet. But that tree had not yet born fruit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patigi = maloi ; teko-teko ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">patigi = maloi ; teko-teko = jangan-jangan ; sèle = tanam</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ka na pua dhèu sab'a ètu d'ara oka, aku nèngu na, &lt;Tèlu tèu kèna, ja'a laku-mai ho ladhe ana aaj'u ne hua le, do dhae, te ngaa ja'a abhu boe ngaa-ngaa. De patue eele ne, te nèngu ne dhoka na'e era di.&gt;<bt>Then he told his garden worker, saying, ‘For three years now, I have come over and over to see/check out if this tree already has fruit, or not yet, but I have not gotten anything. So chop it down, cuz (elaboration) this tree is just taking up space.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patue = tebang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">patue = tebang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ama baku pasori ku. Hud'i nèbhu hari ku ciki laa d'ai ca tèu sa. Pe ja'a kakèi rai reo kapua na, sèna ka tao pupuk, ho na sega.<bt>But that garden worker replied saying, ‘Father don't be in a hurry with a decision. Allow time for this tree one more year. Let me dig around its base, to1 put fertilizer to2 make it fertile.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sega = subur, rindang ; kèi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sega = subur, rindang ; kèi = dig down ; kakèi = dig around and loosen the soil; baku pasori ku = jangan buru-buru</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ladhe d'ai tèu mai nèi, aj'u ne hua, na be'a. Ladhe aad'o, la'a sina ma, patue eele ka laa.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>If next year this tree gives.fruit, well.then, good. But if not, well alright, just chop it down.”’</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu bhèni èci dhu kabodho kapo'o, lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a woman with a bent back, on a worship day</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ca tèka, lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi, Yesus la'e aj'a dhèu ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a.<bt>One time, exactly on the Yahudi people's worship day, Yesus went to teach at the worship house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabodho koe = bent over (leaning)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kabodho koe = bent over (leaning) ; kabodho kapo'o = bent over (forward) ; kabodho kabuku = hunchback</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Ètu ne'e abhu bhèni ca dhèu dhu kabodho kapo'o canguru aru tèu kèna, lula nidhu tao ne. Bhèni ne bisa boe pamola kabodho na.<bt>There there was a woman whose back was bent already eighteen years, because of evil.spirit's doing. She could not straighten her back.</bt><v n="12" />Ropa Yesus ladhe nèdhi, hèia Na paroa ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina! Lamatua patalale le j'aj'èra nèti èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus say that woman then, He called her, saying, “Mother! The Lord/God has released/saved/freed you from your suffering.”</bt><v n="13" />Ka Yesus tao ai mi bhèni ne. Kaca'a laa, kabodho bhèni ne mola dènge kahèi. Hèia bhèni ne manèngi makasi, aa koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then Yesus put his hand on that woman. Unexpectedly that bent back of hers was straight right.way. And she gave thankyou, and praised the name/reputation of Father God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa kapala èmu sabaj'a ne nasa, lula Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a. Ka na peka dènge dhèu ae sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;D'ara ca migu, dhèu sab'a èna lod'o. De be'a risi dhèu pèd'a mai lèke dènge lod'o-lod'o sab'a sèra, sèna ka tenge dhèu puri-pa'èle si. Baku mai lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>But that worship house's head got angry, because Yesus healed that woman on the worship day. And he told the crowd, saying, “One week has six work days. So (consequently) it would be better for sick people to come on those work days, to seek someone to heal them. Don't come on the worship day!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="De be'a risi pa'èle dhèu pèda"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">De be'a risi pa'èle dhèu pèda ètu dara lod'o-lod'o sab'a sèra, sad'i baku lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a!&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:9-10, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:13-14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Yesus b'ala ne, &lt;&lt;Heeh! Dhèu kapod'e-kabèli! Ètu d'ara lod'o sabaj'a, miu sab'a kahèi, si? Te miu lami patabuli sapi dènge keled'ei miu, sèna ka hia ra'a-rinu, si?<bt>But Yesus replied to him, saying, ‘He! Deceiver! On the worship day you-pl also work, right? Cuz (elaboration) you-pl go to free your cows and donkeys to give them food-drink, right?</bt><v n="16" />Bhèni ne, ana-èpu Abraham sama sèmi èdhi. Dhèu aae nidhu paj'èra ne canguru aru tèu kèna. Ladhe Ja'a patabuli ne nèti nidhu, lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i, na èèna sala, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>This woman here, is ancestor Abraham's descendant, just like us-inc. The king of the evil.spirits has caused her to suffer for 18 years. If I free her from an evil spirit on the worship day, na, is that wrong/what's wrong with that?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaas: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Satanaas: da Devil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ropa tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, ka musu Yesus sèra makae. Te ngaa dhèu ae dhu leo sèra karej'e, lula sasab'a Na sèra be'a titu kèna.<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yesus' enemies were embarrassed/ashamed. But those many other people were happy with His incredible good deeds.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka lii upama lula-nèti aj'u dhu lamusi na ana iiki-iiki<bt>The Lord Yesus tells a comparison.story about seed that very small</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:31-32; Markus 4:30-32)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka Yesus peka hari, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pasoro dhèu-dhèu Lamatua sèmi ngaa hari?<bt>Then Yesus spoke further, saying, “What should I compare the Lord's people with?</bt><v n="19" />Hiu-hiu èèna rèngu ciki di, te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu ka rèngu asa tabha ae. Rèngu sèmi aj'u dhu lamusi na ana iiki-iiki. Dhèu sèle ne ètu d'ara oka. Ka muri mai, hèia j'aj'i ana aaj'u dhu kapai aae. Èèna ka manu-bhui mai tao rèd'a ètu dadana na sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>At the beginning they are only just a few, but eventually they increase greatly. They start like a seed that is very tiny. A person plants it in his garden. Then it lives/grows to become a huge tree. Then2 the birds come make nests in it's branches.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka lii pakasame nèti ragi<bt>The Lord Yesus gives a comparison.story about yeast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 13:33)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia Yesus padhai lii hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pasoro dhèu unu Lamatua sèmi ngaa hari?<bt>Then Yesus spoke again, saying, “What else should I compare the Lord's people with?</bt><v n="21" />Nèngu ne nuka sèmi ragi dhu dhèu bhèni nare, ho na pab'ali dènge tarigu dua saku,<bt>It's like yeast which a woman takes to mix with two sacks of flour</bt><note reference="13:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani peka na, tarigu 3 <span class="Italic">sata.</span> Ca sata, pe d'ai 12 liter. De 3 sata, 36 liter tarigu.<bt>The Yunani language says 3 <span class="Italic">sata</span> of flour. One sata, is about 12 liters. So, 3 sata, 36 liters of flour.</bt></note>sèna ka tao roti pa'ae. Lula ragi dhu ciki oo'e èèna, pab'ali dènge tarigu ae-ae, hèia ca'e aa'i. Dhèu unu Lamatua pangaru ra asa tabha kapai sèmi èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>to make lots of bread. Then that flour all raises until it's big, because of that tiny bit of yeast. The Lord's people also increase in influence (loan) like that.” [EXEG: increase in number? or, increase in influence? (Marshall, TH, CONNOT, TN, NLT all favour the latter.); added last sentence from Belu Cons. Check UNS responses to explicate topic.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saku = sack ; sahuu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">saku = sack ; sahuu = kembung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="3 sata: around 55 pounds, a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">3 sata: around 55 pounds, a little more than a standard flour sack. ezymoothee holon: People know the difference in taste between flour tortillas from Taco Bell, made with flour, water, and a little oil, and pita bread, sold in the supermarkets. It's not the size of the risen dough that is at issue (it gets punched down anyway), but the different quality. But LN didn't realize that the yeast at that time was kept moist, like sourdough; she's used to powdered yeast in a sealed envelope.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Babèdho sorga kob'o iiki<bt>Heaven's door is teeny tiny (narrow)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 7:13-14, 21-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle ka, Yesus si mulai kako lasi asa kota Yerusalem. Rèngu kako, lasi dhuli kota-kota dènge rae-rae, ho Na aj'a dhèu.<bt>After that, Yesus (collective) began to walk to Yerusalem city. On the way, He stopped in at cities and villages to teach people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kob'o = sempit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kob'o = sempit</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />D'ai era èci, ka ca dhèu karèi Ne, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ele boe dhèu ciki di, dhu abhu sod'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>At one place, a person asked Him, “Father Teacher! Probably it's only just a very few people who can be saved/get life, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hèb'a maso asa sorga èèna, kob'o. De tenge j'ara paie-iie, sèna ka miu bisa maso re èèna. Te abhu dhèu ae dhu sèku neo maso, te ngaa bisa boe.<bt>He answered, saying, “That door entering heaven is small/narrow. So (consequently) strive/make effort so that you-pl can enter there. Cuz (elaboration) there are many people who want to try to enter, but can't.</bt><v n="25" />Ladhe lamatua èmu patèke le babèdho, èèna na miu titu ètu li'u, ho kad'eu babèdho, dènge pa'oo manèngi, peka na, &lt;Ama! Bhoke ku laa!&gt;<bt>If the house owner has already locked the door, then you-pl stand outside to knock on the door, and yell out requesting help, saying, ‘Father! Open up!’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa na b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;Miu sèra, cee? Ja'a tadhe boe miu!&gt;<bt>But he will reply saying, ‘Who are you-pl? I don't know you!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="egertheei: gets up, not from bed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">egertheei: gets up, not from bed, but from eating a late dinner, gets up from the table, locks up the house, and then goes to bed. apokleiseei: shut with a lock<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia miu peka hari, na, &lt;Nga tao ka ama tadhe boe ji'i? Ji'i se ka dhu tema madhèdi nga'a-nginu dènge ama. Aa ama kahèi dhu tema aj'a-nori ji'i ètu j'ara oka-hoo ji'i.&gt;<bt>Then you will say, ‘How can it be that father (=you) doesn't know us-exc? We are the ones who habitually ate-drank with father. Father also habitually taught us in our streets/avenues/boulevards.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;Deo na ja'a dhu peka le, na, ja'a tadhe boe miu! Miu se, dhèu dhu tema ad'u-ue bhabhelu di. De pakaj'èu nèti ne'e ne!&gt;<bt>Then he will reply, saying, ‘I've already said, I don't know you! You are just people who habitually do evil. Get away from here!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adikia: unrighteousness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">adikia: unrighteousness</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 6:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ladhe d'ai lod'o Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, miu tangi roma iisi dènge kadhi ngutu lii kico-kico. Te miu ladhe mèdhi baki Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob, dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, madhèdi le ètu sorga. Te ngaa miu lèke babège asa li'u.<bt>Then, later when Father God decides everyone's cases, you-pl will just cry sobbingly and grind your teeth. Cuz (elaboration) you got to see grandfather/forefather Abraham, Isak, Yakob and all Father God's spokespersons who are sitting in heaven. But you have been expelled outside.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii kico-kico = sound of teech"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lii kico-kico = sound of teech grinding</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="brygmos: sign of rage and futility"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">brygmos: sign of rage and futility -- don't like it but can't do a thing about it.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 22:13, 25:30</note><v n="29" />Pe dhèu mai nèti suu-suu rai-haha ne, nèti dhimu, nèti haa; nèti badae, nèti balèu, ho aa'i-aa'i ra madhèdi pa'èci, ra'a-rinu rame-rame ètu d'ara èmu Ama Lamatua.<bt>Later humans will come from the ends of the world, from the east, from the west; from the north, from the south, to all sit and eat festively at Father God's house. [kingdom &gt; palace: part-whole as appropriate context and imagery for feast].</bt><note reference="13:28-29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 8:11-12</note><v n="30" />Patadhe pabe'a-be'a j'ara ne'e: ladhe d'ai ka lod'o Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, abhu dhèu dhu uru èèna, pangee, na, nèngu ana iiki d'ai seli, aa te ngaa nèngu kab'ua titu kèna. Aa abhu dhu uru èèna peka, na, nèngu dhèu kapai, te ngaa ètu madha Lamatua, nèngu dhoka ana iiki di.&gt;&gt;<bt>Take good note of this: when the the day arrives that the Lord decides everyone's cases on this earth, there will be those who previously people considered a small/unimportant person, but he will get great honour. And those whom people previously said he was a big/important person, but in God's eyes he is just a small/unimportant person.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="idou: call attention to what he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">idou: call attention to what he is going to say</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 19:30, 20:16, Markus 10:31</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus rasa kasia dènge isi kabarai kota Yerusalem<bt>The Lord Yesus has pity on the inhabitants of Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 23:37-39)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu Parisi pèri-pèri, mai paraga dènge Yesus, ka ra peka, na, &lt;&lt;Hua iia Ama Mese pakaj'èu nèti era ne'e, te dhèu aae Herodes neo pamadhe Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, several Parisi people come to meet with Yesus, then they said, “It's better Father Teacher retreats far to another place, cuz (elaboration) king Herodes wants to murder Father.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32-33" />Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Herodes ne, cakaraa badha dhu d'èlu-mèu kapod'e-kabèli. Lami peka dènge nèngu, na, Ja'a bata eele nidhu dènge pa'èle dhèu nèti papèd'a-tarègu ra, deo ne'e ne dènge bèli. Camèd'a ku, sasab'a Ja'a ne heka èle kèna. Masi ka tasa mera mia èèna ka, nèti kakako Ja'a asa Yerusalem ne, Ja'a neo sab'a hari ku ciki. Te dhèu Yerusalem sèra, dhu d'èi pamadhe dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “This Herodes is like a crafty/deceptively clever animal! You-pl go tell him, that I am expelling evil.spirit/s and healing people from their diseases today and tomorrow. The day after tomorrow, only.then will that work of Mine be finished. No matter what, I still want to work a bit more on My way to Yerusalem. Cuz (elaboration) those Yerusalem people, are the ones who like to murder Father God's spokespersons (*people who bring/bear God's message/words).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papèda-tarègu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">papèda-tarègu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haloopeki: not &quot;sly&quot;, which is how"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">haloopeki: not "sly", which is how the fox is cast in French, German, and English folk tales, but lightweight, no consequence, a pest (Buth). Like the little foxes that spoil the vines in Canticles.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Waa, dhèu kabarai Yerusalem, ee! Miu dhu loe boe pamadhe dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, aa pèci pamadhe dhèu pajuu-paleha sèra dhu mai pad'elo j'ara hia miu. Pèri-pèri hari le, Ja'a neo kaboko miu ho bhiri mi nèti bhelu-katub'a, nuka sèmi manu rena dhu sarimu nare ana na ètu d'ara èla na. Te ngaa miu mo'o boe.<bt>Waa, Yerusalem inhabitants ee! You-pl are the ones who always murder Father God's spokespersons, and throw kill the emmisaries/apostles who want to come show the path/way for you. Already many times I have wanted to gather protect you to block/defend/shield you from evil, like a female chicken who wants to envelop her children in her wings. But you don't want it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èla = sayap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">èla = sayap</Message></Annotation><v n="35" />Limuri ne, Lamatua pusi-pahae heka èmu manèngi-mangaj'i miu. Bèli-camèd'a nèngu j'aj'i èmu pa'ela. Èèna na, miu mèdhi heka Ja'a, toke miu dhaa, na,<bt>Now, the Lord no longer cares about your worship houses. So tomorrow or the next day they will be empty. Later you will not see Me again, until you acknowledge that. [EXEG: Take Gk. house = temple (TN, and mentioned as possibility in TH), since carries imagery in RL of loss of blessing, not carried by house (by itself), or house = city in RL.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hua = kosong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">hua = kosong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua hia mèngi-nale mi dhèu dhu mai nèti kolongara Ama Lamatua,<bt>‘Father God gives blessing to the person who comes bearing the Lord's name,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti here is &lt;bearing, bringing&gt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">nèti here is &lt;bearing, bringing&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu hia Na mai!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>because Father God is the one who caused Him to come!”’</bt><note reference="13:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:26</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu, lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i<bt>The Lord Yesus heals people on the worship day</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i, ca dhèu ama nèti partei agama Parisi nèru Yesus ho ra'a-sisi ètu èmu na. Ropa Yesus madhèdi na'a, abhu dhèu dhu ma'u, neo rèdhi Ne tao ngaa lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i.<bt>One time, on the worship day, a leader/father of the Parisi religion party invited Yesus to come eat at his house. While Yesus was sitting eating, [contrary to expectation] there were people who spied on him to see what He would do on the worship day.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ma'u = intip"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ma'u = intip</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, ca dhèu dhu pèd'a boho madhèdi ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>At that time, there was a person sick with “boho disease” who was also sitting there. [NLT, CEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boho = bere-bere, swollen joints,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">boho = bere-bere, swollen joints,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hydroopikos: accumulation of body fluids. Like"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">hydroopikos: accumulation of body fluids. Like diabetes and other things.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Hèia Yesus karèi dhèu d'èlu-mèu atora Yahudi dènge dhèu Parisi dhu madhèdi ra'a ètu sèra kahèi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu atora nèti baki Musa, bisa pa'èle dhèu pèd'a lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked the Yahudi lawyers (experts on Yahudi regulations) and Parisi people who were sitting eating there, saying, “According to grandfather Musa's regulation(s), is it permissible to heal people on the worship day, or not?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="He knew that they knew."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">He knew that they knew.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa dhèu èci sa bhoka boe hèb'a. Hèia Yesus gai dhèu pèd'a ne, ka na èle dènge nèti papèd'a na. Ka Yesus pua dhèu ne, sèna ka lèpa ka.<bt>But not a single person opened his mouth. Then Yesus touched that sick person, and he was healed immediately from his disease. Then Yesus told him to go home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="goi = often uses elbow; gai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">goi = often uses elbow; gai = touch with hand</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Èle ka Yesus karèi hari si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ana èci manahu asa d'ara èi lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a, miu lami ère eele ana ne'e, do aad'o? Ladhe sapi manahu asa d'ara èi la'e, miu soro tèke, do, lami kaso ne asa li'u? Tatu miu kaso ne asa li'u. De èèna, sasoa na, miu sab'a le, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 Yesus asked them again, saying, “If a child falls into a well/water, on the worship day, do you-pl go pull the child out, or not? If its a cow that falls into the well/water, do you leave it, or pull it out? Surely you pull it out. So (consequently) really, that means you-pl have done work, right?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaso = tarik (dari dalam) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaso = tarik (dari dalam) ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa tadèngi lii padhai Yesus ne, èci sa bisa boe dhaa.<bt>Hearing what Yesus said, there was not a single person who could respond to Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku padedha iisi<bt>Don't elevate yourselves</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Lod'o èèna, Yesus taru kira mi dhèu mai ra'a-sisi ètu d'ara èmu ne. Dhèu ae ka dhu d'èi era re madha, ho lasi madhèdi. Ropa nèdhi sèmi èèna, Yesus peka,<bt>At that time, Yesus was watching people who came to eat the feast at that house. There were many people who liked/wanted places in front, to go sit there. Seeing like.that, Yesus spoke saying,</bt><v n="8" />&lt;&lt;Sanèd'e, ee! Ladhe dhèu nèru miu asa pesta kab'i, mage lami madhèdi ka asa era dhèu aae-dhèu kapai. Mage dhoka lamatua pesta ne nèru tamu dhu kapai risi.<bt>“Remember, ee (=warning)! If someone invites you-pl to a wedding feast, don't go sit in the places for the big/important people (doublet). Lest the feast master has invited more important guests.</bt><v n="9" />Ladhe sèmi èèna, lamatua pesta mai gai èu, peka na, &lt;Mage mu nasa kahèi, ama! Ama pidha sa kabodho, ee. Te ja'a tèke kadera ne hia dhèu kapai nèi.&gt; Hèia èu kèd'i dènge makae, tèke eele kadera ne, ka lamu madhèdi asa kabodho.<bt>If it's like that, the feast master will come touch you-sg, saying, “Don't get angry (polite = I'm sorry)! Father (=you) move to the back, ee. Cuz (elaboration) I have prepared these chairs for these big/important people here.’ Then you stand up embarrassed, leave that chair, and go sit in the back.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eskhaton: most humble"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eskhaton: most humble</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />De ladhe èu abhu nèru, lamu madhèdi ètu kadera re kabodho tèka. Ropa lamatua pesta ladhe nèdhi èu, na mai peka, &lt;Ama! Mai madhèdi asa madha ne.&gt; Dènge j'ara ne, miu abhu pakab'ua ètu madha tamu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>So (consequently), if/when you get an invitation, just go sit in the chairs in the very back. When the feast master sees you, and he comes, saying, ‘Father! Come sit in the front here.’ In that way you will receive respect in front of all the guests.</bt><note reference="14:8-10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Hini 25:6-7</note><v n="11" />Te dhèu dhu padedha iisi ra, èèna na Lamatua pahaha si. Te ngaa dhèu dhu tao iisi ra sèmi dhèu haha, èèna na Lamatua ded'e padedha si.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who elevates himself, the Lord will lower/humble him. But a person (unmarked for number) who makes himself like a small/unimportant person, the Lord will raise/elevate them up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eskhaton: least important"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eskhaton: least important</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 23:12, Lukas 18:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus peka dènge lamatua èmu ne, &lt;&lt;Lod'o leo, ladhe ama neo tao tatao, mage nèru dhoka a'ari ama dènge dhèu kaja sèra mesa ra! Te tatu rèngu bisa nèru hari ama.<bt>After that, Yesus spoke with that house master, saying, “Another time, if/when father makes a feast, don't just invite father's family and rich friends! Cuz (elaboration) they certainly can reciprocate the invitation to father (=you)</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa ladhe ama tao tatao, nèru dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, dhèu haga roe cabèka, dhèu karuku, dènge dhèu bèdhu sèra.<bt>But if you make a feast, invite the poor people, the people with a weak leg (=short or limp), the lame people (who cannot walk), and the blind people.</bt><v n="14" />Tatu rèngu b'ala rare boe ama. Te ngaa ladhe ama nèru si, Ama Lamatua ka dhu b'ala ama. Ladhe d'ai lod'o Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu-dhèu parcaya dhu madhe le, Na bhèlu boe babe'a ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Surely they cannot reciprocate father. But if/when father invites them, Father God will be the one who reciprocates/rewards. If/when Father God makes the believers who have died live again, He will not forget father's goodness.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame nèti pesta kapai<bt>Comparison story about a big feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 22:1-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa tadèngi lii padhai lii Yesus ne, ca dhèu dhu madhèdi ca mei dènge Yesus, padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhu karej'e risi ka, rèngu dhu madhutu ra'a pa'èci ètu d'ara èmu Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing what Yesus said, a person who was sitting at the same table with Yesus said, “The one who is the most fortunate, are those who participate eating festively in Father God's house, oo!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a lolo sèmi ne'e: abhu ca dhèu dhu tao tatao kapai. Hèia na nèru dhèu ae titu kèna.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “I'll tell a story like.this: there was a person who made a big feast. Then he invited many people.</bt><v n="17" />Ropa d'ai tadha dhèu ra'a-rinu, ka na pua ènu na, la'e paroa dhèu dhu ra nèru sèra, peka na, &lt;Mai lati ka, te neo mulai pesta kèna.&gt;<bt>When the feast was ready, he ordered his servant/slave to go call people who were invited, saying, ‘Come on now, cuz (elaboration) the feast/party is about to begin.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tadha = waktu yg ditentukan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">tadha = waktu yg ditentukan</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te ngaa dhèu se'e padhai lii rupa-rupa, sèna ka lasi boe asa d'ara pesta. Ca dhèu peka sèmi ne'e, &lt;Ja'a heka hèli kore oka cue, de neo laku ladhe sèku. De mage nasa, te ja'a lake kore boe.&gt;<bt>But they all made all.sorts.of excuses why they could not come to the feast. One person said like this, ‘I have just bought a garden, so I must go have a look at it. Don't get angry, cuz I am unable to come.’</bt><v n="19" />Dhèu leo hari peka na, &lt;Ja'a heka hèli kore sapi maroo rai lèmi pasa. De ja'a neo laku cob'a si. Baku nasa, te ja'a lake kore boe!&gt;<bt>There was another person who said, ‘I have just bought five pairs of plow cows. I need to go try them out. Don't get angry, cuz I am unable to come.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maroo = bajak ; ma'are ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">maroo = bajak ; ma'are = sawah</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Dhèu leo hari peka na, &lt;Ja'a heka kab'i kèna, de bisa boe dhiu.&gt;<bt>Yet another person said, ‘I just married, so I am unable to stop in.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: maroo artinya: bajak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: maroo artinya: bajak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka ènu ne, lèpa peka dènge lamatua na. Ropa tadèngi nare, ka nasa titu kèna. Hèia na paredha ènu na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, èu lamu lai-lai! Lamu asa j'ara-j'ara, dènge asa sasanga j'ara ètu kota ne'e, sèna ka nèru dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa, dhèu kasia, dhu haga roe cabèka, dhu bèdhu, dènge dhèu-dhèu karuku sèra.&gt;<bt>Then that servant/slave went home to report to his master. Hearing like.that, he got very angry. Then he ordered that servant, saying, ‘If that's the case, you go out quickly! Go to all the main.streets and branches of streets in this city, to invite the poor people, the misfortunate, the weak legged/limping people, the blind people and the lame people.’ [EXEG: vs. 21 is in city, vs. 23 in country outside city. NLT, Marshall.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèpa (2) = makanan dari tepung"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lèpa (2) = makanan dari tepung beras atau jagung yg dicampur dgn gula dan santan</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Ropa tadèngi nare, la'e dènge ka nèru dhèu-dhèu sèra. Ka na lèpa hari, hèia na peka dènge lamatua na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ama! Dhèu se, ka se'e le. Te ngaa era madhèdi ae era.&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, that servant went to invite those people. Then he came.home and reported to his master, saying, ‘Father! They have all come, but there are still many places to sit.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia lamatua na peka, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, lamu hari asa rae-rae ètu li'u kota, toke d'ai d'ara oka sèi. Lamu pamako sad'i cee èèna ka, mèti si mai ho ra madhèdi papènu d'ara pesta ne.<bt>Then that master said, ‘If that's the case, you go again to the villages outside the city, to the point of (going) to the gardens/fields. Persuade anyone and bring them, so.long.as this feast place is made full. [EXEG: see note at vs. 21. “roads” here is taken as leading to surrounding villages; Gk here is lit. ‘fences’ which in RL worldview is taken as going to the fields, with support from LN sense #1.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ro'a-ro'a kakilu = lorong sempit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ro'a-ro'a kakilu = lorong sempit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lamu hari asa j'ara-j'ara, toke dai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lamu hari asa j'ara-j'ara, toke dai ro'a-ro'a kakilu sèi. Lamu pamako sad'i dhèu cee èèna ka, mèti si mai ho ra madhèdi papènu dara pesta ne.</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Nanene, ee! Dhèu dhu pahae boe dènge lii nèru ja'a ne, rèngu se re'a boe babe'a tatao ne ciki sa hèi!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen! Those people who don't care about that invitation of mine, they will not get to taste even a tiny bit of this feast's goodness.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pangee paie-iie ku, heka madhutu Lamatua Yesus kèna<bt>Think carefully first, only.then follow the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 10:37-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka Yesus si lasi taruu asa Yerusalem. Dhèu ae madhutu Ne. Hèia Na kabib'a ladhe sa rèngu, ka Na peka, na,<bt>After that, Yesus (collective) travelled on to Yerusalem. Many people were following Him. Then He turned around looked at them, and He said,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patae = nantang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">patae = nantang</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />&lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a neo madhutu Ja'a, nèngu hud'i sue ku Ja'a <span class="Italic">risi</span> nèti ngaa-ngaa aa'i-aa'i ra; risi nèti ina-ama na, risi nèti dhèu èmu-kamali na, risi nèti ana niki na, risi nèti a'ari na, aa risi-risi hari nèti ngi'u nèngu unu na. Ladhe aad'o, dhèu ne nia boe j'aj'i ana madhutu Ja'a.<bt>“The person who truly wants to follow/obey Me, s/he must love Me <span class="Italic">more</span> than everything: more than his mother-father, more than his spouse, his children, more than his relatives, and even more than his own self. If not, that person is not worthy of/equal to being My follower.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana niki na = his own"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ana niki na = his own children (1UNS not know)</Message></Annotation><note reference="14:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:37</note><v n="27" />Te dhèu dhu d'èi boe pasae j'aj'èra lula nèngu madhutu Ja'a, nèngu nia boe j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a. Dhèu dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a, masi ka dhèu neo pamadhe ne, te ngaa nèngu pasae j'aj'èra na taruu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who does not want to carry/endure suffering because he follows Me, he is not worthy of being My person. A person who wants to be My person, even though people want to kill him, nevertheless s/he endure continually his/her suffering,</bt><note reference="14:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:38, 16:24, Markus 8:34, Lukas 9:23</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />De ladhe neo madhutu Ja'a, ngee pabe'a-be'a ku. Nuka sèmi dhèu neo tao èmu dhu dènge tad'a-tad'a. Nèngu hud'i ige uuru ku, ogo d'ai lutu sela. Mage dhoka doi d'ai boe.<bt>So (consequently) if [you] want to follow Me, think carefully first. It's like a person building a layered/multi-storied house. He must count first the cost to the finest details. Lest the money be insufficient (lit. not reach/arrive).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tad'a = lapisan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">tad'a = lapisan</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Ladhe ige boe paie-iie, ele boe d'ai fanderen di, doi dhu aad'o heka le. Ladhe sèmi èèna, dhèu mari madhe aa pamakae ne hèi,<bt>If [he] doesn't count it carefully, probably/perhaps he will only have made the house's foundation, and the money runs out. If it's like that, people will laugh and ridicule/shame him,</bt><v n="30" />peka na, &lt;Miu ladhe ku dhèu ne'e laa! Heka na sab'e fanderen kèna, te ngaa doi na saku aa'i le!&gt;<bt>saying, ‘You-pl have a look at this person! He just made the foundation, but the money is already all.gone.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Conto dhu leo, nuka sèmi dhèu lasi pamusu. Dhèu aae dhu neo la'e pamusu hud'i madhèdi ku, sèna ka pare'a uuru ku dènge angalai na. Ladhe sordad'u rèngu dhoka canguru riho dhèu di, bisa segi musu dua nguru riho dhèu, do aad'o?<bt>Another example is in regards to people going to war. The king that wants to go to war must sit and first talk things through with his cronies/friends. If he only has an army of 10.000 people, is it possible to win against an enemy of 20.000, or not?</bt><v n="32" />Ladhe ige rare, te ngaa rèngu bisa boe segi, be'a risi lod'o musu dhu kaj'èu era, ra pua dhèu lasi peka sèna ka uri padame.<bt>If/when he has finished counting, but they cannot win, it's better when the enemy is still far, they send a person to go arrange peace.</bt><v n="33" />Sama sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge dhèu dhu neo madhutu Ja'a. Nèngu hud'i kali bagi ku la'e-mai, dhu peka na, nèngu dhu pa'èra le tèke eele aa'i ngaa-ngaa, do aad'o? Te ladhe aad'o, na, dhèu ne'e nia boe j'aj'i ana madhutu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Like that also the person who wants to follow Me. He must ponder back and forth whether he is ready to leave everything or not? Cuz (elaboration) if not, that person is not worthy/appropriate to be/become My *disciple.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kali bagi = cermat, pangee"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kali bagi = cermat, pangee</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu pantas boe madhutu Yesus, nuka sèmi masi dhu guna heka<bt>The person who is not worthy to follow Yesus, is like salt that has no more use</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 5:13; Markus 9:50)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34-35" />Yesus tuhu lii padhai pake lii pakasame dhu leo hari, na, &lt;&lt;Masi ne, be'a. Èdhi pake ne ho pabe'a nganga'a. Te ngaa ladhe na sèro heka, j'aj'i ngaa hari? Bisa heka pake ne, ho pabe'a nganga'a. Neo tao mi pupuk, bisa boe kahèi. Dhodhoka core eele iia d'ara di. Dhèu cee dhu dènge ro'a dhilu, nanene paie-iie!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus continued His speaking with another example again, saying, “Salt, is good. We-inc use it to make food delicious. But if it is not longer salty, what else is it [good for]? Can't use it anymore to make food delicious. We can't use it even to make fertilizer. We just throw it away. Who ever has earholes, listen carefully!” [EXEG: From Gk &amp; NRSV ftn; NOTE to daughter translations: if "sonde asin lai" is problematic, try "su tawar".]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kahib'i-kalèbho dhu ele<bt>The sheep which disappeared</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 18:12-14)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu roro bea dènge dhèu dhu laku-laku boe mai ae-ae asa Yesus, sèna ka nanene lii padhai Na. Te ngaa dhèu Yahudi peka, na, rèngu sèra dhèu karehe.<bt>At that time, the tax collectors and the people considered ‘down.and.outers’ kept coming to Yesus to listen to Him/what He had to say. But the Yahudi people considered these [to be] bad people. [NOTE: last sentence clarifies cultural knowledge, that both categories are “bad”, and sets the background info for the social dynamics of rest of the chapter.]</bt><v n="2" />Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu Parisi dènge mese agama Yahudi sèra ka'uu-kamuki, peka na, &lt;&lt;Huuh! Dhèu ne pa'angalai dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu laku boe se. Ngaa hari Na madhèdi na'a-ninu dènge si!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they saw like.that, the Parisi people and the Yahudi religion teachers complained (doublet), saying, “Huuh! This person is mutual.friends with the down.and.outers. He even sits and eats with them!”</bt><note reference="15:1-2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 5:29-30</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka Yesus lolo dènge ra lii pakasame èci, aku Nèngu na,<bt>When (He) heard like.that, Yesus told them a comparison.story, saying,</bt><v n="4" />&lt;&lt;Ladhe nèti miu abhu ca dhèu dhu unu kahib'i-kalèbho cangasu ngi'u. Ka ci'u ele. Na tao tasamia? Tatu na tèke eele dhu ceo nguru ceo se ètu era dhu be'a, aa la'e tenge dhu ele deo na, toke rage ne.<bt>“Suppose that one of you had one hundred tails (animal counter) of sheep. Then one tail disappeared. Now what should s/he do? Surely he would leave those sheep who were ninety nine tails in a safe/good place, then he would go hunt for that sheep that disappeared until he found it.</bt><v n="5" />Ropa nèdhi hari kahib'i-kalèbho ne, ka na pasae nèti, dènge karej'e-karae.<bt>When he sees/encounters that sheep, then he happily shoulder.carrys it and brings it home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kacuu = carrying piggy-back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kacuu = carrying piggy-back</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />D'ai èmu, ka na paroa angalai na aa'i-aa'i, hèia na peka dènge si, &lt;Mai, sèna ka karej'e dènge ja'a! Te kahib'i-kalèbho ja'a dhu ele èèna, kèdhi hari le.&gt;<bt>Arriving home, then he calls all his friends, [NOTE: friends is RL category conflating friends and neighbours] then tells saying, ‘Hey! You-pl come and be happy/pleased along with me! Cuz (elaboration) I have found that sheep of mine that had disappeared.’</bt><v n="7" />Ètu sorga, sèmi èèna kahèi. Ladhe ca dhèu dhu tao sala, hèia ele-ho'a, ka na lèpa hari asa Lamatua, ana kabarai sorga aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e-karae. Rèngu karej'e risi lula ca dhèu dhu lèpa hari asa Lamatua, nèti ceo nguru ceo dhèu dhu mamuri mola, dhu sala boe j'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>In heaven it is also like.that. If/when one sinner repents, then returns to the Lord, all the citizens/inhabitants of heaven are happy (doublet). They are happier because of this one person who has returned to the Lord, than [because of] ninety nine people who live straight and haven't lost their way (physically, morally, spiritually).” [NOTE: last clause reinforces the point (=beautiful style), brings lexical cohesion to the whole pericope, and lexical ties with following pericopes.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Doi iia dhu ele<bt>The silver money which disappeared</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Yesus lolo hari lii pakasame dhu leo èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ca dhèu ina, dhu doi iia na canguru bua.<bt>Then Yesus told yet another comparision.story, saying, “There was a mother who had ten silver coins.</bt><note reference="15:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na 10 <span class="Italic">drakma.</span> Drakma cue, èci èèna ka dènge gaji tuka d'ara ca lod'o.<bt>The Yunani language writing says 10 <span class="Italic">drakma.</span> One drakma, is one craftsman/workers wage for one day.</bt></note>Ne'a na, dhu ele ca doi. Ka na tao tasamia? Tatu la'e suru labhu ho d'elo palème era, aa saku èmu ne d'ai ro'a kakilu, sèna ka tenge doi cue dhu ele ne.<bt>It.turns.out that one coin disappeared. Now what should she do? Surely she will go light a lamp and inspect all over, and sweep that house even to the nooks and crannies, to carefully look for that one money/coin that disappeared.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kakilu = huk-huk nat-nat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kakilu = huk-huk nat-nat</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ropa nèdhi hari doi ne, na paroa dènge dhèu dhu ètu baboa èmu na sèra, hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;Miu mai, ho karej'e sama-sama dènge ja'a. Te doi ja'a cue dhu ele deo na, kèdhi hari le!&gt;<bt>When she sees/finds that money, she calls people from the next house, and tells them, saying, ‘You-pl come to be lively happy with me! Cuz (elaboration) I have found again that money of mine that disappeared!’ [EXEG: Gk. “friends and neighbours” is grammatically feminine, but in most lgs in this region forcing it would make it a highly marked construction that is not natural. Would skew the focus.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ètu baboa èmu na = neighbour"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ètu baboa èmu na = neighbour</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ètu sorga sèmi èèna kahèi. Ladhe abhu ca dhèu dhu tao sala, ka na ele-ho'a, ho lèpa hari asa Ama Lamatua, tatu ana pajuu ètu sorga aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e-karae.&gt;&gt;<bt>In heaven it's also like.that. If there is one sinner who repents, then returns to the Lord, certainly all the angels in heaven are very happy/celebrate.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana dhu ele<bt>The child which disappeared</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na dènge lii pakasame kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama ca dhèu dènge ana mone na dhèu dua.<bt>Then Yesus continued His story with yet another comparison.story, saying, “There was a father and his two male children.</bt><v n="12" />Ca lod'o, ana limuri peka dènge ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ama! Hia ka pala ja'a nèti pusaka sèra, deo ne'e ne kahèi!&gt; Hèia ama na bagi hia dua ra pusaka na, sèna ka èci-èci dènge pala ra.<bt>One time, that youngest child told his father, saying, ‘Father! Divide out my inheritance possessions now! [+insistence like a 2-year-old]’ So his father divided his inheritance to the two of them, so each of them got his share/portion.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="In Near Eastern culture, this is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">In Near Eastern culture, this is like saying 'Father, I wish you were dead!'</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Nèbhu boe ka ana limuri ne pahie unu na. Hèia na lalau mèdha na, ka la'e asa rae kaj'èu. Ètu era nèi, ana limuri ne pasaku aa'i-aa'i doi-dhari na, ho pakarej'e iisi.<bt>Not long then (=soon), that youngest child sold his portion. Then he wrapped his clothes, and he left to go to a country/village that was far. There (remote), he scattered/wasted all his money to please himself. [NOTE to daughter translations: /idop foya-foya/ was difficult for a couple teams. Try “live according to his own desires” or “to please himself”, but check as there should be a conventionalised way of talking about this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaku = habiskan ; cebe-lebhe ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasaku = habiskan ; cebe-lebhe = hambur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="synagagoon panta: the father's assets were"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">synagagoon panta: the father's assets were varied, including land, which the boy couldn't take with him. He converted everything into cash. asootoos: dissolutely, profligately = he just couldn't hold on to his money, he spent it like it was never going to run out. He was stupid about money and ran up a lot of debts (like some people who go to Las Vegas). It doesn't say he was immoral in other ways: that was the assumption his older brother made.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ropa doi na èle aa'i mèu-mèu, rai ne dhu lèke manganga bia, ka mamuri ana ne j'èra d'ai seli.<bt>When his money was all.gone, then that country was afflicted with a severe hunger season, and/so he lived in great difficulty/strife.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The family money had gone to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">The family money had gone to Gentiles. This was a deep insult to family and community.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ka la'e tenge sasab'a. Hèia ca dhèu nèti kabarai èèna hia na panga'a hahi.<bt>Then he went to hunt for work. So one person from that country accepted him in.order.to order him to work feeding pigs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ekolleethee: attached himself to. It wasn't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">ekolleethee: attached himself to. It wasn't a real job. He had a chance to scrounge food, but no pay.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Lula ana ne manganga d'ai seli, ka neo na'a nganga'a hahi se. Te abhu boe ca dhèu sa hia ne na'a.<bt>Because that child was so hungry, he wanted to/was about to eat those pigs' food. Cuz (elaboration) there was no one to give him food [+obviously].</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Nèbhu-nèbhu, ka na pangee la'e-mai, aku nèngu na, &lt;Anga ee! Ja'a ètu ne'e, oe madhe manganga kèna. Te ngaa ètu d'ara èmu ama ku, dhèu sab'a ra'a toke bècu.<bt>Eventually he began to think over.and.over, saying, ‘Anga ee! [+regret] I here am just about ready to die from hunger. But In my father's house, the workers get to eat until they are satisfied. [EXEG: “came to himself / his senses” implied by the process of thinking it through plus what he says to himself. Forcing it would be overtranslation.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = 1) healthy, 2) aware"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">mase'a = 1) healthy, 2) aware (sadar) ; anga ee = (penyesalan)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ètu dara èmu ama ku, dhèu-dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Ètu dara èmu ama ku, dhèu-dhèu sab'a ra'a toke bècu. Te ngaa ja'a ètu ne'e, oe madhe manganga kèna.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eis heauton elthoon: not repentance, but"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eis heauton elthoon: not repentance, but "he got smart."</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />De be'a risi ja'a lèpa hari asa ama ku, ho peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a tao le sala dhu kapai titu kèna, mi Lamatua dènge ama.<bt>So (consequently) it's better I just go.home to my father, to tell him, “Father! I have done great/big wrongs toward the Lord and father.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="What the boy wants to tell"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">What the boy wants to tell his father is almost word for word what Pharaoh says to Moses to get him off his back in Exodus 10:16: "I wen do bad ting to yoa God da Boss# Above, an to you guys." This is not repentance, it's a deal to keep from being thrown out by the community for what he had done to his family.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ja'a nia boe j'aj'i ana ama ku. Hud'i laa ama sèmi more ja'a ne j'aj'i mi kuli ètu d'ara èmu ama, ngaa-ngaa tao boe!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>I am not worthy of being father's (=your) child anymore. Allow father to accept me to just be a kuli (lowest level of worker) in father's house, there's nothing wrong with that (idiomatic).’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kuli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kuli</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="If the son has the status"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">If the son has the status of a hired laborer, that would neutralize some of the shame for the family.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ropa pangee nare sèmi èèna, hèia na kèd'i dènge ka, lèpa la'e asa èmu ama na. Nèti kaj'èu era, ama na ladhe nèdhi le nèngu, ka ama na rasa kasia. Ka na puru nèti èmu, rai la'e soru nare ana dhu lèpa hari ne. Hèia na liku nare, ka uu ne.<bt>After thinking like that, then he got up and went.home to his father's house. From still far away his father already saw him, and felt pity/mercy on him. He went down from the house to run to greet that child of his who had come.home. Then the old.man hugged and kissed him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe bhilu = sangat sedih ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">roe bhilu = sangat sedih ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna ka, ana ne peka dènge ama na, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ama! Ja'a ne tao le sala dhu kapai mi dedha Lamatua dènge ama ku. Ja'a nia heka j'aj'i hari ana ama.&gt;<bt>Then that child spoke with his father saying, ‘Father! I have done great/big wrongs towards the Lord and father (=you). I am not worthy of being father's child anymore.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa ama na paredha dènge ka dhèu-dhèu sab'a na, peka na, &lt;Karohe! Lami mere kodho madhera dhu be'a risi, ho papake ne. Mere kadheli, ho pasaluu mi kacui-aai na. Aa papake salapa mi haga na.<bt>But his father immediately ordered his workers, saying, ‘Hurry! Go get the very best robe (long shirt) for him to wear. Put rings on his fingers, and shoes on his feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe = malai = cepat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">karohe = malai = cepat</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Lami ère mere sapi kab'oi èèna ho pare, te èdhi neo ta'a-tinu rame-rame.<bt>Go drag/pull that carefully.handfed/fatten cow in.order to cut/slaughter it, cuz (elaboration) we-inc are going to make a lively feast.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaboi = piara, paron"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaboi = piara, paron</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Lula ana ja'a ne, nuka sèmi dhu madhe le, te ngaa na mamuri hari. Nèngu dhu ele le, te ngaa ja'a abhu hari ne.&gt; Na padhai lii èle sèmi èèna, ka mulai ra'a-rinu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Because this child of mine was as if he had died, but now he lives again. He had disappeared, but now I have got him again.’ After speaking like.that, they begain to feast festively. [NOTE: made 1st sentence into simile, cohesion with vs 32.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: ai atau kacui-aai? (Dalam hal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: ai atau kacui-aai? (Dalam hal memakai cincin)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Lod'o èèna, ana uuru dhu aad'o ètu èmu, te na sab'a ètu d'ara oka. Ropa na lèpa, nèti kaj'èu era, na tadèngi le dhèu karihu musiik dènge roge-ledho.<bt>At that time, the eldest child was not at home, cuz (elaboration) he was working in the garden. When he returned.home, from far.off he heard people playing music and dancing (doublet).</bt><v n="26" />Ka na paroa nare dhèu sab'a ca dhèu, hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee! Tao rarame ngaa ètu ne'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he called a worker and asked him, saying, ‘Ee! [+surprise, confused] What are they celebrating here?’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hena toon paidoon: more probably &quot;one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">hena toon paidoon: more probably "one of the village kids," not "worker." The workers were busy putting on the party. Bailey points out this this village kid acts like the chorus in a Greek drama.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia dhèu sab'a ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ari mu lèpa hari le. De ama mu pua pare sapi, sèna ka tao pesta kapai, te ana na lèpa hari dènge sod'a.&gt;<bt>That worker answered saying, ‘your younger.sibling has come home. So (consequently), your father ordered to slice/slaughter the cow to make a big feast, cuz (elaboration) he child has come.home safely.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apelaben: accepted him. The father didn't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">apelaben: accepted him. The father didn't give the boy a chance to propose his deal. He forgave the boy publicly and took the loss of half his assets. This is a picture of Jesus forgiving us, and paying a high price to do it. hygiainonta: shalom, everything okay<span class="Italic">(27)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa tadèngi nare, hèia ana uuru ne pasaree. Na no'o boe maso asa d'ara èmu. Ka ama na la'e rarange ne.<bt>Hearing that, that eldest child got angry/upset. He no longer wanted to enter the house. Then his father went to coax him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaree = jengkel sifat kelainan, mirip"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasaree = jengkel sifat kelainan, mirip ke iri hati, cemburu, jengkel ; rarange = pamako</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa na ka'ugu, peka na, &lt;Ama! Pangee ku laa! Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, ja'a sab'a toke èi kabhèsu hae, nuka sèmi kuli sa, hia mi ama. Ja'a ne ke'a boe sisu dad'èi ama. Masi ka sèmi èèna, abhu mèka ama hia ana kahib'i ci'u, sèna ka ja'a pakarej'e dènge mone aanga-angalai ja'a.<bt>But he complained angrily saying, ‘Father! Think about it! All this time I have worked very hard like the lowest kuli for father (you). I do not know how (=have never) to oppose father's will/wishes. Even though that's the case, nevertheless father has not yet ever given one goat offspring so that I can make a happy feast with my friends.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'ugu = comel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ka'ugu = comel</Message></Annotation><v n="30" />Te ngaa ropa ana ama dhu bhera-lelu doi-dhari ama, ho la'e karihu dènge bhèni karehe, lèpa hari mai, ka ama pare sapi kab'oi na, tao pesta aae hia ne.&gt;<bt>But wouldn't you know it, when your sons squanders wastefully your wealth and went and played around with bad women, now he comes.home, and father slaughters the very best cow to make a big feast for him.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhera lelu = buang-buang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bhera lelu = buang-buang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa ama na b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ana pasue, ee! Nanene paie-iie. Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, èu ne bera-bera dènge ja'a. Aa'i-aa'i dhu unu ja'a, sèra sa unu èu kahèi.<bt>But his father replied, saying, ‘Beloved child, ee! Listen carefully! For all this time you have stayed together with me. Everything which I owns, they also belong to you.</bt><v n="32" />Te ngaa limuri ne, èdhi hud'i karej'e dènge karae ku, lula ari mu ca dhèu ne. Uru èèna, nuka sèmi dhu madhe le, te ngaa limuri ne mamuri hari. Nèngu dhu ele le, te ngaa abhu hari.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But now we-inc must happily feast, because of this one younger.sibling of yours. Previously, it was as if he had died, but now he lives again. He had disappeared, but now has been found again.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="edei: fitting, proper, we just have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">edei: fitting, proper, we just have to do this -- inner compulsion, impossible not to. hoti ho adelphos sou houtos: this brother of yours -- a direct comeback to ho hyios sou houtos in 30 "this son of yours"<span class="Italic">(32) (32) </span>If the father hadn't taken the initiative and forgiven the boy publicly, the townspeople would have insisted on a ceremony (still used) that would result in everybody treating him as dead, no longer part of the community, because he had taken money for town lands and thrown it away to the Gentiles.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kapala urusan dhu ne'a pa'uri<bt>The manager who is astute/skilled at making things happen</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Yesus hia lii upama èci mi ana madhutu Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu kaja ca dhèu dhu ded'e dhèu sab'a na èci j'aj'i kapala urusan. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, na tadèngi dhèu palolo, peka na, kapala urusan ne mulai kapod'e-kabèli ka parugi nèngu.<bt>Then Yesus told another comparision story to His underlings, saying, “There was a rich person who elevated a worker to become his manager. But eventually he heard rumours that that manager had begun to be crooked (doublet) making him suffer.financial.loss.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia dhèu kaja ne paroa kapala urusan na, ka peka dènge ne, &lt;Èu ne, tasamia? Ja'a tadèngi, na, èu kapod'e mèdha-panyau ja'a. De lamu suri ku ngaa dhu èu ad'u-ue ètu d'ara sasab'a èu, ho ja'a parisa ku. Ladhe parisa kore, ja'a kalua eele èu.&gt;<bt>So (consequently), the rich man summoned that manager, to tell him saying, ‘How is it with you-sg? I have heard that you are being crooked with my possessions (doublet). So (consequently) you go make a work report so that I can examine it. When I have finished examining it, I am getting rid of you.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa na tadèngi nare, hèia kapala urusan ne mulai pajiko, na, &lt;Ja'a ne j'èra kèna! Ja'a neo sab'a ngaa hari? Pare rai, ja'a èra boe. J'aj'i dhèu hèb'a mènyi, ja'a makae.<bt>Hearing like.that, that manager thought/mulled.over.it, saying, ‘I'm really in trouble here! What am I going to do now? To hoe soil, I'm not strong. Even to become a beggar (idiom), I'm ashamed.</bt><v n="4" />Ladhe ja'a sab'a heka ètu ne'e, ja'a hud'i tenge j'ara ku, sèna ka dhèu leo bisa hari sèmi rare ja'a ho sab'a.&gt;<bt>If I cannot work here anymore, I must find a way so that other people still want to accept me to work (for them).’ [EXEG: Gk has word-play /oikonomias/ ‘stewardship, kapala urusan, house/business management, manage household affairs’ and /oikos/ ‘house’; so “receive me into their house” could be taken as “accept me to work for them”. See LN on the first word. But broader like the Kupang is better.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Nèti èèna ka, na paroa nare aa'i dhèu dhu pakèlu lamatua na. Na karèi dhèu uru, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ee! Kèlu èu ca ngaa ètu lamatua ja'a?&gt;<bt>Because of that, he began to call all the people who were endebted to his master He asked the first person, saying, ‘Ee! How much do you owe my master?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ja'a dhu pakèlu èi lèngi saitun èpa riho liter.&gt;<bt>That person answered, saying, “I have a debt of 4000 liters of olive oil.’</bt><note reference="16:6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na &lt;cangasu <span class="Italic">batos</span>&gt;. Batos èci sama sèmi 35-40 liter.<bt>The Yunani language writing says &lt;100 batos&gt;. One batos is 35-40 liters.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia kapala urusan ne peka, na, &lt;Tare'a. Sasuri pakèlu èu ka ne'e. Ciu eele ka, madhèdi ho suri gati sasuri kèlu dhu hiu, peka na, kèlu èu dua riho liter di.&gt;<bt>So that manager said, ‘True. This is your debt letter. Now tear it up throw it away, then sit down and quickly write a new replacement debt letter, saying you only owe 2000 liters.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka karèi dhèu pakèlu ka dua, peka na, &lt;Aa èu hari, kèlu ca ngaa?&gt;<bt>Then he went and asked the second person, saying, ‘So how much do you owe?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu ne dhaa, na, &lt;Ja'a pakèlu are, cariho karo.&gt;<bt>He answered, saying, ‘I owe 1000 sacks of padi.’</bt><note reference="16:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na &lt;cangasu <span class="Italic">koros</span>&gt;. Koros èci nuka, 390 liter.<bt>The Yunani language writing says &lt;100 koros&gt;. One koros, is 390 liters.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia kapala urusan ne peka, na, &lt;Ciu eele sasuri dhui èèna, ho suri dhu hiu hari, peka na, kèlu èu, aru ngasu karo di.&gt;<bt>That manager told him saying, ‘Rip up and throw away that debt letter of yours, then write a new one, saying just 800 sacks.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Na tao sèmi ne'e ka, toke lamatua na ne'a tatao nèngu. Te ngaa lamatua ne hud'i mangaku, na, dhèu kapala urusan dhu bhelu ne mema mèu kapod'e-kabèli.<bt>He did like.that, until his master found out about it. But that master acknowledged that, this person was certainly astute/clever at arranging things.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De Ja'a lolo lii upama ne, sèna ka miu me'a, na, ladhe pasoro dènge dhèu parcaya, dhèu dhu parcaya boe d'èlu-mèu risi tenge j'ara ho pa'oto ngi'u ra ètu talora aae kabarai limuri ne.<bt>So [+shift to conclusion]! I tell this comparison.story so that you-pl understand, that, if compared with believers, people who don't believe certainly are more astute finding ways to benefit themselves in the midst of the current.day populace. [NOTE: reworked modelling on NLT, because 1) KM /orang dunya/ would translate literally into many vernaculars with their term for 'human', but here it should be 'people who don't believe'; and 2) /su pintar cari jalan ko bekin ontong dia pung diri sandiri./ misread by Belu team as "clever obtaining profit", rather than "clever finding ways to advantage themselves".] [CHECK: Dhao still has potential for ambiguous reading as in #2 in the note above.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'oto = untungkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pa'oto = untungkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="De, nèti lii upama dhu Ja'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">De, nèti lii upama dhu Ja'a lolo ne, sèna ka miu me'a na dhèu rai-haha dèlu-mèu tenge j'ara ho pa'oto ngi'u na. Dhèu parcaya dhu mamuri ètu saraa, mèu boe uri sèmi èèna ètu rai-haha ne.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adikia: unrighteousness, unjust"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">adikia: unrighteousness, unjust</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Miu ngee sèku. Masi ka dhèu rai-haha ne karihu kaj'alu re mèdha-panyau ra, te ngaa be'a risi miu pake mèdha-panyau miu sèra, ho soru-bara dhèu. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, miu abhu angalai ae. Masi ka mèdha se èle, te ngaa bèli-camèd'a Lamatua tao tèke era hia miu ètu sorga.<bt>So, have a think about it. Even though people of the world/humans play dirty using their possessions, nevertheless it's better you-pl use your-pl possessions to help people. In that way, you will obtain many friends. Even if those possessions get used.up/finished, nevertheless the Lord will prepare a place for you in heaven. [See NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mamoona adikias: money may be associated"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">mamoona adikias: money may be associated with or gained by unjust means (UBS). Used in the Targums and the Talmud.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ladhe dhèu mola ètu j'ara dhu ana iiki, tatu na mola kahèi ètu j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu mèu kapod'e ètu j'ara dhu ana iiki, tatu na kapod'e kahèi ètu j'ara dhu kapai.<bt>If a person is honest with small matters, surely he will also be honest with big/important matters. But if a person is cleverly crooked with small matters, surely he will also be crooked with big matters.</bt><v n="11" />Ladhe dhèu parcaya heka miu, ho uri mèdha-panyau ètu j'ara-j'ara dhu ana iiki ètu rai-haha ne, tasamia ka Lamatua parcaya miu ètu j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai?<bt>If people cannot trust you-pl to take care of things/belongings (doublet) and small matters in this world, how can the Lord trust you with big/important matters in heaven? [EXEG: Marshall points out that “mammon” here must mean ‘worldly wealth’ (a la NLT) rather than ‘wealth dishonestly acquired or used’ (a la NRSV and CEV). And that it is something entrusted, rather than owned.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pistoi: trustworthy, faithful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">pistoi: trustworthy, faithful</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ladhe miu bisa boe uri mèdha-panyau dhèu leo, na, dhèu cee ka dhu bani ho hia miu mèdha-panyau ra?<bt>If you-pl cannot take.care of other people's possessions, na, who will dare give their possessions to you?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dhèu sab'a èci bisa boe nanene dua lamatua. Te aad'o na, nèngu d'èi boe èci, aa sue èci. Nèngu d'ara kateme dènge ca dhèu, te ngaa pusi boe dènge èci. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge miu. Te dhèu bisa boe sue Ama Lamatua palere dènge sue doi-dhari.&gt;&gt;<bt>One low.rank.worker cannot hear/obey two masters. Cuz he will hate one, and love one. [CHECK use of negative in this sentence.] He will be faithful/wholehearted to one, but not care about the other. It's also like that with you-pl. Cuz (elaboration) people cannot love Father God together with loving money. [EXEG: why love? because ‘serve’ doesn't collocate with money; neither do several other candidates that were considered.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oiketeis: household servant, personal servant (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">oiketeis: household servant, personal servant (not doulos here)</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 6:24</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii nèti doi-dhari, nèti Lii Lolo Be'a, aa nèti pa'ia-pa'ela<bt>The Lord Yesus talks about money, about the Good News, and about marriage-divorce</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 11:12-13, 5:31-32; Markus 10:11-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu Parisi pèri-pèri dhu nanene lii padhai Yesus deo na. Ka ra sasei Ne, lula rèngu se dhèu manga'a doi-dhari.<bt>At that time, there were several Parisi people who were listening to what Yesus had to say. Then they ridiculed Him, because they were greedy for money.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasei = olok"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sasei = olok</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge si, &lt;&lt;Masi ka miu pamèu iisi ètu madha dhèu, te ngaa Ama Lamatua ne'a d'ara bhelu miu. Abhu j'ara ae dhu dhèu rai-haha ded'e padedha-dedha, te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka na, j'ara sèra karehe, aa dhu madenge dènge rèngu.<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, “Even though you-pl make yourselves out to be holy in front of people, nevertheless Father God knows that your insides are evil. There are many things with humans regard highly, but [contrary to expectation] Father God considers those things evil, and is appalled/disgusted by them. [NOTE to daughter translations: The Gk has a parallel proverb-type of structure in the last sentence, "for what is prized by human beings is an abomination in the sight of God." KM can't do that easily because of the problems with mesolectal speakers not knowing /noju/. If possible, mirror the Gk.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Toke mamai Yohanis tuka sarani, èdhi dhèu Yahudi muri madhutu atora nèti baki Musa aa nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua. Te ngaa limuri ne, Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Lamatua pale-lème le ètu mia-mia. Dhèu ae dhu tenge le j'ara, sèna ka ra mamuri madhutu dad'èi Lamatua.<bt>Until the time of Yohanis the habitual baptiser, we-inc Yahudi people lived according to grandfather Musa and the Lord's spokespersons' regulations. But now the Lord's Good News has spread everywhere. Many people are trying to find ways so that they can live following God's will2 (=the things of God).</bt><note reference="16:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 11:12-13</note><v n="17" />Masi ka dedha-liru dènge rai-haha ne ele, te ngaa Atora nèti Ama Lamatua ciki sa, ele boe. Ca katèd'a sa ele boe hèi!<bt>Even.if the sky and earth disappear, nevertheless Father God's regulations/Law even a little bit won't disappear. Not even a full.stop-comma will disappear!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katèda = titik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">katèda = titik</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dhèu dhu pa'ia-pa'ela dènge dhèu èmu na, aa na madhèdi hari dènge bhèni leo, nèngu bersina. Aa dhèu dhu leo dènge bhèni dhu pa'ia-pa'ela, nèngu bersina kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>A person who divorces his spouse, then marries2 again with another woman, he is adulterous. And the other person who marries that divorced wife, he also is adulterous.” [NOTE to daughter translations: (alternate) /Abis laki-laki yang kawin deng parampuan yang dia pung laki su cere buang,/] [double-CHECK: why loan here for adultery?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'ia-pa'ela = divorce ; madhèdi (2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pa'ia-pa'ela = divorce ; madhèdi (2) = marry</Message></Annotation><note reference="16:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:32, 1 Korintus 7:10-11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii lolo dhèu kaja dènge Lasarus<bt>Story of the rich person and Lasarus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Yesus lole tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu kaja ca dhèu. Nèngu d'èi pake mèdha-papake dhu be'a-be'a, tao nèti bèla alus. Mèu-mèda na'a-ninu nganga'a dhu be'a hua, aa karae taruu.<bt>Yesus story-ed further, saying, “There was a rich person. He liked to use fancy clothes that were made out of fine cloth. Day-night he ate-drank enjoyably, and was always extravagant.</bt><v n="20" />Ètu kota ne'e, abhu kahèi ca dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa. Ngara na, Lasarus. Ngi'u na dhu pènu dènge kamèu. Bèli-bèli angalai na rèti pamadhèdi ne ètu hèb'a tedhe dhèu kaja èèna.<bt>In that city there was also an impoverished person. His name was Lasarus. His body was full of smelly wounds. Every day his friends brought him to place/sit him in front of that rich person's outer gate.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kamèu = luka koreng, (smallpox? scars"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kamèu = luka koreng, (smallpox? scars for life), penyakit kulit, water blister, smell like fish (amis), not too painful, but leave scars, hard to get rid of, cacar air, can have pus ; kamèu pèdi = (same but gatal) ;</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Na sanao teko-teko abhu kaha'i nganga'a nèti dhèu kaja ne, sèna ka bisa na'a, te ngaa na abhu boe ngaa-ngaa. Dhoka busa di mai, ho j'ore nana kamèu na.<bt>He desired to get food from that rich person's left over food, so he could eat, but he didn't get anything. Only the dogs came to lick his wounds' pus. [EXEG: Marshall “unfulfilled wish”, TN “he did not get anything to satisfy his hunger”, which is also probable reading of NRSV, NLT, GW, and Green; CEV assumes it was fulfilled, without any support that I can see. Result of neglect was Lazarus died.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaha'i = 1) leftover 2) pakaian"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kaha'i = 1) leftover 2) pakaian lusuh (old and worn) ; j'ore = jilat ; tao-tao = teko-teko - jang-jang , jang smpe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Kamèu artinya: Luka koreng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Kamèu artinya: Luka koreng</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Nèbhu boe ka, Lasarus madhe. Hèia ana pajuu Ama Lamatua mai nèti sorga, ka rèti lasi pamadhèdi ne ètu baboa Abraham.<bt>Not long (=soon), Lasarus died. Then Father God's underlings from heaven came and took him, to sit him at grandfather Abraham's side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baboa = karasa = samping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">baboa = karasa = samping</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa nèbhu boe ka, dhèu kaja ne madhe kahèi, ka dhèu ded'e lasi padhane.<bt>And not long after that the rich person also died, and people buried him.</bt><v n="23" />Te ngaa dhèu kaja ne maso boe sorga. Nèngu maso asa d'ara naraka, sama-sama dènge dhèu-dhèu leo dhu madhe le. Ètu era nèi, dhèu kaja ne abhu j'aj'èra taa-taa. Ca tèka na boti kètu, ka ladhe nèdhi Lasarus madhèdi ètu baboa baki Abraham.<bt>But the rich man didn't enter heaven. He entered hell, together with many other dead people. There (remote) the rich man was afflicted with torture and misery continually. Then one time, he lifted his head then he could see Lasarus sitting happily at grandfather Abraham's side. [EXEG &amp; NOTE to daughter translations: because of the TB “sitting in his lap” expect your teams to query KM “at his side”. See NRSV, NLT, CEV, Marshall, LN (1.16) for meaning of Gk idiom “in his bosom” = closely associated with, place of honour, at his side, next to”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baboa = di samping, rebis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">baboa = di samping, rebis</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Hèia na pa'oo, peka na, &lt;Baki Abraham, ee! Sue ku ja'a laa! Pua ku Lasarus cèb'u kolo ai na asa d'ara èi, sèna ka mai pabasa ku kolo he'o ja'a ne. Te ja'a j'èra titu kèna ètu d'ara ai naraka ne!&gt;<bt>Then he yelled out saying, ‘Grandfather Abraham ee! Have love/pity on me! Tell Lasarus to dip the tip of his finger in water, in.order.to come wet even just the tip of my tongue. Cuz (elaboration) I am very miserable in hell fire here!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="suu ai = 1) tip of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">suu ai = 1) tip of finger, 2) puntung api ; kolo = ujung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Baboa artinya: Disamping."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Baboa artinya: Disamping.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa Abraham dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ana, ee! Sanèd'e ku! Uru èèna lod'o èu mamuri era ètu rai-haha nèi, èu abhu le aa'i-aa'i dhu be'a. Te ngaa Lasarus ne, unu dhodhoka sasusa di. Ka limuri ne, Lamatua pakarej'e ne ètu ne'e, te ngaa èu pasae more j'aj'èra.<bt>But Abraham replied saying, ‘Child, ee! Think carefully now. Earlier when you still lived on earth (remote), you had everything that was good. But Lasarus only had just suffering. So now the Lord comforts/consoles him here, but you endure suffering.</bt><v n="26" />Risi-risi hari, ètu talora aae èu dènge ji'i, Lamatua tao tèke loe aae èci dhu taleo dènge marèma. De dhèu nèti ne'e bisa boe dhiu asa era èèna, aa dhèu nèti èèna bisa boe pège sa ne'e mai.&gt;<bt>And even more, between you and us-exc, there is a deep gap/chasm. So (consequently) people from here cannot stop in/go there, and people from there cannot cross over to here.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pège = langgar, nyebrang ; loe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pège = langgar, nyebrang ; loe = jurang, goa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia dhèu kaja ne pamako hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, baki Abraham pua Lasarus la'e asa èmu ama ku.<bt>Then that rich person cajoled again, saying, ‘If that's the case, grandfather please order Lasarus to go to my father's house.</bt><v n="28" />Te ja'a ne dènge ari dhèu mone, dhèu lèmi era. Sèna ka Lasarus la'e pasanèd'e si, ho ra lèpa ka asa Lamatua. Masi ka lod'o d'ai ra madhe, rèngu maso ia ka asa era j'aj'èra ne.&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I still have five male younger.siblings there. So Lasarus should go remind/warn them, to return to the Lord. Even if they died, they shouldn't enter this horrible/miserable place here.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa Abraham b'ala ne, &lt;Ama Lamatua hia le rèngu sasuri nèti baki Musa dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Na. Ari mu si, bisa baca pahari-pahari ho re'a dad'èi Lamatua.&gt;<bt>But Abraham replied, ‘Father God has given them grandfather Musa and His spokespersons' writings. Your younger.siblings can read them over.and.over, so they understand the Lord's will.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Te ngaa dhèu kaja ne pasisu, peka na, &lt;Baki Abraham, ee! Èèna dhae d'ai mèka. Rèngu sèi pahae boe Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua! Hud'i abhu ku ca dhèu nèti talora dhèu madhe la'e asa rèngu, heka rèngu ele-ho'a, aa neo nanene kèna.&gt;<bt>But that rich person protested, saying, ‘Grandfather Abraham, ee! That's not enough. They don't pay attention to the Lord's Teachings/Words. There must be someone from among dead people who goes to tell them, only.then will they change/repent/stop their sins and want to listen/obey.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = sadar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">mase'a = sadar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa Abraham dhaa, peka na, &lt;Ladhe rèngu sèi ro'o boe nanene lii holo-nori nèti Musa dènge nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua, na, masi ka dhèu madhe bhodho nèti d'ara ro'a ra, ho padhai lii dènge rèngu èèna ka, rèngu ro'o boe nanene.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But Abraham responded, saying, ‘If they don't want to listen to/obey Gf Musa and God's spokespeople's words/teachings/advice, then even if the dead people appeared from the graves to speak to them, (nevertheless) they would not listen.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèdi = bangkit ; sabhoka ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kèdi = bangkit ; sabhoka =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti dhèu dhu manahu asa d'ara sasala, aa dhu manèngi abho<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about people who fall into sin, and those who request forgiveness</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 18:6-7, 21-22; Markus 9:42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na, &lt;&lt;Ae ka dhèu manahu asa d'ara sasala, lula tatao dhèu leo. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pamanahu dhèu asa d'ara sasala èèna, pasae nare mamadhe-mamopo.<bt>Yesus told His underlings, saying, “Many times there are people who fall into sin, because of other people's deeds/ actions/behaviour. But the person who makes someone fall into that sin, is the one who is most misfortune/in.trouble.</bt><v n="2" />Ladhe dhèu ad'u-ue j'ara karehe, toke ana iiki parcaya boe Ja'a, èèna na Ama Lamatua huku ne bia. Dhu samaa risi, ladhe èki ladha goro dhèu ne'e dènge hadhu aae cue, ho parèu eele asa d'ara dhasi ètu talora lèu.<bt>If/when a person does something evil to the point that there is a small child who doesn't believe in Me, then Father God will heavily punish him. It's lighter to tie a big stone on his neck, then drown him out at sea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parèu = tenggelamkan, jatuhkan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">parèu = tenggelamkan, jatuhkan ;</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />De j'aga ngi'u pabe'a-be'a, sèna ka miu baku pamanahu dhèu asa d'ara sasala! Te ngaa ladhe a'ari mu tao sala, pasanèd'e ne. Ladhe na ele-ho'a, hèia na mai manèngi abho, na pabhèlu eele sasala na.<bt>So (consequently), watch/guard yourselves carefully so you-pl don't also cause people to fall into sin! But if your-sg sibling (broad) sins, na, remind/warn him. If he *repents, then come and asks forgiveness, na, completely forget that sin of his.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="holo = nasehati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">holo = nasehati</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ladhe a'ari èu tao sala pidhu hari d'ara ca lod'o, ka na ele-ho'a, hèia na mai pidhu hari ho manèngi abho, èu hud'i pabhèlu eele sasala na pidhu hari kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>If your-sg sibling does you wrong seven time in one day, then he repents, then2 he comes seven time to request forgiveness, you must completely forget his sin seven times.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu hud'i parcaya ku koasa Ama Lamatua<bt>People must believe in Father God's power/authority</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ca lod'o, ana madhutu se<bt>One day, Yesus' underlings</bt><note reference="17:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani ètu ne'e, peka na, &lt;&lt;dhèu pajuu-paleha&gt;&gt;. Lukas d'èi suri na, &lt;&lt;dhèu pajuu-paleha&gt;&gt; mi ana madhutu Yesus dhèu canguru dua sèra.<bt>The Yunani language writings here write, “*apostle”. Lukas likes to/often writes “apostle” for the Lord Yesus' 12 *disciples.</bt></note>mai asa Yesus, ka ra manèngi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Parcaya ji'i se èra boe. De Ama pa'èra ku parcaya ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>came and met Him to request, saying, “Father Teacher! Our-exc faith is not strong. So (consequently) please make our faith stronger.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu parcaya koasa nèti Ama Lamatua, masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka, te ngaa miu bisa paredha aj'u aae ne, &lt;Tahoi eele, ho pidha asa d'ara dhasi!&gt; Ka aj'u ne madhutu lii paredha miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “If you have faith in Father God's power/authority, even just a little bit, [contrary to expectation] you can order this big tree, saying, “Get.uprooted and move into the sea!&gt; Then that tree will follow/ obey your command.” [1st sent. is faith in God's power.] [NOTE: to follow TN suggestion on process would be severely overtranslating this well known verse. TN seems to be the only source that reads it this way.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Tahoi artinya: Tercabut dengen akar-akarnya."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Tahoi artinya: Tercabut dengen akar-akarnya.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu sab'a dhu be'a, nuka dhu madhutu dad'èi lamatua na<bt>A worker who is good, is one who follows his master's will</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èle ka Yesus lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare conto èci. Nuka sèmi ènu dhu pare rai ètu d'ara oka, do, ladhe kahib'i-kalèbho ètu d'ara pad'a sod'a. Sab'a nare, ka lèpa sa èmu. Tatu lamatua na peka boe dènge ne, &lt;Mai ho dua ti ta'a sama-sama!&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke, saying, “Take an example/ illustration. There was/is a lowly servant/ slave who hoes dirt/soil in the garden, or watches sheep in the field. After working then, s/he returns home. Surely his/her master will not tell him saying, ‘Come let's the two of us eat together!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pada sod'a = padang luas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pada sod'a = padang luas</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Aad'o, sina ma? Dhu lèke ka, lamatua paredha ne, peka na, &lt;Lamu lalau mei hia ja'a. Ku'a-kinu kore ku, pe èu mu'a-minu ètu kabodho nèi!&gt;<bt>No, right? What is natural/ appropriate is for his master to order him, saying, ‘Go arrange the table for me. When I have finished eating-drinking, then you-sg eat-drink later on.’</bt><v n="9" />Ladhe ènu ne lalau nare madhutu dad'èi lamatua na, miu ngee, na, lamatua ne manèngi makasi mi ènu ne, do? Aad'o!<bt>If/when that slave has done according to his master's will, do you-pl think that master will later say thank you to that slave, [tag question]? No!</bt><v n="10" />Miu èci èèna kahèi. Ladhe sab'a mere aa'i dhu Lamatua paredha le, miu peka na, &lt;Ji'i dhoka ana pua-paleha di. Ji'i tenge boe lii koa-kad'iri. Ji'i dhoka pakako sasab'a-la'a ji'i di.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>You-pl are also like.that. If/when you have finished doing everything God has commanded, you speak, saying, ‘We are only just low.level.workers/ slaves. We do not seek praise. We only just carried out our duty/work.’”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koa-kadiri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">koa-kadiri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle canguru dhèu dhu pèd'a kusta<bt>The Lord Yesus heals ten leprosy people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o Yesus si lasi asa Yerusalem, rèngu d'ai too propensi Galilea dènge propensi Samaria.<bt>When Yesus (collective) was walking/going to Yerusalem, they arrived at the boundary of Galilea province and Samaria province.</bt><v n="12" />Ropa rèngu neo maso asa d'ara rae cue ètu èèna, dhèu canguru dhu pèd'a kusta mai, neo paraga dènge Yesus. Rèngu se titu nèti kaj'èu.<bt>When they were about to enter into a village there, ten leprosy people came wanting to meet with Yesus. The stood far off.</bt><v n="13" />Ka ra pa'oo palere-lere, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus! Mone Kapai, ee! Sue ku ji'i laa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they called out enthusiastically, saying, “Yesus! Master2 (euphemism), ee! Have love/pity/mercy on us-exc!” [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk word for ‘master’ here is different from /kurios/ which we normally translate as ‘bos’. So KM /tuan/ is a way to reflect there is a difference.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mone eele (Pacele)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Mone eele (Pacele)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi lii pa'oo ra, ka Na ladhe si, hèia Na pua, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lami pad'elo uuru ku isi miu asa ama agama, sèna ka ra parisa papèd'a kusta miu sèra, èle le, do dhae!&gt;&gt; Ra tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka lasi dènge. Te ngaa ropa d'ai talora j'ara, cag'ag'a laa, rèngu dhu èle le nèti kusta.<bt>When Yesus heard what they were calling, and saw them, then He ordered saying, “You-pl go show your bodies to the heads of religion (=*priests) first, so that they can examine whether that leprosy of yours have disappeared or not.yet.” When they heard that, they went straightaway. But in the middle of the road/journey, suddenly, they were all healed of their leprosy.</bt><note reference="17:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 14:1-32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Rèngu lasi taruu dènge karej'e-karae. Te ngaa abhu ca dhèu di, dhu lèpa hari mai asa Yesus. Na pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Koa-kio Lamatua! Te ja'a èle le nèti papèd'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>They travelled on happily. But there was one person who returned to Yesus. S/he called out, saying, “Praise the Lord! Cuz (elaboration) I am healed of my disease!”</bt><v n="16" />Hèia na patitu kètu urutuu na, ho manèngi makasi ae-ae mi Yesus. (Te'a boe, te nèngu ne dhèu Yahudi boe. Nèngu ne ca dhèu Samaria dhu loe boe tao lii langu dènge dhèu Yahudi.)<bt>Then he knelt to say much thankyou to Yesus. (As it turns out, that person wasn't even a Yahudi person. That person was a Samaria person who continually have disputes with the Yahudi people.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka Yesus karèi dhèu sèra dhu madhutu dènge Ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ee? Deo na Ja'a pa'èle dhèu canguru si? Dhu ceo, mia lasi?<bt>Then Yesus asked the people who were following Him, saying, “How is it, ee? Earlier I healed ten people, right? Where are the nine?</bt><v n="18" />Tasamia ka dhoka dhèu leo kara ne'e di, dhu lèpa mai ho manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, dènge koa-kio kolongara Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Why is it that it is only just this foreign person who come to say thankyou to Father God, and praise His name/reputation?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia Na peka mi dhèu ne, na, &lt;&lt;Èu èle le, lula èu parcaya Ja'a tare'a-re'a. De kèd'i, lèpa ka dènge sod'a-mole!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He told that person, saying, “You-sg are healed because you truly believe in Me. So (consequently) get up and go.home in peace and safety (doublet)!” DISCOURSE: note there are possible shifts of addressee between 17 and 18 and 19. Most (all?) AN lgs in eastern Indonesia do not (cannot) put a quote margin in for a continuation of same speaker.][EXEG: Most translations and commentators are vague or do not address this. Marshall points out the obvious, that 19 is addressed to the just-healed leper. 18 is fairly clearly including His followers (from vs. 5). So the exegetical question focuses on 17. It could be read as addressed to a) the leper, or b) to include His followers. In the Gk. there is a quote margin in 17, and another in 19. This could suggest 17 + 18 = general RQ's for the benefit of His followers, followed by 19 = to the leper. But a number of people reading various translations in various lgs see 17 as addressed to the leper. Green appears to imply 17 is directed at (b) and adds “By keeping Jesus’ companions offstage, however, or at least in the background, Luke allows Jesus’ queries to be aimed more pointedly at Luke’s audience.” TH doesn't address the issue at all. TN recognises the problem but does not lobby for either (a) or (b), and says, in effect, because the issue is not clear, the safer solution is to be broad “Jesus asked those who were with Him”. A better solution which preserves the ambiguity of the Gk (in which both possible options are acceptable) if the language allows it is just a vague “Jesus asked”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu ne'e,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Hèia Yesus peka dènge dhèu ne'e, &lt;&lt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus lole lod'o èle rai-haha, dènge mamai hari Na<bt>The Lord Yesus story-s about the end.of.the.world, and His coming back</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:23-28, 37-41)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20-21" />Ca lod'o, dhèu Parisi pèri-pèri mai karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Peka ku dènge ji'i, lod'o mia Ama Lamatua neo pakako paredha Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>One day, there were several Parisi people who came asking Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher! Please tell us! When will Father God begin to carry out His rule?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nui = not respond, but simpan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">nui = not respond, but simpan dalam hati</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ouk ... meta parateereeseoos: not just"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">ouk ... meta parateereeseoos: not just a thing you go to gawk at, like a public spectacle. Predictable by signs, as with the Wise Men?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Mage mi pangee, na, Lamatua pakako paredha Na dènge rupa-rupa tadha ètu rai-haha ne, dhu dhèu bisa rèdhi dènge musi madha ra. Dhèu abhu boe tadha dhu peka na, &lt;Ladhe ku asa ne'e mai! Te Ama Lamatua pakako paredha Na ètu ne'e!&gt; Do, &lt;Na pakako paredha Na ètu nèi!&gt; Aad'o! Te Na pakako paredha Na ètu talora aae miu, ètu d'ara dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus responded, “It's like.this! Don't think/assume the Lord will carry out His rule with all.sorts.of signs in this world which people can examine with their eyes. People will not get a sign that says, ‘Look over here! Cuz (elaboration) Father God is carrying out His rule here!’ Or, ‘He is carrying out His rule over yonder!’ No! Cuz (elaboration) He carries out His rule in the midst of you-pl in people's insides.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu boe, na, Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, pa'èci heka dènge miu. D'ai ka lod'o j'aj'èra sèra, miu d'èi titu kèna neo mèdhi mamai hari Ja'a. Te ngaa d'ai mèka lod'o mamai Ja'a.<bt>Then Yesus told His underlings, “Not much longer (=soon) I, this Authentic Human, will not be together with you anymore. Later when its the days of difficulty, you will yearn to see My return. But I will not yet come. [EXEG: see extensive discussion in Marshall on 6 different interpretations of “the days of the Son of Man”. This rendering following HCE, &amp; Western Bukidnon Manobo BT.]</bt><v n="23" />Ladhe èèna na dhèu mai peka, na, &lt;Kristus ètu ne'e!&gt; do, &lt;Kristus ètu nèi!&gt; Na, miu baku bhute ho patangi-tenge, te lii padhai rèngu sèra, kapod'e-kabèli.<bt>Then if people come saying, ‘Kristus is here!’ or, ‘Kristus is yonder!’ Na, you don't need to worry or go hunt all around, cuz (elaboration) that speaking of this is deceitful (doublet). [EXEG: Messiah, as in Marshall &amp; TN]</bt><v n="24" />Te ladhe Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, lèpa hari mai, tadha na dhu mèu aadha-aadha, nuka sèmi bela dhu heo kacèb'a ètu dedha-liru nèti suu asa suu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) when the Authentic Human return, the signs will be very clear, the same as lightning which flashes in the sky from one end to the other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèu aadha-aadha = sangat jelas ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">mèu aadha-aadha = sangat jelas ; kacèba = blitz</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Te ngaa Nèngu hud'i abhu uuru ku j'aj'èra rupa-rupa. Ka dhèu rai-haha taa limuri ne, ro'o boe nanene, aa neo tule eele Ne.<bt>But He also must bear all.sorts.of suffering first. And humans in this time don't want to listen/obey and will reject Him. [EXEG: vs.25-29, UNS's were not getting the parallels between when Jesus returns, Noah's time, and Lot's time. Restructured to make parallels with more obvious lexical ties. Problem: Luke seems to assume two things: 1) everyone knows the stories of Noah and Lot, and that the people were punished for their evil lifestyles, and 2) everyone knows these people were given fair warning (perhaps repeated warnings) and chose to ignore them, continuing on unrepentant and unchanged. UNS &amp; team pointed out that without making these explicit, it's hard to understand what the problem is to follow what's supposed to be parallel.]</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa bèli-camèd'a, ladhe Na neo mai hari, dhèu mamuri karehe sama biasa, èci èèna ka dènge lod'o Noh mamuri era.<bt>But in the future, when He is going to come back, people will be living evil as they normally do, the same as in Noh's age.</bt><note reference="17:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 6:5-8</note><v n="27" />Taa èèna, rèngu ra'a-rinu, tao pesta kab'i toke lod'o Noh maso asa d'ara kapa na. Te ngaa rèngu ro'o boe nanene kahèi. Kaca'a laa, èi aae lala, ka pamadhe aa'i si.<bt>At that time they ate-drank, made wedding feasts, until the day Noh entered his boat. But those people also did not want to hear/obey. Suddenly, the big flood came and killed off all of them.</bt><note reference="17:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 7:6-24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, lod'o Lot mamuri era, dhèu mamuri karehe titu kèna. Taa èèna, rèngu ra'a-rinu, bad'aga, sab'a oka-tedhe, patitu èmu, aa mamuri karehe sèmi biasa.<bt>That is also the same as people who lived evilly in Lot's age. At that time, they ate-drank, traded, made gardens (doublet), and built houses, living evil just like normal.</bt><v n="29" />Te ngaa ro'o boe nanene kahèi. Hèia mad'ae aae era, ropa Lot rai eele nèti kota Sodom, cag'ag'a laa, èj'i ai dènge èi nasu bhori mai nèti dedha-liru, aa labhu pakèpu rèngu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>But they also did not want to hear/obey. So then that same morning, when Lot ran leaving behind Sodom city, suddenly, fire rain and sulfer poured out from the sky and burned them all up.</bt><note reference="17:28-29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 18:20--19:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />De miu baku pamud'e ku! Mage dhoka bèli-camèd'a Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, lèpa hari mai, dhèu mamuri dhoka sèmi biasa di. Te ngaa kaca'a laa, Na cèu mai.<bt>So (consequently), you all watch out! Lest in the future when the Authentic Human comes back, people are living just like normal. But suddenly He will appear.</bt><v n="31" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ètu madha èmu, maso ia ka asa d'ara ho lalau mèdha. Dhèu dhu sab'a ètu d'ara oka, lèpa ia ka asa èmu ho rare mèdha ra.<bt>At that day/time, people who are on a house's porch/yard, shouldn't enter again inside the house to organise things/possessions. People who are working in the garden, shouldn't go.home again to get their stuff.</bt><note reference="17:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 24:17-18, Markus 13:15-16</note><v n="32" />Sanèd'e ku ngaa dhu uru èèna j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu Lot. Na madhe, lula nèngu ngee mèdha-panyau ètu èmu na.<bt>Remember what happened with Lot's spouse long.ago. She died, because she thought about/remembered her stuff (doublet) at home.</bt><note reference="17:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 19:26</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Dhèu dhu d'èi boe madhutu Ja'a lula sue ngi'u na, èèna na mamuri na ele iia d'ara. Te ngaa dhèu dhu madhutu Ja'a toke soro mamuri na, lula sue Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a abhu sod'a-mole, aa mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>The person who does not want to follow Me because he loves his own self, later his life will be completely lost/disappear. But the person who follows Me to.the.point.of handing over his life because he loves Me, he will obtain salvation (doublet), and live continually with Father God.</bt><note reference="17:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:39, 16:25, Markus 8:35, Lukas 9:24, Yohanis 12:25</note><v n="34" />Ja'a pasanèd'e mema! Ropa Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, lèpa hari mai, ladhe dhèu dua j'unu ètu era èci, kabèdhi laa Lamatua ded'e paca'e ca dhèu, aa tèke eele ca dhèu.<bt>I'm reminding/warning (= mark my words)! When the Authentic Human, comes back, if there are two people sleeping in one bed, suddenly the Lord will pick up one, and leave behind the other.</bt><v n="35" />Ladhe abhu dhèu bhèni dhèu dua dhu maj'u are, èèna na Lamatua ded'e paca'e ca dhèu, aa tèke eele ca dhèu.<bt>If there are two women pounding padi together, the Lord will pick up one, but leave behind the other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maj'u = tumbuk"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">maj'u = tumbuk</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />[Ladhe abhu dhèu dua dhu sab'a ètu d'ara oka, Lamatua mai ded'e nèti èci, aa tèke eele ca dhèu.]&gt;&gt;<bt>[If there are two people working together in the garden, the Lord will lift up one, and leave behind the other.]&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="17:36" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat 36 ne abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani dhu be'a risi.<bt>Verse 36 is not in the best Yunani writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ropa ana madhutu tadèngi rare, hèia ra karèi Yesus, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Sèra sa bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, then Yesus' underlings asked Him saying, “Father Teacher! Where will all that happen?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus core lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Ladhe miu mèdhi ka manu-bhui dhu tema ra'a sisi badha madhe, ra lela pa'oru ètu mia, na, miu me'a èèna j'aj'i mi tadha, dhu peka na, tatu abhu sisi hèu ètu era èèna.&gt;&gt; [Dènge sasoa dhu pahuni, peka na, ladhe Yesus Kristus lèpa hari mai, tadha na dhu mèu aadha-aadha, sad'i dhèu re'a baca tadha sèra.]<bt>Then Yesus threw out language (=spoke figuratively) saying, “It's like this. Whereever you-pl see the birds who habitually eat animal corpses flying gathering, na, you know that is a sign that surely they are eating rotten meat at that place.” [With a hidden meaning, that, later when Yesus Kristus comes back, the signs will be very clear, as long as people know how to read them.] [EXEG: Pattern from Mrk 7:27-28; explication following Marshall, NLT and TN] [NOTE to daughter translations: Proverb in quote may be able to be more succinct in some lgs.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parai oru = balari pi-datang, saling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">parai oru = balari pi-datang, saling baku rampas ; lela pa'oru = terbang bakumpul</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii lolo nèti bhèni balu èci, dènge hakim dhu karehe<bt>Story about a widow woman, and a bad judge</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Ca tèka, Yesus padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na, pake lii pakasame ho rèngu loe boe manèngi-mangaj'i, aa baku ma'ète sanao-maena. Rèngu hud'i parcaya taa-taa Lamatua.<bt>One time, Yesus was speaking with His underlings using a comparison story, so they would pray unendingly, and not lose enthusiasm/hope. They must continually believe in the Lord. [literal + explication]</bt><v n="2" />Lii lolo na sèmi ne'e ka: &lt;&lt;Ètu d'ara kota cue, abhu ca dhèu ama pama'ète lii langu, dhu pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua. Na pahae boe ca dhèu sa hèi.<bt>The story is like this: “In a city there was a judge lit. father/leader who decides disputes) who didn't care about (doublet) Father God. He didn't even care.about anyone.</bt><v n="3" />Ètu era èèna, abhu kahèi bhèni balu èci, dhu loe boe mai sa dhèu pama'ète lii ne, ho manèngi, peka na, &lt;Ama hakim! J'ue ku lii langu ja'a dènge mola!&gt;<bt>There there was also a widow woman who kept coming to that judge to request, saying, ‘Father judge (loan)! Decide2 my case correctly/fairly!’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hiu-hiu èèna, dhèu pama'ète lii ne pusi boe dènge bhèni balu ne. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu ka, na roca nanene ne. Hèia na madhèdi pangee ka, &lt;Mema ja'a ne pusi boe dènge Ama Lamatua, risi-risi dènge dhèu rai-haha.<bt>Initially that judge didn't pay any attention to that widow. But eventually he got fed.up hearing her. So he sat and thought, saying, ‘It's very true that I don't care about Father God, and even less about humans.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hiu-hiu = at the beginning, initially"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">hiu-hiu = at the beginning, initially</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ngaa bhèni ne pakabo'o kètu ja'a. De be'a risi ja'a pama'ète lii na dènge mola. Te ladhe ja'a panena, na mai taruu paj'èra ja'a.&gt;<bt>But this widow has keeps annoying my head. So (consequently) it's better that I fairly decide her case. Cuz (elaboration) if I keep stalling/delaying (deliberately), she will keep coming and continually make me worn.out/in difficulty.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakatate = memaksa, pojokan ; pakabo'o"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pakatate = memaksa, pojokan ; pakabo'o = bekin pusing (CIE with pakaboko)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />De miu pangee ku lii padhai dhèu pama'ète lii dhu bhelu ne.<bt>So (consequently), you-pl (need to) think about the words of that evil judge. [DISCOURSE: Gk has “And the Lord /kurios/ said”; but AN lgs in eastern Indonesia do not (cannot) have quote margin in continuation of same speaker talking, so it's removed here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adikias: unrighteousness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">adikias: unrighteousness</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ladhe nèbhu-nèbhu dhèu pama'ète lii ne tao ai-hèb'a mi bhèni balu ne, tatu Ama Lamatua kahèi neo tao ai-hèb'a mi dhèu unu Na dhu sabaj'a mèu-mèda mi Nèngu ho manèngi sasue Na. Te ngaa Lamatua mate heka panèbhu.<bt>If eventually the judge helped/attended to that widow, surely Father God also wants to help/attend to His people who pray day-night requesting help/pity/mercy from Him. But the Lord doesn't delay. [EXEG: /chosen/ explicit &gt; implicit in /his people/; would skew the focus to force it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="panena = perlambat, stalled, stretched out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">panena = perlambat, stalled, stretched out (deliberately long) [also panèbhu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa Lamatua mate boe panèbhu."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Te ngaa Lamatua mate boe panèbhu.</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te Nèngu uri lii langu rèngu dènge boe pamata. De Ja'a neo karèi sèmi ne'e: ladhe Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne mai hari, Ja'a bisa paraga dènge dhèu parcaya ètu rai-haha ne era, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He handles/takes care of their cases without delay2. So (consequently) I want to ask like this: when I, the Authentic Human here, return again, do you think I will still be able to meet with/encounter believers still on this earth, or not?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamata = tunggu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pamata = tunggu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Parisi èci, dènge dhèu roro bea èci lasi manèngi-mangaj'i<bt>A Parisi person and a tax collector go pray (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Yesus lolo tabha hari pake lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu dhu pangee na ne'a aa'i mèu-mèu, aa dhu d'èi pahaha dhèu leo. Na peka na,<bt>Yesus told another comparison.story, about people who think of themselves as clever, and they like to look disparagingly at other people. He said,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu tao iisi ne'a aa'i mèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhu tao iisi ne'a aa'i mèu = sok pintar</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />&lt;&lt;Abhu ama dhèu dua dhu lasi sabaj'a asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ca dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi, aa èci hari dhèu roro bea. [Dhèu Yahudi peka na dhèu Parisi sèra, dhèu dhu mola. Te ngaa ra pangee, na, dhèu roro bea, dhèu karehe.]<bt>“There were two fathers/men who went to pray at the *Temple. One was a person from the Parisi religious party; the other one a tax collector. [The Yahudi people consider/say the Parisi people, holy people. But they consider tax collectors, bad/not good people.]</bt><v n="11" />D'ai èmu sabaj'a dhèu Parisi ne titu mesa-mesa na, ka na manèngi-mangaj'i, peka na, &lt;Makasi Lamatua, te ja'a ne dhèu be'a. Ja'a ne bhelu boe nuka sèmi dhèu leo sèra. Ja'a mana'u boe. Ja'a manga'a boe. Ja'a dhèu dhu bersina boe. Makasi Lamatua, te ja'a ne bhelu boe nuka sèmi dhèu roro bea ne.<bt>Arriving at the worship house, that Parisi person stood off by himself and prayed, saying, ‘Thank you Lord, cuz (elaboration) I here am a good person. I am not evil like other people. I don't steal. I am not greedy. I am not adulterous. Thankyou Lord, cuz (elaboration) I also am not evil like this tax collector here. [NOTE: Sentence broken up to emphasize self-praise.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adikoi: unrighteous"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">adikoi: unrighteous</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ja'a ne maj'èni puasa ca migu dua hari. Aa ja'a d'èi hia ca pala nèti canguru pala nèti aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a abhu.&gt; Dhèu Parisi ne, sabaj'a sèmi èèna ka.<bt>I diligently fast two times a week. And I always give a tenth from everything I obtain.’ That Parisi person prayed like.that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa dhèu roro bea ne titu pakaj'èu ètu kabodho nèi. Na bani boe boti kètu ho ladhe sa dedha. Nèngu dhoka pacud'u di, dhu dènge d'ara ma'ète mae-mae. Na sabaj'a, peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua! Sue ku ja'a, dhèu dhu pènu dènge sasala-sasigo ne! Abho eele ku sasala ja'a!&gt;<bt>But that tax collector stood far in the back. He did not dare lift his face to look upwards. He only bowed his head with his insides crushed (=broken.hearted), saying, ‘Father God. Have pity on me, this sinful human! Can [You] forgive me of my sins?’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacud'u = tondo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pacud'u = tondo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o dhèu dua se lèpa lasi asa èmu ra, cee ka dhu pabe'a dènge Ama Lamatua? Dhèu Parisi dhu pamone, do dhèu roro bea ne? Tatu Na sèmi dènge be'a, dhèu roro bea dhu pahaha iisi ne. Te ngaa Na pusi boe dènge dhèu Parisi ne. Te Ama Lamatua pahaha dhèu dhu pamone-pabhèni, te ngaa Na padedha dhèu dhu re'a pahaha iisi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When those two people returned home, which one (do you think) was in a good.relationship with Father God? That proud Parisi person, or that tax collector? Surely He accepted that tax collector who was low-livered (=humble). But He didn't care about that Parisi person. Cuz (elaboration) Father God brings down/lowers proud (doublet) people, but He lifts up/exalts/ honours people who are humble.”</bt><note reference="18:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 23:12, Lukas 14:11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii hia mamèngi mi ana-ana<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks giving blessing to the children</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 19:13-15; Markus 10:13-16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ca tèka, dhèu sa'u rèti ana ra dhu rara iisi hiu asa Yesus, sèna ka Na tao ai Na mi ana iiki se, aa padhai lii hia si mamèngi. Ropa rèdhi sèmi èèna, ana-ana madhutu Yesus kai dhèu se'e.<bt>One time, people were carrying bringing their newborns to Yesus, so that He would put his hands and speak giving blessing to them. Seeing like that, Yesus' underlings scolded those people. [NRSV, LN, Marshall; NOTE to daughter translations: the Gk word here is “infant” in vs.15; because this is different from the Matthew and Mark versions, don't be surprised if your team queries this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gèru-gèru ~ pagèru = comel-comel, cari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">gèru-gèru ~ pagèru = comel-comel, cari hal</Message></Annotation><v n="16-17" />Te ngaa Yesus soru mamai ra dènge be'a. Hèia Na kai ana-ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa ana iiki sèra mai asa Ja'a. Miu baku bhabhae si. Sanèd'e paie! Dhèu dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, nèngu hud'i sanao-maena dhoka mi Ama Lamatua, nuka sèmi ana iiki dhu sanao-maena dhoka mi ina-ama na.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus invited them to come to Him. Then He scolded his underlings, saying, “Allow those small children to come to Me. Don't you-pl block/prevent them. Remember well! The person who wants to become Father God's person, he must depend/hang on/hope in Father God, just like small children depend on their mother-father.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhabhae = menghalangi, pele ; sarai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bhabhae = menghalangi, pele ; sarai = sandar ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu kaja dhu neo maso sorga<bt>Rich person who desires to enter heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 19:16-30; Markus 10:17-31)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ca lod'o, dhèu kapai Yahudi èci, mai karèi Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese dhu hua iia! Ja'a ne hud'i tao ku tasamia, sèna ka ja'a ke'a tare'a, na, ja'a maso sorga, aa mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua?&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, there was an important person of the Yahudi people who asked Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher who is most.respected! What must I do so.that I know for sure that I can enter heaven to live continually with Father God?” [EXEG: Gk ‘ruler, important person’]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Yesus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka èu ne peka na, Ja'a &lt;dhu hua iia&gt;? Dhodhoka èci di dhu hua iia, nuka Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then Yesus responded, “Why do you-sg address Me saying ‘who is most.respected’? There is only just one who is most.respected, that is Father God alone.</bt><v n="20" />Èu me'a le atora Ama Lamatua karèi nèti uru ka, dhu peka na:<bt>You know Father God's regulations from long.ago, which say:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku j'unu pa'èci dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu boe èu;<bt>Don't commit adultery (lit. sleep together with a person who is not your spouse);</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku pamadhe dhèu;<bt>don't murder people;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku mana'u;<bt>don't steal;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">baku j'aj'i sakasii dhu leko-monya;<bt>don't be a twisted (=deceitful) witness;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa pakab'ua ina dènge ama mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>and respect to your-sg mother and father.”</bt><note reference="18:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:12-16, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:16-20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka dhèu ne dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, Ama! Ja'a dhu madhutu le atora sèra, karèi nèti ja'a ana iiki era.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person responded saying, “True, Father! I have followed those regulations beginning from when I was still a small child.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Be'a! Te ngaa èu kura ca madha j'ara era. Nuka, lamu ho pahie mèdha-panyau èu aa'i-aa'i. Kab'ua ra, lamu pabagi hia dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa sèra. Èle na, èu lèpa hari mai sèna ka madhutu Ja'a. Te èèna na, Ama Lamatua b'ala hari mèdha-panyau èu ètu sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like that, Yesus said, “Good! But you-sg are still lacking one thing. Which is, you go.home and sell all your possessions (doublet). Their price/value, go divide out the money to the destitute/poor people. After that, you come back so you follow Me. Cuz (elaboration) Father God will reciprocate giving you possessions in heaven.”</bt><v n="23" />Ropa tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu ne d'ara na susa, te nèngu kaja d'ai seli.<bt>Hearing like.that, then that person's insides were distressed, cuz (elaboration) he was very rich.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa Yesus nèdhi dhèu ne lèpa dènge d'ara na laho mae-mae, hèia Na padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu kaja mema carui titu kèna maso sorga.<bt>When Yesus saw him go with destroyed insides (=broken.hearted), He told His underlings, saying, “It's truly difficult for rich people to enter heaven [Following NLT and TN]</bt><v n="25" />Èdhi pasèku ku dènge j'ara leo. Mema bisa boe badha unta dhu kapai bisa maso asa d'ara oka na re ro'a j'aj'au. Nuka sèmi èèna kahèi, dhèu dhu maena dhoka mèdha-panyau na, te ngaa maena boe Lamatua, tatu nèngu bisa boe maso sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>We-inc can compare it with a different thing. Truly it's impossible for a camel animal which is big to enter his pen through the hole of a needle. It's like that also for the person who only hopes in his possessions (doublet), but doesn't hope in the Lord, surely s/he will not be able to enter heaven.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasèku = 1) cocokkan ukuran, samakan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasèku = 1) cocokkan ukuran, samakan ukuran, 2) banding</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Dhèu dhu tadèngi Yesus padhai lii sèmi sèra, karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu kaja carui maso sorga, dhèu sèmi mia ka dhu bisa abhu mamuri taa-taa?&gt;&gt;<bt>The people who heard Yesus speaking like.that, asked Him, saying, “If it's difficult for rich people to enter heaven, then what kind (categories) of people can be saved/get eternal life?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ka Yesus b'ala si, &lt;&lt;Mi dhèu rai-haha, j'ara ae-ae mema carui. Te ngaa bagi Ama Lamatua, aa'i-aa'i bisa j'aj'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded to them, “For humans, it's true many things are not possible. But for Father God everything can happen/come to be.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia Petrus tuhu lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i tèke eele aa'i mèdha-panyau ji'i, ka mai madhutu Ama. Bèli-camèd'a ji'i abhu ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus connected.his.speach, saying, “Papa! We-exc have gone leaving behind all our possessions to follow Papa. But what will we get?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèke eela = pl object ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">tèke eela = pl object ; tèke eele = singular subject</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Nanene paie-iie. Dhèu dhu tèke eele èmu na, dhèu èmu-kamali na, a'ari na, ina-ama na, do ana-ana na, lula nèngu pakako sasab'a Ama Lamatua,<bt>Yesus replied saying, “Petrus! Listen carefully. The person who leaves behind his house, his spouse, his elder-younger.siblings (=relies), his mother-father (=parents), or his children, because he carries out work/tasks from Father God,</bt><v n="30" />tatu na abhu hari ae risi ètu rai-haha ne. Aa ladhe èle rai-haha ne, nèngu abhu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ama Lamatua kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>surely he will receive back more in this world. And when this world ends, he will also gain eternal life with Father God.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èle ka = su kiamat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">èle ka = su kiamat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mamadhe Na tèlu hari kèna<bt>For the third time the Lord Yesus talks about His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 20:17-19; Markus 10:32-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yesus gale nèti ana madhutu Na canguru dua dhèu sèra, ho lasi padhue-padhai mesa ra. Hèia Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Miu se aa'i-aa'i mi me'a, na, èdhi kako ne, lati asa kota Yerusalem. D'ai nèi, j'ara aa'i-aa'i nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua sèra dhu suri tèke le, lula-nèti Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a, pe j'aj'i nuka sèmi dhu ra suri.<bt>Then Yesus summoned away His twelve underlings to go speak (doublet) alone with them. He told them, saying, “You all know, that, now we-inc are travelling to Yerusalem city. Arriving there (remote), everything which the Lord's spokespersons wrote about that Authentic Human, will happen exactly like what they wrote.</bt><v n="32" />Èèna na, ra soro Ja'a asa dhèu leo dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua. Aa ra padhai lii pamakae Ja'a, pahahe Ja'a rupa-rupa, paru'e ilu ra mi Ja'a,<bt>They will hand Me over to foreigners who don't know/recognise Father God. Then they will mock/scoff at Me, do humiliate/insult Me, spit at Me,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Laz Aplugi says pahaha = merendahkan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Laz Aplugi says pahaha = merendahkan, while pahahe = menghina</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />ra hake kalabhe Ja'a. Èle èèna ka, ra pamadhe Ja'a. Te ngaa asa camèd'a èèna, Ja'a mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>whip/beat Me. After that they will kill Me. But on the day.after.the.tomorrow, I will live again.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa tadèngi Yesus peka sèmi èèna, ana madhutu Na bingu, lula rèngu dhane rare mèka sasoa nèti lii padhai Yesus.<bt>Hearing Yesus' speaking like.that, His underlings were confused, because they could not yet fully comprehend the meaning of what Yesus said.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhane = paham"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhane = paham</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pa'èle dhèu bèdhu ca dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a blind person</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 20:29-34; Markus 10:46-52)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Lod'o Yesus si oe maso kota Jeriko, abhu dhèu bèdhu ca dhèu dhu madhèdi kanata ai ètu sebhe j'ara.<bt>When Yesus (collective) were about to enter into Yeriko city, there was a blind person who sitting begging on the side of the road.</bt><v n="36" />Ropa na tadèngi dhèu ae kako re èèna, ka na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ngaa ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard a great many people passing.by there, he asked, saying, “What's (happening) here?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka dhèu peka dènge ne, na, &lt;&lt;Yesus nèti Nasaret dhu kako re ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then people told him saying, “Yesus from Nasaret is passing by here.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Hèia dhèu bèdhu ne rodhe pamèdhu-mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus! Ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud, ee! Sue ku ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then that blind person yelled.out loudly, saying, “Yesus! Raja Daud's descendant (doublet)! Have love/pity/mercy on me!”</bt><note reference="18:38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud&gt; na, ca ropa dènge &lt;Kristus&gt;, nuka Dhèu dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u le nèti uuru ka mai. Dènge sèmi èèna, dhèu bèdhu ne mangaku na, Yesus na, Kristus.<bt>That phrase ‘Raja Daud's descendant’, is one title for ‘Kristus’ who was the Person whom the Lord designated from long.ago. In that.way, this blind person is acknowledging that Yesus there, was Kristus.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Hèia dhèu dhu kako uuru nèti Yesus kai ne, sèna ka na mau-mau. Te ngaa asa na hino dènge lii rodhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud, ee! Sue ku ja'a laa!&gt;&gt;<bt>People who were walking in front of Yesus scolded him to be quiet. But he yelled out even louder saying, “Ee! Raja Daud's descendant! Have pity on me!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi, ka Na titu. Hèia Na pua dhèu lasi pakako rèti dhèu bèdhu ne. D'ai madha Na, ka Yesus karèi ne,<bt>When Yesus heard that, He stood (=stopped walking). Then he ordered people to go lead that blind person. Arriving in front of Him, then Yesus asked him, saying,</bt><v n="41" />&lt;&lt;Èu neo Ja'a tao ngaa hia èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>“What do you-sg want Me to do for you?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a manèngi sèna ka ja'a bisa kèdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>He replied, “Father! I'm requesting to be able to see.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Yesus b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a. Lula èu lèka na Ja'a bisa pa'èle èu, de èu bisa mèdhi dènge kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus replied to him, saying, “Ok. Because you believe that I can heal you, now you can see.”</bt><v n="43" />Kaca'a laa, musi madha dhèu ne be'a dènge ka. Ka la'e madhutu Yesus dènge koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu ladhe rèdhi ne, koa-kio kolongara Lamatua kahèi.<bt>Suddenly, that person's blind eye(s) were healed right.away. Then he followed Yesus and praised (doublet) the name/reputation of Father God. Everyone who saw him/it, also praised (doublet) the name/reputation of the Lord.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus paraga dènge dhèu roro bea èci, ngara na Sakeos<bt>The Lord Yesus meets a tax collector, named Sakeos</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Ka Yesus si maso re kota Jeriko, ho neo lasi taruu.<bt>Then Yesus (collective) entered into Yeriko city, to continue travelling.</bt><v n="2" />Ètu ne'e, abhu ca dhèu kapala roro bea dhu roro doi hia dhèu paredha Roma. Ngara na Sakeos, aa nèngu ne dhèu kaja.<bt>There, there was a head tax collector who collected money for the Roma government. His name was Sakeos, and he was a rich person.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa na tadèngi Yesus kako re èèna, ka nèngu neo nèdhi. Te ngaa bisa boe nèdhi dènge be'a, lula katitu na bab'a d'ai seli, aa dhèu ae dhu kalibhu rare Yesus.<bt>When he heard Yesus was about to pass by there, then he desired to see [Him]. But he was not able to see [him] well, because he stood too short, and too many people were crowding around Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katitu = ketinggian ; bab'a ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">katitu = ketinggian ; bab'a = pendek ; kalibhu = kelilingi, kerumun</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Nèti èèna ka, na rai uru, ka na ca'e asa kolo aj'u ca kapua ètu sebhe j'ara, dhu Yesus neo re èèna.<bt>That's why he ran on ahead, then climbed up into a tree on the side of the road where Yesus was going to pass.by.</bt><note reference="19:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na, aj'u <span class="Italic">sukomorea.</span> Aj'u ne abhu boe ètu Idhonesia re bèka dhimu.<bt>The Yunani language writing says this tree is sukomorea. This type of tree does not exist in eastern Indonesia.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa d'ai kapua aj'u ne, Yesus ladhe asa dedha. Hèia Na paroa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sakeos! Puru ka! Karohe, te deo ne'e kahèi, Ja'a neo manubha ètu d'ara èmu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving at the base of that tree, Yesus looked up. Then He called out, saying, “Sakeos! Come, on down! Quickly, cuz (elaboration) today I want to stay.over.night at your house.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Sakeos malaa. Hèia na puru pamèri-pamèri, la'e dènge Yesus asa èmu na. D'ara na karej'e-karae.<bt>Sakeos was surprised. Then he came down quickly, and brought Yesus to his house. His insides were very happy (doublet).</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa dhèu ae dhu ka'ugu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hmm! Sakeos ne, dhèu karehe! Nga tao ka Yesus manubha ètu d'ara èmu na?! Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a le!&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were many people who grumbled, saying, “Hmm! This Sakeos here, is a bad person! Why is Yesus going to stay over at his house?! Everyone knows that [+obviously]!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />D'ai d'ara èmu, Sakeos titu ètu madha Yesus, ka lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Nèti deo ne'e ne, ja'a bagi mèdha-panyau ja'a mi dua, capala hia mi dhèu dhu dènge boe ngaa-ngaa. Ladhe ja'a roro bea parisi, ja'a b'ae hari mi rèngu èpa kali lipat.&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving at the house, Sakeos stood in front of Yesus, and spoke saying, “Father Teacher! From today I will divide all my possessions in two, to give one part to the poor people. If I ever collected excessive tax, I will pay it back to them four times over.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Yesus b'ala ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a. Deo ne'e kahèi, Ama Lamatua pala-bagi sod'a-mole mi èu dènge isi èmu èu aa'i-aa'i, lula èu parcaya Lamatua kahèi, nuka sèmi baki Abraham.<bt>Then Yesus reponded, saying, “Good. This day Father God has saved you-sg and all your household, because you believe in the Lord like grandfather Abraham.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK: what is like Abraham?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">CHECK: what is like Abraham?</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Te Ama Lamatua pua Ja'a mai j'aj'i Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ètu rai-haha ne. Mamai Ja'a ne, sèna ka tenge dhèu dhu sero nèti j'ara Lamatua, ho hia si sod'a-mole.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Father God is the one who commissioned/sent Me to be the Authentic Human in this world. I came to seek people who have strayed/ deviated from the Lord's path, in.order.to save them/give them life.”</bt><note reference="19:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame nèti ènu dhu pab'unge doi-dhari lamatua na<bt>Story about the slave/lowly servant who carefully manages his master's money (doublet)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juru = uang emas. ; pabunge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">juru = uang emas. ; pabunge = dapa bunga, perbungakan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 25:14-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae nanene lii padhai Yesus. Rèngu oe dètu dènge kota Yerusalem. Rèngu pangee, na, Yesus neo pakako paredha Ama Lamatua ètu èèna, nuka sèmi dhèu aae. Hèia Yesus lolo dènge si lii pakasame èci.<bt>At that time, there were many people who were following listening to Yesus. They were nearing Yerusalem city. They also supposed He wanted to carry out Father God's rule there, like a raja. Then Yesus told them another comparison.story.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neo la'a = sangka (check w/UNS)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">neo la'a = sangka (check w/UNS)</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu kapai èci. Neo la'e asa rai kaj'èu, ho dhèu ded'e ne j'aj'i dhèu aae ètu nèi. Ladhe èle, nèngu neo lèpa hari mai ho j'aj'i dhèu aae ètu d'ara kabarai na.<bt>He said, “There was a big/important person. He wanted/ was.about.to leave to go to a far away land/country, so people could install him to be king there (remote). After that, then he would come back again to be king in his (own) country.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="go to a far away province"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">go to a far away province ; SUGGESTION: neo lèpa hari mai ho j'aj'i dhèu aae ètu dara kabarai na.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eugeneis: high status, important, possibly of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eugeneis: high status, important, possibly of noble birth</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Lod'o nèngu pa'èra neo pakèd'i, paroa nare dhèu sab'a na canguru dhèu, ka na bagi hia si ca dhèu, juru cue.<bt>When he was ready to travel, he called his ten workers, and gave each one of them one gold coin.</bt><note reference="19:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na, nèngu hia &lt;canguru <span class="Italic">mina</span>.&gt; <span class="Italic">Mina</span> èci kab'ua na cangasu <span class="Italic">dinari,</span> nuka sèmi gaji tuka d'ara cangasu lod'o sasab'a.<bt>The Yunani language writing says he gave them, ‘10 mina’. One mina is worth 100 dinari, or one worker's wage for 100 days' work.</bt></note>Na paredha si, peka na, &lt;Miu pake doi se j'aj'i mi poko. Te lod'o d'ai ja'a lèpa, miu hud'i peka ku leto na ca ngaa.&gt; Èle èèna ka, na pakèd'i.<bt>He commanded them, saying, ‘You-pl use this money as seed.money. Cuz (elaboration) later when I come.home, you report how much you have gained.’ Then he left. [NOTE to daughter translations: it needs to be clear that the ten mina are one to each servant (see vs.16)]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juru ; poko = modal ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">juru ; poko = modal ; leto = oto, untung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa kabarai na d'èi boe ne. Ka ra hia dhèu lasi peka, na, &lt;Ji'i ngo'o boe dhèu ne paredha ji'i.&gt;<bt>But his populace/people didn't like him. And they sent a envoy over there to tell, saying, ‘We don't want this person to rule us.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, ra ded'e ne j'aj'i dhèu aae. Hèia na lèpa hari ka. D'ai èmu na, ka na paroa dhèu sab'a na, dhèu canguru sèra, ka karèi si, peka na, &lt;Miu se leto ca ngaa nèti juru dhu ja'a hia miu sèra?&gt;<bt>Even that being the case, they installed him as king. Then he came.home. Arriving at his house, then he called those ten workers, and asked them, saying, ‘How much have you gained from that gold money which I gave to you?’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Dhèu sab'a dhu uru, peka na, &lt;Ama dhèu aae! Ja'a leto juru canguru bua nèti poko dhu ja'a abhu!&gt;<bt>The first worker said, “Father king! I have profited ten times from that seed.money which I received!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juru = gold sovereign"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">juru = gold sovereign</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka dhèu aae peka dènge ne, &lt;Be'a! Èu ne dhèu sab'a dhu maj'èni. Lula ja'a bisa lèka èu nèti j'ara dhu ana iiki, nèti èèna ka karèi nèti deo ne'e, ja'a ded'e èu ho paredha canguru kota.&gt;<bt>Then the king told him, saying, ‘Good! You here are a good/diligent worker. Because I can trust you with small things, that's why now I am raising you up to rule ten cities.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Èle ka dhèu sab'a ka dua, peka na, &lt;Ama dhèu aae! Ja'a abhu leto juru lèmi bua nèti poko dhu ja'a sèmi.&gt;<bt>Next, worker number two said, ‘Father king! I have profited five gold coins from that seed.money which I received.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka dhèu aae peka, na, &lt;Be'a! Ladhe sèmi èèna, ja'a ded'e èu ho paredha lèmi kota.&gt;<bt>So that king said, ‘Good! If that's the case, I raise you up to rule five cities.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Krèi artinya: Kalau begitu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Krèi artinya: Kalau begitu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a ka tèlu nèti hari juru na. Ka na peka, &lt;Doi ama ka ne'e! Ja'a rapi ka pahuni ne, mage ele.<bt>But worker number three brought back his coin. Then he said, ‘Here is father's money! I wrapped it up and hid it so it wouldn't disappear.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rapi = bungkus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">rapi = bungkus</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ja'a tao sèmi èèna, lula madha'u. Ja'a ke'a ama, dhèu nasa. Te ama d'èi more ngaa dhu unu boe ama, aa d'èi puu hua dhu ama sèle boe!&gt;<bt>I did like.that, because I am/was afraid. I know that father here is a hard/angry person. Cuz (elaboration) father likes to take what is not father's, and likes to pick/harvest produce that father did not plant!’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa dhèu aae tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka na jèke ne, &lt;Èu ne, dhèu goa d'ara! Lii padhai èu ne pabia ngi'u èu mesa mu. Èu me'a, na, ja'a dhèu nasa, ho kore ngaa dhu unu boe ja'a, aa puu ngaa dhu ja'a sèle boe.<bt>When the king heard like.that, he scolded him, saying, ‘You here don't know manners (idiom)! Your own words have judged/ punished you yourself. You know that I here am an angry person, who takes what is not mine, and harvests what I have not planted.</bt><v n="23" />De ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka lamu boe tèke ne asa bank? Ho sèna ka lod'o ja'a lèpa, ja'a bisa abhu leto. Masi ka ciki di.&gt;<bt>So (consequently) if that's the case, why didn't you go store this money in the bank? So that when I came home, I could get the interest. Even a little.bit (would be ok).’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Rapi artinya: Di bungkus."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Rapi artinya: Di bungkus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Hèia dhèu aae ne pua dhèu leo ètu sèra, peka na, &lt;Mere doi nèngu ne, sèna ka hia mi dhèu sab'a dhu abhu leto canguru deo na.&gt;<bt>Then that king ordered other people there, saying, ‘Take that money of his, and hand it over to that earlier worker who got ten profit.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa ra pasisu, peka na, &lt;Ama! Dhèu ne abhu ae le. Nga tao ka neo more nèti dhèu dhu unu ciki, ho patabha sa nèngu hari?&gt;<bt>But they protested, saying, ‘Father! That person has enough. Why do you want to take it from a person who has only a little.bit, to add even more to him?’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Te ngaa dhèu aae b'ala, peka na, &lt;Pangee paie-iie ku! Ladhe dhèu dhu mèu uri ngaa dhu dhèu hia ne, èèna na nèngu abhu tabha hari. Te ngaa dhèu dhu bai-eed'a, èèna na rare aa'i ngaa dhu na unu.<bt>But that king answered saying, ‘Think well! If a person who is skilled in managing what people have given/entrusted to him, later he will obtain even more. But the person who is lazy (in managing), later they will take away everything that he has/owns.</bt><note reference="19:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 13:12, Markus 4:25, Lukas 8:18</note><v n="27" />De lami kèpe mere musu ja'a, dhu ro'o boe ja'a j'aj'i dhèu aae. Mèti si mai sa ne'e, sèna ka pamadhe si ètu madha ja'a. Lami ka!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) you-pl go capture/arrest my enemies who don't like me being king. Bring them here, then kill all of them in front of me. Go now!’”</bt><note reference="19:11-27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 25:14-30</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus maso asa d'ara kota Yerusalem<bt>The Lord Yesus enters into Yerusalem city</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:1-11; Markus 11:1-11; Yohanis 12:12-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa Yesus lolo èle, hèia lasi taruu ka asa Yerusalem. Yesus dhu kako uru.<bt>Yesus finished telling the story then, they travelled on to Yerusalem. Yesus was walking in front.</bt><v n="29" />Ropa oe dètu dènge dua rae, nuka Betfage dènge Betania, dhu ètu karasa ledhe Saitun, ka Na pua ana madhutu Na dhèu dua lasi uru.<bt>When nearing two villages, that is Betfage and Betania, which were on the slope of Saitun mountain, then He ordered two of His underlings to go on ahead.</bt><v n="30" />Na pua si peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu dua mi lami asa rae dhu ètu madha nèi. Pe miu mèdhi keled'ei ngèru ci'u dhu èki tèke ètu èèna. Keled'ei ne, dhèu manya'e rèdhi mèka. Mi lècu dhari na, pakako mèti mai.<bt>He commanded them, saying, “You two go to that village in front there. You will see a young donkey tied there. A person has not yet ridden it. You open/untie it's rope to pull bring it here.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lècu = buka ikatan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">lècu = buka ikatan</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu karèi, &lt;Tasamia ka mi lècu eele dhari keled'ei èèna?&gt; Mi peka dènge si, na, &lt;Lamatua ji'i neo pake ne.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But if anyone asks, ‘Why are you untying that donkey's rope?’, Tell them, saying, ‘Our-exc Lord wants to use it.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Dua ra lasi ka, hèia ra rage keled'ei ngèru nuka sèmi dhu Yesus peka.<bt>The two of them went, and encountered that young donkey just like Yesus' speaking.</bt><v n="33" />Ropa ra lècu dhari keled'ei ne, ka lamatua badha ne karèi si, na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu patabuli badha ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were undoing that donkey's rope, the master/owner(s) of the animal asked them, saying, “Why are you releasing this animal?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua ji'i neo pake ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they answered, saying, “Our-exc Lord wants to use it.”</bt><v n="35" />Lamatua badha ne d'èi kahèi, ka dua ra nuni rèti keled'ei asa Yesus. Ra hèle sig'i-kalolo ra mi dedha kabodho keled'ei ne. Èle èèna ka, ra paca'e Yesus asa dedha na.<bt>That animal owner(s) agreed, then the two of them pulled/led that donkey offspring to Yesus. They opened their blankets/ male.sarongs on that donkey offspring's back. Then they mounted Yesus on top.</bt><note reference="19:35" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu nèi, dhèu aae-dhèu kapai manya'e jara, dhèu haha manya'e keled'ei. De Lamatua Yesus ca'e keled'ei ne, j'aj'i mi tadha Na pahaha iisi. Ètu <span class="Italic">Sakaria</span> 9:9, abhu kahèi lii padhadha dhu peka na, bèli-camèd'a dhèu aae Isra'el mai ca'e keled'ei.<bt>There (remote), big/important people ride horses, but small/unimportant people ride donkeys. So (consequently) the Lord Yesus getting on that donkey, became a sign that he humbled himself. In Sakarias 9:9 there is also a promise that says the king of the Isra'el people was going to come riding on a donkey.</bt></note><v n="36" />Dhèu ae kahèi hèle sig'i-kalolo dènge salalu ra mi j'ara, ho soru Yesus nuka sèmi soru dhèu kapai.<bt>Many people also took their blankets/ male.clothes and their (female) shawls, and opened them on the road, to welcome Yesus like they were recieving a big/important person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="salalu = selendang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">salalu = selendang</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Ropa Na puru nèti ledhe Saitun, ka dhèu se dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, mulai pa'oo koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula rèngu rèdhi le tadha-tadha koasa.<bt>When He started to descend from Saitun mountain, then those many people and His underlings began to call out praises (doublet) to the name/reputation of Father God, because of all those (various) signs of power which they had seen. [EXEG: ‘signs of power’ here, not miracles.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eerksanto ... khairontes ainein: this is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eerksanto ... khairontes ainein: this is outward behavior manifested by yelling and whooping it up</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Ra pa'oo peka na,<bt>They yelled out, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, Dhèu Aae dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai!<bt>He here, is the King whom Father God commissioned/sent to come!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ama Lamatua hia Ne berkat!<bt>The Father God gives Him blessing!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Dhèu rai-haha limuri ne, bisa padame le dènge Lamatua ètu sorga.<bt>Now humans can be in mutual.peace with the Lord in heaven.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua dhu madhèdi nèd'u paredha ètu dedha-liru dhu dedha risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Praise (doublet) the name/reputation of the Lord who sits ruling in the very highest sky.”</bt><note reference="19:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:26</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu-dhèu Parisi ètu talora aae dhèu ae sèra. Ka ra peka dènge Yesus, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Kai ku dhèu se, ho baku ra pakii-pakèce sèmi ne'e, te seli-kolane!&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were also some Parisi people in the midst of the crowd. They reported to Yesus, “Father Teacher! Scold/Rebuke them so they don't yell (doublet) like.that, cuz (elaboration) this is just too much!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakii-pakèce = berteriak yg sonde ada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pakii-pakèce = berteriak yg sonde ada pung atoran (shrill)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pasanèd'e mema! Ladhe dhèu se'e kutu hèb'a ra, èèna na, hadhu se ka dhu koa-kio kolongara Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, “I'm telling/ reminding you! If these people shut their mouths, then these rocks will be the ones who praise (doublet) the name/reputation of the Lord!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kutu hèb'a = silent ; hutu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kutu hèb'a = silent ; hutu hèb'a =cover their mouths (with hand)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus tangi lula tatao dhèu Yerusalem<bt>The Lord Yesus cries for Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ropa rèngu oe dètu Yerusalem, Yesus ladhe nèdhi kota ne, hèia Na tangi,<bt>When they were nearing Yerusalem, Yesus saw that city, and He cried/wept.</bt><v n="42" />peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Dhèu Yerusalem, ee! Dad'èi Ja'a deo ne'e, miu abhu dame dhu Ja'a kèti mai. Te ngaa lula miu pahae boe Lamatua, ka miu unu heka. Dame ne pakaj'èu le nèti miu.<bt>He said, “Iraii [+regret]! Yerusalem people, ee! I want so.that today you get/obtain the peace which I bring. But because you don't care about the Lord, now it's your own (responsibility). That peace is already far from you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="if: There's no &quot;then&quot; clause, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">if: There's no "then" clause, and the implication is a wish that cannot be fulfulled. ta pros eireeneen: the things that bring about peace (inner peace? freedom from strife? peace with God?) NEB "the way that leads to peace", TEV "what is needed for peace." UBS prefers reconciliation to God; in commenting on 1:79 negative as lack of strife between persons and absence of war, positive as fulness of well-being resting on confidence in God. There's also outward peace (from war, peace with God) and inner peace (like John 14:1, which doesn't use the word) to choose here. Stick with "stay good wit God".<span class="Italic">(42)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Bèli-camèd'a musu miu mai udhu padedha rai palème li'u tedhe miu ne, hèia ra maso sa d'ara, musu dènge miu.<bt>Later your enemies will heap up dirt around your city's walls, then they will enter and attack you. [EXEG: dirt embankment. LN, Also “rampart” sense #1; HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="reo = keliling ; li'u ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">reo = keliling ; li'u = di luar</Message></Annotation><v n="44" />Ra dhedhe palaho kota miu, toke pamera dènge rai, hèia ra pamadhe aa'i miu dènge ana-ana mi. Ra tèke eele boe hadhu cue sa dhu titu, lula miu mo'o boe tadhe Lamatua lod'o Na mai hia miu mamuri!&gt;&gt;<bt>They will knock.down your city flat to the ground, then murder you-pl and all your children. They will not leave one stone standing, because you do not want to know/recognize the Lord when He comes wanting to save you!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus maso asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>The Lord Yesus enters into the Central Worship House</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:12-17; Markus 11:15-19; Yohanis 2:13-22)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus maso asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ètu madha èmu ne, dhèu tao sèmi pasa sa, ho ra pahia badha korban. Ropa nèdhi, hèia Yesus babège si nèti era èèna.<bt>After that, Yesus entered into the Central Worship House. In that house's yard, people had made it like a market in.order to sell sacrifice animals. When He saw that, Yesus was expelling them out from there.</bt><v n="46" />Ka Na jèke si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu suri tèke le, peka na,<bt>He spoke angrily, saying, “The Lord's spokesperson has written in.advance, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ja'a patitu Èmu ne,<bt>&lt;I build this House,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa mai manèngi-mangaj'i ètu era ne'e.&gt;<bt>so that all people can come worship (doublet) in this place.’</bt><note reference="19:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 56:7, Yermia 7:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa mi tao ne nuka sèmi era pakaboko dhèu parapo.&gt;&gt;<bt>But you have made it become a robbers' gathering place.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Èle èèna ka, bèli-bèli Yesus la'e aj'a-nori dhèu ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Te ngaa kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama, dènge dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi sèra, patangi-tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Ne.<bt>After that, every day Yesus went to the Central Worship House to teach there. But the *chief priests, the religion teachers and the traditional Yahudi elders kept looking for a way to murder Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patangi-tenge = kept trying (probably unsuccessfully)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">patangi-tenge = kept trying (probably unsuccessfully) ; patangi = kasi manangis</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:47" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 21:37</note><v n="48" />Te ngaa ra abhu boe j'ara, lula dhèu ae dhu d'èi titu kèna, nanene lii padhai Yesus.<bt>But they did not find a way, because many people were very happy listening to Yesus' speaking.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pakarèi hak dènge koasa Yesus<bt>They debate Yesus' power/authority and rights</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:23-27; Markus 11:27-33)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, Yesus la'e asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ka Na aj'a-nori Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua ètu èèna. Hèia kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama, dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi sèra, mai karèi Ne.<bt>One day, Yesus went to the Central Worship House then taught (doublet) the Lord's Good New there. Then the *chief priests, the teachers of religion, and the traditional elders came and questioned Him.</bt><v n="2" />Ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Mu peka ku laa! Cee ka dhu hia Èu hak sèna ka ad'u-ue maruru ètu ne'e med'a na?&gt;&gt;<bt>They said, “Who gave You the right to make everything chaotic here yesterday/the other day? Tell us! [NOTE to daughter translations: /yesterday/ here is in the broad sense, not the narrow sense.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Yesus b'ala si, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo karèi miu ca madha j'ara kahèi, heka Ja'a dhaa lii karèi miu kèna.<bt>Then Yesus replied saying, “I also want to ask one thing, only.then I will answer your-pl question.</bt><v n="4" />Sèmi ne'e: miu se tadhe Yohanis tuka sarani dhèu, do? Cee ka dhu hia ne koasa ho sarani dhèu? Ama Lamatua do, dhèu rai-haha?&gt;&gt;<bt>It's like this: you know Yohanis the habitual baptizer, right? Who gave him power/authority to baptise people? Father God, or humans?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia ra papeka èci dènge èci, &lt;&lt;Ira ee! Èdhi sèmi tare le pala ti ngaa. Ladhe èdhi peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua ka pua&gt;, èèna Na b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka miu lèka boe Yohanis?&gt;<bt>Then they discussed it with each other, “Ira ee! We-inc are caught now (idiom). If we say ‘Father God is the one who told.him.to.do it’, then He will reply, saying, ‘If that's the case, why don't you believe in Yohanis then?’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èdhi sèmi tare le pala ti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Èdhi sèmi tare le pala ti ngaa = kotong su tarima kotong pung bagian ~</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi dhaa, peka na, &lt;dhèu rai-haha ka pua&gt;, na dhèu ae sèra pèci pamadhe èdhi. Te dhèu sèra parcaya, na, Yohanis ne dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if we respond, saying, ‘humans told.him.to.do it’, then these crowds will stone us to death. Cuz (elaboration) these people believe that Yohanis there, was Father God's spokesperson.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i nge'a boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>So the replied, saying, “We-exc don't know.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, Ja'a ko'o boe peka kahèi, cee ka dhu pua Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told them, “If that's the case, I also don't want to say who it was that ordered/told Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame dhèu sab'a oka anggor<bt>Comparison story of the grape garden workers</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:33-46; Markus 12:1-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Yesus lolo dènge dhèu ae sèra, pake lii pakasame, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu èci dhu sèle anggor ètu d'ara oka na. Na hia dhèu seb'a oka anggor ne, sèna ka rèngu pabagi isi rai nèti oka-tedhe ne. Ka na pidha la'e pea panèbhu asa rai kaj'èu.<bt>Then Yesus story-ed to those many people, using another comparison.story, saying, “There was a person who planted a grape garden. He rented that garden out to workers so that they could divide out the harvest. Then he moved to a far country to stay there for a long time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seb'a = sewa ; osa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">seb'a = sewa ; osa = hasil (kerja dari laut, makan meting) ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="20:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 5:1</note><v n="10" />D'ai hèru puu-g'ètu, hèia lamatua oka anggor ne pua ana paleha na ca dhèu, la'e nare pala nèngu. Te ngaa dhèu sab'a oka anggor se, game ana paleha ne, ka ra hia ne lèpa dènge ai hua.<bt>When it came harvest (doublet) season, that grape garden master/owner ordered one of his servants to go get his share. But those grape garden workers beat up that servant, then they sent him home with empty hands (=purpose not accomplished).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai hua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ai hua</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, lamatua oka ne pua ana paleha na ca dhèu hari. Te ngaa dhèu sab'a oka se game, ka ra pamakae ne. Hèia ra babège ne lèpa dènge ai hua da'u-da'u.<bt>After that, that garden master/owner sent another of his servants. But those garden workers beat him up, and shamed/embarrased him. Then they chased him away to go.home with empty hands2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="da'u-da'u = adv for ai hua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">da'u-da'u = adv for ai hua</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, lamatua oka ne pua hari ana paleha na ka tèlu, te ngaa ra game ne, toke diu raa, ka ra core ne asa li'u oka.<bt>After that, the garden master sent again his third servant, but they beat him up to the point of bleeding wounds, then they threw him out of the garden.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia lamatua oka ne pangee ka, &lt;Ja'a tao hari ku tasamia? Be'a risi ja'a pua ana pasue ja'a ka la'e. Ele boe ra pakab'ua ne, de ra sèmi ne dènge be'a.&gt; De na pua ana d'èlu na la'e.<bt>That garden master thought about it, saying, ‘What else should I do? It's better I just send my beloved child to go. Surely they will respect him and receive him well.’ So he sent his own/birth child there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu sab'a oka anggor se ladhe rèdhi ne, hèia ra papeka èci dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;Mi ladhe ku laa! Te lamatua oka ne hia ana d'èlu na nuka mai nèi. Nèngu ne ka dhu bèli-camèd'a unu pusaka ama na aa'i-aa'i ra. De ta pamadhe ne! Sèna ka èdhi ka dhu unu oka anggor ne.&gt;<bt>But when those garden workers saw him, then they spoke.with.each.other, saying, ‘Look at that! Cuz (elaboration) the old.man has sent his own child coming yonder. He is the one who will receive all the father's inheritance. So (consequently), let's kill him! So, that we are the ones who own/possess this garden.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta = ti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ta = ti</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Ropa ana ne d'ai, hèia dhèu se nuni pa'oro ne rèti asa li'u oka, ka ra pamadhe ne.<bt>When that child arrived, then they dragged him along.the.ground out of that garden, then they killed him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De Ja'a neo karèi miu sèmi ne'e: miu pangee, na, lamatua oka ne tao dhèu sab'a oka sèra tasamia?<bt>So (consequently) [+shift to implications], I want to ask like.this: what do you think that garden master should do with those workers?</bt><v n="16" />Madhutu a'abhu Ja'a, tatu na mai pamadhe aa'i si, ka na hia hari dhèu leo seb'a oka ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>According to Me, surely he will come and kill them all, then rent that garden out to other people.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa dhèu se tadèngi lii padhai Yesus, rèngu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe bisa, na, ji'i baku abhu huku nèti Ama Lamatua sèmi èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>When those people heard Yesus speak like.that, then they said, “If possible/Hopefully Father God won't punish us like that!” [EXEG: explication of “heaven forbid”. Most complete discussion in TN. Marshall points out “The remark may be taken as expressing horror at the reaction of the owner or at the whole course of events; in either case the application of the story to the Jewish leaders is in mind.” Realisation is in vs. 19. Green says “the answer is self-evident. Surely the destruction of Jerusalem marks the obliteration of Israel as well! But this misses the careful distinction drawn in the parable between vineyard and tenants, and thus between Israel and its leaders.”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Yesus laladhe patae si, ka Na karèi, &lt;&lt;Ladhe huku boe si sèmi èèna, nga tao ka dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua suri, na:<bt>Then Yesus looked sternly at them, and asked them, “If it doesn't happen that [He] sends punishment like that, then why did the Lord's spokesperson write saying like.this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Hadhu cue dhu tuka hadhu core eele le,<bt>‘There was a stone which the craftsmen threw out/discarded,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa limuri ne dhu j'aj'i le era padhèdi agarii talora?&gt;<bt>but now it has become the main pole's foundation stone?’</bt><note reference="20:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:22</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dhèu dhu kadhunu lèke hadhu ne, nèngu tatu laho teb'o-teb'o, lula abhu huku. Aa ladhe hadhu ne bèbhe lèke dhèu cee, nèngu laho kao-kao, lula lèke huku.&gt;&gt;<bt>The person who trips.over that stone, surely will destroyed, because of obtaining punishment. And if that stone falls on a person, he also will be completely destroyed, because of obtaining punishment.” [EXEG: punishment from Marshall, MC]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadhunu = stub foot on s.t.,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kadhunu = stub foot on s.t., terantuk ; laho teb'o-teb'o = ancor-ancor (young UNS don't know teb'o-teb'o)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ropa mese agama dènge kètu agama Yahudi se tadèngi lii lolo ne, rèngu re'a, na, Yesus padhai lii padhèto dènge rèngu pake lii pakasame. Rèngu se cakaraa dènge dhèu seb'a oka anggor deo sa. De ra nasa titu kèna. Ka ra tenge j'ara ho neo kèpe Ne. Te ngaa rèngu madha'u dènge dhèu ae sèra, dhu d'èi nanene lii aj'a Yesus. Ka lasi tèke eele Ne.<bt>When the religion teachers and the chief priests heard that story, they knew that Yesus was targeting them using that comparison story. They were exactly like those garden workers. So they got very angry. So they looked for a way to arrest Him. But they were hesitant/afraid of the many people who liked Yesus' teaching. Then/so they went off leaving Him behind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèto = maen karitik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">padhèto = maen karitik</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Hia mi Ama Lamatua ngaa dhu j'aj'i mi hak Nèngu&gt;&gt;<bt>“Give Father God what is His right”</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 22:15-22; Markus 12:13-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle ka, musu-musu Yesus ma'u Ne. Rèngu tenge dhèu j'aj'i mata-mata dhu bisa tao iisi ra sèmi dhèu mola, sèna ka ra kèpe Ne. Rèngu sanao sèna ka Yesus padhai lii dhu palab'a dènge dhèu paredha Roma, ho èèna na lasi peka dènge gubernur, sèna ka ra pua dhèu lasi kèpe Yesus.<bt>After that, Yesus' enemies were angry (?_mama'u) at Him. They sought people to be spies who could make themselves like straight/ righteous/devout people, so they could catch Him. They hoped Yesus would speak against the Roma government, and.then they wanted to go report to the governor so that they would order people to go capture/arrest Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ma'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ma'u</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Ka ra pua mata-mata, sèna ka pakarèi dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ji'i nge'a Ama ca dhèu dhu d'ara mola. Ama me'a boe kapod'e-kabèli, aa hag'e boe dhèu. Ama aj'a-nori dhèu madhutu Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua dènge mola.<bt>So they sent spies to go debate with Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher! We-exc know that Father's liver is straight (=righteous/just/honest). Father doesn't twist-turn (=decieve), and doesn't choose faces (=discriminate). Father (=you) always teaches Father God's Words straight/correctly.</bt><v n="22" />De ji'i neo karèi ca j'ara: madhutu atora agama èdhi dhèu Yahudi, hud'i ji'i b'ae ku doi bea mi dhèu aae kapai paredha Roma, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) we-exc want to ask one thing: according to our-inc Yahudi religious regulations, must we-inc pay tax to the Roma government's big king, or not?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ftn? @@@ Yahudi people hated the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ftn? @@@ Yahudi people hated the Roman govt. Yahudi regs say pay tax to the temple</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa Yesus ne'a le ngangee kaj'alu rèngu ho neo pamanahu Ne. Ka Na dhaa, aku Nèngu na,<bt>But Yesus knew their evil2 intent to try to bring Him down. So He replied, saying,</bt><v n="24" />&lt;&lt;Pad'elo sèku Ja'a doi iia cue.&gt;&gt; Hèia ra pad'elo dènge Ne doi èci. Ka Yesus karèi si, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, rupa cee ka ne? Aa ngara cee, ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>“Show Me a silver money.” Then they showed that money to Him. And He asked them, “This here, whose picture/form is this? And this here, whose name?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èèna, dhèu aae kapai, Keser.&gt;&gt;<bt>They replied, saying, “That is the big raja, Keser.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, hia asa dhèu paredha, ngaa dhu unu rèngu. Aa hia mi Ama Lamatua ngaa dhu j'aj'i hak Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus said, “If that the case, na, give to the government what belongs to the government. And give to Father God what Father God has rights.to.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, dhèu se malaa, lula rèngu bisa boe sii pamanahu rare Ne ètu madha dhèu ae. Ka hèb'a ra kutu mèno.<bt>Hearing like.that, they were amazed because they could not bring Him down (successfully) in front of many people. So they shut their mouths.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sii = hiki ; kutu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">sii = hiki ; kutu = tutup, (jahit sampe tertutup)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus aj'a lula-nèti mamuri hari nèti mamadhe<bt>The Lord Yesus teaches about living again from death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 22:23-33; Markus 12:18-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle èèna ka, pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Saduki mai ho neo kèpe Yesus. Dhèu Saduki aj'a, na, dhèu madhe mamuri heka ètu lod'o èle rai-haha ne. Rèngu mai pakarèi dènge Yesus, na,<bt>After that, there were several people from the Saduki religious party who wanted to catch Yesus. Saduki people teach that, dead people don't live again at the end of the world. They came to debate with Yesus, saying,</bt><note reference="20:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 23:8</note><v n="28" />&lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Atora Musa dhu suri tèke hia èdhi, peka na: ladhe dhèu mone madhe, aa dhu dènge mèka kolo, na, ari nèti dhèu madhe ne madhèdi nare hari bhèni balu ne, sèna ka abhu kolo hia a'a dhu madhe ne.<bt>“Father Teacher! Musa's regulations that he has written leaving behind for us-inc, says: if a male dies, but doesn't leave behind a child/descendants, na, his younger.sibling must marry his widow, in.order.to give a descendant to that elder.brother of his who is dead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhèdi nare hari = kawin ame"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">madhèdi nare hari = kawin ame lai ; gati madha a'a = pengganti kakak</Message></Annotation><note reference="20:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 25:5</note><v n="29" />Mema uru èèna baki Musa aj'a sèmi èèna ka. Te ngaa ji'i neo karèi sèmi ne'e: ana mone dhèu pidhu dhu pa'a'ari. Dhu uru leo-èmu, te ngaa madhe dènge boe ana.<bt>Certainly grandfather Musa taught like that previously. But now we-exc want to ask like this: there were seven male siblings. The eldest married, but died and did not leave behind a child.</bt><v n="30" />Hèia ari na todhe nare hari bhèni balu ne. Nèbhu boe ka, na madhe, dhu dènge mèka kolo kahèi.<bt>Then the younger sibling who followed him married that widow. Not long, and he died, but didn't leave behind a child either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="todhe = ame (kawin)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">todhe = ame (kawin)</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge ana ka tèlu. Na leo dènge bhèni balu ne, te ngaa madhe kahèi dènge boe ana. Toke ari ra limuri tèka, madhe kahèi dènge boe kolo.<bt>Similarly with child number three. He married that widow, but he died without leaving behind a child. Until the youngest sibling also died, without leaving a child.</bt><v n="32" />Hèia bhèni balu ne madhe.<bt>Then that widow woman also died.</bt><v n="33" />De ji'i neo karèi Ama sèmi ne'e: bhèni ne leo nèdhi le dènge ana mone dhèu pidhu sèra. Ladhe d'ai èle rai-haha ne, ho Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe sèra, bhèni ne j'aj'i mi dhèu èmu cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) we want to ask Father (=you) like.this: that woman had married those seven males. When the world ends, and the Lords makes the dead people live again, that woman will be whose wife?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhodhoka paleo èmu ètu rai-haha ne di.<bt>Then Yesus responded to them, saying, “Humans mutually.marry only on this earth.</bt><v n="35-36" />Te ngaa ètu sorga dhèu paleo boe èmu. Aa ètu era nèi, dhèu madhe heka. Rèngu èci èèna ka dènge ana pajuu nèti Ama Lamatua ètu sorga. Te, lod'o Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe, Na hag'e nare si, sèna ka j'aj'i mi ana Na.<bt>But later in heaven people will no longer mutually.marry. And there (remote) they will no longer die. They will be like Father God's underlings in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) when Father God makes the dead people live again, He will/has selected them (out from among a group) to be/become HIs children.</bt><v n="37" />Ètu d'ara sasuri baki Musa, dhu lole aj'u iiki ca kapua dhu ai na'e, te ngaa kèpu boe. Nèti lii lolo ne, èdhi te'a, na, dhèu madhe bisa mamuri hari. Ètu èèna, Ama Lamatua peka dènge Musa, na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua nèti baki èu dhu uru-uru sèra. Nuka baki Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob. Rèngu se mangaj'i taa-taa mi Ja'a toke d'ai sange ne'e ne.&gt;<bt>In grandfather Musa's writing there is a story about a little tree that was on.fire but didn't get burn.up. From that story we-inc know that dead people can live again. There Father God told Musa saying, “I here, am your-sg grandfathers' Father God. That is grandfather Abraham, Isak, and Yakob. They all continually worship Me until now.’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aj'u iiki 1 = small tree"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">aj'u iiki 1 = small tree ; aj'u iiki 2 = the part of the backstrap loom that has the threads attached to lift up and separate from the others ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="20:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 3:6</note><v n="38" />Masi ka baki mu se madhe karèi jahi ali. Te ngaa, lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu peka na, Nèngu j'aj'i mi Lamatua rèngu era, de èdhi te'a le, na, rèngu se mamuri era. De masi ka dhèu madhe le, te ngaa ra mamuri hari. Te dhoka dhèu dhu mamuri di, dhu pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua; dhèu madhe, aad'o si!&gt;&gt;<bt>In actual.fact those grandfathers had already been dead a long time. But because Father God said He was still their Lord, that's why we know that they were living. So (consequently) even though people have died, nevertheless they will live again. Cuz (elaboration) only living people are the ones who worship Father God, not dead people, right!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jahi ali = su lama sekali,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">jahi ali = su lama sekali, waktu yg tidak diketahui</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Jahi ali artinya : Dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Jahi ali artinya : Dari zaman Yesus.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pantes gar autooi zoosin: in relationship"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">pantes gar autooi zoosin: in relationship to God they are all alive</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Tadèngi Yesus dhaa sèmi èèna, ka mese agama padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lii dhaa Ama Mese èèna, lèke kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing Yesus answer like.that, then a/some religon teacher spoke, saying, “Father Teacher's answer there, is very true.”</bt><v n="40" />Nèti lod'o èèna, abhu heka ca dhèu sa dhu bani karèi Yesus, lula abhu boe j'ara dhu bisa pamanahu rare Ne.<bt>From that time, there was not one person who dared ask anything more to Yesus, because there was no one who could bring Him down (successfully).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kristus mema ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud, aa j'aj'i Lamatua nèngu kahèi<bt>The Kristus is truly king Daud's descendant, and is also his Master</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 22:41-46; Markus 12:35-37)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Yesus aj'a-nori dhèu ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i era. Ka Na karèi dhèu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu a'abhu miu, tasamia? Mese agama sèra, aj'a peka na, Kristus èèna, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u karèi nèti uru-uru ka. Madhutu a'aj'a rèngu, Nèngu ne dhodhoka ana-èpu dhèu aae Daud di. Te ngaa èèna dhae d'ai mèka.<bt>Yesus was still teaching people at the Central Worship House. Then he asked the people, saying, “According to your thinking, how.is.it? The religion teachers teach that the Kristus, is the Person whom Father God had designated from long.ago. According to their teaching, He is only king Daud's descendant. But that is not enough.</bt><v n="42" />Lula uru èèna, dhèu aae Daud mesa na dhu suri le, ètu d'ara Lii Sod'a Koa-kio, na,<bt>Because long.ago king Daud himself is the one who wrote in the book of Praise Songs, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua peka le dènge Lamatua ja'a, na,<bt>‘Father God has told my Master/Lord, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;&lt;Mai madhèdi mi era dhu kab'ua ètu babo g'ana Ja'a ne.<bt>“Come to sit in this most.honoured place at My right side.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="43" />Te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a tao musu-musu èu,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I will make your-sg enemies</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke ra pahaha iisi mi èu.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>to the point that they subjugate.themselves to You.’”</bt><note reference="20:42-43" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />De nèti sasuri ne, èdhi te'a, na, dhèu aae Daud mesa na paroa Kristus ne, &lt;Lamatua&gt;. Sasoa na, ladhe dhèu peka na Kristus ne dhoka ana-èpu nèti dhèu aae Daud di, èèna dhae d'ai mèka! Lula Nèngu ne j'aj'i Lamatua nèti dhèu aae Daud kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) from that writing, we-inc know that king Daud himself called the Kristus, saying ‘Master’. That means, if people say the Kristus is only just king Daud's descendant, that is not enough! Because he also is king Daud's Master!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku pamud'e dènge mese-mese agama dhu pahuni sasala ra<bt>Be careful with the religion teachers who cover their sins</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 23:1-36; Markus 12:38-40)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ropa dhèu aa'i-aa'i taru kira mi lii padhai Yesus, hèia Na peka dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na,<bt>When all the people were paying attention to listen to Yesus, then He spoke with His underlings, saying,</bt><v n="46" />&lt;&lt;Baku pamud'e dènge mese agama sèra. Te rèngu d'èi kako pake kodho robho rai, lasi paraga dènge dhèu ae, ho dhèu koa si, peka na, &lt;Rèngu se dhèu kapai!&gt; Rèngu d'èi tenge era re madha ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a, ètu d'ara pesta, aa ètu era-era dhèu ae pakaboko.<bt>“You-pl must be careful about the religion teachers. Cuz (elaboration) they like to go.out wearing long to the ground robes, and go meet with many people, so.that people praise them, saying, ‘They there are big/important people!’ They like to find the most respected place in the worship houses, at feasts, and in the places many people gather.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="robho = panjang sampe di feet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">robho = panjang sampe di feet ; era iia-aala = tempat rame (known by one younger UNS, but not the other) ;</Message></Annotation><v n="47" />De miu baku pamud'e, lula rèngu d'èi kapod'e-kabèli bhèni balu ho parame rare èmu ra. Te ngaa ètu madha dhèu ae, rèngu pahuni bhabhelu ra dènge titu ho sabaj'a panèbhu-nèbhu. Rèngu d'èi dhèu koa ra, peka na, rèngu dhèu mola. Te ngaa Lamatua ne'a sasala ra, de èèna na Nèngu huku si bia risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But be careful, cuz (elaboration) they keep decieving widow women in.order to snatch away their house/s. But in front of many people, they hide that evil of theirs and stand praying for a long time. They want people to praise them saying that they are pious people. But the Lord knows their wrongs, so (consequently) He will give punishment that is heavier/more severe to them.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhèni balu dhu unu boe ngaa-ngaa, hia kolete dhu ae risi<bt>A poor widow gives the biggest offering</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 12:41-44)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o Yesus aj'a ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ladhe nèdhi dhèu kaja mai pamaso doi asa d'ara boaraka derma.<bt>When Yesus taught in the Central Worship House, He saw rich people come putting offering in the collection box.</bt><v n="2" />Ladhe nèdhi kahèi bhèni balu ca dhèu dhu unu boe ngaa-ngaa mai madhutu sabaj'a. Na pamaso kahèi doi dua sen asa d'ara boaraka ne. Doi na se'e, kab'ua ciki oo'e di.<bt>He also saw a poor widow come to participate in praying. She put two cents of money in that box. The value of that money/coin is the very smallest.</bt><v n="3" />Ka Yesus lii dènge ana madhutu Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene pabe'a-be'a! Bhèni balu ne, dhoka pamaso doi dua sen di, te ngaa na hia risi nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Then Yesus spoke with His underlings, saying, “Listen well! This widow here only put in just two cents of money, but she has given more than all people. [NOTE: ‘widow’ in vs.3 tracks to ‘poor widow’ in vs.2. ‘Poor’ is a whole phrase, so to force it here would make extremely heavy information load in Dhao and skew the focus, even though it's in the Gk.]</bt><v n="4" />Dhèu leo se pamaso doi kolete nèti doi karisi rèngu. Te ngaa bhèni balu ne hia aa'i mèu-mèu doi na tao mi doi kolete. Masi ka nèti doi ne'e, nèngu ako taha mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>These other people just put in collection money from their excess/leftover money. But this widow here, she has completely given all her money. In fact, that was her money for living.” [Last clause explicating Gk / bios/]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ako = sementara ; ag'o ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ako = sementara ; ag'o = tipu secara halus ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka gaguri Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>The Lord Yesus tells about the Central Worship House's destruction/collapse</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:1-2; Markus 13:1-2)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lod'o èèna, ana madhutu Yesus dhu koa-kad'iri Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ladhe ku laa, Èmu ne be'a titu kèna! Ra pake hadhu cetak dhu kapai hua, ka ra paca'e mera titu kèna. Aa dhèu hia kahèi mèdha ra dhu kab'ua, sèna ka pasaraga Èmu Lamatua ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Yesus' underlings spoke praising (doublet) that Central Worship House, saying, “Father! Look at the beauty of this House! They made it using cut stones which were very big, and.then they stacked/compiled them very neatly. And there were people who gave expensive things to decorate this House of the Lord's!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadiri = padedha = koa ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kadiri = padedha = koa = praise, exalt, ; pudhi = susun (pagar) ; paca'e = stack</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Yesus b'ala, na,<bt>But [contrary to expectation] Yesus replied saying,</bt><v n="6" />&lt;&lt;Èmu ne mema saraga. Te ngaa nèbhu heka, dhèu paguri eela hadhu se, toke mera dènge rai.&gt;&gt;<bt>“This house really is beautiful. But soon people will completely knock.over all these stones, until they are flat to the ground.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aku Yesus na = Jesus said"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">aku Yesus na = Jesus said</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lod'o-lod'o sasusa dènge j'aj'èra<bt>Days of difficulty and suffering</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:3-14; Markus 13:3-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia ana madhutu Yesus se karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ngaa dhu Ama peka-padhai deo na, j'aj'aj'i na pèri lod'o? Ladhe lod'o na dètu le, tadha-tadha na sèmi ngaa sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus' underlings asked, saying, “Father Teacher! That which Father spoke about earlier, approximately when will it happen? If the time is near, how will the signs be?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sad'i miu j'aga paie-iie, ho baku lèke tipu. Te èèna na rupa-rupa dhèu mai tèb'a kakara ra, peka na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Kristus.&gt; Abhu kahèi dhu peka na, &lt;Lod'o a'èle rai-haha dètu kèna!&gt; Te ngaa baku mi parcaya kahèi!<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “As.long.as (=it's important that) you-pl guard carefully so you don't get decieved (loan). Cuz (elaboration) there will be all.sorts of people coming beating their chest, saying, ‘I here am Kristus.’ There are also those who say, ‘The end of the world is nearly come!’ But don't believe it! [EXEG: “the time has drawn near” = the End is near, see Marshall, TN; Gk either implies or leaves open the possibility that it could be the same group that says both quotes, so restructured to not insist they are said by different groups of people.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèb'a ~ tèb'e = pukul, tempeleng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">tèb'a ~ tèb'e = pukul, tempeleng ; ag'o = young UNS not know, so changed to tipu (they all agree is fully assimilated) ; bèle = tipu</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Ladhe miu tadèngi ka dhèu palolo, peka na: dhèu patao-palaha, dènge papara-pakèj'i ètu mia-mia, baku mi cag'ag'a. Sèra sa hud'i j'aj'i uru ku. Te ngaa d'ai mèka lod'o èle rai-haha ne.<bt>If you hear news that people are mutually.making. chaos (doublet) and mutually.warring (doublet) everywhere, don't be startled. All that must happen first. But the end of the world is not yet arrived.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Bèli-camèd'a suku èci pamusu dènge suku leo. Negara èci papara-pakèj'i dènge negara leo.<bt>One clan will war against another clan. One nation will war against another nation. [DISCOURSE: Gk has quote margin here, but local languages can't have a quote margin where the same speaker is continuing, since a quote margin indicates “change of speaker”.]</bt><v n="11" />Èèna na, j'aj'i rai opo dhu kapai aae. Ètu mia-mia, manganga-mad'èu dhu seli eele, aa èi papèd'a pad'ai cèu palème era. Bèli-camèd'a dhèu ladhe rèdhi kahèi tadha dhu pamadha'u dhèu, aa tadha-tadha dhu kapai aae ètu dedha-liru.<bt>There will be very big earthquakes. In many/various places there will be severe hunger seasons (doublet), and dangerous illnesses spreading. Later people will see signs that terrify them, and unusual/incredible signs in the sky.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padai = menular ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">padai = menular ;</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />J'ara se'e se j'aj'i aa'i mèka, te ngaa èèna na dhèu mai kèpe rare miu, aa paj'èra miu, lula miu parcaya Ja'a. Hèia ra soro miu asa dhèu dhu uri lii langu ètu d'ara èmu-èmu sabaj'a, aa ra taha miu ètu d'ara bèdho. Ra rèti miu asa madha dhèu aae-dhèu aae, dènge dhèu paredha leo. Aa'i-aa'i se j'aj'i, lula miu madhutu Ja'a.<bt>All these thing will not yet have happened (=before all this happens), but people will capture/arrest you and torture/cause you suffering because you believe in Me. Then they will hand you over to people to take.care of your case in the worship houses, and restrain you in jail. They will bring you before kings and other government people. All of this happens, because you follow Me.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa miu hud'i pake lod'o ne'e, sèna ka peka dènge rèngu Lii Lolo Be'a Ja'a.<bt>But you must use that opportunity to tell them My Good News.</bt><v n="14" />De mage pangee tasamia miu siri iisi.<bt>So don't keep thinking/ worrying about how you will defend yourselves.</bt><v n="15" />Te lod'o èèna, Ja'a hia miu lii-lii dhu pamèci dènge lii dhaa. Dènge sèmi èèna, musu miu sèra, re'a heka peka-padhai sèmi ngaa hari.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) at that time, I will give words which are fitting/exact for you to respond. In that way, your enemies won't know what else to say.</bt><note reference="21:14-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 12:11-12</note><v n="16-17" />Bèli-camèd'a dhèu tèka d'ara dènge miu, lula miu madhutu Ja'a. Abhu nèti a'ari miu unu mi, sèmi ina-ama, a'ari, kera ba'i, rae lesa dènge mone anga-aangalai. Èèna na nèti rèngu se'e ka, tenge j'ara ho pahie eele miu, toke ra pamadhe miu cahag'e.<bt>Later many people will hate you, because you follow Me. There will be those from your own families, like mother-father, elder-younger.siblings, in-laws, and friends. Later there will be those from them who seek ways to betray/sell you off, to.the.point that there are some of you who are killed. [NOTE: Local categories generally covering the same as the Gk.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kera ba'i = kunyadu ; rae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kera ba'i = kunyadu ; rae lesa = tetangga satu kampung</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thanatoosousin: probably the ones to whom"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">thanatoosousin: probably the ones to whom the others were betrayed</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te ngaa miu baku madha'u, te Lamatua bhèlu boe miu. Rèu kètu miu ca loa sa kabhui eele boe, ladhe dènge boe dad'èi Na.<bt>But you don't be afraid, cuz (elaboration) the Lord will not forget you. Not even one hair can drop from your-pl heads, if it is not His will.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kai thriks ...: probably means that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">kai thriks ...: probably means that the community as a whole won't be harmed or wiped out, even though a few people get killed.</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Ladhe miu taha mere taruu, tatu Ama Lamatua pala-bagi mamuri hia miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>If you keep on enduring, surely Father God will save/give life to you.” [EXEG: LN “Gk = idiom: save yourselves from grave danger”; QUESTION: does this clash with 16, where “some of you will die”? NRSV “gain your souls” and NLT “win your souls” may not be recognising the idiom. See TN, but don't overtranslate to try and get the “not die spritually” sense.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èèna na kota Yerusalem ele iie<bt>The city of Yerusalem's end</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:15-21; Markus 13:14-19)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Yesus padhai lii tabha hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu mèdhi ka sordad'u mai pamusu reo rare Yerusalem, miu me'a le, na, d'ai lod'o ele iie Yerusalem kèna.<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, “If/when you-pl see soldiers come mutually.enemy/war against and encircle Yerusalem, you will know that the time of Yerusalem's end/destruction is there. [EXEG: Gk literally “armies”, but carried in KM by combination of /musu/ with military term /kepung ame/ “surround, encricle, besiege”.]</bt><v n="21" />Ropa ladhe mèdhi sèmi èèna, dhèu ètu propensi Yudea rai dènge ka asa ledhe-ledhe. Dhèu ètu d'ara kota kèd'i kahèi, sèna ka rai. Aa dhèu ètu rae, mai ia ka asa d'ara kota.<bt>Seeing that, people in Yudea province [should] get up and run/flee immediately to the mountains. People in the city should also get up and run. And people in the villages shouldn't enter the city again.</bt><v n="22" />Te Lamatua hia lod'o-lod'o sasusa sèra, ho huku dhèu-dhèu dhu ro'o boe nanene Nèngu. Se'e se lèke nuka sèmi lii padhai nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu suri tèke karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the Lord gives/allows those difficult days to judge/punish people who don't want to hear/obey Him. That all happens exactly in accord with what Father God's spokespersons have written ahead.of.time long.ago.</bt><note reference="21:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hosea 9:7</note><v n="23" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu dhu j'èra risi, nuka, dhèu bhèni dhu dènge babia, aa ina-ina dhu dènge ana susu. Lod'o èèna, abhu susa palème rai-haha, aa dhèu Yahudi j'èra bia, lula Ama Lamatua nasa dènge rèngu sèra.<bt>At that time, the people who suffer most/in greatest difficulty, are the women who are pregnant and mamas who have nursing children. At that time, the entire world will have difficulty, and all the Yahudi people will have heavy suffering, because Father God is angry with them. [EXEG: Gk. normal phrasing for “on the earth” NRSV and impact in vs. 24, although some want to take the also legitimate rendering “on the land” (restricting it to Israel), from context of 20,21,24. This rendering carries both as a high-level parallelism.]</bt><v n="24" />Èèna na musu mai pamadhe si cahag'e, aa taha cahag'e ho j'aj'i ènu ètu mia-mia ètu rai-haha ne. Ka dhèu leo rai kara dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua, mai j'aj'èli pakaj'alu kota Yerusalem, aa koasa rare kabarai na, toke èle lod'o ra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later enemies will kill some of them, and detain some of them to become slaves everywhere in this world. Then foreigners who don't know/recognise Father God will come and step all over (can also mean ‘oppress’) making Yerusalem city dirty/defiled, and control all of the city's contents/inhabitants, until their time is over.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamai hari Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a<bt>The Authentic Human's coming</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:29-31; Markus 13:24-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle ka Yesus lole mamai hari Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a ladhe Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a neo mai hari, abhu tadha ètu madha lod'o, hèru, dènge hua hètu-hua hètu. Ètu rai-haha ne abhu tadha kahèi, sèmi uli sea, dhasi ko'a dhu loe boe, aa naha aae lalulu mai. Se'e se tao dhèu rai-haha ne, madha'u dènge ele ngangee, toke re'a heka tao ngaa-ngaa.<bt>Then Yesus told about His coming back, saying, “Later when the Authentic Human is about to come back, there will be signs in the sun, in the moon and the stars. On earth there will also be signs, such as very big noisy wind/storm/cyclone, the sea running amok and giant waves breaking coming. All this makes humans afraid and paralysed (in their thinking), until they don't know what to do anymore. [NOTE: local categories that evoke the same picture.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhasi ko'a = laut mangamok ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhasi ko'a = laut mangamok ; uli sea = puting beliung, tofan, cyclone, ; lalulu = (wave) breaking ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 13:10, Yeskial 32:7, Yoel 2:31, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 6:12-13</note><v n="26" />Koasa-koasa ètu dedha-liru loe boe karèbha. Ropa ladhe rèdhi aa'i-aa'i, hèia ra madha'u titu kèna, lula rai-haha ne oe ele iie kèna!<bt>The powers which are in the sky will shake in tumult. Seeing like that then, people will become very afraid, because the earth is about to have disaster/destruction!</bt><v n="27" />Èle ku heka dhèu ladhe rèdhi Ja'a kèna, &lt;Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne puru mai ètu d'ara ra'i-liru&gt;. Ja'a mai dènge koasa, aa dènge dadedha dhu kapai risi eele.<bt>After that, then people will see Me, ‘the Authentic Human, coming down with/by cloud’. I will come.down with power, and with all My glory/majesty/highness of the greatest degree.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dadedha = kemuliaan &lt; dedha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dadedha = kemuliaan &lt; dedha</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 7:13, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:7</note><v n="28" />Ladhe mulai j'aj'i ka tadha sèra, na, miu boti ka kètu miu, te lod'o d'ai kèna, Lamatua hia mamuri mi miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When all these signs have begun to happen, na, you must lift up your heads, cuz (elaboration) the Lord's time has arrived to save you.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame nèti aj'u<bt>Comparison.story from a tree</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 24:32-35; Markus 13:28-31)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus lolo pake lii pakasame, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu taru kira pabe'a-be'a ku mi aj'u sèra.<bt>After that Yesus began to speak using a comparison.story, saying, “You-pl pay careful attention to the trees.</bt><v n="30" />Ladhe d'ai ka hèru rèu ra karara, èèna tadha na hèru hadhu dètu le.<bt>When it comes time/season for their leaves begin to yellow, that is a sign that the hot season is near.</bt><v n="31" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge lod'o-lod'o sasusa. Ladhe cèu, èèna tadha na paredha Ama Lamatua dhu dètu iiki le.<bt>Like.that also with the difficult days. When they appear, that is a sign that Father God's rule is very close.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ja'a pasanèd'e mema miu! Nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri limuri ne, bèli-camèd'a cahag'e dhae madhe mèka, te lod'o-lod'o j'aj'èra se mai le.<bt>I'm telling you beforehand (=mark my words)! From all the people who live nowadays, there will some who have not.yet died, when those difficulty days have come.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ameen: Here he seems responding to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">ameen: Here he seems responding to some recognition of the Kingdom on their part, so "Dass good! An I like tell you guys dis too," the regular Rabbinical teaching formula, could fit, as taking them one new step beyond their current understanding. It's not as if the disciples were complete buffoons that never caught on to anything, as they are sometimes made out to be in a kind of low comedy scenario (also in Jesus Christ Superstar).</Message></Annotation><v n="33" />Masi ka liru dènge rai-haha ele, te ngaa Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a taha taa-taa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Even.if the sky and the earth disappear, nevertheless these Words of Mine will endure continually.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mate tatae mamai hari Lamatua Yesus<bt>Need to carefully watch for the Lord's coming</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia Yesus tuhu lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mi j'aga-j'aga, te cag'ag'a laa Ja'a mai hari sahèka! Mage dhoka miu taru kira heka, hèia miu mamuri dènge minu mahu, aa bhute dhoka tenge mamuri karej'e di. Mage dhoka miu me'a boe tadha ne, lula miu bhute dènge j'ara dhu leo.<bt>Then Yesus continued His speaking, saying, “Be careful/watchful (for s.t.), cuz (elaboration) suddenly I will appear! May it not be that you no longer know how to think correctly, so you are living getting drunk and busying yourselves seeking to just live pleasantly. May it not be that you don't read the signs, because you are preoccupied with other matters.</bt><v n="35" />Ladhe Ja'a lèpa hari mai, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa pahuni iisi ra nèti madha Ja'a.<bt>When I come back, there will not be a single person who can hide himself from My face.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palu'u = hide = pahuni"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">palu'u = hide = pahuni</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />De miu hud'i mate tatae ku. Baku ma'ète manèngi-mangaj'i, sèna ka miu bisa taha ètu talora aae sasusa sèra. Dènge sèmi èèna, ropa Ja'a lèpa hari mai, miu makae boe titu ètu madha Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), always be watchful. Pray not stopping, so that you can endure in the midst of all that difficulty. In that way, when I have come back, you will not be embarrassed to stand in front of the Authentic Human.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Bèli-bèli, ladhe re mèu, Yesus la'e aj'a Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Te ngaa ladhe re mèda, kalua nèti Yerusalem ho la'e bhèj'i asa rae ètu ledhe Saitun.<bt>Every day, Yesus went to teach the Lord's Message/Words at the Central Worship House. But when it was night He went.out of Yerusalem to go sleep in a village on Saitun mountain over.there. [NOTE: ‘teach’ usually requires a DO (teach what) or IO (teach who).]</bt><note reference="21:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 19:47</note><v n="38" />Mad'ae aae era, dhèu ae-ae dhu mai le pakaboko ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ho nanene lii aj'a-nori Na.<bt>Very early in the morning, many people had already come gathering at the Central Worship House. in.order.to listen to Him teach.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu agama Yahudi tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The chief priests seek a way to kill the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:1-5; Markus 14:1-2; Yohanis 11:45-53)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, oe d'ai lod'o hua iia dhèu Yahudi, nuka pesta Roti dhu dènge boe Ragi. Ètu d'ara lod'o hua iia se, ra roro kahib'i-kalèbho tao kalela Paska kahèi. Rèngu tao sèmi ne'e, sèna ka pasanèd'e uru èèna, lod'o bèi-baki rèngu kalua nèti Masir.<bt>At that time, it was near the Yahudi people's holiday, which was the feast of Bread without Yeast. On that holiday, they also slaughter a sheep to make the Paska feast. They did like.that to remember the time long.ago, when their ancestors come out of Masir [Expansion from vs. 7; background info appropriate here].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roti parèko j'ara = roti bakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">roti parèko j'ara = roti bakal</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:1-27</note><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Yesus. Te ngaa ra mage dhèu ae sèra maruru, lula dhèu se d'èi nanene Ne.<bt>At that time the chief priests and the religion teachers were hunting for ways to kill Yesus. But they were afraid those many people would make chaos/riot, because they liked to listen to Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aneloosin: not &quot;kill&quot; directly, but &quot;get"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">aneloosin: not "kill" directly, but "get rid," a euphemism.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yudas Iskariot pahie Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yudas Iskariot sells.off/betrays the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:14-16; Markus 14:10-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Nèti dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus, dhèu canguru dua sèra, èci ngara na Yudas Iskariot. Lod'o kètu agama Yahudi sèra tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Yesus, dhèu aae nidhu maso asa d'ara Yudas Iskariot.<bt>From Yesus' twelve underlings, one was named Yudas Iskariot. When the chief priests were seeking a way to kill Yesus, the head of the evil spirits entered into Yudas insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaas: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Satanaas: da Devil</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Hèia la'e tenge kètu agama Yahudi se dènge kètu nèti dhèu madhenga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. La'e neo pane'a dènge ra, sèna ka pahie Yesus dènge rèngu.<bt>Then he went out to go seek the heads of religion and the head guard of the Central Worship House. He wanted to mutually conspire with them to sell off (=betray) Yesus to them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pane'a = sakongkol"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pane'a = sakongkol</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ropa tadèngi lii padhai Yudas, hèia ra karej'e titu kèna. Ra pamoa, peka na, &lt;&lt;La'a, ma! Ladhe èu neo pahie Yesus dènge ji'i, na ji'i b'ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they heard Yudas speaking like that, then they were very happy. They promised, saying, “Ok! If you want to sell Yesus to us, we will pay.”</bt><v n="6" />Ka Yudas d'èi, hèia na mulai tenge lod'o dhu lake nare, sèna ka dhèu ae baku re'a nèngu pahie eele Yesus.<bt>Yudas agreed, and then he began to look for opportunities to sell off Yesus quietly to them, so.that the many people would not know.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana madhutu Lamatua Yesus sadia nganga'a kalela Paska<bt>The Lord Yesus' underlings prepare food for the Paska feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:17-25; Markus 14:12-21; Yohanis 13:21-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia d'ai ka lod'o hua iia dhèu Yahudi, dhu rèngu biasa roro ana kahib'i-kalèbho sèna ka tao kalela Paska.<bt>Then that holiday of the Yahudi people arrived, for them to (ritually) slaughter a lamb for the Paska festival.</bt><v n="8" />Ka Yesus pua Petrus dènge Yohanis, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dua mi lami uuru, sèna ka sadia tèke nganga'a kalela Paska ho ta'a sama-sama.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yesus ordered Petrus and Yohanis, saying, “You two go ahead to prepare for us-inc to eat the Paska feast together.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka dua ra karèi, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i la'a sadia nganga'a asa mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the two of them answered, saying, “Father! Where should we go prepare the food?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia Na b'ala, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu maso asa d'ara kota Yerusalem, pe miu paraga dènge dhèu mone ca dhèu dhu pasae g'ala èi cue. Madhutu ne toke d'ai èmu na.<bt>He replied saying, “If/when you enter into Yerusalem city, you will meet/encounter a male who is shoulder.carrying a clay.pot of water. Follow him to his house.</bt><v n="11" />Peka dènge lamatua èmu ne, &lt;Ama Mese ji'i manèngi ca kama, ho neo pake tao kalela Paska dènge ana-ana madhutu Na. Abhu, do?&gt;<bt>Tell the house owner there, saying, ‘Our-exc Father Teacher is requesting a room to use to make the Paska feast with His underlings. Is there one?’</bt><v n="12" />Èèna na lamatua èmu ne pad'elo dènge miu kama èci dhu taleo ètu èmu dedha. Nèngu lalau pamèci nare aa'i le kama èèna. Ate dhoka miu dua mi lami sadia nganga'a ètu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>That house owner will show you a wide room on the floor above (=not ground floor). He has completed prepared that room. The only thing lacking is for you two go just go prepare the food there.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalaga dedha ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kalaga dedha =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka dua ra lasi. Hèia ra paraga ka nuka sèmi ngaa dhu Yesus peka le. Ka dua ra sadia nganga'a-nganginu Kalela Paska ètu nèi.<bt>So the two of them went. And they encountered everything which Yesus had told them. Then they prepared the food (doublet) for the Paska feast there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kalela Paska<bt>Paska Feast</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:26-30; Markus 14:22-26; 1 Korintus 11:23-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa lalau rare aa'i, Yesus si mai. Yesus madhèdi ètu mei, aa ana-ana pajuu-paleha Na madhèdi kahèi ra'a pesta.<bt>When everything was ready, Yesus (collective) came. Yesus sat at the table, and His commissioned.ones (apostles) also sat.down to eat the feast. [EXEG: Gk. ‘apostles’ here.] [EXEG: NRSV &amp; Marshall's phrasing “took his place at the table” is ambiguous between 1) sat at the head of the table, and 2) he sat down. Passover Seder rules suggest #1, but safer interpretation is just #2 as NLT.]</bt><v n="15" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge si, &lt;&lt;Ja'a d'èi titu kèna madhèdi ku'a kalela Paska dènge miu aa'i-aa'i mi, uru nèti Ja'a abhu j'aj'èra.<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “I greatly desire to sit and eat this Paska feast with you-pl all, before I obtain/ experience suffering.</bt><v n="16" />Patadhe pabe'a-be'a. Te èle ne'e ne, Ja'a madhèdi heka ku'a kalela Paska dènge miu. Ladhe dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a mèu ku, peka na, Ama Ku nèd'u paredha, Ja'a heka ku'a hari kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Take good note of this. Cuz (elaboration) after this, I will not sit again to eat Paska feast with you anymore. When all people plainly/clearly know that, My Father is holding rule/governing, only.then I will eat (feast) again.” [EXEG: “until it is fulfilled in the kingdom of God” has complex possibilities, and wide range in translations. This rendering (also in 18) leaves open at least 3 possibilities: 1) until resurrection, 2) glorification at ascension, 3) glorification upon return and rule. Extensive work with one consultant.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Na kèpe nare galaa cue dhu isi èi anggor. Ka Na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, èle ka Na soro galaa ne asa rèngu. Hèia Na padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi mere galaa ne, ho èci-èci minu.<bt>Next He picked up a glass which was filled with grape liquid. Then He gave thanks to Father God, and he extended that glass to them. Then He spoke, saying, “Accept this glass, for each one of you to drink.</bt><v n="18" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Karèi nèti mèda ne'e ne, Ja'a kinu heka èi anggor. Ladhe dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a mèu ka, peka na, Ama Ku nèd'u paredha, Ja'a heka kinu hari kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember well! Starting from this night, I will not drink grape liquid again. Later when all people clearly know that Father is holding rule/governing, only.then I will drink again.” [NOTE: See EXEG note at 16.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia Na kèpe nare roti cue, ka manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Na pamae roti ne, hèia Na soro sa rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra. Ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Roti ne'e ne, ngi'u aae Ja'a dhu Ja'a hia sa miu aa'i-aa'i mi. Lod'o-lod'o dhu miu mi'e ne, pasanèd'e taruu miu, lula tatao Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He picked up a (loaf of) bread, and He gave thanks to Father God. Then He broke that bread into.bits, and extended it to them. He said, “This bread here, is My body which I give for you all. Each time you-pl eat it, you must remember/think of Me.” [EXEG: Gk aspect on last clause is on-going “do this (durative) ... as a memorial, not just this once”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="touto poieite ... anamneesin: do this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">touto poieite ... anamneesin: do this (durative) ... as a memorial, not just this once.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ropa ra'a rare, ka Na ded'e nare galaa dhu isi èi anggor. Hèia Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èi anggor ne'e ne, raa Ja'a ka ne, dhu bhori mai sèna ka hia sod'a-mole mi miu. Nèti raa ne'e ka, Ama Lamatua pa'èki lii pajaji dhu hiu dènge miu.<bt>When they were finished eating, then He took a glass filled with grape liquid. Then He spoke, saying, “This grape (juice) here, is my blood, which is poured out to save (doublet) you. From this blood, Father God mutually ties/binds a new promise with you.</bt><note reference="22:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 31:31-34</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Mage pamud'e, te abhu dhèu dhu madhèdi sama-sama dènge èdhi ètu mei ne, èèna na, nèngu pahie eele Ja'a.<bt>But be careful, cuz (elaboration) there is a person who now sits together with us-inc at this table, who will sell Me off (betray).</bt><note reference="22:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 41:10</note><v n="22" />Mema Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, hud'i madhe ku madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pahie eele Ja'a, sanèd'e, ee! Te bèli-camèd'a, nèngu pasae nare mamadhe-mamopo!&gt;&gt;<bt>It's true that I, the Authentic Human, must die in accord with Father God's will. But that person who sells Me off, remember, ee (=warning)! Cuz (elaboration) he will carry/bear his own misfortune (doublet)!” [STYLE: Strong wording, almost veiled curse.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa ra tadèngi lii ne, ana-ana pajuu-paleha se pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu ad'u-ue madha j'ara bhelu ne mi dedha Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then Yesus' underlings began to ask.each.other, saying, “Who do you think it is that will do evil like that to Him?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana madhutu Lamatua Yesus pasisu lula-nèti cee ka dhu dhèu re madha<bt>The Lord Yesus' underlings argue about who is the most important</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka ana madhutu Yesus se pasisu, peka na, nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, cee ka dhu dhèu re madha.<bt>Then Yesus' underlings began to argue about who from them was the most important/prominent.</bt><note reference="22:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 18:1, Markus 9:34, Lukas 9:46</note><v n="25" />Te ngaa Yesus kai si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ètu rai-rai dhu kabarai ra tadhe boe Lamatua, dhèu aae ra hia paredha dhu bia risi mi kabarai rèngu. Te ngaa rèngu neo sèna ka kabarai paroa rèngu, peka na, &lt;Ama dhu taru kira kabarai&gt;.<bt>But Yesus scolded them, saying, “In the nations who don't know the Lord, the kings give heavy/excessive commands to their citizens. But they want their citizens to call them, saying, ‘Father who attends to (the needs of) citizens.’ [EXEG question: who calls them benefactors? TH, TN, NIV, CEV rulers call themselves; NLT, Marshall, irony, sarcasm--want to be called]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taru kira = perhatikan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">taru kira = perhatikan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dhèu aae-dhèu aae nèti rai-rai dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Dhèu aae-dhèu aae nèti rai-rai dhu tadhe boe Lamatua, hia paredha bia risi mi kabarai ra. Masi ka rèngu se dhaa le, peka na, dhèu dhu rèd'u koasa hud'i biri kabarai.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="euergetai: helper of the people, benefactor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">euergetai: helper of the people, benefactor (not defender as in BI)</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ngaa miu baku madhutu j'ara sèra. Cee dhu neo j'aj'i dhèu kapai, mamuri na hud'i tare'a-re'a sama sèmi dhèu haha ho lalau-lalo'o dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra. Dhu neo j'aj'i kètu, hud'i ladhe-leru ku sama sèmi ana pua-paleha.<bt>But you may not do like.that. Whoever wants to become a big/important person, his life must truly be like a small/unimportant (low) person to serve all people. The one wants to be head/ leader must serve all that a low ranking servant. [NOTE to daughter translations: Compare wording with Mark 9:35. Flesh it out similarly.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neooteros: youngest. SK &quot;Who goin listen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">neooteros: youngest. SK "Who goin listen to da younges?"</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:25-26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 20:25-27; 23:11, Markus 9:35; 10:42-44</note><v n="27" />Miu pangee sèku, dhèu kapai sèra nuka mia? Dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu mei, do, dhu lalau mei? Tatu dhèu dhu madhèdi ne, dhèu kapai, si? Te ngaa Ja'a ne, tao boe ngi'u sèmi sèra. Ja'a mai lalau-lalo'o miu.<bt>Have a think, which one is the big/important person? The person who sits at the table, or, the the one who serves the table? Surely the one who sits is the one who is the big person, right. However, I don't make myself like them. I came/come to serve (doublet) you.</bt><note reference="22:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:12-15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Miu se'e ka dhu bera-bera dènge Ja'a, lod'o Ja'a paraga dènge j'aj'èra.<bt>You here are the ones always together with Me when I am afflicted with suffering.</bt><v n="29" />Ama Ku ded'e le Ja'a, sèna ka kèd'u paredha ètu era paredha Na. Ka limuri ne, Ja'a ded'e miu kahèi,<bt>My Father has lifted/appointed Me to rule in His kingdom. So now I also lift/appoint you,</bt><v n="30" />ho miu bèli-camèd'a madhèdi mi'a dènge Ja'a ca mei ètu sorga. Ja'a hia koasa kahèi, sèna ka miu paredha canguru dua suku dhèu Isra'el.&gt;&gt;<bt>so that you will sit and eat at the same table with Me in heaven. I also will give power/authority for you to rule the twelve clans who are in Isra'el.” [EXEG: judging = Marshall “judicial function”; TH, all versions; only Green and TN, evokes both judge and ruler; see also context of vs. 31 “sift like wheat”; So ‘rule’ has support, but is problematic, but ‘judge/decide cases’ may also be too narrow for meaning in context.]</bt><note reference="22:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 19:28</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema, na, bèli-camèd'a Petrus pasili, na tadhe boe Nèngu<bt>The Lord Yesus tells that Petrus will deny knowing Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:31-35; Markus 14:27-31; Yohanis 13:36-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Yesus lii dènge Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Petrus. Dhèu aae nidhu neo hia miu pacèri nèti Ja'a, nuka sèmi dhèu tatai ho hag'e eele èto nèti laludhu.<bt>Then Yesus told Petrus, saying, “Petrus. The king of the evil.spirts will try to separate you-pl from Me, like a person winnows rice to separate the husks from the rice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="raroo = shake basket so stuff"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">raroo = shake basket so stuff separates out to different places ; madhaa = biji padi yg masi berkulit ; laludhu = beras bersih ; èto = katak, yg kotoran alus, dan kulit luar ; tatai = winnow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Satanaas: da Devil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Satanaas: da Devil</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani, peka ngara Petrus dhu leo, nuka Simon.<bt>In the Yunani language writing, they mention Petrus' other name, which is Simon.</bt></note><v n="32" />Te ngaa Ja'a sabaj'a hia èu, Petrus, ho èu lèka Ja'a taruu. Ladhe èu lèpa hari mai asa Ja'a, na, èu hud'i pa'èra ku d'ara a'ari èu, nuka dhèu unu Lamatua sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I am praying for you, Petrus, so that you-sg continually believe in Me. Later when you have come back to Me, then you must strengthen/encourage your siblings' insides, that is, of God's people.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia Petrus b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, Ama! Masi ka tasamia èèna ka, ja'a bisa boe tèke eele Ama. Te ja'a pa'èra maso bui sama-sama dènge Ama. Masi ka ja'a madhe palere-lere dènge Ama, ngaa-ngaa tao boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus replied, saying, “No, Father! No matter what, I am not going to leave Father. Cuz (elaboration) I am prepared to enter jail together with Father. Even to die together with Father, would be ok.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Nanene paie. Mèda ne'e kahèi, manu dhae kokotoo mèka, èu pasili le tèlu hari, na, èu tadhe boe Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus replied, saying, “Petrus! Listen carefully. This night, the chicken will not.yet crow, but you-sg will already have denied three times, saying, you do not know Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus hud'i pa'èra d'ara ladhe paraga dènge j'aj'èra<bt>The Lord Yesus' people must prepare themselves in case they encounter/experience difficulty/suffering (supported by TN, Marshall, Green)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èdhi bori mema tas doi, tas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Èdhi bori mema tas doi, tas mèdha-papake, dènge rèka</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus padhai lii dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ca hari na, Ja'a pua miu lami lole Lii Lolo Be'a Ja'a asa mia-mia, Ja'a peka dènge miu, ho baku mèti doi, tas, dènge salapa. Lod'o èèna, miu kura ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus spoke with them, saying, “That (earlier) time when I commissioned you-pl to go tell My Good News everywhere, I said you didn't need to take money, bag, and sandals. At that time, what did you lack?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bori = siap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bori = siap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka aa'i-aa'i ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ca hari na, ji'i kura boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they all replied, saying, “At that time we did not lack a single thing!”</bt><note reference="22:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:9-10, Markus 6:8-9, Lukas 9:3, 10:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Hèia Yesus peka tabha hari, na, &lt;&lt;Te ngaa limuri ne, leo. Ladhe miu dènge doi, na todhe mèti. Ladhe dènge tas, na mèti kahèi. Ladhe dènge boe samala, pahia kodho miu, sèna ka hèli.<bt>Then He spoke further, saying, “But now it's different. If you have money, na, take it along. If a bag, na, take it also. If don't have a fighting.sword, na, go sell one of your shirts/clothings, to buy one.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="todhe = 1) pull sampan behind"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">todhe = 1) pull sampan behind 2) take along</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="himation: outer garment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">himation: outer garment</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Te dhèu Yahudi pangee na, Ja'a ne dhèu bhelu. Hèia nèbhu heka, rèngu mai kèpe Ja'a. J'ara ne, nuka sèmi dhu baki Yesaya suri tèke le:<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the Yahudi people consider Me an evil person. So in a little bit more they will come capture/arrest Me. That fits exactly with what grandfather Yesaya wrote ahead.of.time, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ra tao Ne sèmi dhèu bhelu-katub'a!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>‘They stamp/brand/categorise Him as an evil person!’</bt><note reference="22:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i ngèti hela dua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they said, “Father! We've brought two machetes.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka, &lt;&lt;D'ai le. Ale ia ka sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus said, “That's enough. It's not neccessary to speak about that anymore!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus la'e sabaj'a asa ledhe Saitun<bt>The Lord Yesus goes to pray at Saitun mountain</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:36-46; Markus 14:32-42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ra'a rare Paska, ka Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na lasi asa ledhe Saitun, sèmi biasa.<bt>After eating Paksa then Yesus and His underlings went out to Saitun mountain, like usual.</bt><v n="40" />D'ai nèi, Yesus peka dènge si, &lt;&lt;Miu hud'i sabaj'a ku, ho baku lèke dadugu-rariu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving there, He told them saying, “You-pl need to pray so that you don't get afflicted with temptation (doublet).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Hèia Na tèke eele si, la'e kaj'èu boe. Ka Na patitu kètu urutuu Na, ho sabaj'a, peka na,<bt>Then He moved away from them, going not far. And He knelt to pray, saying,</bt><v n="42" />&lt;&lt;Ama! Ladhe Ama d'èi na, pakaj'èu ku j'aj'èra ne nèti Ja'a. Te ngaa mage madhutu dad'èi Ja'a; hud'i laa madhutu dhoka dad'èi Ama di.&gt;&gt;<bt>“Father! If Father (=you) wants, na, distance this suffering from Me. But don't follow My will; let it just be Father's will.”</bt><v n="43" />[Ka ana pajuu Ama Lamatua èci mai nèti sorga pa'èra d'ara Na.<bt>[Then one of the God's underlings from heaven came and strengthened/ encouraged His insides.</bt><v n="44" />Lula d'ara Na j'èra titu kèna, toke èi kabhèsu Na suti sèmi raa sa.]<bt>Because He was suffering very greatly, to the point that His sweat drops came out like blood.]</bt><note reference="22:43-44" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru tèka dènge dhu be'a risi, suri boe ayat 43-44 se'e.<bt>The oldest and best Yunani language writings do not write these verses 43-44.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ropa sabaj'a nare, Na kèd'i la'e paraga dènge ana madhutu Na. Te ngaa rèngu dhu bhèj'i, lula ngi'u roe aa d'ara susa.<bt>After [He] finished praying, He got up and went to meet His underlings. But they were sleeping, because they were tired and their insides were distressed.</bt><v n="46" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka miu se bhèj'i? Be'a risi miu sabaj'a, ho ladhe paraga dènge dadugu-rariu, miu baku manahu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke to them, “Why are you sleeping?! It's better you pray so that if you meet/encounter temptation, you will not fall.” [EXEG: NLT. Although wording in 40 &amp; 46 is similar in Gk. phrased differently here like NLT to broaden the reader's fuller understanding of the possibilities of what is meant.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra kèpe Lamatua Yesus<bt>They capture/arrest the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:47-56; Markus 14:43-50; Yohanis 18:3-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii era, Yudas (ca dhèu nèti canguru dua ana madhutu Na), mai dènge dhèu ae-ae. Na mai padètu-dètu dènge Yesus, neo kèpe ho uu Ne.<bt>Yesus was still speaking, [contrary to expectation =unexpectedly] Yudas (one of His twelve underlings), came and brought many people. He came close to Yesus in.order to hug-kiss Him. [Note: Gk is only “kiss”; Dhao here is a single complex action.]</bt><v n="48" />Te ngaa Yesus lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yudas! Èu neo pahie eele Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a dènge a'uu, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus scolded him, saying, “Yudas! Are you trying to sell/betray off the Authentic Human with a kiss, (or what)?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uu = v ; a'uu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">uu = v ; a'uu = ciuman</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Ropa ana madhutu leo sèra re'a tatao bhelu nèti Yudas ne, ka ra karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i lab'a si, do? Te ji'i dhu ngèti hela.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the other underlings found out Yudas evil deed/behaviour, they asked Yesus, saying, “Father! Do we just oppose/fight them? Cuz (elaboration) we have brought machetes.”</bt><v n="50" />Ka ca dhèu nèti rèngu se, bete hela na, ka na pare pama'ète rèu dhilu g'ana nèti dhèu èci. Dhèu ne, ènu nèti kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi.<bt>Then one of them pull out his machete, and cut severed one person's right ear. That person was the servant/slave of the big head/leader of the Yahudi priests (=high priest).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sange èèna ka! Baku lab'a si.&gt;&gt; Hèia Na g'ag'e dhilu dhèu ne, ka pa'èle.<bt>But Yesus replied saying, “That's enough! Don't oppose them.” Then He touched that person's ear, and healed him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Dhèu-dhèu dhu mai kèpe Yesus, nuka: kètu agama Yahudi sèra, dhèu heka d'ara rae, kètu nèti dhèu madhenga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, dènge dhèu leo hari kahèi. Yesus karèi si, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Miu se ngee, na, Ja'a ne dhèu bhelu, ka mai kèpe Ja'a mèti samala dènge aj'u cèki, do?<bt>Those people who came to capture/arrest Yesus were: the chief priests, the traditional elders and the head(s) of the guards of the Central Worship House, and still other people. Yesus asked them, saying, “How is it? Do you think that I here am an evil person, so that you come capture/arrest Me bringing fighting swords and night.sticks/clubs? [EXEG: Gk /machaira/ is the same word in vs. 36, 38, and 52. It is a semi-generic term that includes a range of sharp cutting instruments from dedicated fighting swords and sabers down to knives and daggers (LN, BADG). So the teams and UNS's feel it is appropriate to be context relevant in the translation of the term. Soldiers, guards, and symbols of fighting wars are translated “sword”. In an occupied territory with soldiers fearful of attacks by rebels, it is appropriate for fishermen to have access to machetes (as work tools) rather than happening to have full-fledged fighting swords handy. Hence the different translations.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aj'u cèki = club, kayu kudung/pentungan/gada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">aj'u cèki = club, kayu kudung/pentungan/gada</Message></Annotation><v n="53" />Bèli-bèli èèna, Ja'a aj'a miu ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, te ngaa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu mai kèpe Ja'a. De hud'i laa! Ne'e d'ai lod'o miu. Ne'e ne mai nèti koasa dhèu aae nidhu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Every day I taught you in the Central Worship House, but there was not a single person who came to capture/arrest Me. But never mind! This is your time. Now it's the king of the evil spirits who controls this!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: aj'u cèki, artinya kayu kudung/pentungan/gada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: aj'u cèki, artinya kayu kudung/pentungan/gada</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:53" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 19:47, 21:37</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus pasili, peka na, nèngu tadhe boe Lamatua Yesus<bt>Petrus denies that he knows the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:57-58, 69-75; Markus 14:53-54, 66-72; Yohanis 18:12-18, 25-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Hèia ra kèpe rare Lamatua Yesus, ka nuni rèti Ne asa èmu kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi. Petrus kako mau-mau re kabodho.<bt>Then they captured/arrested Yesus, and they dragged/led brought Him to the house of the *high priest. Petrus also went following along secretly from behind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paki'u = follow ; ro'a kala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">paki'u = follow ; ro'a kala = anus, * ; ki'u = bottom</Message></Annotation><v n="55" />Ètu madha èmu ne, dhèu tao ai raci. Hèia Petrus la'e manyiru ai kahèi.<bt>At that house's yard people had made a camp.type.fire. Then Petrus went to also sit and warm himself at that fire.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai raci = bonfire, api unggun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">ai raci = bonfire, api unggun (campfire or bonfire)</Message></Annotation><v n="56" />Ka bhèni sab'a ca dhèu ladhe nèdhi Petrus dhu manyiru ai. Na ladhe patae rèhu Petrus, ka peka dènge dhèu leo ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne dhu madhutu Yesus kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>A female worker saw Petrus warming over the fire. She looked carefully at Petrus' face, then told the other people there, saying, “This person was also following Yesus!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Ai raci artinya Api unggun."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Ai raci artinya Api unggun.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Te ngaa Petrus pasili, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Ja'a tadhe boe Dhèu ne. Èu me'a ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus denied, saying, “No! I do not know that Person [+protest]. What do you-sg know?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />Nèbhu boe ka, ca dhèu ladhe sa Petrus, èle ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Èu ne, mema ca dhèu nèti dhèu Yesus sèra, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>Not much longer, then another person looked at Petrus, then s/he spoke, saying, “It's true. You-sg here, really are one of Yesus' people, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Petrus pasili, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Èu peka leli na!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus protested, saying, “No! You are just talking thoughtlessly/reckless!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Pe d'ai ca jam sa, ca dhèu leo hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ke'a dhèu ne'e ne, ca dhèu nèti ana madhutu Yesus. Te nèngu ne, dhèu Galilea kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>About one more hour then yet another person spoke, saying, “I know this person here is one of Yesus' underlings. Cuz (elaboration) he is also a Galilea person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="60" />Te ngaa Petrus pasili hari kahèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu monya èèna!&gt;&gt; Ropa Petrus padhai lii sèmi èèna, kaca'a laa manu kokotoo.<bt>But Petrus denied even more strongly, saying, “You're speaking emptily there (=lying)!” When Petrus spoke like.that, then the chicken crowed.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Hèia Yesus kabib'a sa nèngu. Ka Petrus sanèd'e lii Yesus deo na, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Mèda ne'e ne kahèi, manu dhae kokotoo mèka, te èu pasili le Ja'a tèlu hari kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus turned his head to (look at) him. And Petrus remembered that earlier speaking of Yesus', saying, “Tonight, the chicken will not yet crow, but [contrary to expectation] you will have already denied Me three times.”</bt><v n="62" />Ngee nèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia Petrus kalua nèti madha èmu ne, dènge tangi dhu d'ara laho mae-mae.<bt>Remembering that, then Petrus went out from that yard crying sobbingly/remorsefully.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra game aa pahaha Lamatua Yesus<bt>They beat and humiliate the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:67-68; Markus 14:65)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="63" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu dhu j'aga Yesus, padhai lii pahaha Ne, dènge game pa'oke Ne.<bt>After that, those people who were guarding Yesus began to mock Him, and repeatedly beat Him.</bt><v n="64" />Ra pahutu rèhu Na pake bèla, ka ra karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Ladhe èu ne dhèu mèti lii padhai Lamatua, na, èu peka sèku! Cee ka dhu j'ubhu èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they shut His eyes using cloth, and asked Him, saying, “Wee! If you-sg are the Lord's spokesperson, na, try to discern! Who is it that is punching you?</bt><v n="65" />Èle ka, ra padhèd'a aape Ne.<bt>Then they verbally abused/swore.at Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhède aape = maki ancor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">padhède aape = maki ancor</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ètu era pama'ète lii langu agama<bt>The Lord Yesus in the place of deciding religious litigations</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:59-66; Markus 14:55-64; Yohanis 18:19-24)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="66" />Mad'ae aae era, kètu agama Yahudi, mese agama, dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi sèra, pakaboko le uri lii langu Yesus. Ka ra pua dhèu lasi nuni rèti Yesus asa era pama'ète lii langu agama.<bt>Still early morning, the chief priests, the religion teachers, and the traditional elders had gathered to handle Yesus' litigation/case. Then they order that a person drag/lead bring Yesus to the place of dealing with religious litigations.</bt><v n="67" />Ropa Yesus maso, ka ra karèi Ne, &lt;&lt;Èu peka ku laa! Èu ne, tare'a Kristus, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When He had entered, then they asked Him, saying, “Tell us! Are you here truly the Kristus, [tag question]?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Na b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Masi ka Ja'a dhaa na tare'a, miu se lèka boe.<bt>Then He replied, saying, “Even if I answer truly, you-pl won't believe.</bt><v n="68" />Aa ladhe Ja'a bari miu ca madha j'ara, tatu miu dhaa boe.<bt>And if I reciprocate and ask you something, surely you won't answer.</bt><v n="69" />Nèbhu heka Ama Lamatua pake koasa Na dhu kapai èèna, ded'e padedha-dedha Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Ho èèna na, Ja'a madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana Na, sèna ka paredha sama-sama dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Not much longer, Father God will use His amazing power/authority, to raise Me up, this Authentic Human. Then I will sit at His right side to govern/rule together with Him.”</bt><note reference="22:69" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="70" />Ropa ra tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka aa'i-aa'i ra karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, Èu ngee, na, Èu ne Ana Ama Lamatua, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then they all asked, saying, “If that's the case, do You think that You here are Father God's Child, [tag question]?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a, sèmi dhu miu peka na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “That's true, like you said.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="71" />Hèia dhèu dhu uri lii langu se, aa'i-aa'i peka, na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti tadèngi le, si? Na ded'e iisi Na, j'aj'i Ana Ama Lamatua. Ne'e ne lii pahahe kolongara Ama Lamatua! Madhutu atora agama èdhi, ladhe dhèu tao iisi ra nuka sèmi Lamatua, dhèu ne hud'i madhe ku. De tasamia? Èdhi parluu heka sakasii. Huku pamadhe Ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those people who handle litigations all/enthusiastically talked, saying, “We-inc all have heard ourselves, right? He lifts himself to be Father God's Child. This is slander/ blasphemy (= slandering the name/reputation of Father God)! According to our-inc religious regulations, if someone makes himself the same as the Lord, that person must die. So (consequently) how about it? We-inc don't need witnesses anymore. Sentence/punish Him with death!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lere rèti Lamatua Yesus asa gubernur Pilatus<bt>They bring the Lord Yesus to gubernor Pilatus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:1-2, 11-14; Markus 15:1-5; Yohanis 18:28-38)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <v n="1" />Masi ka dhèu uri lii langu agama Yahudi sèra pama'ète rare le sèna ka huku pamadhe Yesus, te ngaa rèngu dènge boe hak ho huku pamadhe dhèu. Nèti èèna ka, lere rèti Yesus asa madha gubernur nèti paredha Roma, dhu ètu èèna nuka Pilatus. Rèngu d'èi ladhe gubernur ka dhu huku Ne.<bt>Even though those who were handling the Yahudi religious litigations had already handed down the decision to punish Yesus with death, nevertheless they did not have the right/authority to sentence/punish people to death. That's why they brought Yesus to face the governor from the Roma government, who in that place was Pilatus. They wanted, that the governor be the one to sentence/ punish Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa, dhèu uri lii langu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Te ngaa, dhèu uri lii langu agama Yahudi sèra dènge boe hak ho huku pamadhe dhèu.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />De ropa d'ai madha gubernur, ra lole sasala Yesus èci-èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, tuka lab'a paredha Roma. Na aj'a peka na, dhèu baku b'ae bea sa dhèu paredha. Na ded'e iisi Na, peka na, Nèngu ne, Kristus, dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) arriving in front of the governor, then they narrated each of Yesus' wrongs, saying, “This person here, is a habitual opposer to the Roma government. He teaches that people shouldn't pay tax to the government. He also lifts himself up saying that he here is Kristus, the Yahudi people's king.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka gubernur karèi Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, do? Èu ne, dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then the governor asked Him, saying, “Is that true? Are you the Yahudi people's king, [tag question]?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Sèmi lii padhai ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus replied, saying, “True. It's like what father (=you) say.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Parisa èle ka, gubernur ladhe sa kètu agama Yahudi, dènge dhèu ae sèra. Ka na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a abhu boe sasala Dhèu ne ciki sa hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>After he finished examining him, the governor looked at those chief priests and those many people. Then he spoke, saying, “It's like.this. I don't find this Person has even a little bit of wrong.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa dhèu se pakadhii taruu, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, ama gubernur. Dhèu ne la'e aj'a sa mia-mia, ho kakèj'i kabarai, sèna ka palab'a dènge dhèu paredha. Na tao maruru mulai nèti propensi Galilea toke d'ai kota Yerusalem ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>But they persisted, saying, “No, father gub. This person goes teaching everywhere, poking (=provoking) citizens to rebel against the government. He had made chaos starting from Galilea province to Yerusalem city here.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Gubernur hia rèti Lamatua Yesus asa dhèu aae Herodes<bt>The Governor sends the Lord Yesus to king Herodes</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia gubernur karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, Nèngu ne dhèu Galilea, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that then, the governor asked them, saying, “If that's the case, is he a Galilea person?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu se dhaa, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Nèngu nèti Galilea.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they answered, “True. He is from Galilea.”</bt><v n="7" />Ropa ne'a nare sèmi èèna, hèia gubernur pua lere rèti Yesus asa dhèu aae Herodes, dhu paredha propensi Galilea. Lod'o èèna, nèngu ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>Finding out like.that, then the governor ordered Yesus to be led to face king Herodes who governed Galilea province. At at time, he was in the city of Yerusalem.</bt><v n="8" />Herodes ne, dhu tadèngi ae le, dhèu palolo tatao Yesus, aa nèbhu le neo paraga dènge Ne kahèi. Nèngu dhu sanao-maena bisa nèdhi dènge madha na tadha malaa èci-dua sa nèti Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o lere rèti Yesus asa nèngu, d'ara na karej'e.<bt>This king Herodes had heard people tell lots about Yesus' deeds/behaviour and for a long time he had been desiring to meet Him too. He was hoping (doublet) to be able to see for himself Yesus show one-or-two miracles. That's why, when they brought Yesus to him, his insides were happy.</bt><v n="9" />Hèia na karèi Yesus rupa-rupa j'ara, te ngaa Yesus dhaa boe ca hèb'a sa.<bt>Then he asked Yesus all.sorts of things, but He didn't respond a single word.</bt><v n="10" />Ropa Herodes padhai lii era dènge Yesus, te ngaa kètu agama Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra galaa hari Yesus dènge rupa-rupa sasala.<bt>Herodes was still talking with Yesus, but the chief priests and the religion teachers began to accuse Yesus again of all.sorts of wrongs. [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk here is ambiguous between whether Herod had finished and the accusations started as simultaneous or sequential. English translations vary on that point. So if simultaneous as above is problematic, then just use a sequential connector ‘then’.]</bt><v n="11" />Hèia dhèu aae Herodes dènge sordad'u na padhai lii pahahe Ne. Ka ra papake Yesus kodho saraga dhu madhera robho d'ai rai èci, sèmi dhèu aae tema pake, hèia ra padhai lii pahahe Ne taruu. Ka rèti hari Ne la'e asa gubernur Pilatus.<bt>Then king Herodes and his soldiers began to mock Him. Then they put on Him a beautiful long clothing like kings usually wore, then they continued to mock/ridicule Him. Then2 they sent him back to governor Pilatus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@GRAM: kodho saraga dhu madhera robho"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">@GRAM: kodho saraga dhu madhera robho dai rai èci = kodho saraga èci dhu madhera robho dai rai</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Uru nèti èèna, gubernur dènge dhèu aae Herodes dhu pamusu. Te ngaa nèti lod'o èèna, dua ra pa'angalai.<bt>Previously, the governor and king Herodes were mutual enemies. But starting from that day the two of them were mutual friends.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="**(Team thinks this is mistake or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">**(Team thinks this is mistake or misunderstanding) Diperhatikan: Pahahe artinya: Bertatapan muka. Pahaha artinya: Berbicara tdk bertatapan muka.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakadheke ai = bergandengan tangan (=bersahabat,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pakadheke ai = bergandengan tangan (=bersahabat, kerjasama)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Gubernur pama'ète huku madhe mi Lamatua Yesus<bt>The governor decides a death sentence for the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:15-26; Markus 15:6-15; Yohanis 18:39--19:16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, gubernur Pilatus paroa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi, sama-sama dènge dhèu ae sèra, mai pakaboko ho nanene lii pama'ète.<bt>After that, governor Pilatus called the chief priests and other traditional leaders together with those many people, to come gather and hear his decision.</bt><v n="14" />Aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu mèti le Yesus asa ja'a, aa mi galaa Ne, peka na, Nèngu d'èi kakèj'i kabarai ho lab'a paredha Roma. Ja'a parisa le toke lutu ètu madha miu, te ngaa ja'a abhu boe sasala Na èci sa.<bt>He said, “You-pl brought Yesus to me, and accused him, saying He likes to stir up the people to oppose the Roma government. I have examined Him very carefully (in detail) in front of you, but I have not found anything He has done wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apostrephonta: turning the people away from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">apostrephonta: turning the people away from allegiance to Rome was the hot button the leaders pressed. "misleading" in some translations misses the political overtones because it sounds like maybe Jesus' doctrine wasn't pure enough for the religious leaders; but Pilate wouldn't have taken that argument as seriously as he took "apostrephonta."</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Dhèu aae Herodes parisa le kahèi. Te ngaa na abhu boe sasala ngaa-ngaa kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, na hia hari Ne mai sa ja'a. Dhèu Ne dènge boe sasala ngaa-ngaa. De ja'a bisa boe huku pamadhe Ne.<bt>King Herodes has also examined Him. But didn't find anything He did wrong either. That's why he sent this Person back to me. This Person hasn't done any wrong, so I cannot sentence/punish Him to death.</bt><v n="16" />Ja'a neo pama'ète sèmi ne'e: ja'a pua kalabhe Ne pake gui, èle na ja'a patabuli eele Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), I am going to decide like.this: I will order to whip/beat Him, and then I will release Him.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhedhe = titi, hit (with fists)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhedhe = titi, hit (with fists) ; hake pake gui</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia ra pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe! Pamadhe Ne! Patabuli Barabas.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing like.that, then they began to yell (doublet), saying, “Not.allowed! Kill Him! Release Barabas.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">[Ra pa'oo-parodha sèmi èèna, lula tèu mai-tèu mai, dhu tema le, ladhe d'ai lod'o kalela Paska dhèu Yahudi, gubernur patabuli ca dhèu nèti d'ara bèdho madhutu dad'èi rèngu].<bt>[They yelled like.that, because every year when the Yahudi people had Paska feast, the governor usually released one jail person according to their desires.]</bt><note reference="23:17" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat 17 dhu ètu d'ara kurung, abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru sèra.<bt>This verse 17 in parentheses, is not found in the Yunani language writing which are the very oldest.</bt></note><v n="19" />(Barabas ne maso bèdho, lula na kakèj'i dhèu lab'a paredha Roma ètu kota Yerusalem, aa na pamadhe dhèu kahèi.)<bt>(This Barabas, was put in jail, because he was a habitual provocateur (stirred up the people) to rebel against the Roma government in Yerusalem city, and he also murdered person/people.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa gubernur neo patabuli Yesus. Ka na karèi hari dhèu ae sèra, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ladhe ja'a patabuli Yesus?&gt;&gt;<bt>But the governor wanted to free Yesus. So he asked again to those many people, “How about it if I release Yesus?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Te ngaa asa ra pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha! Paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they all yelled boisterously saying, “No! Just nail kill Him on the crossed wood! Nail kill Him on the crossed wood!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="KT for discussion = aj'u palolo-palèbha,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">KT for discussion = aj'u palolo-palèbha, ada usul aj'u palèbha-palolo ; palebha = palang (horizontal) ; palolo 2 = vertical ; but doublet can also carry meaning of a pile of wood laying all helter-skelter</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa gubernur ngee na j'ara ne lèke boe, ka na karèi d'ai tèlu hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka ja'a madhutu miu ho paku pamadhe Ne? Bhabhelu Na ngaa? Ja'a parisa le Nèngu ne, te ngaa abhu boe j'ara èci sa kahèi, ho huku pamadhe Ne. De ja'a neo dhoka kalabhe Ne, èle ku, heka patabuli Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the governor felt that that was not right, so he asked again for the third time, saying, “Why should I nail kill Him? What is his evil? I have examined Him, but I have not found even one reason why I should sentence/punish Him to death. So (consequently), just let me order to whip/beat Him, and when that's done then free/release Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra pa'oo-parodha hari pamèdhu-mèdhu, sèna ka laka-seti ne ho paku pamadhe Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Hèia gubernur taha nare heka,<bt>But all those people yelled even louder, to force him to nail kill him on the crossed wood. Finally, the governor could not endure anymore,</bt><v n="24" />ka na pama'ète madhutu dad'èi dhèu sèra.<bt>so he decided to follow their will/desires.</bt><v n="25" />Hèia na patabuli Barabas, ca dhèu dhu d'èi palab'a, dènge pamadhe dhèu. Te ngaa na soro Yesus la'e asa adhe-aai dhèu se'e, sèna ka ra tao Ne madhutu dad'èi rèngu.<bt>Then he freed Barabas, that habitual rebel and murderer. But he surrendered/handed over Yesus to their hands, so that they could do to Him according to their desires.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra paku pamadhe Lamatua Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha<bt>They nail hanging the Lord Yesus on the *cross (crossed wood)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:32-44; Markus 15:21-32; Yohanis 19:17-27)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle ka, sordad'u Roma sèra nuni rèti Yesus asa li'u kota Yerusalem. Ètu talora j'ara, ra paraga dènge dhèu èci nèti kota Kirene, dhu ngara na Simon, dhu neo maso asa d'ara kota Yerusalem. Ka ra laka-seti ne, sèna ka pasae aj'u palolo-palèbha ne gati Yesus. Ka na kako re limuri madhutu Yesus.<bt>After that, they pulled brought Yesus outside of Yerusalem city. In the middle of the road they met a man from the city of Kirene named Simon, who was just about to enter the city of Yerusalem. They forced him to substitute carry Yesus' crossed wood, then to walk following behind Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ètu talora j'ara, ra paraga dènge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Ètu talora j'ara, ra paraga dènge dhèu èci, dhu heka mai nèti kota Kirene. Ngara na Simon.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae mai laladhe Yesus. Abhu kahèi ina-ina dhu pasuti èi madha, lula d'ara pèd'a ropa rèdhi Ne.<bt>That day, many people come to watch (the spectacle of) Yesus. There were also various women who wept for Him.</bt><v n="28" />Ropa Yesus ladhe bhèni se tangi, hèia Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina-ina nèti Yerusalem. Baku tangi Ja'a ne. Tangi hiu ngi'u miu mesa mi, dènge ana niki miu.<bt>Seeing the women cry like.that, then Yesus spoke, saying, “Mothers of Yerusalem. Don't cry for Me. Cry for your own selves and your children.</bt><v n="29" />Te bèli-camèd'a, sasusa dhu kapai risi mai, hèia dhèu peka na, &lt;Bhèni dhu kalua hua iia, nuka, bhèni dhu rara iisi rèdhi boe, aa dhu pasusu rèdhi boe ana.&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in the future great difficulty will come, and people will say, ‘The women who are the most fortunate, are women who have never given birth, and never nursed newborns.’</bt><v n="30" />Lod'o sasusa aae na mai, dhèu j'èra titu kèna, toke ra manèngi, peka na, &lt;Be'a risi, ledhe guri mai ho kabhie ka ji'i!&gt; Aa ra peka kahèi, &lt;Dènge j'aj'èra sèmi ne'e ne, be'a risi kabhuku dhènu eele ka ji'i.&gt;<bt>When those difficult days come, people will suffer greatly, to.the.point.that they will ask, saying, ‘It's better, the mountains fall over and crush us down!’ The also speak, saying, ‘With suffering like this, it's better the hills bury us!’</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhuku = bukit ; bèbhe ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kabhuku = bukit ; bèbhe = fall from above ; guri = fall over</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hosea 10:8, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 6:16</note><v n="31" />Ladhe dhèu bisa paj'èra dhèu dhu dènge boe sasala, tasamia hari mi dhèu bhelu?&gt;&gt;<bt>If people can cause suffering like this for people who have not done wrong, how much more with evil people?” [EXEG: following Marshall, Barclay, CEV note &amp; TN.]</bt><note reference="23:31" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara sasuri lii Yunani uru èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu re'a tao sèmi ne'e mi aj'u dhu mamuri era, ngaa hari dènge aj'u dhu madhe le.&gt;&gt;<bt>The original Yunani language writing says, ‘If people can do like this with trees that are still living, even.more.so with trees which are dead.”</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa sordad'u se rèti Yesus, ra nuni rèti kahèi dhèu bhelu dhèu dua, ho huku pamadhe palere-lere dènge Ne.<bt>When the soldiers were bringing Yesus, they also dragged/led brought two evil people to punish kill together with Him.</bt><v n="33" />Rèngu d'ai era èci, dhu ngara na &lt;Rui Kètu.&gt; Hèia ra paku Yesus dènge dhèu bhelu dhèu dua se, mi aj'u palolo-palèbha ra èci-èci. Ka ra sèle patitu aj'u palolo-palèbha sèra. Ra hia dhèu bhelu èci ètu karasa g'ana Yesus, aa èci hari ètu karasa kariu Na.<bt>They arrived at a place, called &lt;Head Bone (=skull)&gt;. Then they nailed Yesus and those two evil people on each one's crossed wood. Then they planted standing up those crossed woods. They hung one evil person on Yesus' right side, and the other one on His left side. [NOTE to daughter translations: Luke version doesn't mention proper name of ‘Golgotha’; just ‘Place of the Skull’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />[Lod'o èèna, Yesus sabaj'a peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Bhèlu eele sasala dhèu se, te rèngu re'a boe ngaa dhu ra ad'u-ue.&gt;&gt;]<bt>[At that time, Yesus prayed, saying, “Father! Completely forget these people's wrong/s, cuz (elaboration) they don't know what they do.”]</bt><note reference="23:34a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii padhai ètu d'ara kurung ne'e, abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru tèka dènge dhu be'a risi.<bt>That verse in parentheses, does not exist in many of the oldest and best Yunani language writings.</bt></note>Èle ka sordad'u se ère lot, sèna ka neo re'a cee ka dhu abhu mèdha-papake Na.<bt>Then the soldiers pull/drew lots to find out who got His clothes (doublet).</bt><note reference="23:34b" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Dhèu ae mai laladhe ètu era èèna. Dhèu aae-dhèu kapai Yahudi sèra, peka pa-aape Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu dhu patabuli nare le dhèu leo nèti mamadhe-mamopo, te ngaa bisa boe patabuli ngi'u Nèngu mesa Na. Ladhe Nèngu ne, tare'a-re'a Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare, hud'i laa Na puru unu Na nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Many people came to watch/spectate at that place. The Yahudi leaders ridiculed Yesus, saying, “He has saved other people, but can't save/release His own self. If He here really is Kristus, whom Father God choose ahead.of.time, well.then, let Him get himself down from that crossed wood.” [NOTE: not chief priests here, but leaders.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paaape = VVV = minghina, merendahkan;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">paaape = VVV = minghina, merendahkan; laladhe = spectate, gawk</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Sordad'u se padhai lii pa-aape Ne kahèi. Ra hia Ne ninu èi anggor manyilu,<bt>Those soldiers also ridiculed Him. They gave Him sour grapejuice to drink,</bt><note reference="23:36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:22</note><v n="37" />aa ra parodha pahaha Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Èu ne tare'a-re'a dhèu aae Yahudi, na, patabuli eele ka ngi'u Mu nèti mamadhe!&gt;&gt;<bt>and called out mockingly, saying, “If You here really are the Yahudi people's king, well.then save Yourself from death!”</bt><v n="38" />Ra suri ètu papa èci, peka na,<bt>They wrote on a board, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>“This is the Yahudi people's king.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra paku papa ne re dedha kètu Yesus, sèna ka dhèu re'a, na, ra huku Ne lula j'ara ne'e ka.<bt>Then they nailed that board above Yesus' head, to tell the reason they punished Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ca dhèu bhelu dhu paku ètu karasa Yesus padhai lii pa-aape Ne kahèi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne tare'a Kristus, do? Ladhe tare'a, na, patabuli eele ka èdhi!&gt;&gt;<bt>One of the evil people who was nailed hanging at Yesus' side also went along mocking, saying, “Are you really Kristus? If that is true, na, save/release us all!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Te ngaa dhèu bhelu èci hari kai ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Èu ne me'a boe madha'u dènge Ama Lamatua, hèi? Te èu ne abhu huku madhe èci èèna ka dènge Nèngu kahèi.<bt>But the other evil person scolded him, saying, “Weh! Don't you know to be afraid of Father God? Cuz (elaboration) you also got a death sentence like Him.</bt><v n="41" />Èdhi dua ti pasae tare huku madhe ne, lèke dènge tatao èdhi. Te ngaa Dhèu ne, tao boe sasala ngaa-ngaa.&gt;&gt;<bt>The two of us-inc got punishment fitting with our-inc deeds. But this Person has not done any evil.”</bt><v n="42" />Ka dhèu ne, peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yesus! Ladhe Ama maso ka asa era paredha Ama, na baku bhèlu ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he spoke in addition, saying, “Yesus! When Father (=you) enters into Father's kingdom, na, don't forget me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ja'a peka tare'a-re'a dènge èu kèna, na, lod'o deo ne'e kahèi, èu lamu asa sorga palere-lere dènge Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus replied, “I tell you truly that even today you will enter into heaven together with Me.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="moa = promise (but can imply"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">moa = promise (but can imply after a distance of time)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paradeisooi: from a Persian word for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">paradeisooi: from a Persian word for a rich person's private hunting park, a place well kept and pleasant. Our word "Paradise" comes from it. SK "O cute!"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus madhe<bt>The Lord Yesus dies</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:45-56; Markus 15:33-41; Yohanis 19:28-30)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44-45" />Lod'o èèna, dhu lod'o nètu le. Te ngaa madha lod'o saraa boe, aa maroga kiu-kiu abhe nare era èèna, toke d'ai hake tèlu lod'o nihia. Ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, abhu bèla bhèla aae èci dhu ra kadhoe pa'abhe Kama Luri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Kaca'a laa, bèla ne mae bagi mi dua.<bt>At that time, it was midday. But the sun did not shine, so extreme darkness covered over that place until three in the afternoon. At the Central Worship House there was a big curtain which was hung to block.off Father God's Room that was Most Clean/Holy. Suddenly, that curtain tore separating in two.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèla bhèla"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bèla bhèla</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 26:31-33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Ètu era dhu ngara na &lt;Rui Kètu&gt; èèna, Yesus pa'oo, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a pangèd'u samanga Ja'a mi d'ara adhe-aai Ama.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii èle, hèia Yesus ma'ète a'ae.<bt>In that named ‘Place of the Skull’, Yesus called out, saying, “Father! Now I surrender/turn over My spirit/soul/life force to Father's hands.” When finished speaking like.that, then Yesus breath stopped right.away (=he died).</bt><note reference="23:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 31:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Abhu komedhaa sordad'u Roma titu ètu era èèna, dhu padètu dènge aj'u palolo-palèbha Yesus. Ropa ladhe nèdhi Yesus madhe, ka na koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Dhèu ne'e ne, tare'a re'a Dhèu d'ara mola!&gt;&gt;<bt>There was a Roma soldier standing near Yesus' crossed wood. When he saw that death of Yesus, then he praised (doublet) Father God, saying, “Waa! This Person is truly a straight livered Person (=honest/not guilty)!”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dikaios: not &quot;righteous,&quot; but in this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">dikaios: not "righteous," but in this context "innocent, not guilty"</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:47" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ètu ne'e, sasoa na, bisa kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne dènge boe sasala.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yunani language words here, can also mean, “This Person does not have wrong/s.”</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ropa dhèu ae sèra rèdhi mamadhe Yesus, ra manyasa, dènge d'ara ra roe bhilu, ka ra lèpa dènge d'ara susa.<bt>When the many people who were gathered there saw Yesus' death, they were regretful, and then went.home with distressed insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe bhilu = susa ; bhilu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">roe bhilu = susa ; bhilu = ?? (not known, \lf Max for roe)</Message></Annotation><v n="49" />Te ngaa dhèu-dhèu Yesus titu ètu kaj'èu, rèdhi Na madhe. Ina-ina dhu madhutu Ne nèti Galilea toke Yerusalem, ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>But Yesus' people were standing far off, watching His death. The women who followed Him from Galilea to Yerusalem, were also there.</bt><note reference="23:49" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 8:2-3</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu padhane Lamatua Yesus<bt>They bury the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:57-61; Markus 15:42-47; Yohanis 19:38-42)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50-51" />Ropa Yesus madhe, dhèu èci tenge j'ara, sèna ka papuru ngi'u aae Na nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha. Dhèu ne, ngara na Yusuf nèti kota Arimatea. Nèngu ne, dhèu d'ara mola, tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a. Yusuf ne dhu tatae Ama Lamatua pad'elo, na, Nèngu nèd'u paredha Na. Yusuf kahèi ca dhèu nèti dhèu dhu uri lii langu agama Yahudi. Te ngaa nèngu d'èi boe dènge lii pama'ète huku madhe mi Yesus.<bt>When Yesus died, there was a person who sought a way to take down His corpse from that crossed wood. This person's name was Yusuf, from Arimatea city. His insides liver was straight (=righteous), doing many good things. Yusuf was waiting for the Lord to show that He ruling/ governing. Yusuf was also a member who sat to take.care of Yahudi religious litigations, but he did not agree with their decision to sentence Yesus to death.</bt><v n="52" />Lula na neo papuru ngi'u aae Yesus nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha, ka la'e asa gubernur Pilatus, manèngi sèna ka nèngu uri ngi'u aae Yesus.<bt>Because he wanted to take down Yesus' corpse from the crossed wood, he went to governor Pilatus to request to take.care of Yesus corpse.</bt><v n="53" />Ka Pilatus d'èi, hèia Yusuf la'e papuru ngi'u aae Yesus. Èle ka na pahutu ngi'u aae dènge bèla alus. Ka ded'e rèti asa d'ara ro'a hadhu èci, dhu heka pae rare kèna. Ètu ro'a ne, padhane rèdhi mèka ca dhèu sa.<bt>After Pilatus agreed, then Yusuf went to take it down. Then he wrapped that corpse in fine cloth. Next he went to put that corpse in a stone/ rock hole, which people had just chisled. In that hole, they had not yet buried anyone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kain kapan = BI kain yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kain kapan = BI kain yg disediakan untuk bungkus mayat ; bèla alus = tipis dan licin, mahal, dan bermutu ; bèla nidhu</Message></Annotation><v n="54" />Mamadhe Yesus lèke dènge hari Jumat. Lod'o Yusuf si padhane rare Ne, lod'o nihia le. Ladhe lod'o cèna, d'ai lod'o sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi.<bt>Yesus' death happened on Friday. When Yusuf (collective) had buried Him, it was already late afternoon. If/when the sun went.down, then the Yahudi people's worship day had arrived. [See Marshall, NCV, TN, etc.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soro le = late afternoon (until"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">soro le = late afternoon (until about 4) ; lod'o nihia = just before dust</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Ina-ina dhu mai palere dènge Yesus nèti Galilea, lasi madhutu Yusuf nèti limuri, sèna ka neo re'a era padhane Yesus ètu ro'a mia.<bt>Those women who came together with Yesus from Galilea, they folowed Yusuf from behind, in.order.to know which (of possibilities) hole he had buried Yesus in.</bt><v n="56" />Ropa rèdhi era ne, ka ina se lèpa lasi sadia bunga dènge èi hèu mèngi. D'ai lod'o cèna, rèngu ae nèti sasab'a ra, madhutu atora lod'o a'ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi. Rèngu mate èle ku lod'o sabaj'a, heka neo lasi tao bunga mi ngi'u aae Yesus kèna.<bt>Watching/Seeing carefully that place, then those women went.home to prepare flowers/grave.spices and fragrant oil. When the sun went down, they stopped work, according to the Yahudi people's regulation for the worship day. They waited for that worship day to pass, then they wanted to go put the flowers/grave.spices on Yesus' corpse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="entoleen: commandment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">entoleen: commandment</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:56" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:10, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:14</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mamuri hari!<bt>The Lord Yesus lives again!</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 28:1-10; Markus 16:1-8; Yohanis 20:1-10)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o hari Migu oe mèu sa, ina se rèti bunga dènge èi hèu mèngi, ho lasi ro'a Yesus.<bt>Sunday almost dawn, those women brought that fragrant oil and grave spices to go to Yesus' grave/hole.</bt><v n="2" />Ropa rèngu d'ai nèi, ladhe rèdhi hadhu aae dhu Yusuf pake katange ro'a Yesus, dhu bhaloli le sa karasa na.<bt>When they arrived there, they saw the big stone which Yusuf had used to close Yesus' grave, was already rolled to the side.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhaloli = taguling, digulingkan ; loli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">bhaloli = taguling, digulingkan ; loli = guling ; paloli = menggulingkan</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Hèia lasi dènge ka asa d'ara, te ngaa abhu boe ngi'u aae Yesus.<bt>Then they entered into the grave, but they did not see Yesus' corpse there.</bt><v n="4" />Ka rèngu ele ngangee. Cag'ag'a laa dhèu dua dhu pake mèdha kale'e, mai titu ka ètu sebhe rèngu.<bt>So they were very confused. Suddenly, two people who wore shiny clothes, came and stood at their side.</bt><v n="5" />Ina se madha'u bia, ka ra pacud'u d'ai rai. Ka dhèu se karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu mai tenge dhèu mamuri ètu era dhèu madhe?<bt>Those women were very afraid, so they bowed to the ground. Then those two people asked, saying, “Why are you-pl coming looking for people who live in dead people's place?</bt><v n="6" />Yesus aad'o heka ètu era ne'e! Te Na mamuri hari le. Ele boe miu bhèlu eele le, ngaa dhu peka nare, lod'o Na ètu Galilea era, sina ma?<bt>Yesus isn't here anymore! Cuz (elaboration) He already lives again. Probably you-pl have forgotten what He once said when still in Galilea, [tag question]?</bt><v n="7" />Te Nèngu peka mema le, na, bèli-camèd'a ra pahie eele Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, asa d'ara adhe-aai dhèu bhelu-katub'a. Hèia ra paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Te ngaa asa camèd'a èèna, Nèngu mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) He had foretold that, they would sell off/betray the Authentic Human to evil (doublet) people's hands. Then they would nail kill Him on the crossed wood. But the day.after.tomorrow, He would live again.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Bhaloli artinya Di gulingkan. Loli"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">Diperhatikan: Bhaloli artinya Di gulingkan. Loli artinya: Digulingkan.</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:6-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:21, 17:22-23, 20:18-19, Markus 8:31, 9:31, 10:33-34, Lukas 9:22, 18:31-33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa tadèngi rare, heka rèngu sanèd'e lii padhai Yesus uru èèna.<bt>Hearing like.that, then they remembered that speaking of Yesus previously.</bt><v n="9" />Hèia ra lèpa dènge ka, lasi peka dènge ana madhutu Yesus dhèu canguru èci sèra, dènge dhèu-dhèu leo dhu madhutu Ne.<bt>Then2 they immediately went home, to tell everything to Yesus eleven underlings, and the other people who followed Him.</bt><v n="10" />(Ina-ina dhu ètu ro'a èèna, nuka Maria ina Yakobis, dènge Maria nèti rae Magdala. Abhu kahèi Yohana dènge ina-ina dhèu pèri dhu leo. Rèngu se'e ka dhu lasi peka aa'i-aa'i dènge ana-ana pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra.)<bt>(The women who went to that grave, were Yakobis' mother Maria, and Maria from Magdala village. There was also Yohana and several other women. They were the ones who went to tell all this to Yesus' commissioned ones/apostles.) [NOTE to daughter translations: Why is this in parentheses? Because it's author's background comment out of place.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa ropa ana madhutu sèra tadèngi lii lolo ne, ra pangee na ina se monya.<bt>But when the disciples/followers heard that story, they they thought that those womens were just speaking emptily (=deceiving).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia Petrus kèd'i dènge ka, rai la'e asa ro'a. D'ai nèi, na patigi sa d'ara ro'a, te ngaa nèdhi dhoka bèla hutu di. Hèia na lèpa, ka na pangee, &lt;&lt;Sa mia ka ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus got up and ran to the grave. Arriving there, he looked inside that grave, but he only saw just the wrapping cloth. Then he went home thinking/mulling it over, “How is this [possible]?”</bt><note reference="24:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e dhu suri boe ayat 12 ne.<bt>Some of the Yunani language writings don't write this verse 12.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana madhutu dhèu dua paraga dènge Lamatua Yesus ètu j'ara la'e asa Emaus<bt>Two underlings meet the Lord Yesus on the road to Emaus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 16:12-13)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, ana madhutu Yesus dhèu dua lasi asa rae cue, ngara na Emaus. Kaj'èu na pe d'ai canguru ca kilo nèti kota Yerusalem.<bt>That same day, two of Yesus' underlings went to a village, named Emaus. It's distance was approximately 11 kilometres from Yerusalem city.</bt><note reference="24:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;60 <span class="Italic">stadia</span> nèti Yerusalem&gt;&gt;. 60 <span class="Italic">stadia</span> èèna, èci èèna ka dènge canguru èci koma èci (11,1) kilometer.<bt>The Yunani language writings say, “60 stadia from Yerusalem. 60 stadia are the same as 11.1 kilo.</bt></note><v n="14" />Ètu j'ara, ra palolo nèti mamadhe Yesus.<bt>They walked while mutually.talking about Yesus' death.</bt><v n="15" />Kabèdhi laa, Yesus padètu-dètu le dènge rèngu dua ra, ka kako palere-lere dènge ra.<bt>Unexpectedly, Yesus himself came near to the two of them, then walked together with them.</bt><v n="16" />Te ngaa dua ra tadhe boe, Dhèu ne, Yesus, te Lamatua ka dhu tao si, sèna ka baku ra tadhe.<bt>But they did not recognize that this Person was Yesus, cuz (elaboration) the Lord made it so they didn't recognize [him]. [NLT + TN]</bt><v n="17" />Hèia Yesus karèi si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu dua mi se, padhue-padhai ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked them, saying, “What are you two so busy talking about?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa ra tadèngi sèmi èèna, ka ra titu. Rèhu ra sèmi dhèu susa titu kèna.<bt>Hearing like.that, then the two of them stopped (walking; LIT: stood). Their faces were like they were very distressed.</bt><v n="18" />Ka dhu ngara na Kleopas, karèi Ne, &lt;&lt;Ama ne sèmi dhèu hiu sa, dhu me'a boe ngaa-ngaa dhu lai-lai ne j'aj'i ètu Yerusalem, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, the one named Kleopas, asked Him, “Father here is like a new person who doesn't know anything about what just happened in Yerusalem here, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia Yesus karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked, saying, “What's that?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus nèti Nasaret èèna! Nèngu na tare'a dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Aa Lamatua pangèd'u Na koasa, ka Na tao tadha malaa rupa-rupa. Nèngu d'èlu-mèu kahèi aj'a-nori dhèu. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e dènge Ne. Aa Lamatua karej'e dènge Ne kahèi.<bt>They replied, saying, “About that Yesus from Nasaret! He is truly Father God's spokesperson. And the Lord gave power/authority to Him to do all.sorts of miracles. He is also skilled in teaching people. All the people are happy with Him. And the Lord also is happy with Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa te'a boe, na, kètu agama èdhi dènge dhèu heka ad'a sèra, kèpe rare Ne. Ka ra hia Ne asa gubernur sèna ka huku pamadhe Ne. De ra paku Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha toke madhe.<bt>But contrary.to.what.one.might.expect, our-exc *chief priests and the traditional elders captured/arrested Him. Then they gave Him to the governor to sentence/punish Him to death. So (consequently) they nailed Him on crossed wood until dead.</bt><v n="21" />Uru èèna, ji'i sanao Nèngu ne'e ka Kristus, dhu mai patabuli dhèu-dhèu èdhi nèti paredha Roma, dhu paj'èra èdhi. Te ngaa ètu d'ara hari Jumat lai-lai ne, ra pamadhe Ne.<bt>In the beginning we hoped that He was the Kristus, who came to free/save our nation/people from the Roma government that oppresses us. But last Friday, they killed Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hari jumat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">hari jumat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Limuri ne, ji'i asa ele ngangee. Te deo na, ina-ina ji'i mai peka, na, mad'ae aae era rèngu lasi asa ro'a.<bt>Now, we-exc are even more confused. Cuz (elaboration) earlier our women came to report, that, in the early morning they went to the grave.</bt><v n="23" />Te ngaa ra palolo, peka na, ngi'u aae Yesus ele le. Hèia ladhe rèdhi ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga dhu peka dènge rèngu, na, Yesus mamuri hari le!<bt>But they narrated, saying, Yesus' corpse had disappeared. Then they saw Father God's underlings from heaven, who told them, saying, Yesus was alive again!</bt><v n="24" />Ropa tadèngi ngare, hèia angalai ji'i dhèu pèri-pèri, rai lasi asa ro'a. Ka rèdhi sèmi dhu ina-ina sa peka. Rèngu rèdhi boe ngi'u aae Yesus hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>After hearing that, then several of our friends ran to the grave. And they saw like what those women had said. They also did not see Yesus' corpse.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ropa lolo rare, Yesus lii dènge si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Gagoa miu se! Nga tao ka miu mo'o boe parcaya ngaa dhu uru èèna dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra peka tèke!<bt>The two of them finished telling the story like.that, then Yesus spoke to them, saying, “You-pl are stupid! Why did you not want to believe what the Lord's spokespersons had told ahead.of.time from long.ago.</bt><v n="26" />Te rèngu suri le, na, Kristus ne hud'i pasae ku j'aj'èra rupa-rupa, heka Na abhu pakab'ua dènge dadedha kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) they had written that the Kristus, must bear/experience various sorts of suffering, only.then would He receive honour and glory/high-ness.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="KT dadedha = glory (UNS got"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">KT dadedha = glory (UNS got it)</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ka Yesus aj'a si, aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua suri tèke lula-nèti Kristus ne. Karèi nèti sasuri baki Musa toke dhèu rèti lii padhai dhu leo sèra.<bt>Then Yesus taught them everything which the Lord's spokespersons had written ahead.of.time about Kristus. Starting from grandfather Musa's writings, until the other spokespersons'.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa rèngu oe d'ai Emaus, ka Yesus pasabhe eele neo kako taruu.<bt>When they had almost arrived in Emaus, then Yesus made as if He wanted to walk on.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasabhe = pretend, make as if"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pasabhe = pretend, make as if to</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Te ngaa ra manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! J'unu taha ku dènge ji'i mèda ne'e, te lod'o oe cèna kèna.&gt;&gt; Ka Yesus maso palere-lere dènge rèngu asa d'ara èmu.<bt>But the two of them requested, saying, “Father! Just spend the night with us tonight, cuz (elaboration) the sun is about to go down.” So Yesus entered together with them into the house.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa rèngu madhèdi neo ra'a, hèia Yesus nare roti ca balok. Ka Na sabaj'a manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, hèia Na pamae roti ne. Ropa Na j'ole roti ne sa rèngu dua ra,<bt>When they were sitting about to eat, then Yesus took a loaf of bread. Then He prayed giving thanks to Father God, then He divided up that bread. When he extended that bread to the two of them,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eulogeesen: pronounce a blessing (not &quot;gave"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">eulogeesen: pronounce a blessing (not "gave thanks," which is a different kind of thing in local culture)</Message></Annotation><v n="31" />heka ra tadhe, na, Nèngu ne Yesus. Te ngaa kabèdhi laa, Na ele nèti madha rèngu dua ra!<bt>only.then did they know/recognise that that was Yesus. But suddenly, He disappeared from in front of the two of them!</bt><v n="32" />Hèia dua ra padhue, peka na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Deo na ropa Na peka paled'a lii padhai nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua, d'ara èdhi taleo moro-moro sange rai-haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the two of them spoke.to.each.other, saying, “Waa! When hearing Him speaking making clear the spokespersons' writings earlier, we-inc felt as if our insides were opened up &amp; suddenly catching on (idiom: broadened as wide as the earth).” [NOTE: lit. ‘burn’ implies anger]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèko-dhèko = berdebar, duk-dak ; tunu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">dhèko-dhèko = berdebar, duk-dak ; tunu = ; ridhu-ridhu = 1) lompat, 2) ; boti-boti = bounce up and down, excited ; sèmi tao cuhi re èi = like splashed with water (Idiom: rasa segar) ; taleo moro-moro = luas \lf Max Idiom =&gt; baru mangarti</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samangat tinggi tagal dapat pengertian baru"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">samangat tinggi tagal dapat pengertian baru yang kena</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, dua ra kèd'i dènge ka, lèpa asa Yerusalem. Lasi paraga dènge canguru ca dhèu ana madhutu Yesus sèra, dènge dhèu leo dhu pakaboko ètu era èèna.<bt>At that time, then the two of them got up right.away to return to Yerusalem. They met Yesus' eleven underlings, and other people who were gathered there.</bt><v n="34" />Hèia ana madhutu se peka dènge rèngu dua ra, na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Lamatua Yesus mamuri hari le! Deo na pad'elo iisi Na dènge Petrus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those underlings told the two of them, saying, “Certainly true! Lord Yesus lives again! Earlier He showed Himself to elder.brother Petrus.”</bt><note reference="24:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani peka na, &lt;Simon&gt; ètu ne'e. Simon ne, ngara leo na Petrus.<bt>The Yunani language writing says &lt;Simon&gt; here. Simon is Petrus' other name.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Èle ka dhèu dua se lole aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i ètu j'ara, toke rèngu dua ra tadhe Yesus ropa Na pamae roti.<bt>Then those two people told everything which happened on the road, to.the.point. that they recognized Yesus when He divided the bread.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pad'elo iisi Na mi ana-ana madhutu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus reveals himself to His underlings</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 28:16-20; Markus 16:14-18; Yohanis 20:19-23; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:6-8)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Lod'o rèngu palolo era, kaca'a laa, Yesus titu ètu talora aae rèngu. Na hia maho'o mi rèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Saloom!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were still telling like.that, suddenly, Yesus himself was standing in their midst. He gave greetings to them, saying, ‘Saloom!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka ra cag'ag'a aa madha'u, lula ra ngee na nidhu.<bt>But they were startled and afraid, cuz they thought it was a ghost/spirit of a dead person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Te ngaa Yesus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu madha'u? Miu parcaya boe, na, Ja'a ne mamuri hari le, do?<bt>But Yesus spoke, saying, “Why are you afraid like.this? Don't you believe that this is Me,who live again, (tag question)? [see TN display]</bt><v n="39" />Miu ladhe sèku ai dènge haga Ja'a ne. Ja'a ka ne'e ne. J'ole ai miu ho g'ag'e unu mi! Sèna ka mi lèka, na, Ja'a ka ne'e ne, nidhu boe. Te nidhu dènge boe ngi'u, te ngaa miu mèdhi ngi'u Ja'a ne, si?!&gt;&gt;<bt>Come look at My hands and feet. It's Me. Just extend your hand to touch for yourselves! So that you believe that this is Me, not a ghost. Cuz (elaboration) ghosts don't have a body, but you all can see My body, right?!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ropa Na padhai lii era, Na pad'elo dènge si era nu'a dhu ètu adhe-aai dènge haga Na.<bt>Still speaking like.that, He showed them the place of the (fresh) wound on His hands and feet.</bt><v n="41" />Rèngu karej'e titu kèna, lula Yesus mamuri hari le. Dhoka ra bingu, te re'a boe tasamia ka bisa j'aj'i sèmi èèna. Hèia Yesus karèi si, &lt;&lt;Miu mi'a ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>They were very happy, because Yesus lived again. Only they were confused, cuz (elaboration) they could not understand how it could happen like.that. Then Yesus asked them, saying, “What are you eating?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thaumazontoon: too good to be true:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">thaumazontoon: too good to be true: "totally max out."</Message></Annotation><v n="42" />Ka ra j'ole hia Ne i'a paga ca kadhèli.<bt>Then they extended gave to Him a piece of grilled fish. [EXEG: Gk “grilled, broiled”, not “fried” as in TB. Don't be surprised if you get challenged on this.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadhèli = a piece cut crosswise"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">kadhèli = a piece cut crosswise</Message></Annotation><v n="43" />Yesus sèmi nare i'a ne, hèia na'e dènge ka ètu madha rèngu.<bt>Yesus accepted that fish, then He ate it front of them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Èle ka, Na lii dènge rèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Miu sanèd'e era lod'o Ja'a uru èèna dhu bera-bera dènge miu? Ja'a peka dènge miu ca hari ni, hud'i j'aj'i ku aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra suri tèke lula-nèti Ja'a ne. Nuka nèti baki Musa, aa nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu leo sèra, aa nèti sasuri Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He spoke, saying, “How is it? Do you still remember when I was together with you previously? I told one time, that, everything which Father God's spokespersons had written about Me, had to happen. That is, from grandfather Musa, and from the other spokespersons, and from the book of Praise Songs.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Torah, Nevi'im, Ktuvim, the three divisions"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">Torah, Nevi'im, Ktuvim, the three divisions of the Hebrew Bible</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Èle ka, Na bhoke paled'a, sèna ka re'a mèu sasoa nèti isi Sasuri Lamatua.<bt>After that, He open making clear so they could truly understand the meaning of the *Scriptures.</bt><v n="46" />Na peka tabha hari, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua se dhu suri le, na, Kristus dhu Lamatua hia mai èèna, hud'i abhu ku rupa-rupa j'aj'èra, heka Na madhe kèna. Te ngaa ladhe d'ai camèd'a, Na mamuri hari. Te dhu suri aa'i le j'ara se'e!<bt>He spoke further, saying, “The Lord's spokespersons wrote, that, Kristus, who the Lord sent, must get/experience all.sorts of suffering, then He would die. But later on the day.after.tomorrow, He would live again. They've written all of that [+obviously]!</bt><v n="47" />Nèti deo ne'e, Ja'a hia miu koasa, ho lami mèti Lii Lolo Be'a mi suku aa'i-aa'i, mulai nèti Yerusalem ne. Peka dènge rèngu, na, dhèu dhu mangaku sasala ra, aa lèpa hari asa Lamatua, pe Lamatua saku pamèu sasala ra aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Now I give power/authority for you to take this Good News here to all the tribes/people groups, starting from Yerusalem here. Tell them that, people who confess their wrongs and return to the Lord, the Lord will completely erase all their wrongs. [EXEG: NLT takes “in his name” as “with my authority”. See CEG word study on “name” as summary.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epi tooi onomati autou: in connection"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z" status="Information">epi tooi onomati autou: in connection with him (put at the end so as not to overload the syntax)</Message></Annotation><v n="48" />Miu hud'i j'aj'i ku sakasii, sèna ka miu lolo, peka na, Ja'a dui j'aj'èra, ka madhe, hèia mamuri hari.<bt>You must be/become witnesses to tell (the story) that I suffered, then died, then lived again.</bt><v n="49" />Èèna na, Ja'a hia Roh dhu Mola-Mèci, dhu Ama Ku pajaji nare le. Te ngaa miu hud'i tatae ku Nèngu ètu kota Yerusalem ne, toke abhu koasa nèti sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>Later I will send the Holy Spirit, whom My Father has promised. But you must wait here in Yerusalem city, until recieving power/authority from heaven. [as per NLT, CEV note, TH, TN, and Marshall]</bt><note reference="24:49" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 2:28-29; Yohanis 14:16-17; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:4</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ca'e asa sorga<bt>The Lord Yesus ascends to heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Markus 16:19-20; Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:9-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Ca lod'o, Yesus nèti si asa li'u kota. Ropa rèngu dètu dènge rae Betania, Na baa ai sèna ka hia ra berkat.<bt>One day, Yesus brought them outside that city. When they arrived closed to Betania village, He lifted his hands to speak giving blessing to them.</bt><note reference="24:50-51" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:9-11</note><v n="51" />Yesus padhai lii hia berkat era, hèia ded'e Ne ca'e la'e asa sorga.<bt>While He was still speaking giving blessing like.that, then He ascended up to heaven.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pecèri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:45:29Z">pecèri</Message></Annotation><v n="52" />Ladhe rèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra patitu kètu urutuu ho pahaha iisi mi Yesus. Ka ra lèpa asa Yerusalem dènge d'ara dhu karej'e-karae.<bt>Seeing like.that, they all knelt to worship Yesus. Then they returned home to Yerusalem with insides that were very happy (doublet).</bt><v n="53" />Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu pakaboko ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ho koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Every day they gathered at the Central Worship House to lift up praises (doublet) to Father God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Teofilus! Lii lolo ja'a ne, d'ai sange ne'e ka.<bt>Father Teofilus! My story reaches this limit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Salam,<bt>Greetings,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Lukas<bt>Lukas</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>